{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1783806712387,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"id":"prt_f532a5a42001gK0v652LQ0HUse","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","snapshot":"fe03b20dde9c4dbba7dc0e6f79ecce2c3c838fcc","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723702,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_saBRJUUjbvbjz3ARndHG8Atw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n2: # DEEP REVIEW: AUTONOMOUS DEEP REVIEW LOOP (AUTO MODE)\n3: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n4: # DEEP REVIEW: AUTONOMOUS DEEP REVIEW LOOP (AUTO MODE)\n5: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n6: role: Deep Review Loop Manager\n7: purpose: Iterative code/spec review with convergence detection across review dimensions\n8: action: Run deep-review loop from initialization through synthesis\n9: operating_mode:\n10:   workflow: iterative_loop\n11:   workflow_compliance: MANDATORY\n12:   workflow_execution: autonomous\n13:   approvals: none\n14:   tracking: progressive_review_state\n15:   validation: convergence_detection\n16: \n17: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n18: # OPERATING PRINCIPLES\n19: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n20: operating_principles:\n21:   core: \"Fresh context per iteration + externalized state = no context degradation\"\n22:   approach: \"Dispatch focused review agent per dimension, evaluate convergence, repeat or stop\"\n23:   mandate: \"Never hold findings in memory; write everything to files. Review target is READ-ONLY.\"\n24: \n25: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n26: # USER INPUTS (from setup phase)\n27: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n28: user_inputs:\n29:   review_target: \"[REVIEW_TARGET] - What to review. REQUIRED.\"\n30:   review_target_type: \"[spec-folder|skill|agent|track|files] - Target type for scope derivation. REQUIRED.\"\n31:   review_dimensions: \"[all|correctness,security,traceability,maintainability] - Dimensions to check. Default: all.\"\n32:   spec_folder: \"[SPEC_FOLDER] - Spec folder path for state files. REQUIRED.\"\n33:   session_id: \"[SESSION_ID] - Optional caller-supplied session id for fan-out lineages. Default: timestamp.\"\n34:   lineage_mode: \"[auto|resume|restart] - Session lifecycle intent. Default: auto. The runtime only persists lineage events for `resume` (same sessionId, no archive) and `restart` (new sessionId, generation+1, prior review/ archived). `fork` and `completed-continue` are deferred and no longer accepted — see deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md §Lifecycle Branches.\"\n35:   max_iterations: 7\n36:   convergence_threshold: 0.10\n37:   convergence_mode: \"[default|off|sliding-window|divergent] - Convergence policy modifier. Default: default.\"\n38:   stop_policy: \"[convergence|max-iterations] - Stop behavior. Default: convergence. max-iterations treats convergence as telemetry until the hard iteration ceiling.\"\n39:   config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir: \"[optional internal path] - Fan-out lineage artifact override for command-owned single-lineage execution.\"\n40: \n41: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n42: # CONTEXT LOADING\n43: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n44: context_loading:\n45:   trigger: \"At workflow START, before phase_init\"\n46:   purpose: \"Load prior review context for the target and buffer it until strategy.md exists\"\n47:   mcp_integration:\n48:     tool: memory_context\n49:     note: \"Call MCP tools directly - NEVER through Code Mode\"\n50:     parameters: { input: \"{review_target}\", mode: \"focused\", intent: \"understand\", includeContent: true }\n51:   when_to_skip: [\"User says 'skip context' or 'fresh start'\"]\n52:   behavior:\n53:     if_context_found: \"Store full results as prior_context plus a concise prior_context_summary; inject after strategy.md is created.\"\n54:     if_no_context: \"Set prior_context and prior_context_summary to 'None' and continue.\"\n55: \n56: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n57: # SKILL REFERENCE\n58: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n59: skill_reference:\n60:   skill: system-deep-loop\n61:   skill_md: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/SKILL.md\n62:   references:\n63:     loop_protocol: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md\n64:     state_format: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/state/state_format.md\n65:     convergence: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/convergence/convergence.md\n66:   templates:\n67:     config: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_config.json\n68:     strategy: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_strategy.md\n69: \n70: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n71: # AGENT CONFIGURATION\n72: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n73: agent_config:\n74:   agent: deep-review\n75:   agent_file: \".opencode/agents/deep-review.md\"\n76:   # Canonical path. Runtime-specific directories (e.g. .claude/agents/) reference this source.\n77:   mode: subagent\n78:   model: opus\n79:   leaf_only: true\n80:   tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\n81:   mcp_servers: [mk-spec-memory]\n82:   tool_call_budget: { target: 9, soft_max: 12, hard_max: 13 }\n83: \n84: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n85: # STATE FILE PATHS\n86: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n87: state_paths:\n88:   # Template paths document the canonical packet layout. Runtime resolution happens via\n89:   # step_resolve_artifact_root plus the shared resolver, so root specs keep\n90:   # root-local review/ and child phases keep local review/ packet dirs.\n91:   # Canonical root-spec write targets remain review/deep-review-config.json,\n92:   # review/deep-review-state.jsonl, and review/deep-review-findings-registry.json.\n93:   packet_dir: \"{artifact_dir}\"\n94:   local_packet_dir: \"{spec_folder}/review\"\n95:   legacy_root_report: \"{spec_folder}/review-report.md\"\n96:   config: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json\"\n97:   state_log: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl\"\n98:   findings_registry: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json\"\n99:   strategy: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md\"\n100:   dashboard: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-dashboard.md\"\n101:   pause_sentinel: \"{artifact_dir}/.deep-review-pause\"\n102:   lock_file: \"{artifact_dir}/.deep-review.lock\"\n103:   prompt_dir: \"{artifact_dir}/prompts\"\n104:   iteration_dir: \"{artifact_dir}/iterations\"\n105:   iteration_pattern: \"{artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md\"\n106:   # Per-iteration structured delta stream — complement to the canonical state_log\n107:   # append. MUST contain at least one record with `type === \"iteration\"`; variants\n108:   # like `\"iteration_delta\"` are silently dropped by the reducer.\n109:   delta_dir: \"{artifact_dir}/deltas\"\n110:   delta_pattern: \"{artifact_dir}/deltas/iter-{NNN}.jsonl\"\n111:   review_output: \"{artifact_dir}/review-report.md\"\n112:   resource_map_output: \"{artifact_dir}/resource-map.md\"\n113:   archive_root: \"{artifact_archive_root}\"\n114: \n115: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n116: # WORKFLOW\n117: # ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n118: workflow:\n119: \n120:   step_resolve_artifact_root:\n121:     description: \"Resolve artifact directory — use fan-out lineage override when provided, else resolve from spec_folder\"\n122:     note: \"Root specs keep review artifacts directly in {spec_folder}/review/. Child phases and sub-phases keep local packet directories in {spec_folder}/review/{packet}/, and archives stay local at {spec_folder}/review_archive/{packet}/.\"\n123:     branch_on: \"config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir\"\n124:     if_present:\n125:       bind:\n126:         artifact_dir: \"{config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir}\"\n127:         artifact_root_dir: \"{config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir}\"\n128:         artifact_subfolder: null\n129:         artifact_archive_root: \"{config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir}/_archive\"\n130:     if_absent:\n131:       command: \"node -e \\\"const { resolveArtifactRoot } = require('.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs'); console.log(JSON.stringify(resolveArtifactRoot('{spec_folder}', 'review')));\\\"\"\n132:       outputs:\n133:         - artifact_root_dir: \"Resolved local review owner directory\"\n134:         - artifact_subfolder: \"Local packet subfolder ({ownerSlug}-pt-{NN}), else null\"\n135:         - artifact_dir: \"Resolved review packet directory for this target\"\n136:         - artifact_archive_root: \"Resolved local review archive directory for this target\"\n137: \n138:   step_apply_lifecycle_request:\n139:     description: \"Honor explicit auto-mode restart before fan-out or normal initialization\"\n140:     skip_when: \"lineage_mode != 'restart'\"\n141:     instructions: |\n142:       This is the autonomous equivalent of the confirm-mode restart choice. Run it\n143:       immediately after artifact resolution and before fan-out so old packet files\n144:       cannot be merged with fresh lineage outputs. A restart request must never\n145:       fall back to auto-resume. In auto mode, the explicit restart flag is operator\n146:       authorization to archive the resolved review packet, so do not ask for a\n147:       second confirmation. Rollback is to move the timestamped archive back to\n148:       the packet directory.\n149:     command: \"if [ -d \\\"{state_paths.packet_dir}\\\" ]; then mkdir -p \\\"{state_paths.archive_root}\\\" && mv \\\"{state_paths.packet_dir}\\\" \\\"{state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug}\\\"; fi; mkdir -p \\\"{state_paths.packet_dir}\\\"\"\n150:     outputs:\n151:       - archived_path: \"{state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug} when a prior packet existed, else null\"\n152:       - lineage_mode: \"restart\"\n153:     on_fail: \"Halt with STATUS=FAIL; do not continue as resume or auto.\"\n154: \n155:   step_fanout_spawn:\n156:     description: \"Spawn fan-out lineages; skip and proceed to phase_init normally when single-executor\"\n157:     skip_when: \"config.fanout is absent\"\n158:     instructions: |\n159:       Fan-out mode is active. Spawn all lineages. Each lineage runs the full loop in its own\n160:       isolated sub-packet under {artifact_dir}/lineages/{label}/.\n161:       A cli-opencode lineage inside this fan-out is an explicit parallel-detached OpenCode\n162:       session with a separate lineage directory and session id; it is not the single-executor\n163:       self-invocation path. fanout-run.cjs owns the stack-only recursion guard for that\n164:       first-level detached lineage and still blocks recursive same-kind dispatch from inside it.\n165:       fanout-run.cjs owns native and CLI lineage execution; native is run through the\n166:       deep/review command surface with config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir so the LEAF\n167:       deep-review agent is used only for individual iterations, never as a full-loop\n168:       sub-agent or pasted phase-running prompt.\n169:       After all lineages complete, jump directly to phase_synthesis — skip phase_init and\n170:       phase_main_loop entirely (those are the single-executor path). The merge step in\n171:       phase_synthesis will consolidate results across all lineages.\n172:     sub_steps:\n173:       step_fanout_spawn_cli:\n174:         description: \"Spawn all native and CLI lineages in capped worker pool\"\n175:         skip_when: \"no entries in config.fanout.executors\"\n176:         command: |\n177:           node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/fanout-run.cjs \\\n178:             --spec-folder {spec_folder} \\\n179:             --loop-type review \\\n180:             --fanout-config-json '{config.fanout_json}' \\\n181:             --base-artifact-dir {artifact_dir} \\\n182:             --convergence-threshold {convergence_threshold} \\\n183:             --stop-policy {stop_policy}\n184:         working_directory: \"{repo_root}\"\n185:         wait_for_completion: true\n186: \n187:   # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n188:   # PHASE 1: INITIALIZATION\n189:   # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n190:   phase_init:\n191:     purpose: Create all state files for the review session and resolve review scope\n192:     steps:\n193: \n194:       step_preflight_contract:\n195:         action: \"Validate required setup bindings and executable workflow contract before any file writes\"\n196:         verify:\n197:           - required_values_present: [review_target, review_target_type, review_dimensions, spec_folder, lineage_mode, max_iterations, convergence_threshold, convergence_mode, stop_policy]\n198:           - spec_folder_is_within: \"specs/ or .opencode/specs/ (canonicalize alias roots before validation)\"\n199:           - unresolved_placeholders: \"FAIL if any user-facing template references placeholders not produced by earlier steps\"\n200:           - tool_contract: \"FAIL if executable steps reference tools outside the command allowlist\"\n201:         on_fail: \"Halt with STATUS=FAIL and report the missing binding or unsupported contract reference\"\n202: \n203:       step_create_directories:\n204:         action: \"Create spec folder and canonical review packet directories if they don't exist\"\n205:         command: \"mkdir -p {state_paths.prompt_dir} {state_paths.iteration_dir} {state_paths.delta_dir}\"\n206: \n207:       step_detect_resource_map:\n208:         action: \"Detect resource-map.md before config creation so init can persist coverage-gate state\"\n209:         inspect:\n210:           - \"{spec_folder}/resource-map.md\"\n211:         classify:\n212:           present: \"resource-map.md exists at init\"\n213:           absent: \"resource-map.md does not exist at init\"\n214:         outputs:\n215:           - resource_map_present: \"Boolean true when {spec_folder}/resource-map.md exists, else false\"\n216:           - resource_map_known_context: \"When present: concise resource-map snapshot for Known Context and charter framing. When absent: 'resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate'.\"\n217: \n218:       step_migrate_legacy_review_state:\n219:         action: \"Rehome legacy review artifacts into review/iterations before session classification\"\n220:         detect:\n221:           canonical_review_state:\n222:             - \"{state_paths.config}\"\n223:             - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n224:             - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n225:             - \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n226:           legacy_review_state:\n227:             - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json\"\n228:             - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl\"\n229:             - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md\"\n230:             - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md\"\n231:             - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/iteration-*.md\"\n232:             - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause\"\n233:             - \"{state_paths.local_packet_dir}/iteration-*.md\"\n234:             - \"{state_paths.legacy_root_report}\"\n235:           legacy_review_markers:\n236:             - \"scratch/deep-review-strategy.md exists\"\n237:             - \"scratch/deep-research-config.json declares mode == 'review' OR scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl contains mode == 'review'\"\n238:         migrate_only:\n239:           - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json -> {state_paths.config}\"\n240:           - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl -> {state_paths.state_log}\"\n241:           - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md -> {state_paths.strategy}\"\n242:           - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md -> {state_paths.dashboard}\"\n243:           - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/iteration-*.md -> {state_paths.iteration_dir}/\"\n244:           - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause -> {state_paths.pause_sentinel}\"\n245:           - \"{state_paths.local_packet_dir}/iteration-*.md -> {state_paths.iteration_dir}/\"\n246:           - \"{state_paths.legacy_root_report} -> {state_paths.review_output}\"\n247:         on_canonical_present: \"Leave canonical review/ state untouched and do not overwrite it with legacy scratch artifacts.\"\n248:         on_legacy_detected: \"Move only the review-specific whitelist, append a migration event to the canonical JSONL, and leave unrelated scratch files untouched.\"\n249:         on_conflict: \"If canonical review/ state and legacy scratch review state both exist but disagree, halt for operator repair instead of merging contradictory state.\"\n250:         command: \"mkdir -p {state_paths.iteration_dir} && if [ ! -e {state_paths.config} ] && [ ! -e {state_paths.state_log} ] && [ ! -e {state_paths.strategy} ] && [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md ] && ( [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json ] || [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl ] ); then [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json {state_paths.config}; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl {state_paths.state_log}; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md {state_paths.strategy}; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md {state_paths.dashboard}; find {spec_folder}/scratch -maxdepth 1 -name 'iteration-*.md' -exec mv {} {state_paths.iteration_dir}/ \\\\; ; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause {state_paths.pause_sentinel}; [ -e {state_paths.legacy_root_report} ] && mv {state_paths.legacy_root_report} {state_paths.review_output}; if [ -e {state_paths.state_log} ]; then printf '%s\\n' '{\\\"type\\\":\\\"event\\\",\\\"event\\\":\\\"migration\\\",\\\"mode\\\":\\\"review\\\",\\\"legacyArtifacts\\\":[\\\"deep-research-config.json\\\",\\\"deep-research-state.jsonl\\\",\\\".deep-research-pause\\\"],\\\"canonicalArtifacts\\\":[\\\"deep-review-config.json\\\",\\\"deep-review-state.jsonl\\\",\\\".deep-review-pause\\\"],\\\"timestamp\\\":\\\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\\\"}' >> {state_paths.state_log}; fi; fi; find {state_paths.local_packet_dir} -maxdepth 1 -name 'iteration-*.md' -exec mv {} {state_paths.iteration_dir}/ \\\\; 2>/dev/null || true\"\n251: \n252:       step_acquire_lock:\n253:         action: \"Acquire the single-writer advisory lock before session classification\"\n254:         command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs acquire --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --packet-id {spec_folder}\"\n255:         on_acquire: \"Capture ownerPid from the JSON output and reuse it for every release below. If acquired=false, fail closed — another deep-review run already holds this packet.\"\n256:         note: \"Uses the promoted runtime/ loop-lock CLI (single source of truth: stale-lock reclaim, clean owner-scoped release). macOS/BSD locking is advisory — best-effort single-writer, not a hard mutex across host calls; stale-lock override is confirm-only or explicit recovery-only.\"\n257:         # Lock-cleanup contract: the lock file MUST be released on every terminal exit path that follows acquisition.\n258:         # Runtimes honoring step_acquire_lock are required to perform this cleanup before halting or pausing.\n259:         on_halt:\n260:           action: \"Release the lock before any terminal halt branch returns control\"\n261:           applies_to: [\"step_classify_session.on_invalid_state\", \"step_classify_session.on_completed_session\"]\n262:           command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs release --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --owner-pid {captured_owner_pid}; failures here are logged but do not block the halt\"\n263:         on_cancel:\n264:           action: \"Release the lock on user cancel or pause-sentinel detection before sentinel processing\"\n265:           command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs release --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --owner-pid {captured_owner_pid}; cancel completes regardless of cleanup result\"\n266:         on_workflow_exit:\n267:           action: \"Release the lock as the final step of any workflow exit path (success or failure)\"\n268:           command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs release --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --owner-pid {captured_owner_pid}; idempotent — safe to invoke when already released\"\n269: \n270:       step_classify_session:\n271:         action: \"Classify the session before writing files\"\n272:         inspect:\n273:           - \"{state_paths.config}\"\n274:           - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n275:           - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n276:           - \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n277:         classify:\n278:           fresh: \"None of the three state artifacts exist\"\n279:           resume: \"Config, JSONL, and strategy all exist and config.mode == 'review' and agree on target/spec folder\"\n280:           completed-session: \"Resume artifacts exist and config.status == 'complete'\"\n281:           invalid-state: \"Any partial, missing, or contradictory combination\"\n282:         outputs:\n283:           - session_state: \"fresh | resume | completed-session | invalid-state\"\n284:         lifecycle_routing:\n285:           - \"If lineage_mode == restart and session_state is resume or completed-session, execute on_restart before on_resume or on_completed_session.\"\n286:           - \"If lineage_mode == auto or lineage_mode == resume, preserve the existing resume/completed/fresh behavior.\"\n287:         on_resume:\n288:           log: \"Auto-resume: state artifacts are complete and consistent. Continue the same lineage (sessionId unchanged, generation unchanged, no archive).\"\n289:           append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"parentSessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"lineageMode\":\"resume\",\"continuedFromRun\":{iteration_count},\"generation\":{generation},\"archivedPath\":null,\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"}'\n290:           skip_to: phase_loop\n291:         on_restart:\n292:           action: \"Archive the current review packet under the root-level review_archive/ tree and start a new lineage segment with a fresh sessionId and generation+1.\"\n293:           command: \"if [ -d {state_paths.packet_dir} ]; then mkdir -p {state_paths.archive_root} && mv {state_paths.packet_dir} {state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug}; fi\"\n294:           set:\n295:             lineage_mode: \"restart\"\n296:             parent_session_id: \"{prior_session_id}\"\n297:             generation: \"{prior_generation + 1}\"\n298:           append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"restarted\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"parentSessionId\":\"{prior_session_id}\",\"lineageMode\":\"restart\",\"generation\":{generation},\"archivedPath\":\"{state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug}\",\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"}'\n299:           skip_to: step_create_config\n300:         note_deferred_branches: \"fork and completed-continue are deferred and no longer runtime-supported in this release. The reducer still reads `lineageMode` from config for dashboards and analysis, but only `new`, `resume`, and `restart` are live. See deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md §Lifecycle Branches for the one-session contract.\"\n301:         on_completed_session:\n302:           log: \"Prior session already completed. Either archive the completed review/ tree and start a fresh session, or jump straight to synthesis with the existing artifacts.\"\n303:           skip_to: phase_synthesis\n304:         on_invalid_state:\n305:           halt: true\n306:           message: \"Existing deep-review state in review/ is incomplete or contradictory. Repair or archive the invalid review packet before continuing.\"\n307:         on_fresh:\n308:           action: \"Proceed with a new session\"\n309: \n310:       step_scope_discovery:\n311:         action: \"Resolve review target to a concrete file list based on target type\"\n312:         resolve:\n313:           spec-folder: |\n314:             1. Read spec.md, plan.md, tasks.md, checklist.md, implementation-summary.md\n315:             2. Discover implementation files referenced in spec artifacts\n316:             3. Discover test files associated with implementation\n317:             4. Set scope = all discovered files\n318:           skill: |\n319:             1. Read SKILL.md from .opencode/skills/{skill_name}/\n320:             2. Discover references/, assets/, scripts/ contents\n321:             3. Find agent definitions referencing this skill across runtimes\n322:             4. Find command entry points referencing this skill\n323:             5. Set scope = all discovered files\n324:           agent: |\n325:             1. Find agent definition across repo-managed runtimes (.claude/agents/, .opencode/agents/)\n326:             2. Compare agent definitions for consistency\n327:             3. Set scope = all discovered agent files\n328:           track: |\n329:             1. List all child spec folders under specs/{track}/ or .opencode/specs/{track}/\n330:             2. For each: read spec.md + checklist.md\n331:             3. Set scope = all child spec artifacts\n332:           files: |\n333:             1. Expand glob patterns from review_target\n334:             2. Validate all files exist\n335:             3. Discover immediate cross-references (imports, links)\n336:             4. Set scope = expanded file list + cross-references\n337:         outputs:\n338:           - review_scope_files: \"List of all files in review scope\"\n339:           - cross_reference_targets: \"{ spec_paths: [...], code_paths: [...], test_paths: [...] }\"\n340: \n341:       step_order_dimensions:\n342:         action: \"Order review dimensions based on risk priority\"\n343:         algorithm: |\n344:           1. Iteration 0 (inventory pass): Build artifact map, identify file types, estimate complexity\n345:           2. Subsequent iterations follow risk-ordered deep passes:\n346:              correctness → security → traceability → maintainability\n347:           3. If review_dimensions != \"all\", filter to only requested dimensions\n348:           4. Derive traceability protocol plan:\n349:              - core: spec_code, checklist_evidence\n350:              - overlay: skill_agent, agent_cross_runtime, feature_catalog_code, playbook_capability\n351:           5. If resource_map_present, reserve at least one traceability-oriented pass to cross-check target_files from applied/T-*.md against resource-map.md and classify touched / expected-by-scope / gap / absent-from-map outcomes\n352:           6. Store ordered list as dimension_queue\n353:         outputs:\n354:           - dimension_queue: \"Ordered list of dimensions to review\"\n355:           - inventory_pass: true\n356: \n357:       step_normalize_review_dimensions:\n358:         action: \"Normalize reviewDimensions once during init for config + JSONL reuse\"\n359:         outputs:\n360:           - review_dimensions_normalized: \"Canonical string[] for deep-review-config.json\"\n361:           - review_dimensions_json: \"JSON.stringify(review_dimensions_normalized) for JSONL config record\"\n362:         normalize: |\n363:           Accept {review_dimensions} in any of these shapes and convert once:\n364:             - \"all\" → [\"correctness\",\"security\",\"traceability\",\"maintainability\"]\n365:             - \"correctness,security\" → [\"correctness\",\"security\"]\n366:             - [\"correctness\"] → [\"correctness\"]\n367:           Every element MUST be one of the four canonical dimension names.\n368: \n369:       step_resolve_session_id:\n370:         action: \"Resolve init session id from caller when supplied, else preserve timestamp fallback\"\n371:         branch_on: \"session_id\"\n372:         if_present:\n373:           bind:\n374:             session_id_init: \"{session_id}\"\n375:         if_absent:\n376:           bind:\n377:             session_id_init: \"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"\n378: \n379:       step_create_config:\n380:         action: \"Create deep-review-config.json from template with review-specific fields\"\n381:         template: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_config.json\n382:         populate:\n383:           topic: \"Review: {review_target}\"\n384:           mode: \"review\"\n385:           sessionId: \"{session_id_init}\"\n386:           parentSessionId: null\n387:           lineageMode: \"new\"\n388:           generation: 1\n389:           continuedFromRun: null\n390:           reviewTarget: \"{review_target}\"\n391:           reviewTargetType: \"{review_target_type}\"\n392:           # Reuse the single normalized init-time value from step_normalize_review_dimensions.\n393:           reviewDimensions: \"{review_dimensions_normalized}\"\n394:           resource_map_present: \"{resource_map_present}\"\n395:           reviewScopeFiles: \"{review_scope_files}\"\n396:           severityThreshold: \"P2\"\n397:           crossReference:\n398:             core: [\"spec_code\", \"checklist_evidence\"]\n399:             overlay: [\"skill_agent\", \"agent_cross_runtime\", \"feature_catalog_code\", \"playbook_capability\"]\n400:           maxIterations: \"{max_iterations}\"\n401:           # Semantic: weighted P0/P1/P2 severity ratio. See SKILL.md §\"Convergence Threshold Semantics\".\n402:           convergenceThreshold: \"{convergence_threshold}\"\n403:           antiConvergence.convergenceMode: \"{convergence_mode}\"\n404:           antiConvergence.divergent: {}\n405:           stopPolicy: \"{stop_policy}\"\n406:           stuckThreshold: 2\n407:           maxDurationMinutes: 120\n408:           specFolder: \"{spec_folder}\"\n409:           # Honor the parsed --no-resource-map flag from deep-review.md:71 (default true; false when flag is set).\n410:           # The markdown command parses $ARGUMENTS and binds {resource_map_emit} before this step runs.\n411:           resource_map.emit: \"{resource_map_emit}\"\n412:           createdAt: \"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"\n413:           status: \"initialized\"\n414:           releaseReadinessState: \"in-progress\"\n415:           executionMode: \"auto\"\n416:         output: \"{state_paths.config}\"\n417: \n418:       step_create_state_log:\n419:         action: \"Initialize JSONL state log with config record including review fields and lineage metadata\"\n420:         note: \"Reuse review_dimensions_json from step_normalize_review_dimensions. Never re-normalize or wrap the raw template value.\"\n421:         # Same parsed --no-resource-map flag honored here so config and state_log agree from line 1.\n422:         content: '{\"type\":\"config\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"reviewTarget\":\"{review_target}\",\"reviewTargetType\":\"{review_target_type}\",\"reviewDimensions\":{review_dimensions_json},\"resource_map_present\":{resource_map_present},\"resource_map\":{\"emit\":{resource_map_emit}},\"sessionId\":\"{session_id_init}\",\"parentSessionId\":null,\"lineageMode\":\"new\",\"generation\":1,\"continuedFromRun\":null,\"maxIterations\":{max_iterations},\"convergenceThreshold\":{convergence_threshold},\"antiConvergence\":{\"convergenceMode\":\"{convergence_mode}\",\"divergent\":{}},\"stopPolicy\":\"{stop_policy}\",\"createdAt\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\",\"specFolder\":\"{spec_folder}\"}'\n423:         output: \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n424: \n425:       step_create_findings_registry:\n426:         action: \"Initialize reducer-owned review findings registry\"\n427:         content: '{\"sessionId\":\"{session_id_init}\",\"generation\":1,\"lineageMode\":\"new\",\"openFindings\":[],\"resolvedFindings\":[],\"repeatedFindings\":[],\"dimensionCoverage\":{\"correctness\":false,\"security\":false,\"traceability\":false,\"maintainability\":false},\"findingsBySeverity\":{\"P0\":0,\"P1\":0,\"P2\":0},\"openFindingsCount\":0,\"resolvedFindingsCount\":0,\"convergenceScore\":0.0}'\n428:         output: \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n429: \n430:       step_create_strategy:\n431:         action: \"Create review strategy file from deep_review_strategy.md template\"\n432:         template: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_strategy.md\n433:         populate:\n434:           review_target: \"{review_target}\"\n435:           review_target_type: \"{review_target_type}\"\n436:           dimensions: \"{dimension_queue}\"\n437:           scope_files: \"{review_scope_files}\"\n438:           cross_reference_targets: \"{cross_reference_targets}\"\n439:           max_iterations: \"{max_iterations}\"\n440:           convergence_threshold: \"{convergence_threshold}\"\n441:           stop_policy: \"{stop_policy}\"\n442:         output: \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n443: \n444:       step_seed_coverage_graph:\n445:         action: \"Seed the review coverage graph before the first convergence check\"\n446:         transform: |\n447:           1. Convert review_scope_files into FILE nodes.\n448:           2. Convert review target groupings into coarse SLICE nodes only; do not expand SYMBOL\n449:              or DEPENDENCY nodes in review mode.\n450:           3. Emit COVERS edges from SLICE nodes to FILE nodes when the grouping is known.\n451:           4. Bind coverage_seed_source to \"scope_discovery\" and coverage_seed_confidence to 0.50.\n452:           5. When scope discovery yields no files, emit [] for both arrays; the upsert script\n453:              returns a warning and review continues with an empty graph.\n454:         bash: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/upsert.cjs --spec-folder \\\"{spec_folder}\\\" --loop-type \\\"review\\\" --session-id \\\"{config.sessionId}\\\" --nodes '{coverage_seed_nodes_json}' --edges '{coverage_seed_edges_json}' --seed-source \\\"{coverage_seed_source}\\\" --seed-confidence \\\"{coverage_seed_confidence}\\\"\"\n455:         outputs:\n456:           - coverage_seed_nodes_json: \"Seed nodes for review SLICE and FILE kinds only\"\n457:           - coverage_seed_edges_json: \"Seed COVERS edges where review target groupings resolved\"\n458:           - coverage_seed_warning: \"Warning emitted when the seed batch inserts zero nodes, else empty\"\n459:         on_warning:\n460:           log: \"Coverage graph seed inserted zero nodes; continuing with an empty graph.\"\n461:           proceed: true\n462: \n463:       step_enrich_strategy_context:\n464:         action: \"Ensure Known Context is written only after strategy.md exists\"\n465:         condition: \"prior_context_found\"\n466:         edit: \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n467:         note: \"Append or replace the Known Context section with prior_context_summary and retained detail from prior_context\"\n468: \n469:       step_enrich_strategy_resource_map:\n470:         action: \"Inject resource-map status into Known Context after strategy.md exists\"\n471:         edit: \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n472:         note: \"When resource_map_present is true, append the resource_map_known_context snapshot and add Resource Map Coverage to the Review Charter. When false, append 'resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate'.\"\n473: \n474:       step_init_complete:\n475:         log: \"Initialization complete. Config, state, and strategy files created. Review scope: {review_scope_files_count} files, {dimension_queue_count} dimensions.\"\n476:         set: { current_iteration: 1, stuck_count: 0, p0_count: 0, p1_count: 0, p2_count: 0 }\n477: \n478:   # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n479:   # PHASE 2: ITERATION LOOP\n480:   # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n481:   phase_loop:\n482:     purpose: Dispatch review agent iterations until convergence\n483:     repeat: true\n484:     max_repeats: \"{max_iterations}\"\n485:     steps:\n486: \n487:       step_read_state:\n488:         action: \"Read current state from JSONL, strategy, and config\"\n489:         read:\n490:           - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n491:           - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n492:           - \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n493:           - \"{state_paths.config}\"\n494:         extract:\n495:           - iteration_count: \"Count lines where type === 'iteration'\"\n496:           - current_iteration: \"iteration_count + 1\"\n497:           - last_newFindingsRatio: \"Extract newFindingsRatio from last iteration record\"\n498:           - last_focus: \"Extract focus/dimension from latest iteration record, else 'none yet'\"\n499:           - ratio_prev: \"Extract newFindingsRatio from second-latest iteration record, else 'N/A'\"\n500:           - ratio_latest: \"Extract newFindingsRatio from latest iteration record, else 'N/A'\"\n501:           - next_dimension: \"Next uncovered dimension from dimension_queue in strategy.md\"\n502:           - dimensions_covered: \"List of dimensions already reviewed\"\n503:           - dimensions_remaining: \"List of dimensions not yet reviewed\"\n504:           - dimension_coverage: \"covered / total dimensions\"\n505:           - coverage_age: \"Iterations since dimension coverage last changed; require >= 1 before STOP\"\n506:           - p0_count: \"Count P0 findings across all iterations\"\n507:           - p1_count: \"Count P1 findings across all iterations\"\n508:           - p2_count: \"Count P2 findings across all iterations\"\n509:           - resource_map_present: \"Extract boolean from deep-review-config.json, default false\"\n510:           - resource_map_prompt_line: \"If resource_map_present is true, return 'Resource Map Coverage: cross-check target_files from {spec_folder}/applied/T-*.md against {spec_folder}/resource-map.md and classify only missed coverage as gaps.' Else return 'Resource Map Coverage: resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate.'\"\n511:           - session_id: \"Extract sessionId from deep-review-config.json\"\n512:           - generation: \"Extract generation from deep-review-config.json, else 1\"\n513:           - last_3_summaries: \"Summarize the latest 3 iteration records as 'run N: dimension (ratio, P0/P1/P2)'\"\n514:           - latest_status: \"Extract status from latest iteration record, else 'none yet'\"\n515:           - last_claim_adjudication_passed: \"Scan state.jsonl for the most recent `claim_adjudication` event; use its `passed` boolean. Default true when no event exists or when activeP0 + activeP1 == 0 (gate is vacuous without adjudicable findings).\"\n516:           - claim_adjudication_active_count: \"Count of active P0/P1 findings at the time of the last claim_adjudication event; 0 when none exist\"\n517:           - security_sensitive_fix_scope: \"Boolean true when the current review is a rerun after fixes involving security, path disclosure, auth/authz, sandboxing, env precedence, public schemas, persistence, or user-visible error payloads; derive from the latest review report, remediation notes, or planning packet when present, else false.\"\n518:           - fix_completeness_replay_required_rows: \"Count prior active or remediated P0/P1 findings, plus any prior security/path P2 findings, that require closed-gate replay before STOP.\"\n519:           - fix_completeness_replay_passing_rows: \"Count required replay rows marked PASS with file:line or command evidence and producer/consumer/matrix coverage.\"\n520:           - stop_policy: \"Extract stopPolicy from deep-review-config.json, default 'convergence'. Valid values: convergence, max-iterations.\"\n521:           - convergence_mode: \"Extract antiConvergence.convergenceMode when it is one of 'default', 'off', 'sliding-window', or 'divergent'; default to 'default'\"\n522:           - convergence_mode_warning: \"Boolean true when antiConvergence.convergenceMode is present with an unsupported value; use 'default'\"\n523:           - pivot_lineage: \"Summarize registry.divergence.completed and registry.divergence.overrides with pivot ids, source iterations, and selected review direction; else 'none yet'\"\n524:           - saturated_directions: \"List registry.divergence.saturatedDirections; else 'none yet'\"\n525: \n526:       step_check_pause_sentinel:\n527:         action: \"Check for pause sentinel file\"\n528:         check: \"Does {state_paths.pause_sentinel} exist?\"\n529:         if_exists:\n530:           set:\n531:             pending_stop_event: \"paused\"\n532:             pending_stop_reason: \"userPaused\"\n533:             pending_stop_detail: \"sentinel file detected\"\n534:           skip_to: step_normalize_pause_events\n535:         if_not_exists:\n536:           proceed: true\n537: \n538:       step_validate_convergence_config:\n539:         action: \"Validate convergence mode when loading config\"\n540:         if_convergence_mode_invalid:\n541:           append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"config_warning\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"field\":\"antiConvergence.convergenceMode\",\"fallback\":\"default\",\"message\":\"Unsupported convergenceMode; using default convergence behavior.\",\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"generation\":{generation}}'\n542:           log: \"Unsupported convergenceMode; using default convergence behavior.\"\n543: \n544:       step_graph_convergence:\n545:         action: \"Evaluate coverage-graph convergence before the inline review convergence vote\"\n546:         inspect:\n547:           - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n548:           - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n549:         transform: |\n550:           1. Call graph convergence on the current review lineage before the inline 3-signal vote.\n551:           2. Record the decision as one of CONTINUE, STOP_ALLOWED, STOP_BLOCKED.\n552:           3. Preserve raw graph signals and blockers for reducer rollup and blocked-stop evidence.\n553:           4. Normalize blockers to both JSON array and CSV forms for downstream stop handling.\n554:           5. Set graph_stop_blocked = true only when graph_decision == \"STOP_BLOCKED\".\n555:         bash: 'node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/convergence.cjs --spec-folder \"{spec_folder}\" --loop-type \"review\" --session-id \"{session_id}\" --convergence-mode \"{convergence_mode}\"'\n556:         note: \"Invoke the runtime script directly. Review-side graph convergence must run before the inline review stop vote.\"\n557:         append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"graph_convergence\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"run\":{current_iteration},\"decision\":\"{graph_decision}\",\"signals\":{graph_signals_json},\"blockers\":{graph_blockers_json},\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"generation\":{generation}}'\n558:         outputs:\n559:           - graph_decision: \"CONTINUE | STOP_ALLOWED | STOP_BLOCKED\"\n560:           - graph_signals_json: \"JSON object returned by convergence.cjs\"\n561:           - graph_blockers_json: \"JSON array of graph blockers when present, else []\"\n562:           - graph_blockers_csv: \"Comma-separated blocker summary when graph blocks STOP, else empty string\"\n563:           - graph_stop_blocked: \"Boolean true when graph_decision == STOP_BLOCKED\"\n564: \n565:       step_check_convergence:\n566:         action: \"Evaluate graph-assisted review stop conditions and the legal-stop decision tree\"\n567:         algorithm: |\n568:           0. CLAIM-ADJUDICATION PRE-CHECK (universal STOP veto; runs before hard stops and composite convergence):\n569:              claim_adjudication_gate_pass = (last_claim_adjudication_passed != false) OR (p0_count + p1_count == 0)\n570:              If claim_adjudication_gate_pass == false:\n571:                candidate_decision = \"BLOCKED\"\n572:                stop_blocked = true\n573:                stopReason = \"blockedStop\"\n574:                blocked_gates = [\"claimAdjudicationGate\"]\n575:                recovery_strategy = \"Reviewer must add typed claim-adjudication packets (claim, evidenceRefs, counterevidenceSought, alternativeExplanation, finalSeverity, confidence, downgradeTrigger) for every active P0/P1 finding before STOP is allowed.\"\n576:                Skip hard stops (1) and composite convergence (4); proceed directly to step 5 legal-stop decision-tree assembly so blocked_by_json, gate outputs, and the blocked_stop event still populate consistently.\n577:           1. HARD STOPS:\n578:              a) if iteration_count >= max_iterations: set decision = \"STOP\", stopReason = \"maxIterationsReached\", hard_stop_reason = \"max_iterations_reached\", preserve any failed legal-stop gates as terminal evidence, and proceed to synthesis without legal-stop veto\n579:              b) if stop_policy == \"max-iterations\" AND iteration_count < max_iterations: do not allow all-dimensions-clean or composite convergence to stop; treat convergence signals as telemetry, set decision = \"CONTINUE\", and broaden the next review angle.\n580:              c) if all dimensions clean AND required traceability protocols are covered AND p0_count == 0 AND p1_count == 0 AND coverage_age >= 1 AND all quality gates pass (evidence: every P0/P1 has file:line; scope: all findings within target; coverage: all dimensions reviewed): mark hard_stop_reason = \"all_dimensions_clean\" and promote to STOP candidate\n581:              Operator stop reasons (`maxIterationsReached`, `manualStop`, `userPaused`, unrecoverable `error`) are terminal ceilings. They do not hide failed gates; they record them in synthesis and stop dispatch.\n582:           2. STUCK DETECTION (threshold 2):\n583:              if stuck_count >= 2: STUCK_RECOVERY\n584:           3. GRAPH CONVERGENCE PREREQUISITE:\n585:                graph_decision, graph_signals_json, and graph_blockers_json are already populated by step_graph_convergence.\n586:                Final STOP is never legal unless the inline review vote says STOP AND graph_decision == \"STOP_ALLOWED\".\n587:                If graph_decision == \"STOP_BLOCKED\", set stop_blocked = true and route through blocked_stop emission instead of stopping.\n588:           4. COMPOSITE CONVERGENCE (3-signal weighted vote with split thresholds):\n589:                signals = []\n590:                a) Rolling average (w=0.30, window=2, needs 2+ iterations):\n591:                   avg = mean(last 2 newFindingsRatios)\n592:                   stop if avg <= 0.08\n593:                b) MAD noise floor (w=0.25, needs 3+ iterations):\n594:                   noiseFloor = MAD(all ratios) * 1.4826\n595:                   stop if latest ratio <= noiseFloor\n596:                c) Dimension coverage (w=0.45):\n597:                   coverage = dimensions_covered / total_dimensions\n598:                   stop if coverage >= 1.0 AND required traceability protocols are covered AND coverage_age >= 1\n599:                Redistribute weights for unavailable signals.\n600:                if latest ratio <= 0.05: mark no_progress_threshold_reached\n601:                if stop_policy == \"max-iterations\" AND iteration_count < max_iterations: convergence votes are telemetry only; set weighted_stop_score for diagnostics, keep decision = \"CONTINUE\", and choose a broader next focus.\n602:                else if weighted_stop_score >= 0.60: inline STOP becomes a candidate and binary gates must run\n603:           5. LEGAL-STOP DECISION TREE (review-specific gates; runs whenever step 0, all-dimensions-clean, or the composite vote promotes STOP to a candidate; terminal max-iteration/manual/error stops bypass veto and record failed gates as evidence):\n604:                a) convergenceGate: pass when a hard-stop condition is met OR weighted_stop_score >= 0.60; record score\n605:                b) dimensionCoverageGate: pass when configured dimensions and required traceability coverage are complete and coverage_age >= 1; record covered and missing dimensions\n606:                c) p0ResolutionGate: pass when activeP0 == 0; record activeP0\n607:                d) evidenceDensityGate: pass when every active P0/P1 has concrete file:line evidence and no active P0/P1 relies only on inference; record avgEvidencePerFinding\n608:                e) hotspotSaturationGate: pass when review hotspots have been revisited enough times to satisfy the saturation heuristic\n609:                f) claimAdjudicationGate: pass when claim_adjudication_gate_pass == true (i.e. last_claim_adjudication_passed != false OR there are no active P0/P1 findings to adjudicate); record last_claim_adjudication_passed and claim_adjudication_active_count\n610:                g) fixCompletenessReplayGate: pass when security_sensitive_fix_scope == false OR every required closed-gate replay row passes with file:line or command evidence and producer/consumer/matrix coverage; record security_sensitive_fix_scope, fix_completeness_replay_required_rows, and fix_completeness_replay_passing_rows\n611:                h) candidateCoverageGate: skip entirely when `reviewDepthSchemaVersion` is not 2 on the latest iteration. Otherwise pass when the current iteration's `reviewDepthApplicability.scopeClass` is `trivial` with `enforcement: \"skip\"` AND `reviewDepthApplicability.evidenceRefs` is non-empty, OR when the reducer registry's `searchDebt` is empty AND `candidateCoverage.covered` is a superset of `searchCoverage.requiredBugClasses` for the lineage. Otherwise pass = false; record `searchDebt` items as blocked-stop evidence; blocker name = \"candidateCoverageGate\"; recovery_strategy = \"Resolve deferred/blocked obligations in next iteration or downgrade scope explicitly to trivial with cited evidence.\"\n612:                i) graphlessFallbackGate: skip when `reviewDepthSchemaVersion` is not 2 OR the reducer registry's last-iteration `searchCoverage.graphCoverageMode` is `graph`. Applies when graphCoverageMode is `graphless_fallback` or `unavailable_blocked`. Pass when graphCoverageMode is `graphless_fallback` AND at least one `searchLedger` row exists for each entry in `searchCoverage.requiredBugClasses` with `searchActions[].method` in {\"direct_read\",\"exact_grep\",\"semantic_search\",\"code_graph_status_check\",\"producer_consumer_trace\",\"negative_test_inspection\"} AND non-empty `evidenceRefs`. Fail automatically when graphCoverageMode is `unavailable_blocked`; record the explicit unavailability reason. Otherwise pass = false; blocker name = \"graphlessFallbackGate\"; recovery_strategy = \"Add cited fallback ledger rows (direct read, exact search, producer/consumer trace, negative-test inspection) or set graphCoverageMode to 'graph' once graph data is available.\"\n613:              if STOP is a candidate and any gate fails:\n614:                decision = \"BLOCKED\"\n615:                stop_blocked = true\n616:                stopReason = \"blockedStop\"\n617:                blocked_by_json = JSON array of failing gate names (always include \"claimAdjudicationGate\" when claim_adjudication_gate_pass == false, \"fixCompletenessReplayGate\" when fix_completeness_replay_gate_pass == false, \"candidateCoverageGate\" when candidate_coverage_gate_pass == false, and \"graphlessFallbackGate\" when graphless_fallback_gate_pass == false)\n618:                blocked_by_csv = comma-separated list of failing gate names\n619:                convergence_gate_pass = boolean\n620:                convergence_gate_score = numeric convergence score\n621:                dimension_coverage_gate_pass = boolean\n622:                dimension_coverage_gate_covered_json = JSON array of covered review dimensions\n623:                dimension_coverage_gate_missing_json = JSON array of missing review dimensions\n624:                p0_resolution_gate_pass = boolean\n625:                active_p0_count = number of active P0 findings\n626:                evidence_density_gate_pass = boolean\n627:                avg_evidence_per_finding = numeric evidence density\n628:                hotspot_saturation_gate_pass = boolean\n629:                claim_adjudication_gate_pass = boolean\n630:                claim_adjudication_active_count = numeric count of active P0/P1 at the gate\n631:                fix_completeness_replay_gate_pass = boolean\n632:                security_sensitive_fix_scope = boolean\n633:                fix_completeness_replay_required_rows = numeric count of closed-gate replay rows required for security-sensitive fix reruns\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-633. Use offset=634 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# DEEP REVIEW: AUTONOMOUS DEEP REVIEW LOOP (AUTO MODE)\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# DEEP REVIEW: AUTONOMOUS DEEP REVIEW LOOP (AUTO MODE)\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nrole: Deep Review Loop Manager\npurpose: Iterative code/spec review with convergence detection across review dimensions\naction: Run deep-review loop from initialization through synthesis\noperating_mode:\n  workflow: iterative_loop\n  workflow_compliance: MANDATORY\n  workflow_execution: autonomous\n  approvals: none\n  tracking: progressive_review_state\n  validation: convergence_detection\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# OPERATING PRINCIPLES\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\noperating_principles:","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml","text":"# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# DEEP REVIEW: AUTONOMOUS DEEP REVIEW LOOP (AUTO MODE)\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# DEEP REVIEW: AUTONOMOUS DEEP REVIEW LOOP (AUTO MODE)\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nrole: Deep Review Loop Manager\npurpose: Iterative code/spec review with convergence detection across review dimensions\naction: Run deep-review loop from initialization through synthesis\noperating_mode:\n  workflow: iterative_loop\n  workflow_compliance: MANDATORY\n  workflow_execution: autonomous\n  approvals: none\n  tracking: progressive_review_state\n  validation: convergence_detection\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# OPERATING PRINCIPLES\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\noperating_principles:\n  core: \"Fresh context per iteration + externalized state = no context degradation\"\n  approach: \"Dispatch focused review agent per dimension, evaluate convergence, repeat or stop\"\n  mandate: \"Never hold findings in memory; write everything to files. Review target is READ-ONLY.\"\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# USER INPUTS (from setup phase)\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nuser_inputs:\n  review_target: \"[REVIEW_TARGET] - What to review. REQUIRED.\"\n  review_target_type: \"[spec-folder|skill|agent|track|files] - Target type for scope derivation. REQUIRED.\"\n  review_dimensions: \"[all|correctness,security,traceability,maintainability] - Dimensions to check. Default: all.\"\n  spec_folder: \"[SPEC_FOLDER] - Spec folder path for state files. REQUIRED.\"\n  session_id: \"[SESSION_ID] - Optional caller-supplied session id for fan-out lineages. Default: timestamp.\"\n  lineage_mode: \"[auto|resume|restart] - Session lifecycle intent. Default: auto. The runtime only persists lineage events for `resume` (same sessionId, no archive) and `restart` (new sessionId, generation+1, prior review/ archived). `fork` and `completed-continue` are deferred and no longer accepted — see deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md §Lifecycle Branches.\"\n  max_iterations: 7\n  convergence_threshold: 0.10\n  convergence_mode: \"[default|off|sliding-window|divergent] - Convergence policy modifier. Default: default.\"\n  stop_policy: \"[convergence|max-iterations] - Stop behavior. Default: convergence. max-iterations treats convergence as telemetry until the hard iteration ceiling.\"\n  config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir: \"[optional internal path] - Fan-out lineage artifact override for command-owned single-lineage execution.\"\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# CONTEXT LOADING\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\ncontext_loading:\n  trigger: \"At workflow START, before phase_init\"\n  purpose: \"Load prior review context for the target and buffer it until strategy.md exists\"\n  mcp_integration:\n    tool: memory_context\n    note: \"Call MCP tools directly - NEVER through Code Mode\"\n    parameters: { input: \"{review_target}\", mode: \"focused\", intent: \"understand\", includeContent: true }\n  when_to_skip: [\"User says 'skip context' or 'fresh start'\"]\n  behavior:\n    if_context_found: \"Store full results as prior_context plus a concise prior_context_summary; inject after strategy.md is created.\"\n    if_no_context: \"Set prior_context and prior_context_summary to 'None' and continue.\"\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# SKILL REFERENCE\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nskill_reference:\n  skill: system-deep-loop\n  skill_md: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/SKILL.md\n  references:\n    loop_protocol: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md\n    state_format: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/state/state_format.md\n    convergence: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/convergence/convergence.md\n  templates:\n    config: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_config.json\n    strategy: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_strategy.md\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# AGENT CONFIGURATION\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nagent_config:\n  agent: deep-review\n  agent_file: \".opencode/agents/deep-review.md\"\n  # Canonical path. Runtime-specific directories (e.g. .claude/agents/) reference this source.\n  mode: subagent\n  model: opus\n  leaf_only: true\n  tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\n  mcp_servers: [mk-spec-memory]\n  tool_call_budget: { target: 9, soft_max: 12, hard_max: 13 }\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# STATE FILE PATHS\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nstate_paths:\n  # Template paths document the canonical packet layout. Runtime resolution happens via\n  # step_resolve_artifact_root plus the shared resolver, so root specs keep\n  # root-local review/ and child phases keep local review/ packet dirs.\n  # Canonical root-spec write targets remain review/deep-review-config.json,\n  # review/deep-review-state.jsonl, and review/deep-review-findings-registry.json.\n  packet_dir: \"{artifact_dir}\"\n  local_packet_dir: \"{spec_folder}/review\"\n  legacy_root_report: \"{spec_folder}/review-report.md\"\n  config: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json\"\n  state_log: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl\"\n  findings_registry: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json\"\n  strategy: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md\"\n  dashboard: \"{artifact_dir}/deep-review-dashboard.md\"\n  pause_sentinel: \"{artifact_dir}/.deep-review-pause\"\n  lock_file: \"{artifact_dir}/.deep-review.lock\"\n  prompt_dir: \"{artifact_dir}/prompts\"\n  iteration_dir: \"{artifact_dir}/iterations\"\n  iteration_pattern: \"{artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md\"\n  # Per-iteration structured delta stream — complement to the canonical state_log\n  # append. MUST contain at least one record with `type === \"iteration\"`; variants\n  # like `\"iteration_delta\"` are silently dropped by the reducer.\n  delta_dir: \"{artifact_dir}/deltas\"\n  delta_pattern: \"{artifact_dir}/deltas/iter-{NNN}.jsonl\"\n  review_output: \"{artifact_dir}/review-report.md\"\n  resource_map_output: \"{artifact_dir}/resource-map.md\"\n  archive_root: \"{artifact_archive_root}\"\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# WORKFLOW\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nworkflow:\n\n  step_resolve_artifact_root:\n    description: \"Resolve artifact directory — use fan-out lineage override when provided, else resolve from spec_folder\"\n    note: \"Root specs keep review artifacts directly in {spec_folder}/review/. Child phases and sub-phases keep local packet directories in {spec_folder}/review/{packet}/, and archives stay local at {spec_folder}/review_archive/{packet}/.\"\n    branch_on: \"config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir\"\n    if_present:\n      bind:\n        artifact_dir: \"{config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir}\"\n        artifact_root_dir: \"{config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir}\"\n        artifact_subfolder: null\n        artifact_archive_root: \"{config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir}/_archive\"\n    if_absent:\n      command: \"node -e \\\"const { resolveArtifactRoot } = require('.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs'); console.log(JSON.stringify(resolveArtifactRoot('{spec_folder}', 'review')));\\\"\"\n      outputs:\n        - artifact_root_dir: \"Resolved local review owner directory\"\n        - artifact_subfolder: \"Local packet subfolder ({ownerSlug}-pt-{NN}), else null\"\n        - artifact_dir: \"Resolved review packet directory for this target\"\n        - artifact_archive_root: \"Resolved local review archive directory for this target\"\n\n  step_apply_lifecycle_request:\n    description: \"Honor explicit auto-mode restart before fan-out or normal initialization\"\n    skip_when: \"lineage_mode != 'restart'\"\n    instructions: |\n      This is the autonomous equivalent of the confirm-mode restart choice. Run it\n      immediately after artifact resolution and before fan-out so old packet files\n      cannot be merged with fresh lineage outputs. A restart request must never\n      fall back to auto-resume. In auto mode, the explicit restart flag is operator\n      authorization to archive the resolved review packet, so do not ask for a\n      second confirmation. Rollback is to move the timestamped archive back to\n      the packet directory.\n    command: \"if [ -d \\\"{state_paths.packet_dir}\\\" ]; then mkdir -p \\\"{state_paths.archive_root}\\\" && mv \\\"{state_paths.packet_dir}\\\" \\\"{state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug}\\\"; fi; mkdir -p \\\"{state_paths.packet_dir}\\\"\"\n    outputs:\n      - archived_path: \"{state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug} when a prior packet existed, else null\"\n      - lineage_mode: \"restart\"\n    on_fail: \"Halt with STATUS=FAIL; do not continue as resume or auto.\"\n\n  step_fanout_spawn:\n    description: \"Spawn fan-out lineages; skip and proceed to phase_init normally when single-executor\"\n    skip_when: \"config.fanout is absent\"\n    instructions: |\n      Fan-out mode is active. Spawn all lineages. Each lineage runs the full loop in its own\n      isolated sub-packet under {artifact_dir}/lineages/{label}/.\n      A cli-opencode lineage inside this fan-out is an explicit parallel-detached OpenCode\n      session with a separate lineage directory and session id; it is not the single-executor\n      self-invocation path. fanout-run.cjs owns the stack-only recursion guard for that\n      first-level detached lineage and still blocks recursive same-kind dispatch from inside it.\n      fanout-run.cjs owns native and CLI lineage execution; native is run through the\n      deep/review command surface with config.fanout_lineage_artifact_dir so the LEAF\n      deep-review agent is used only for individual iterations, never as a full-loop\n      sub-agent or pasted phase-running prompt.\n      After all lineages complete, jump directly to phase_synthesis — skip phase_init and\n      phase_main_loop entirely (those are the single-executor path). The merge step in\n      phase_synthesis will consolidate results across all lineages.\n    sub_steps:\n      step_fanout_spawn_cli:\n        description: \"Spawn all native and CLI lineages in capped worker pool\"\n        skip_when: \"no entries in config.fanout.executors\"\n        command: |\n          node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/fanout-run.cjs \\\n            --spec-folder {spec_folder} \\\n            --loop-type review \\\n            --fanout-config-json '{config.fanout_json}' \\\n            --base-artifact-dir {artifact_dir} \\\n            --convergence-threshold {convergence_threshold} \\\n            --stop-policy {stop_policy}\n        working_directory: \"{repo_root}\"\n        wait_for_completion: true\n\n  # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n  # PHASE 1: INITIALIZATION\n  # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n  phase_init:\n    purpose: Create all state files for the review session and resolve review scope\n    steps:\n\n      step_preflight_contract:\n        action: \"Validate required setup bindings and executable workflow contract before any file writes\"\n        verify:\n          - required_values_present: [review_target, review_target_type, review_dimensions, spec_folder, lineage_mode, max_iterations, convergence_threshold, convergence_mode, stop_policy]\n          - spec_folder_is_within: \"specs/ or .opencode/specs/ (canonicalize alias roots before validation)\"\n          - unresolved_placeholders: \"FAIL if any user-facing template references placeholders not produced by earlier steps\"\n          - tool_contract: \"FAIL if executable steps reference tools outside the command allowlist\"\n        on_fail: \"Halt with STATUS=FAIL and report the missing binding or unsupported contract reference\"\n\n      step_create_directories:\n        action: \"Create spec folder and canonical review packet directories if they don't exist\"\n        command: \"mkdir -p {state_paths.prompt_dir} {state_paths.iteration_dir} {state_paths.delta_dir}\"\n\n      step_detect_resource_map:\n        action: \"Detect resource-map.md before config creation so init can persist coverage-gate state\"\n        inspect:\n          - \"{spec_folder}/resource-map.md\"\n        classify:\n          present: \"resource-map.md exists at init\"\n          absent: \"resource-map.md does not exist at init\"\n        outputs:\n          - resource_map_present: \"Boolean true when {spec_folder}/resource-map.md exists, else false\"\n          - resource_map_known_context: \"When present: concise resource-map snapshot for Known Context and charter framing. When absent: 'resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate'.\"\n\n      step_migrate_legacy_review_state:\n        action: \"Rehome legacy review artifacts into review/iterations before session classification\"\n        detect:\n          canonical_review_state:\n            - \"{state_paths.config}\"\n            - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n            - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n            - \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n          legacy_review_state:\n            - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json\"\n            - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl\"\n            - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md\"\n            - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md\"\n            - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/iteration-*.md\"\n            - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause\"\n            - \"{state_paths.local_packet_dir}/iteration-*.md\"\n            - \"{state_paths.legacy_root_report}\"\n          legacy_review_markers:\n            - \"scratch/deep-review-strategy.md exists\"\n            - \"scratch/deep-research-config.json declares mode == 'review' OR scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl contains mode == 'review'\"\n        migrate_only:\n          - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json -> {state_paths.config}\"\n          - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl -> {state_paths.state_log}\"\n          - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md -> {state_paths.strategy}\"\n          - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md -> {state_paths.dashboard}\"\n          - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/iteration-*.md -> {state_paths.iteration_dir}/\"\n          - \"{spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause -> {state_paths.pause_sentinel}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.local_packet_dir}/iteration-*.md -> {state_paths.iteration_dir}/\"\n          - \"{state_paths.legacy_root_report} -> {state_paths.review_output}\"\n        on_canonical_present: \"Leave canonical review/ state untouched and do not overwrite it with legacy scratch artifacts.\"\n        on_legacy_detected: \"Move only the review-specific whitelist, append a migration event to the canonical JSONL, and leave unrelated scratch files untouched.\"\n        on_conflict: \"If canonical review/ state and legacy scratch review state both exist but disagree, halt for operator repair instead of merging contradictory state.\"\n        command: \"mkdir -p {state_paths.iteration_dir} && if [ ! -e {state_paths.config} ] && [ ! -e {state_paths.state_log} ] && [ ! -e {state_paths.strategy} ] && [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md ] && ( [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json ] || [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl ] ); then [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-config.json {state_paths.config}; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-research-state.jsonl {state_paths.state_log}; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-strategy.md {state_paths.strategy}; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/deep-review-dashboard.md {state_paths.dashboard}; find {spec_folder}/scratch -maxdepth 1 -name 'iteration-*.md' -exec mv {} {state_paths.iteration_dir}/ \\\\; ; [ -e {spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause ] && mv {spec_folder}/scratch/.deep-research-pause {state_paths.pause_sentinel}; [ -e {state_paths.legacy_root_report} ] && mv {state_paths.legacy_root_report} {state_paths.review_output}; if [ -e {state_paths.state_log} ]; then printf '%s\\n' '{\\\"type\\\":\\\"event\\\",\\\"event\\\":\\\"migration\\\",\\\"mode\\\":\\\"review\\\",\\\"legacyArtifacts\\\":[\\\"deep-research-config.json\\\",\\\"deep-research-state.jsonl\\\",\\\".deep-research-pause\\\"],\\\"canonicalArtifacts\\\":[\\\"deep-review-config.json\\\",\\\"deep-review-state.jsonl\\\",\\\".deep-review-pause\\\"],\\\"timestamp\\\":\\\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\\\"}' >> {state_paths.state_log}; fi; fi; find {state_paths.local_packet_dir} -maxdepth 1 -name 'iteration-*.md' -exec mv {} {state_paths.iteration_dir}/ \\\\; 2>/dev/null || true\"\n\n      step_acquire_lock:\n        action: \"Acquire the single-writer advisory lock before session classification\"\n        command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs acquire --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --packet-id {spec_folder}\"\n        on_acquire: \"Capture ownerPid from the JSON output and reuse it for every release below. If acquired=false, fail closed — another deep-review run already holds this packet.\"\n        note: \"Uses the promoted runtime/ loop-lock CLI (single source of truth: stale-lock reclaim, clean owner-scoped release). macOS/BSD locking is advisory — best-effort single-writer, not a hard mutex across host calls; stale-lock override is confirm-only or explicit recovery-only.\"\n        # Lock-cleanup contract: the lock file MUST be released on every terminal exit path that follows acquisition.\n        # Runtimes honoring step_acquire_lock are required to perform this cleanup before halting or pausing.\n        on_halt:\n          action: \"Release the lock before any terminal halt branch returns control\"\n          applies_to: [\"step_classify_session.on_invalid_state\", \"step_classify_session.on_completed_session\"]\n          command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs release --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --owner-pid {captured_owner_pid}; failures here are logged but do not block the halt\"\n        on_cancel:\n          action: \"Release the lock on user cancel or pause-sentinel detection before sentinel processing\"\n          command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs release --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --owner-pid {captured_owner_pid}; cancel completes regardless of cleanup result\"\n        on_workflow_exit:\n          action: \"Release the lock as the final step of any workflow exit path (success or failure)\"\n          command: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/loop-lock.cjs release --lock-path {state_paths.lock_file} --owner-pid {captured_owner_pid}; idempotent — safe to invoke when already released\"\n\n      step_classify_session:\n        action: \"Classify the session before writing files\"\n        inspect:\n          - \"{state_paths.config}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n        classify:\n          fresh: \"None of the three state artifacts exist\"\n          resume: \"Config, JSONL, and strategy all exist and config.mode == 'review' and agree on target/spec folder\"\n          completed-session: \"Resume artifacts exist and config.status == 'complete'\"\n          invalid-state: \"Any partial, missing, or contradictory combination\"\n        outputs:\n          - session_state: \"fresh | resume | completed-session | invalid-state\"\n        lifecycle_routing:\n          - \"If lineage_mode == restart and session_state is resume or completed-session, execute on_restart before on_resume or on_completed_session.\"\n          - \"If lineage_mode == auto or lineage_mode == resume, preserve the existing resume/completed/fresh behavior.\"\n        on_resume:\n          log: \"Auto-resume: state artifacts are complete and consistent. Continue the same lineage (sessionId unchanged, generation unchanged, no archive).\"\n          append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"parentSessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"lineageMode\":\"resume\",\"continuedFromRun\":{iteration_count},\"generation\":{generation},\"archivedPath\":null,\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"}'\n          skip_to: phase_loop\n        on_restart:\n          action: \"Archive the current review packet under the root-level review_archive/ tree and start a new lineage segment with a fresh sessionId and generation+1.\"\n          command: \"if [ -d {state_paths.packet_dir} ]; then mkdir -p {state_paths.archive_root} && mv {state_paths.packet_dir} {state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug}; fi\"\n          set:\n            lineage_mode: \"restart\"\n            parent_session_id: \"{prior_session_id}\"\n            generation: \"{prior_generation + 1}\"\n          append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"restarted\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"parentSessionId\":\"{prior_session_id}\",\"lineageMode\":\"restart\",\"generation\":{generation},\"archivedPath\":\"{state_paths.archive_root}/{timestamp_slug}\",\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"}'\n          skip_to: step_create_config\n        note_deferred_branches: \"fork and completed-continue are deferred and no longer runtime-supported in this release. The reducer still reads `lineageMode` from config for dashboards and analysis, but only `new`, `resume`, and `restart` are live. See deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md §Lifecycle Branches for the one-session contract.\"\n        on_completed_session:\n          log: \"Prior session already completed. Either archive the completed review/ tree and start a fresh session, or jump straight to synthesis with the existing artifacts.\"\n          skip_to: phase_synthesis\n        on_invalid_state:\n          halt: true\n          message: \"Existing deep-review state in review/ is incomplete or contradictory. Repair or archive the invalid review packet before continuing.\"\n        on_fresh:\n          action: \"Proceed with a new session\"\n\n      step_scope_discovery:\n        action: \"Resolve review target to a concrete file list based on target type\"\n        resolve:\n          spec-folder: |\n            1. Read spec.md, plan.md, tasks.md, checklist.md, implementation-summary.md\n            2. Discover implementation files referenced in spec artifacts\n            3. Discover test files associated with implementation\n            4. Set scope = all discovered files\n          skill: |\n            1. Read SKILL.md from .opencode/skills/{skill_name}/\n            2. Discover references/, assets/, scripts/ contents\n            3. Find agent definitions referencing this skill across runtimes\n            4. Find command entry points referencing this skill\n            5. Set scope = all discovered files\n          agent: |\n            1. Find agent definition across repo-managed runtimes (.claude/agents/, .opencode/agents/)\n            2. Compare agent definitions for consistency\n            3. Set scope = all discovered agent files\n          track: |\n            1. List all child spec folders under specs/{track}/ or .opencode/specs/{track}/\n            2. For each: read spec.md + checklist.md\n            3. Set scope = all child spec artifacts\n          files: |\n            1. Expand glob patterns from review_target\n            2. Validate all files exist\n            3. Discover immediate cross-references (imports, links)\n            4. Set scope = expanded file list + cross-references\n        outputs:\n          - review_scope_files: \"List of all files in review scope\"\n          - cross_reference_targets: \"{ spec_paths: [...], code_paths: [...], test_paths: [...] }\"\n\n      step_order_dimensions:\n        action: \"Order review dimensions based on risk priority\"\n        algorithm: |\n          1. Iteration 0 (inventory pass): Build artifact map, identify file types, estimate complexity\n          2. Subsequent iterations follow risk-ordered deep passes:\n             correctness → security → traceability → maintainability\n          3. If review_dimensions != \"all\", filter to only requested dimensions\n          4. Derive traceability protocol plan:\n             - core: spec_code, checklist_evidence\n             - overlay: skill_agent, agent_cross_runtime, feature_catalog_code, playbook_capability\n          5. If resource_map_present, reserve at least one traceability-oriented pass to cross-check target_files from applied/T-*.md against resource-map.md and classify touched / expected-by-scope / gap / absent-from-map outcomes\n          6. Store ordered list as dimension_queue\n        outputs:\n          - dimension_queue: \"Ordered list of dimensions to review\"\n          - inventory_pass: true\n\n      step_normalize_review_dimensions:\n        action: \"Normalize reviewDimensions once during init for config + JSONL reuse\"\n        outputs:\n          - review_dimensions_normalized: \"Canonical string[] for deep-review-config.json\"\n          - review_dimensions_json: \"JSON.stringify(review_dimensions_normalized) for JSONL config record\"\n        normalize: |\n          Accept {review_dimensions} in any of these shapes and convert once:\n            - \"all\" → [\"correctness\",\"security\",\"traceability\",\"maintainability\"]\n            - \"correctness,security\" → [\"correctness\",\"security\"]\n            - [\"correctness\"] → [\"correctness\"]\n          Every element MUST be one of the four canonical dimension names.\n\n      step_resolve_session_id:\n        action: \"Resolve init session id from caller when supplied, else preserve timestamp fallback\"\n        branch_on: \"session_id\"\n        if_present:\n          bind:\n            session_id_init: \"{session_id}\"\n        if_absent:\n          bind:\n            session_id_init: \"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"\n\n      step_create_config:\n        action: \"Create deep-review-config.json from template with review-specific fields\"\n        template: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_config.json\n        populate:\n          topic: \"Review: {review_target}\"\n          mode: \"review\"\n          sessionId: \"{session_id_init}\"\n          parentSessionId: null\n          lineageMode: \"new\"\n          generation: 1\n          continuedFromRun: null\n          reviewTarget: \"{review_target}\"\n          reviewTargetType: \"{review_target_type}\"\n          # Reuse the single normalized init-time value from step_normalize_review_dimensions.\n          reviewDimensions: \"{review_dimensions_normalized}\"\n          resource_map_present: \"{resource_map_present}\"\n          reviewScopeFiles: \"{review_scope_files}\"\n          severityThreshold: \"P2\"\n          crossReference:\n            core: [\"spec_code\", \"checklist_evidence\"]\n            overlay: [\"skill_agent\", \"agent_cross_runtime\", \"feature_catalog_code\", \"playbook_capability\"]\n          maxIterations: \"{max_iterations}\"\n          # Semantic: weighted P0/P1/P2 severity ratio. See SKILL.md §\"Convergence Threshold Semantics\".\n          convergenceThreshold: \"{convergence_threshold}\"\n          antiConvergence.convergenceMode: \"{convergence_mode}\"\n          antiConvergence.divergent: {}\n          stopPolicy: \"{stop_policy}\"\n          stuckThreshold: 2\n          maxDurationMinutes: 120\n          specFolder: \"{spec_folder}\"\n          # Honor the parsed --no-resource-map flag from deep-review.md:71 (default true; false when flag is set).\n          # The markdown command parses $ARGUMENTS and binds {resource_map_emit} before this step runs.\n          resource_map.emit: \"{resource_map_emit}\"\n          createdAt: \"{ISO_8601_NOW}\"\n          status: \"initialized\"\n          releaseReadinessState: \"in-progress\"\n          executionMode: \"auto\"\n        output: \"{state_paths.config}\"\n\n      step_create_state_log:\n        action: \"Initialize JSONL state log with config record including review fields and lineage metadata\"\n        note: \"Reuse review_dimensions_json from step_normalize_review_dimensions. Never re-normalize or wrap the raw template value.\"\n        # Same parsed --no-resource-map flag honored here so config and state_log agree from line 1.\n        content: '{\"type\":\"config\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"reviewTarget\":\"{review_target}\",\"reviewTargetType\":\"{review_target_type}\",\"reviewDimensions\":{review_dimensions_json},\"resource_map_present\":{resource_map_present},\"resource_map\":{\"emit\":{resource_map_emit}},\"sessionId\":\"{session_id_init}\",\"parentSessionId\":null,\"lineageMode\":\"new\",\"generation\":1,\"continuedFromRun\":null,\"maxIterations\":{max_iterations},\"convergenceThreshold\":{convergence_threshold},\"antiConvergence\":{\"convergenceMode\":\"{convergence_mode}\",\"divergent\":{}},\"stopPolicy\":\"{stop_policy}\",\"createdAt\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\",\"specFolder\":\"{spec_folder}\"}'\n        output: \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n\n      step_create_findings_registry:\n        action: \"Initialize reducer-owned review findings registry\"\n        content: '{\"sessionId\":\"{session_id_init}\",\"generation\":1,\"lineageMode\":\"new\",\"openFindings\":[],\"resolvedFindings\":[],\"repeatedFindings\":[],\"dimensionCoverage\":{\"correctness\":false,\"security\":false,\"traceability\":false,\"maintainability\":false},\"findingsBySeverity\":{\"P0\":0,\"P1\":0,\"P2\":0},\"openFindingsCount\":0,\"resolvedFindingsCount\":0,\"convergenceScore\":0.0}'\n        output: \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n\n      step_create_strategy:\n        action: \"Create review strategy file from deep_review_strategy.md template\"\n        template: .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/assets/deep_review_strategy.md\n        populate:\n          review_target: \"{review_target}\"\n          review_target_type: \"{review_target_type}\"\n          dimensions: \"{dimension_queue}\"\n          scope_files: \"{review_scope_files}\"\n          cross_reference_targets: \"{cross_reference_targets}\"\n          max_iterations: \"{max_iterations}\"\n          convergence_threshold: \"{convergence_threshold}\"\n          stop_policy: \"{stop_policy}\"\n        output: \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n\n      step_seed_coverage_graph:\n        action: \"Seed the review coverage graph before the first convergence check\"\n        transform: |\n          1. Convert review_scope_files into FILE nodes.\n          2. Convert review target groupings into coarse SLICE nodes only; do not expand SYMBOL\n             or DEPENDENCY nodes in review mode.\n          3. Emit COVERS edges from SLICE nodes to FILE nodes when the grouping is known.\n          4. Bind coverage_seed_source to \"scope_discovery\" and coverage_seed_confidence to 0.50.\n          5. When scope discovery yields no files, emit [] for both arrays; the upsert script\n             returns a warning and review continues with an empty graph.\n        bash: \"node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/upsert.cjs --spec-folder \\\"{spec_folder}\\\" --loop-type \\\"review\\\" --session-id \\\"{config.sessionId}\\\" --nodes '{coverage_seed_nodes_json}' --edges '{coverage_seed_edges_json}' --seed-source \\\"{coverage_seed_source}\\\" --seed-confidence \\\"{coverage_seed_confidence}\\\"\"\n        outputs:\n          - coverage_seed_nodes_json: \"Seed nodes for review SLICE and FILE kinds only\"\n          - coverage_seed_edges_json: \"Seed COVERS edges where review target groupings resolved\"\n          - coverage_seed_warning: \"Warning emitted when the seed batch inserts zero nodes, else empty\"\n        on_warning:\n          log: \"Coverage graph seed inserted zero nodes; continuing with an empty graph.\"\n          proceed: true\n\n      step_enrich_strategy_context:\n        action: \"Ensure Known Context is written only after strategy.md exists\"\n        condition: \"prior_context_found\"\n        edit: \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n        note: \"Append or replace the Known Context section with prior_context_summary and retained detail from prior_context\"\n\n      step_enrich_strategy_resource_map:\n        action: \"Inject resource-map status into Known Context after strategy.md exists\"\n        edit: \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n        note: \"When resource_map_present is true, append the resource_map_known_context snapshot and add Resource Map Coverage to the Review Charter. When false, append 'resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate'.\"\n\n      step_init_complete:\n        log: \"Initialization complete. Config, state, and strategy files created. Review scope: {review_scope_files_count} files, {dimension_queue_count} dimensions.\"\n        set: { current_iteration: 1, stuck_count: 0, p0_count: 0, p1_count: 0, p2_count: 0 }\n\n  # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n  # PHASE 2: ITERATION LOOP\n  # ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n  phase_loop:\n    purpose: Dispatch review agent iterations until convergence\n    repeat: true\n    max_repeats: \"{max_iterations}\"\n    steps:\n\n      step_read_state:\n        action: \"Read current state from JSONL, strategy, and config\"\n        read:\n          - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.strategy}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.config}\"\n        extract:\n          - iteration_count: \"Count lines where type === 'iteration'\"\n          - current_iteration: \"iteration_count + 1\"\n          - last_newFindingsRatio: \"Extract newFindingsRatio from last iteration record\"\n          - last_focus: \"Extract focus/dimension from latest iteration record, else 'none yet'\"\n          - ratio_prev: \"Extract newFindingsRatio from second-latest iteration record, else 'N/A'\"\n          - ratio_latest: \"Extract newFindingsRatio from latest iteration record, else 'N/A'\"\n          - next_dimension: \"Next uncovered dimension from dimension_queue in strategy.md\"\n          - dimensions_covered: \"List of dimensions already reviewed\"\n          - dimensions_remaining: \"List of dimensions not yet reviewed\"\n          - dimension_coverage: \"covered / total dimensions\"\n          - coverage_age: \"Iterations since dimension coverage last changed; require >= 1 before STOP\"\n          - p0_count: \"Count P0 findings across all iterations\"\n          - p1_count: \"Count P1 findings across all iterations\"\n          - p2_count: \"Count P2 findings across all iterations\"\n          - resource_map_present: \"Extract boolean from deep-review-config.json, default false\"\n          - resource_map_prompt_line: \"If resource_map_present is true, return 'Resource Map Coverage: cross-check target_files from {spec_folder}/applied/T-*.md against {spec_folder}/resource-map.md and classify only missed coverage as gaps.' Else return 'Resource Map Coverage: resource-map.md not present; skipping coverage gate.'\"\n          - session_id: \"Extract sessionId from deep-review-config.json\"\n          - generation: \"Extract generation from deep-review-config.json, else 1\"\n          - last_3_summaries: \"Summarize the latest 3 iteration records as 'run N: dimension (ratio, P0/P1/P2)'\"\n          - latest_status: \"Extract status from latest iteration record, else 'none yet'\"\n          - last_claim_adjudication_passed: \"Scan state.jsonl for the most recent `claim_adjudication` event; use its `passed` boolean. Default true when no event exists or when activeP0 + activeP1 == 0 (gate is vacuous without adjudicable findings).\"\n          - claim_adjudication_active_count: \"Count of active P0/P1 findings at the time of the last claim_adjudication event; 0 when none exist\"\n          - security_sensitive_fix_scope: \"Boolean true when the current review is a rerun after fixes involving security, path disclosure, auth/authz, sandboxing, env precedence, public schemas, persistence, or user-visible error payloads; derive from the latest review report, remediation notes, or planning packet when present, else false.\"\n          - fix_completeness_replay_required_rows: \"Count prior active or remediated P0/P1 findings, plus any prior security/path P2 findings, that require closed-gate replay before STOP.\"\n          - fix_completeness_replay_passing_rows: \"Count required replay rows marked PASS with file:line or command evidence and producer/consumer/matrix coverage.\"\n          - stop_policy: \"Extract stopPolicy from deep-review-config.json, default 'convergence'. Valid values: convergence, max-iterations.\"\n          - convergence_mode: \"Extract antiConvergence.convergenceMode when it is one of 'default', 'off', 'sliding-window', or 'divergent'; default to 'default'\"\n          - convergence_mode_warning: \"Boolean true when antiConvergence.convergenceMode is present with an unsupported value; use 'default'\"\n          - pivot_lineage: \"Summarize registry.divergence.completed and registry.divergence.overrides with pivot ids, source iterations, and selected review direction; else 'none yet'\"\n          - saturated_directions: \"List registry.divergence.saturatedDirections; else 'none yet'\"\n\n      step_check_pause_sentinel:\n        action: \"Check for pause sentinel file\"\n        check: \"Does {state_paths.pause_sentinel} exist?\"\n        if_exists:\n          set:\n            pending_stop_event: \"paused\"\n            pending_stop_reason: \"userPaused\"\n            pending_stop_detail: \"sentinel file detected\"\n          skip_to: step_normalize_pause_events\n        if_not_exists:\n          proceed: true\n\n      step_validate_convergence_config:\n        action: \"Validate convergence mode when loading config\"\n        if_convergence_mode_invalid:\n          append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"config_warning\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"field\":\"antiConvergence.convergenceMode\",\"fallback\":\"default\",\"message\":\"Unsupported convergenceMode; using default convergence behavior.\",\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"generation\":{generation}}'\n          log: \"Unsupported convergenceMode; using default convergence behavior.\"\n\n      step_graph_convergence:\n        action: \"Evaluate coverage-graph convergence before the inline review convergence vote\"\n        inspect:\n          - \"{state_paths.state_log}\"\n          - \"{state_paths.findings_registry}\"\n        transform: |\n          1. Call graph convergence on the current review lineage before the inline 3-signal vote.\n          2. Record the decision as one of CONTINUE, STOP_ALLOWED, STOP_BLOCKED.\n          3. Preserve raw graph signals and blockers for reducer rollup and blocked-stop evidence.\n          4. Normalize blockers to both JSON array and CSV forms for downstream stop handling.\n          5. Set graph_stop_blocked = true only when graph_decision == \"STOP_BLOCKED\".\n        bash: 'node .opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/convergence.cjs --spec-folder \"{spec_folder}\" --loop-type \"review\" --session-id \"{session_id}\" --convergence-mode \"{convergence_mode}\"'\n        note: \"Invoke the runtime script directly. Review-side graph convergence must run before the inline review stop vote.\"\n        append_jsonl: '{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"graph_convergence\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"run\":{current_iteration},\"decision\":\"{graph_decision}\",\"signals\":{graph_signals_json},\"blockers\":{graph_blockers_json},\"timestamp\":\"{ISO_8601_NOW}\",\"sessionId\":\"{session_id}\",\"generation\":{generation}}'\n        outputs:\n          - graph_decision: \"CONTINUE | STOP_ALLOWED | STOP_BLOCKED\"\n          - graph_signals_json: \"JSON object returned by convergence.cjs\"\n          - graph_blockers_json: \"JSON array of graph blockers when present, else []\"\n          - graph_blockers_csv: \"Comma-separated blocker summary when graph blocks STOP, else empty string\"\n          - graph_stop_blocked: \"Boolean true when graph_decision == STOP_BLOCKED\"\n\n      step_check_convergence:\n        action: \"Evaluate graph-assisted review stop conditions and the legal-stop decision tree\"\n        algorithm: |\n          0. CLAIM-ADJUDICATION PRE-CHECK (universal STOP veto; runs before hard stops and composite convergence):\n             claim_adjudication_gate_pass = (last_claim_adjudication_passed != false) OR (p0_count + p1_count == 0)\n             If claim_adjudication_gate_pass == false:\n               candidate_decision = \"BLOCKED\"\n               stop_blocked = true\n               stopReason = \"blockedStop\"\n               blocked_gates = [\"claimAdjudicationGate\"]\n               recovery_strategy = \"Reviewer must add typed claim-adjudication packets (claim, evidenceRefs, counterevidenceSought, alternativeExplanation, finalSeverity, confidence, downgradeTrigger) for every active P0/P1 finding before STOP is allowed.\"\n               Skip hard stops (1) and composite convergence (4); proceed directly to step 5 legal-stop decision-tree assembly so blocked_by_json, gate outputs, and the blocked_stop event still populate consistently.\n          1. HARD STOPS:\n             a) if iteration_count >= max_iterations: set decision = \"STOP\", stopReason = \"maxIterationsReached\", hard_stop_reason = \"max_iterations_reached\", preserve any failed legal-stop gates as terminal evidence, and proceed to synthesis without legal-stop veto\n             b) if stop_policy == \"max-iterations\" AND iteration_count < max_iterations: do not allow all-dimensions-clean or composite convergence to stop; treat convergence signals as telemetry, set decision = \"CONTINUE\", and broaden the next review angle.\n             c) if all dimensions clean AND required traceability protocols are covered AND p0_count == 0 AND p1_count == 0 AND coverage_age >= 1 AND all quality gates pass (evidence: every P0/P1 has file:line; scope: all findings within target; coverage: all dimensions reviewed): mark hard_stop_reason = \"all_dimensions_clean\" and promote to STOP candidate\n             Operator stop reasons (`maxIterationsReached`, `manualStop`, `userPaused`, unrecoverable `error`) are terminal ceilings. They do not hide failed gates; they record them in synthesis and stop dispatch.\n          2. STUCK DETECTION (threshold 2):\n             if stuck_count >= 2: STUCK_RECOVERY\n          3. GRAPH CONVERGENCE PREREQUISITE:\n               graph_decision, graph_signals_json, and graph_blockers_json are already populated by step_graph_convergence.\n               Final STOP is never legal unless the inline review vote says STOP AND graph_decision == \"STOP_ALLOWED\".\n               If graph_decision == \"STOP_BLOCKED\", set stop_blocked = true and route through blocked_stop emission instead of stopping.\n          4. COMPOSITE CONVERGENCE (3-signal weighted vote with split thresholds):\n               signals = []\n               a) Rolling average (w=0.30, window=2, needs 2+ iterations):\n                  avg = mean(last 2 newFindingsRatios)\n                  stop if avg <= 0.08\n               b) MAD noise floor (w=0.25, needs 3+ iterations):\n                  noiseFloor = MAD(all ratios) * 1.4826\n                  stop if latest ratio <= noiseFloor\n               c) Dimension coverage (w=0.45):\n                  coverage = dimensions_covered / total_dimensions\n                  stop if coverage >= 1.0 AND required traceability protocols are covered AND coverage_age >= 1\n               Redistribute weights for unavailable signals.\n               if latest ratio <= 0.05: mark no_progress_threshold_reached\n               if stop_policy == \"max-iterations\" AND iteration_count < max_iterations: convergence votes are telemetry only; set weighted_stop_score for diagnostics, keep decision = \"CONTINUE\", and choose a broader next focus.\n               else if weighted_stop_score >= 0.60: inline STOP becomes a candidate and binary gates must run\n          5. LEGAL-STOP DECISION TREE (review-specific gates; runs whenever step 0, all-dimensions-clean, or the composite vote promotes STOP to a candidate; terminal max-iteration/manual/error stops bypass veto and record failed gates as evidence):\n               a) convergenceGate: pass when a hard-stop condition is met OR weighted_stop_score >= 0.60; record score\n               b) dimensionCoverageGate: pass when configured dimensions and required traceability coverage are complete and coverage_age >= 1; record covered and missing dimensions\n               c) p0ResolutionGate: pass when activeP0 == 0; record activeP0\n               d) evidenceDensityGate: pass when every active P0/P1 has concrete file:line evidence and no active P0/P1 relies only on inference; record avgEvidencePerFinding\n               e) hotspotSaturationGate: pass when review hotspots have been revisited enough times to satisfy the saturation heuristic\n               f) claimAdjudicationGate: pass when claim_adjudication_gate_pass == true (i.e. last_claim_adjudication_passed != false OR there are no active P0/P1 findings to adjudicate); record last_claim_adjudication_passed and claim_adjudication_active_count\n               g) fixCompletenessReplayGate: pass when security_sensitive_fix_scope == false OR every required closed-gate replay row passes with file:line or command evidence and producer/consumer/matrix coverage; record security_sensitive_fix_scope, fix_completeness_replay_required_rows, and fix_completeness_replay_passing_rows\n               h) candidateCoverageGate: skip entirely when `reviewDepthSchemaVersion` is not 2 on the latest iteration. Otherwise pass when the current iteration's `reviewDepthApplicability.scopeClass` is `trivial` with `enforcement: \"skip\"` AND `reviewDepthApplicability.evidenceRefs` is non-empty, OR when the reducer registry's `searchDebt` is empty AND `candidateCoverage.covered` is a superset of `searchCoverage.requiredBugClasses` for the lineage. Otherwise pass = false; record `searchDebt` items as blocked-stop evidence; blocker name = \"candidateCoverageGate\"; recovery_strategy = \"Resolve deferred/blocked obligations in next iteration or downgrade scope explicitly to trivial with cited evidence.\"\n               i) graphlessFallbackGate: skip when `reviewDepthSchemaVersion` is not 2 OR the reducer registry's last-iteration `searchCoverage.graphCoverageMode` is `graph`. Applies when graphCoverageMode is `graphless_fallback` or `unavailable_blocked`. Pass when graphCoverageMode is `graphless_fallback` AND at least one `searchLedger` row exists for each entry in `searchCoverage.requiredBugClasses` with `searchActions[].method` in {\"direct_read\",\"exact_grep\",\"semantic_search\",\"code_graph_status_check\",\"producer_consumer_trace\",\"negative_test_inspection\"} AND non-empty `evidenceRefs`. Fail automatically when graphCoverageMode is `unavailable_blocked`; record the explicit unavailability reason. Otherwise pass = false; blocker name = \"graphlessFallbackGate\"; recovery_strategy = \"Add cited fallback ledger rows (direct read, exact search, producer/consumer trace, negative-test inspection) or set graphCoverageMode to 'graph' once graph data is available.\"\n             if STOP is a candidate and any gate fails:\n               decision = \"BLOCKED\"\n               stop_blocked = true\n               stopReason = \"blockedStop\"\n               blocked_by_json = JSON array of failing gate names (always include \"claimAdjudicationGate\" when claim_adjudication_gate_pass == false, \"fixCompletenessReplayGate\" when fix_completeness_replay_gate_pass == false, \"candidateCoverageGate\" when candidate_coverage_gate_pass == false, and \"graphlessFallbackGate\" when graphless_fallback_gate_pass == false)\n               blocked_by_csv = comma-separated list of failing gate names\n               convergence_gate_pass = boolean\n               convergence_gate_score = numeric convergence score\n               dimension_coverage_gate_pass = boolean\n               dimension_coverage_gate_covered_json = JSON array of covered review dimensions\n               dimension_coverage_gate_missing_json = JSON array of missing review dimensions\n               p0_resolution_gate_pass = boolean\n               active_p0_count = number of active P0 findings\n               evidence_density_gate_pass = boolean\n               avg_evidence_per_finding = numeric evidence density\n               hotspot_saturation_gate_pass = boolean\n               claim_adjudication_gate_pass = boolean\n               claim_adjudication_active_count = numeric count of active P0/P1 at the gate\n               fix_completeness_replay_gate_pass = boolean\n               security_sensitive_fix_scope = boolean\n               fix_completeness_replay_required_rows = numeric count of closed-gate replay rows required for security-sensitive fix reruns","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":633,"totalLines":634,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml","time":{"start":1783806723693,"end":1783806723699}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb03983c8191bdcdae95f2a97e61"}},"id":"prt_f532a863d001Eji95nt77ACyvP","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723727,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_L6hqyX5RSdYeCHwTZA0igoU0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/quick_reference.md","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/quick_reference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Review Quick Reference\n3: description: One-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep review loop.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"deep review quick reference\"\n6:   - \"review loop cheat sheet\"\n7:   - \"p0 p1 p2 severity ladder\"\n8:   - \"release readiness verdicts\"\n9:   - \"review loop troubleshooting\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: general\n12: version: 1.11.0.16\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Deep Review Quick Reference\n16: \n17: One-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep review loop.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Purpose\n24: \n25: Use this quick reference when you need the command shape, artifact names, convergence rules, and synthesis outputs for the autonomous deep-review loop without loading the full protocol references.\n26: \n27: ### When to Use\n28: \n29: - Looking up the canonical `/deep:review` invocation without re-reading the full SKILL.md.\n30: - Confirming default thresholds, verdicts, or release-readiness states at a glance.\n31: - Refreshing the artifact-name and packet-file checklist before a manual orchestration pass.\n32: - Triaging a stuck loop and need the fastest path to convergence semantics.\n33: \n34: ### Commands\n35: \n36: | Command | Description |\n37: |---------|-------------|\n38: | `/deep:review:auto \"target\"` | Run autonomous review (no approval gates) |\n39: | `/deep:review:confirm \"target\"` | Run review with approval gates at each iteration |\n40: | `/deep:review \"target\"` | Ask which mode to use |\n41: \n42: ### Parameters\n43: \n44: | Parameter | Default | Description |\n45: |-----------|---------|-------------|\n46: | `--max-iterations` | 7 | Maximum review iterations |\n47: | `--convergence` | 0.10 | Base sensitivity for review convergence |\n48: | `--stop-policy` | convergence | Use `max-iterations` when convergence must not end the run before the iteration ceiling |\n49: | `--spec-folder` | auto | Target spec folder path |\n50: | `--restart` | off | Archive the current review packet and start a fresh lineage |\n51: | `--severity-threshold` | P2 | Minimum severity to report |\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ## 2. WHEN TO USE\n56: \n57: | Scenario | Use |\n58: |----------|-----|\n59: | Multi-pass code quality audit | `/deep:review` |\n60: | Simple single-pass code review | `sk-code` (code-review mode) |\n61: | Pre-release readiness check | `/deep:review:auto \"spec folder\"` |\n62: | Spec/implementation alignment check | `/deep:review:auto \"skill sk-name\"` |\n63: | Deep technical investigation | `/deep:research` (different skill) |\n64: \n65: ---\n66: \n67: ## 3. ARCHITECTURE\n68: \n69: ```\n70: /deep:review  -->  YAML workflow  -->  @deep-review agent (LEAF)\n71:     |                    |                      |\n72:     |                    |                      +-- Read state\n73:     |                    |                      +-- Review (3-5 actions)\n74:     |                    |                      +-- Write findings (P0/P1/P2)\n75:     |                    |                      +-- Update state\n76:     |                    |\n77:     |                    +-- Init (config, strategy, state)\n78:     |                    +-- Loop (dispatch, evaluate, decide)\n79:     |                    +-- Synthesize (review-report.md)\n80:     |                    +-- Save (memory context)\n81: ```\n82: \n83: ---\n84: \n85: ## 4. STATE FILES\n86: \n87: Review mode stores its packet under the resolved local review path rooted at `{spec_folder}/review/`:\n88: \n89: | File | Location | Format | Purpose |\n90: |------|----------|--------|---------|\n91: | Config | `review/deep-review-config.json` | JSON | Review parameters (immutable) |\n92: | State | `review/deep-review-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Iteration log (append-only) |\n93: | Registry | `review/deep-review-findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned finding registry |\n94: | Strategy | `review/deep-review-strategy.md` | Markdown | Dimensions, findings, next focus |\n95: | Dashboard | `review/deep-review-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Auto-generated review dashboard |\n96: | Iterations | `review/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration findings (write-once) |\n97: | Report | `review/review-report.md` | Markdown | Final 9-section review report |\n98: | Pause | `review/.deep-review-pause` | Sentinel | Pause between iterations |\n99: \n100: ### Lifecycle Modes\n101: \n102: | Mode | Effect |\n103: |------|--------|\n104: | `resume` | Continue the current review lineage without resetting generation |\n105: | `restart` | Archive current review state and start a new generation |\n106: | `fork` (deferred) | Reserved. Start a sibling lineage branch with explicit parent linkage. Not runtime-wired. |\n107: | `completed-continue` (deferred) | Reserved. Snapshot the completed review and reopen it for amendment-only review deltas. Not runtime-wired. |\n108: \n109: ---\n110: \n111: ## 5. REVIEW DIMENSIONS\n112: \n113: | ID | Dimension | Priority | Description |\n114: |----|-----------|----------|-------------|\n115: | D1 | Correctness | 1 | Logic errors, off-by-one, wrong return types, broken invariants |\n116: | D2 | Security | 2 | Injection, auth bypass, secrets exposure, unsafe deserialization |\n117: | D3 | Traceability | 3 | Spec/code alignment, checklist evidence, cross-reference integrity |\n118: | D4 | Maintainability | 4 | Patterns, clarity, documentation quality, ease of safe follow-on changes |\n119: \n120: ---\n121: \n122: ## 6. REVIEW VERDICTS\n123: \n124: | Verdict | Condition | Meaning | Next Command |\n125: |---------|-----------|---------|--------------|\n126: | FAIL | Active P0 findings remain OR any binary gate fails | Does not meet quality standards | `/speckit:plan` for remediation |\n127: | CONDITIONAL | No P0, but active P1 findings remain | Meets threshold but has required fixes | `/speckit:plan` for fixes |\n128: | PASS | No active P0/P1 findings | Shippable, set `hasAdvisories=true` when P2 findings remain | `/create:changelog` |\n129: \n130: ### Release Readiness\n131: \n132: `releaseReadinessState` is the canonical config/report field for review readiness tracking.\n133: \n134: | State | Meaning |\n135: |-------|---------|\n136: | `in-progress` | Review still running or required coverage incomplete |\n137: | `converged` | All 4 dimensions covered and the stabilization pass found no new P0/P1 findings |\n138: | `release-blocking` | At least one unresolved P0 remains active |\n139: \n140: ---\n141: \n142: ## 7. REVIEW QUALITY GUARDS\n143: \n144: | Gate | Rule |\n145: |------|------|\n146: | Evidence | Every active finding has file:line evidence and is not inference-only |\n147: | Scope | Findings and reviewed files stay within declared review scope |\n148: | Coverage | Configured dimensions plus required traceability protocols are covered before STOP |\n149: \n150: ---\n151: \n152: ## 8. REVIEW CONVERGENCE\n153: \n154: | Signal | Weight | Description |\n155: |--------|--------|-------------|\n156: | Rolling Average | 0.30 | Last 2 severity-weighted `newFindingsRatio` values average below `0.08` |\n157: | MAD Noise Floor | 0.25 | Latest ratio within noise floor |\n158: | Dimension Coverage | 0.45 | All 4 dimensions plus required traceability protocols covered, with `minStabilizationPasses >= 1` |\n159: \n160: **Key defaults:** `maxIterations=7`, `convergenceThreshold=0.10`, `rollingStopThreshold=0.08`, `noProgressThreshold=0.05`, `stuckThreshold=2`, `minStabilizationPasses=1`\n161: \n162: **P0 override:** Any new P0 finding sets `newFindingsRatio >= 0.50`, blocking convergence.\n163: \n164: ---\n165: \n166: ## 9. AGENT ITERATION CHECKLIST\n167: \n168: Each @deep-review iteration:\n169: 1. Read `deep-review-state.jsonl`, `deep-review-findings-registry.json`, and `deep-review-strategy.md`\n170: 2. Determine focus dimension from strategy \"Next Focus\"\n171: 3. Execute 3-5 review actions (Read, Grep, Glob, code_graph_query + Grep)\n172: 4. Write `review/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` with P0/P1/P2 findings\n173: 5. Run adversarial self-check on any P0 findings (Hunter/Skeptic/Referee)\n174: 6. Update `deep-review-strategy.md` (findings, coverage, next focus)\n175: 7. Append iteration record to `deep-review-state.jsonl`\n176: \n177: ---\n178: \n179: ## 10. REVIEW REPORT SECTIONS\n180: \n181: | # | Section | Purpose |\n182: |---|---------|---------|\n183: | 1 | Executive Summary | Verdict, active P0/P1/P2 counts, scope, `hasAdvisories` |\n184: | 2 | Planning Trigger | Why the verdict routes to planning or changelog follow-up |\n185: | 3 | Active Finding Registry | Deduped active findings with evidence and final severity |\n186: | 4 | Remediation Workstreams | Grouped action lanes derived from active findings |\n187: | 5 | Spec Seed | Minimal spec delta derived from review results |\n188: | 6 | Plan Seed | Action-ready plan starter for remediation |\n189: | 7 | Traceability Status | Core vs overlay protocol status and unresolved gaps |\n190: | 8 | Deferred Items | P2 advisories, blocked checks, and follow-up items |\n191: | 9 | Audit Appendix | Coverage, replay validation, and convergence evidence |\n192: \n193: ---\n194: \n195: ## 11. TUNING GUIDE\n196: \n197: | Goal | Adjustment |\n198: |------|------------|\n199: | Deeper review | Lower convergence (0.05), raise max iterations (10) |\n200: | Forced iteration ceiling | Set `--stop-policy=max-iterations` with the desired `--max-iterations` |\n201: | Faster completion | Raise convergence (0.15), lower max iterations (5) |\n202: | Focus on security | Specify `--dimensions security,correctness` |\n203: | Broad coverage | Use all 4 default dimensions and allow the stabilization pass to run |\n204: \n205: ---\n206: \n207: ## 12. TROUBLESHOOTING\n208: \n209: | Problem | Fix |\n210: |---------|-----|\n211: | Stops too early | Lower `--convergence` from 0.10 to 0.05, or use `--stop-policy=max-iterations` when early convergence is unacceptable |\n212: | Stuck on one dimension | Check strategy.md \"Next Focus\" rotation |\n213: | P0 findings blocking convergence | Expected behavior: P0 override prevents premature stop |\n214: | Review-report missing sections | Verify synthesis phase completed (check state.jsonl for synthesis event) |\n215: | Agent ignores state | Verify file paths in dispatch prompt |\n216: \n217: ---\n218: \n219: ## 13. RELATED\n220: \n221: | Resource | Purpose |\n222: |----------|---------|\n223: | `deep-research` | Investigation/research (not review) |\n224: | `sk-code` (code-review mode) | Single-pass code review |\n225: | `@deep-review` | Single review iteration agent (LEAF) |\n226: | `@context` | Single-pass codebase search |\n227: | `generate-context.js` | Memory save script |\n228: \n229: For review-specific protocol documentation, see local `references/`:\n230: - `loop_protocol.md`, Review loop lifecycle (4 phases)\n231: - `../state/state_format.md`, Review state file schemas\n232: - `../convergence/convergence.md`, Review convergence algorithms\n\n(End of file - total 232 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Quick Reference\ndescription: One-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep review loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep review quick reference\"\n  - \"review loop cheat sheet\"\n  - \"p0 p1 p2 severity ladder\"\n  - \"release readiness verdicts\"\n  - \"review loop troubleshooting\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.11.0.16\n---\n\n# Deep Review Quick Reference\n\nOne-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep review loop.\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/quick_reference.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Quick Reference\ndescription: One-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep review loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep review quick reference\"\n  - \"review loop cheat sheet\"\n  - \"p0 p1 p2 severity ladder\"\n  - \"release readiness verdicts\"\n  - \"review loop troubleshooting\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.11.0.16\n---\n\n# Deep Review Quick Reference\n\nOne-page cheat sheet for the autonomous deep review loop.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nUse this quick reference when you need the command shape, artifact names, convergence rules, and synthesis outputs for the autonomous deep-review loop without loading the full protocol references.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Looking up the canonical `/deep:review` invocation without re-reading the full SKILL.md.\n- Confirming default thresholds, verdicts, or release-readiness states at a glance.\n- Refreshing the artifact-name and packet-file checklist before a manual orchestration pass.\n- Triaging a stuck loop and need the fastest path to convergence semantics.\n\n### Commands\n\n| Command | Description |\n|---------|-------------|\n| `/deep:review:auto \"target\"` | Run autonomous review (no approval gates) |\n| `/deep:review:confirm \"target\"` | Run review with approval gates at each iteration |\n| `/deep:review \"target\"` | Ask which mode to use |\n\n### Parameters\n\n| Parameter | Default | Description |\n|-----------|---------|-------------|\n| `--max-iterations` | 7 | Maximum review iterations |\n| `--convergence` | 0.10 | Base sensitivity for review convergence |\n| `--stop-policy` | convergence | Use `max-iterations` when convergence must not end the run before the iteration ceiling |\n| `--spec-folder` | auto | Target spec folder path |\n| `--restart` | off | Archive the current review packet and start a fresh lineage |\n| `--severity-threshold` | P2 | Minimum severity to report |\n\n---\n\n## 2. WHEN TO USE\n\n| Scenario | Use |\n|----------|-----|\n| Multi-pass code quality audit | `/deep:review` |\n| Simple single-pass code review | `sk-code` (code-review mode) |\n| Pre-release readiness check | `/deep:review:auto \"spec folder\"` |\n| Spec/implementation alignment check | `/deep:review:auto \"skill sk-name\"` |\n| Deep technical investigation | `/deep:research` (different skill) |\n\n---\n\n## 3. ARCHITECTURE\n\n```\n/deep:review  -->  YAML workflow  -->  @deep-review agent (LEAF)\n    |                    |                      |\n    |                    |                      +-- Read state\n    |                    |                      +-- Review (3-5 actions)\n    |                    |                      +-- Write findings (P0/P1/P2)\n    |                    |                      +-- Update state\n    |                    |\n    |                    +-- Init (config, strategy, state)\n    |                    +-- Loop (dispatch, evaluate, decide)\n    |                    +-- Synthesize (review-report.md)\n    |                    +-- Save (memory context)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. STATE FILES\n\nReview mode stores its packet under the resolved local review path rooted at `{spec_folder}/review/`:\n\n| File | Location | Format | Purpose |\n|------|----------|--------|---------|\n| Config | `review/deep-review-config.json` | JSON | Review parameters (immutable) |\n| State | `review/deep-review-state.jsonl` | JSONL | Iteration log (append-only) |\n| Registry | `review/deep-review-findings-registry.json` | JSON | Reducer-owned finding registry |\n| Strategy | `review/deep-review-strategy.md` | Markdown | Dimensions, findings, next focus |\n| Dashboard | `review/deep-review-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Auto-generated review dashboard |\n| Iterations | `review/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Per-iteration findings (write-once) |\n| Report | `review/review-report.md` | Markdown | Final 9-section review report |\n| Pause | `review/.deep-review-pause` | Sentinel | Pause between iterations |\n\n### Lifecycle Modes\n\n| Mode | Effect |\n|------|--------|\n| `resume` | Continue the current review lineage without resetting generation |\n| `restart` | Archive current review state and start a new generation |\n| `fork` (deferred) | Reserved. Start a sibling lineage branch with explicit parent linkage. Not runtime-wired. |\n| `completed-continue` (deferred) | Reserved. Snapshot the completed review and reopen it for amendment-only review deltas. Not runtime-wired. |\n\n---\n\n## 5. REVIEW DIMENSIONS\n\n| ID | Dimension | Priority | Description |\n|----|-----------|----------|-------------|\n| D1 | Correctness | 1 | Logic errors, off-by-one, wrong return types, broken invariants |\n| D2 | Security | 2 | Injection, auth bypass, secrets exposure, unsafe deserialization |\n| D3 | Traceability | 3 | Spec/code alignment, checklist evidence, cross-reference integrity |\n| D4 | Maintainability | 4 | Patterns, clarity, documentation quality, ease of safe follow-on changes |\n\n---\n\n## 6. REVIEW VERDICTS\n\n| Verdict | Condition | Meaning | Next Command |\n|---------|-----------|---------|--------------|\n| FAIL | Active P0 findings remain OR any binary gate fails | Does not meet quality standards | `/speckit:plan` for remediation |\n| CONDITIONAL | No P0, but active P1 findings remain | Meets threshold but has required fixes | `/speckit:plan` for fixes |\n| PASS | No active P0/P1 findings | Shippable, set `hasAdvisories=true` when P2 findings remain | `/create:changelog` |\n\n### Release Readiness\n\n`releaseReadinessState` is the canonical config/report field for review readiness tracking.\n\n| State | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| `in-progress` | Review still running or required coverage incomplete |\n| `converged` | All 4 dimensions covered and the stabilization pass found no new P0/P1 findings |\n| `release-blocking` | At least one unresolved P0 remains active |\n\n---\n\n## 7. REVIEW QUALITY GUARDS\n\n| Gate | Rule |\n|------|------|\n| Evidence | Every active finding has file:line evidence and is not inference-only |\n| Scope | Findings and reviewed files stay within declared review scope |\n| Coverage | Configured dimensions plus required traceability protocols are covered before STOP |\n\n---\n\n## 8. REVIEW CONVERGENCE\n\n| Signal | Weight | Description |\n|--------|--------|-------------|\n| Rolling Average | 0.30 | Last 2 severity-weighted `newFindingsRatio` values average below `0.08` |\n| MAD Noise Floor | 0.25 | Latest ratio within noise floor |\n| Dimension Coverage | 0.45 | All 4 dimensions plus required traceability protocols covered, with `minStabilizationPasses >= 1` |\n\n**Key defaults:** `maxIterations=7`, `convergenceThreshold=0.10`, `rollingStopThreshold=0.08`, `noProgressThreshold=0.05`, `stuckThreshold=2`, `minStabilizationPasses=1`\n\n**P0 override:** Any new P0 finding sets `newFindingsRatio >= 0.50`, blocking convergence.\n\n---\n\n## 9. AGENT ITERATION CHECKLIST\n\nEach @deep-review iteration:\n1. Read `deep-review-state.jsonl`, `deep-review-findings-registry.json`, and `deep-review-strategy.md`\n2. Determine focus dimension from strategy \"Next Focus\"\n3. Execute 3-5 review actions (Read, Grep, Glob, code_graph_query + Grep)\n4. Write `review/iterations/iteration-NNN.md` with P0/P1/P2 findings\n5. Run adversarial self-check on any P0 findings (Hunter/Skeptic/Referee)\n6. Update `deep-review-strategy.md` (findings, coverage, next focus)\n7. Append iteration record to `deep-review-state.jsonl`\n\n---\n\n## 10. REVIEW REPORT SECTIONS\n\n| # | Section | Purpose |\n|---|---------|---------|\n| 1 | Executive Summary | Verdict, active P0/P1/P2 counts, scope, `hasAdvisories` |\n| 2 | Planning Trigger | Why the verdict routes to planning or changelog follow-up |\n| 3 | Active Finding Registry | Deduped active findings with evidence and final severity |\n| 4 | Remediation Workstreams | Grouped action lanes derived from active findings |\n| 5 | Spec Seed | Minimal spec delta derived from review results |\n| 6 | Plan Seed | Action-ready plan starter for remediation |\n| 7 | Traceability Status | Core vs overlay protocol status and unresolved gaps |\n| 8 | Deferred Items | P2 advisories, blocked checks, and follow-up items |\n| 9 | Audit Appendix | Coverage, replay validation, and convergence evidence |\n\n---\n\n## 11. TUNING GUIDE\n\n| Goal | Adjustment |\n|------|------------|\n| Deeper review | Lower convergence (0.05), raise max iterations (10) |\n| Forced iteration ceiling | Set `--stop-policy=max-iterations` with the desired `--max-iterations` |\n| Faster completion | Raise convergence (0.15), lower max iterations (5) |\n| Focus on security | Specify `--dimensions security,correctness` |\n| Broad coverage | Use all 4 default dimensions and allow the stabilization pass to run |\n\n---\n\n## 12. TROUBLESHOOTING\n\n| Problem | Fix |\n|---------|-----|\n| Stops too early | Lower `--convergence` from 0.10 to 0.05, or use `--stop-policy=max-iterations` when early convergence is unacceptable |\n| Stuck on one dimension | Check strategy.md \"Next Focus\" rotation |\n| P0 findings blocking convergence | Expected behavior: P0 override prevents premature stop |\n| Review-report missing sections | Verify synthesis phase completed (check state.jsonl for synthesis event) |\n| Agent ignores state | Verify file paths in dispatch prompt |\n\n---\n\n## 13. RELATED\n\n| Resource | Purpose |\n|----------|---------|\n| `deep-research` | Investigation/research (not review) |\n| `sk-code` (code-review mode) | Single-pass code review |\n| `@deep-review` | Single review iteration agent (LEAF) |\n| `@context` | Single-pass codebase search |\n| `generate-context.js` | Memory save script |\n\nFor review-specific protocol documentation, see local `references/`:\n- `loop_protocol.md`, Review loop lifecycle (4 phases)\n- `../state/state_format.md`, Review state file schemas\n- `../convergence/convergence.md`, Review convergence algorithms","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":232,"totalLines":232,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/quick_reference.md","time":{"start":1783806723722,"end":1783806723726}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb0398508191bce8224d42e1e6e5"}},"id":"prt_f532a866e001uSp9An0Jca8Nvt","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723743,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_BvDiuraXZDKrVaBS71l9yhwQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Review Loop Protocol\n3: description: Complete lifecycle specification for the autonomous deep review loop, initialization, iteration, convergence, synthesis, and save phases.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"deep review loop protocol\"\n6:   - \"review iteration lifecycle\"\n7:   - \"review loop initialization\"\n8:   - \"review auto resume\"\n9:   - \"review synthesis phase\"\n10: importance_tier: important\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.11.0.29\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Deep Review Loop Protocol\n16: \n17: Complete lifecycle specification for the autonomous deep review loop.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Purpose\n24: \n25: The deep review loop has 4 phases: initialization, iteration (repeated), synthesis, and save. The YAML workflow manages the lifecycle. The `@deep-review` agent (LEAF-only, no WebFetch) executes individual review iterations with fresh context each time.\n26: \n27: ### When to Use\n28: \n29: - Initiating a deep-review loop on a spec folder, skill, agent, or track.\n30: - Resuming a paused or interrupted review session from prior state.\n31: - Validating the 4-phase lifecycle and lineage protocol against current behavior.\n32: - Auditing iteration-dispatch, convergence, or save-phase contracts before changes.\n33: \n34: ```\n35: ┌──────────────┐     ┌───────────────────────────────┐     ┌───────────────┐     ┌──────────┐\n36: │  INIT        │────>│  LOOP                         │────>│  SYNTHESIS    │────>│  SAVE    │\n37: │              │     │  ┌─────────────────────────┐  │     │               │     │          │\n38: │ Scope        │     │  │ Read State              │  │     │ Finding       │     │ Memory   │\n39: │ Discovery    │     │  │ Check Convergence       │  │     │ Registry      │     │ Context  │\n40: │ Dimension    │     │  │ Check Pause Sentinel    │  │     │ Dedup         │     │ Save     │\n41: │ Ordering     │     │  │ Generate State Summary  │  │     │               │     │          │\n42: │ Traceability │     │  │ Dispatch @deep-review   │  │     │ Severity      │     │          │\n43: │ Planning     │     │  │ Evaluate Results        │  │     │ Reconcile     │     │          │\n44: │ State Files  │     │  │ Claim Adjudication      │  │     │               │     │          │\n45: │              │     │  │ Dashboard Generation    │  │     │ Replay        │     │          │\n46: │              │     │  │ Loop Decision           │  │     │ Validation    │     │          │\n47: │              │     │  └────────┬────────────────┘  │     │               │     │          │\n48: │              │     │           │ repeat            │     │ review-report │     │          │\n49: │              │     │           │                   │     │ (9 core +     │     │          │\n50: │              │     │           │                   │     │  resource-map)│     │          │\n51: └──────────────┘     └───────────────────────────────┘     └───────────────┘     └──────────┘\n52: ```\n53: \n54: ### Core Innovation\n55: \n56: Each agent dispatch gets a fresh context window. State continuity comes from files on disk, not in-context memory. This eliminates context degradation in long review sessions where accumulated findings would otherwise bias subsequent dimensions.\n57: \n58: ### Key References\n59: \n60: | Resource | Path | Purpose |\n61: |----------|------|---------|\n62: | Review contract | `assets/review_mode_contract.yaml` | Dimensions, verdicts, gates, protocols |\n63: | Auto workflow | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml` | Unattended review loop |\n64: | Confirm workflow | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_confirm.yaml` | Step-by-step review with approval gates |\n65: | Agent | `@deep-review` (LEAF) | Single iteration executor, no sub-agents, no WebFetch |\n66: | Memory save | `generate-context.js` | Context preservation script |\n67: \n68: ---\n69: \n70: ## 2. PHASE 1: INITIALIZATION\n71: \n72: ### Purpose\n73: \n74: Set up all state files for a new review session. Discover the scope, order dimensions by risk priority, establish the traceability protocol plan, and create the review state packet.\n75: \n76: ### Steps\n77: \n78: 1. **Classify session state before writing**:\n79:    - `fresh`: no config/state/strategy files exist\n80:    - `resume`: config + state + strategy all exist and agree\n81:    - `completed-session`: consistent prior state with `config.status == \"complete\"`\n82:    - `invalid-state`: partial or contradictory artifacts\n83: \n84: 2. **Resolve local artifact owner**: `artifact_dir = resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'review').artifactDir`, then `mkdir -p {artifact_dir}/iterations`\n85: \n86: 3. **Scope discovery**: Resolve the review target into a concrete file list using one of 5 target types:\n87: \n88:    | Target Type | CLI Value | Resolution Strategy |\n89:    |-------------|-----------|---------------------|\n90:    | **Spec Folder** | `spec-folder` | Read `spec.md`, `plan.md`, implementation files listed in `tasks.md` |\n91:    | **Skill** | `skill` | Read `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, `scripts/`, find agent definitions and command entry points |\n92:    | **Agent** | `agent` | Find agent definitions across all runtimes, compare for consistency |\n93:    | **Track** | `track` | List all child spec folders under the track, read `spec.md` + `checklist.md` for each |\n94:    | **Files** | `files` | Expand glob patterns, validate existence, discover cross-references |\n95: \n96:    Store the resolved file list in strategy.md \"Files Under Review\".\n97: \n98: 4. **Dimension ordering**: Order the 4 review dimensions for iteration based on risk priority:\n99: \n100:    | Priority | Dimension | Rationale |\n101:    |----------|-----------|-----------|\n102:    | 1 | Correctness | Logic errors have the highest blast radius |\n103:    | 2 | Security | Vulnerabilities require immediate attention |\n104:    | 3 | Traceability | Spec/code alignment ensures completeness |\n105:    | 4 | Maintainability | Patterns and documentation quality (lowest immediate risk) |\n106: \n107:    Default order: D1 Correctness, D2 Security, D3 Traceability, D4 Maintainability. This order is configurable but the default prioritizes highest-impact dimensions first.\n108: \n109: 5. **Traceability protocol planning**: Partition the 6 cross-reference protocols into core vs overlay, and schedule only applicable overlays for the target type:\n110: \n111:    | Level | Protocol | Applies To | Gate Class | Purpose |\n112:    |-------|----------|------------|------------|---------|\n113:    | Core | `spec_code` | all targets | hard | Verify normative claims resolve to shipped behavior |\n114:    | Core | `checklist_evidence` | all targets | hard | Verify checked completion claims have evidence |\n115:    | Overlay | `skill_agent` | skill | advisory | Verify SKILL.md and runtime agents agree |\n116:    | Overlay | `agent_cross_runtime` | agent | advisory | Verify runtime agent parity |\n117:    | Overlay | `feature_catalog_code` | skill, spec-folder, track, files | advisory | Verify catalog claims match capability |\n118:    | Overlay | `playbook_capability` | skill, agent, spec-folder | advisory | Verify playbook scenarios match executable reality |\n119: \n120:    Only schedule overlay protocols that apply to the resolved target type.\n121: \n122: 6. **Write config**: `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json` with `mode: \"review\"`, lineage metadata (`sessionId`, `parentSessionId`, `lineageMode`, `generation`, `continuedFromRun`, `releaseReadinessState`), and review-specific fields including target, target type, dimensions, protocol plan, and release-readiness state.\n123: \n124: 7. **Initialize state log**: First line of `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl` with config record including `mode: \"review\"` and the lineage fields.\n125: \n126: 8. **Initialize reducer state**: Create `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json` with empty `openFindings`, `resolvedFindings`, `repeatedFindings`, `dimensionCoverage`, `findingsBySeverity`, and `convergenceScore`.\n127: \n128: 9. **Initialize strategy**: `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md` from review template with:\n129:    - Topic (review target description)\n130:    - Review Dimensions checklist\n131:    - Files Under Review table\n132:    - Cross-Reference Status table grouped by core vs overlay\n133:    - Known Context from `memory_context()` results (if any)\n134:    - Resource-map snapshot when `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` exists at init\n135:    - `resource-map.md not present. Skipping coverage gate` when it does not\n136:    - Review Boundaries from config\n137: 9a. **Initialize resource-map coverage state**:\n138:    - If `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` exists at init: set `resource_map_present = true`, add `Resource Map Coverage` to the Review Charter, and persist a concise map summary in `Known Context`\n139:    - If absent: set `resource_map_present = false`, record the skip note in `Known Context`, and continue without failing\n140: \n141: 10. **Validate review charter**:\n142:    - Verify strategy.md contains Non-Goals and Stop Conditions sections (may be empty but must exist)\n143:    - In **confirm mode**: present the charter (target, dimensions, scope, non-goals) for user review before proceeding\n144:    - In **auto mode**: accept automatically and continue\n145: \n146: 11. **Resume only if config, JSONL, strategy, and findings registry agree**. Otherwise halt for repair instead of guessing.\n147: \n148: ### Outputs\n149: \n150: | File | Location | Purpose |\n151: |------|----------|---------|\n152: | Config | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json` | Review parameters (immutable after init) |\n153: | State | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl` | Iteration log (1 initial line) |\n154: | Registry | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json` | Reducer-owned findings state |\n155: | Strategy | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md` | Dimensions, findings, next focus |\n156: \n157: ---\n158: \n159: ## 3. PHASE 2: ITERATION LOOP\n160: \n161: ### Loop Steps (repeated until convergence)\n162: \n163: #### Step 1: Read State\n164: \n165: - Read `deep-review-state.jsonl` -- count iterations, extract `newFindingsRatio`, `findingsSummary`, `findingsNew`, `traceabilityChecks`, and lineage data\n166: - Read `deep-review-findings-registry.json` -- extract `dimensionsCovered`, `findingsBySeverity`, `openFindings`, `resolvedFindings`, and `convergenceScore`\n167: - Read `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md` -- get next focus dimension/files, remaining dimensions, and protocol gaps\n168: \n169: Reducer contract for every loop refresh:\n170: \n171: | Reducer Part | Canonical Value | Notes |\n172: |--------------|-----------------|-------|\n173: | Inputs | `fullJSONLHistory`, `iterationFiles`, `priorReducedState` | Normal loop refresh is full-history: replay the persisted JSONL state and current iteration corpus each refresh so reducer output stays deterministic across restart, compaction, and synthesis audit paths. |\n174: | Outputs | `findingsRegistry`, `dashboardMetrics`, `strategyUpdates` | The same refresh pass updates the canonical registry, refreshes dashboard metrics, and applies strategy updates. |\n175: | Metrics | `dimensionsCovered`, `findingsBySeverity`, `openFindings`, `resolvedFindings`, `convergenceScore` | These metrics drive convergence decisions, dashboard summaries, and synthesis readiness. |\n176: \n177: #### Step 2: Check Convergence\n178: \n179: Run `shouldContinue_review()` (see `../deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md` Section 10.3):\n180: \n181: - Max iterations reached? `STOP`\n182: - Stuck count `>= 2` using `noProgressThreshold = 0.05`? `STUCK_RECOVERY`\n183: - Composite convergence votes `STOP` only after:\n184:   - Rolling average uses `rollingStopThreshold = 0.08`\n185:   - Dimension coverage reaches 100% across the 4-dimension model\n186:   - Coverage has aged through `minStabilizationPasses >= 1`\n187:   - Required traceability protocols are covered\n188:   - Evidence, scope, and coverage gates pass\n189: - Otherwise: `CONTINUE`\n190: \n191: If convergence math or a hard-stop candidate points to STOP, the workflow must run the review legal-stop decision tree before actually stopping. That decision tree records nine review-specific gates: `convergenceGate`, `dimensionCoverageGate`, `p0ResolutionGate`, `evidenceDensityGate`, `hotspotSaturationGate`, `claimAdjudicationGate`, `fixCompletenessReplayGate`, `candidateCoverageGate`, and `graphlessFallbackGate` (see `../convergence/convergence.md` §Section-1 blocked_stop event example for the authoritative shape). The Step 4a claim-adjudication path treats `claimAdjudicationGate` as a hard STOP gate, so the count covers both the convergence decision tree and the adjudication enforcement path. `candidateCoverageGate` and `graphlessFallbackGate` are v2-rollout gates that pass trivially when the review-depth-v2 search path is inactive. If any gate fails, the loop does **not** stop. Instead it emits a first-class `blocked_stop` JSONL event with:\n192: \n193: - `blockedBy`: array of the failed review gate names\n194: - `gateResults`: per-gate pass/fail payloads using the review gate names above\n195: - `recoveryStrategy`: one-line hint describing the next review action\n196: \n197: The blocked-stop event is append-only evidence that legal-stop blocked the run. The loop then continues with the recovery or next-focus path rather than synthesizing.\n198: \n199: Convergence signals and weights:\n200: \n201: | Signal | Weight | Description |\n202: |--------|--------|-------------|\n203: | Rolling Average | 0.30 | Last 2 severity-weighted `newFindingsRatio` values average below `rollingStopThreshold` |\n204: | MAD Noise Floor | 0.25 | Latest ratio within noise floor derived from historical ratios |\n205: | Dimension Coverage | 0.45 | All 4 dimensions plus required traceability protocols covered, with stabilization |\n206: \n207: **P0 override**: Any new P0 finding sets `newFindingsRatio >= 0.50`, blocking convergence regardless of composite score.\n208: \n209: #### Step 2a: Check Pause Sentinel\n210: \n211: Before dispatching, check for a pause sentinel file:\n212: \n213: 1. Check if `review/.deep-review-pause` exists (note: the file name uses the shared `-pause` suffix)\n214: 2. If present:\n215:    - Log event to JSONL: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"userPaused\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"stopReason\":\"userPaused\",\"reason\":\"sentinel file detected\"}`\n216:    - Halt the loop with message:\n217:      ```\n218:      Review paused. Delete review/.deep-review-pause to resume.\n219:      Current state: Iteration {N}, {reviewed}/{total} dimensions complete, {P0}/{P1}/{P2} findings.\n220:      ```\n221:    - Do NOT exit to synthesis -- the loop is suspended, not stopped\n222: 3. On resume (file deleted and loop restarted):\n223:    - Log event: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"fromIteration\":N}`\n224:    - Continue from step_read_state\n225: \n226: **Use case**: In autonomous mode, this provides the only graceful intervention mechanism short of killing the process. Users can create the sentinel file at any time to pause review between iterations.\n227: \n228: Normalization rule: if the runtime first observes a raw `paused` condition or a raw `stuck_recovery` condition, it MUST rewrite the emitted JSONL event names to `userPaused` and `stuckRecovery` before appending them. Persisted review JSONL should never contain raw `paused` or raw `stuck_recovery` rows after emission.\n229: \n230: #### Step 2b: Generate State Summary\n231: \n232: Generate a compact state summary (~200 tokens) for injection into the dispatch prompt:\n233: \n234: ```\n235: STATE SUMMARY (auto-generated, review mode):\n236: Iteration: {N} of {max} | Mode: review\n237: Target: {config.reviewTarget} ({config.reviewTargetType})\n238: Dimensions: {reviewed}/{total} complete | Next: {nextDimension}\n239: Findings: P0:{count} P1:{count} P2:{count} active\n240: Traceability: core={core_status} overlay={overlay_status}\n241: Last 2 ratios: {ratio_N-1} -> {ratio_N} | Stuck count: {stuck_count}\n242: Provisional verdict: {PASS|CONDITIONAL|FAIL|PENDING} | hasAdvisories={hasAdvisories}\n243: Next focus: {strategy.nextFocus}\n244: ```\n245: \n246: This summary is prepended to the dispatch context (Step 3) to ensure the agent has baseline context even if detailed strategy.md reading fails or is incomplete.\n247: \n248: #### Step 3: Dispatch Agent\n249: \n250: Dispatch `@deep-review` with review-specific context:\n251: \n252: ```\n253: {state_summary}  // Auto-generated (Step 2b)\n254: \n255: Review Target: {config.reviewTarget}\n256: Review Mode: {config.reviewTargetType}\n257: Iteration: {N} of {maxIterations}\n258: Focus Dimension: {strategy.nextFocus.dimension}\n259: Focus Files: {strategy.nextFocus.files}\n260: Remaining Dimensions: {strategy.remainingDimensions}\n261: Traceability Protocols:\n262:   - Core: {core_protocols}\n263:   - Overlay: {overlay_protocols}\n264: Active Findings: {findingsSummary}\n265: State Files:\n266:   - Config: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json\n267:   - State: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl\n268:   - Registry: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json\n269:   - Strategy: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md\n270: Output: Write findings to {artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md\n271: CONSTRAINT: LEAF agent -- do NOT dispatch sub-agents\n272: CONSTRAINT: Target files are READ-ONLY -- never modify code under review\n273: ```\n274: \n275: #### Executor Resolution (spec 018 + 019)\n276: \n277: Before dispatching, the YAML resolves the executor via `parseExecutorConfig` from `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`. The resolved `config.executor.kind` selects the dispatch branch:\n278: \n279: - `native` (spec 018): dispatch `@deep-review` agent with model Opus.\n280: - `cli-opencode` (spec 018): pipe rendered prompt via stdin to `opencode run --model X --format json --dangerously-skip-permissions --pure --dir {repo_root} [--variant Y]`. **This grants full OS-level workspace write access.** There is no `--sandbox workspace-write` flag in the live command, and `sandboxMode='read-only'` is NOT currently honored/enforced by opencode (no opencode equivalent exists). The only real containment is (a) the prompt-level \"ALLOWED WRITE PATHS\" / \"BANNED OPERATIONS\" contract rendered into the iteration prompt (`assets/prompt_pack_iteration.md.tmpl`), which relies on the model obeying instructions rather than an OS-level sandbox, and (b) post-dispatch validation (`validateIterationOutputs`) catching some violations after the fact. Because review targets are arbitrary code/spec files, they MUST be treated as potentially adversarial content (untrusted) for prompt-injection purposes — the same containment posture as untrusted fetched content in deep-research.\n281: - `cli-claude-code` (spec 019): `claude -p \"$(cat prompt)\" --model X --permission-mode acceptEdits --output-format text` with optional `--effort Y`. Default permission-mode is `plan` (read-only). We override to `acceptEdits` so iteration writes succeed.\n282: \n283: All branches share:\n284: 1. Pre-dispatch prompt rendering via `renderPromptPack` (writes to `{artifact_dir}/prompts/iteration-{n}.md`).\n285: 2. Post-dispatch validation via `validateIterationOutputs` (asserts iteration file + JSONL delta + required fields).\n286: 3. Executor audit append via `appendExecutorAuditToLastRecord` (skipped when kind=='native').\n287: \n288: Per-kind flag-compatibility is enforced at config parse time by `EXECUTOR_KIND_FLAG_SUPPORT` in `executor-config.ts`. Setting a flag that the chosen kind does not support throws `ExecutorConfigError` before dispatch.\n289: \n290: Cross-CLI delegation (a running executor invoking other CLIs via its shell) is documented design intent. Runtime recursion detection is out of scope. See the SKILL.md Cross-CLI Delegation subsection.\n291: \n292: Failure handling remains unchanged from spec 018: `schema_mismatch` → conflict event → 3 consecutive failures → `stuck_recovery`.\n293: \n294: **Agent constraints**:\n295: - `@deep-review` is LEAF-only: it cannot dispatch sub-agents\n296: - No WebFetch: review is code-only and read-only\n297: - Target 8-11 tool calls per iteration (max 12). Breadth over depth per cycle\n298: - Tools available: Read, Grep, Glob, Edit (state files only), code_graph_query + Grep\n299: \n300: #### Step 3a: Cross-Reference Protocol Execution\n301: \n302: During iterations focused on the Traceability dimension, the agent executes applicable cross-reference protocols. Each protocol produces a structured result appended to the JSONL `traceabilityChecks.results[]` array.\n303: \n304: | Protocol | Execution | Expected Output |\n305: |----------|-----------|-----------------|\n306: | `spec_code` | Compare normative claims in spec.md against shipped implementation | Pass/partial/fail per claim with file:line evidence |\n307: | `checklist_evidence` | Verify every `[x]` mark in checklist.md has supporting evidence | Pass/partial/fail per checked item |\n308: | `skill_agent` | Compare SKILL.md contracts against runtime agent definitions | Agreement/drift/disagreement per capability |\n309: | `agent_cross_runtime` | Compare agent definitions across runtimes (.opencode, .claude, .opencode) | Parity/drift/divergence per runtime pair |\n310: | `feature_catalog_code` | Compare catalog claims against discoverable implementation | Match/stale/missing per feature |\n311: | `playbook_capability` | Validate playbook scenarios against executable reality | Executable/needs-update/impossible per scenario |\n312: \n313: Each protocol result includes:\n314: - `protocolId`: Protocol identifier\n315: - `status`: `pass`, `partial`, or `fail`\n316: - `gateClass`: `hard` or `advisory`\n317: - `applicable`: Whether the protocol applies to this target type\n318: - `counts`: `{ pass, partial, fail, skipped }`\n319: - `evidence`: Array of file:line citations\n320: - `findingRefs`: Array of finding IDs generated from this protocol\n321: - `summary`: Human-readable summary text\n322: \n323: #### Step 3b: Resource Map Coverage Audit\n324: \n325: When `config.resource_map_present == true`, at least one loop iteration MUST audit implementation-vs-resource-map coverage:\n326: \n327: 1. Read `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md`\n328: 2. Read applied reports under `{spec_folder}/applied/T-*.md`\n329: 3. Cross-check `target_files` from the applied reports against resource-map entries\n330: 4. Classify outcomes into:\n331:    - entries touched\n332:    - entries not touched (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`)\n333:    - implementation paths absent from the map\n334: 5. Emit any resulting findings with category `resource-map-coverage`\n335: \n336: When `config.resource_map_present == false`, skip this audit and rely on the `Known Context` note: `resource-map.md not present. Skipping coverage gate`.\n337: \n338: #### Step 4: Evaluate Results\n339: \n340: After agent completes:\n341: \n342: 1. Verify `{artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md` was created\n343: 2. Verify JSONL was appended with review iteration fields:\n344:    - `dimensions` (array of dimensions covered)\n345:    - `filesReviewed` (array of file paths)\n346:    - `findingsSummary` (cumulative P0/P1/P2 counts)\n347:    - `findingsNew` (this iteration's new findings)\n348:    - `traceabilityChecks` (protocol results if applicable)\n349: 3. Verify strategy.md was updated (dimension progress, findings count, protocol status)\n350: 4. Extract `newFindingsRatio` from JSONL record\n351: 5. Update stuck tracking using `noProgressThreshold = 0.05`:\n352:    - Skip if `status == \"thought\"` (no change)\n353:    - Reset to 0 if `status == \"insight\"` (breakthrough counts as progress)\n354:    - Increment if `newFindingsRatio < noProgressThreshold`\n355:    - Reset otherwise\n356: \n357: #### Step 4a: Claim Adjudication\n358: \n359: Before the next convergence pass, the orchestrator adjudicates every new P0/P1 finding with a **typed claim-adjudication packet**. This step prevents false positives from inflating severity and distorting convergence, AND acts as a hard STOP gate: `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication` appends a `claim_adjudication` event to `deep-review-state.jsonl`, and the next iteration's `step_check_convergence` legal-stop decision tree consults that event via `claimAdjudicationGate` (gate `f`). A missing or failing packet vetoes STOP even when every other gate passes.\n360: \n361: Each new P0/P1 must carry a typed packet with the following required fields (see `../state/state_format.md` §9 for the full schema and a worked example):\n362: \n363: | Field | Type | Description |\n364: |-------|------|-------------|\n365: | `findingId` | string | Matches the finding ID in the iteration body |\n366: | `claim` | string | The single assertion the finding makes |\n367: | `evidenceRefs` | string[] | `file:line` or `file:range` citations (≥ 1) |\n368: | `counterevidenceSought` | string | Where the orchestrator looked for contradicting evidence |\n369: | `alternativeExplanation` | string | An alternative explanation, even if rejected |\n370: | `finalSeverity` | `\"P0\"` \\| `\"P1\"` \\| `\"P2\"` | Severity after adjudication |\n371: | `confidence` | number `[0, 1]` | Orchestrator confidence in `finalSeverity` |\n372: | `downgradeTrigger` | string | Concrete condition that would cause a future downgrade |\n373: | `transitions` | object[] | Optional, required when `finalSeverity` differs from the originally asserted severity |\n374: \n375: **Protocol**:\n376: \n377: 1. Re-read the cited evidence at the referenced file:line locations.\n378: 2. Seek counterevidence in adjacent code, docs, or prior iteration history.\n379: 3. Record an alternative explanation even if it is rejected.\n380: 4. Confirm or downgrade severity before the finding becomes convergence-visible.\n381: 5. Emit the typed packet inside the iteration file so `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication` can parse it.\n382: \n383: **Failure semantics**: when any new P0/P1 finding is missing a packet or a required field, the workflow records `{\"event\":\"claim_adjudication\",\"passed\":false,\"missingPackets\":[...]}` in `deep-review-state.jsonl`. On the next loop, `step_check_convergence` step 0 (universal pre-check) routes STOP to `BLOCKED` with `blockedBy: [\"claimAdjudicationGate\"]` until a follow-up iteration rewrites the packet. Downgraded findings have their `finalSeverity` updated. The original severity is preserved in the iteration file for audit trail.\n384: \n385: #### Step 4b: Generate Dashboard\n386: \n387: Generate `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-dashboard.md` with review-specific sections:\n388: \n389: | Section | Content |\n390: |---------|---------|\n391: | Status | Provisional verdict (`PASS`/`CONDITIONAL`/`FAIL`/`PENDING`) and `hasAdvisories` flag |\n392: | Findings Summary | P0/P1/P2 counts with deltas from previous iteration |\n393: | Progress Table | Iteration number, focus dimension, `newFindingsRatio`, findings count, status |\n394: | Coverage | Files reviewed, dimensions completed, traceability protocol status |\n395: | Trend | Last 3 `newFindingsRatio` values with direction indicator (ascending/descending/flat) |\n396: | Active Risks | Guard violations, stuck count, budget warnings |\n397: \n398: Dashboard behavior:\n399: - Auto-generated only -- never manually edited\n400: - Overwritten each iteration (not appended)\n401: - Non-blocking: if generation fails, log a warning and continue the loop\n402: - In **confirm mode**: displayed to the user at each iteration approval gate\n403: - In **auto mode**: written silently for post-hoc review\n404: \n405: #### Step 5: Loop Decision\n406: \n407: - If convergence check returns STOP: exit to synthesis\n408: - If STUCK_RECOVERY: apply review-specific recovery strategies (see Section 3a), reset stuck count, continue\n409: - Otherwise: increment iteration counter, go to Step 1\n410: \n411: ### Stuck Recovery (Review-Specific)\n412: \n413: **Threshold:** 2 consecutive no-progress iterations (`noProgressThreshold = 0.05`).\n414: \n415: | Failure Mode | Detection | Recovery Strategy |\n416: |-------------|-----------|-------------------|\n417: | Same dimension stuck | Last 2 iterations reviewed the same dimension with ratios `< 0.05` | **Change granularity**: if reviewing at file level, zoom into functions, if reviewing functions, zoom out to module level |\n418: | Traceability plateau | Required protocols remain partial while ratios stay `< 0.05` | **Protocol-first replay**: re-run the unresolved traceability protocol directly against the conflicting artifacts |\n419: | Low-value advisory churn | Last 2 iterations found only P2 work | **Escalate severity review**: explicitly search for P0/P1 patterns or downgrade unsupported severity claims |\n420: \n421: **Selection logic**:\n422: \n423: ```\n424: function selectReviewRecoveryStrategy(stuckIterations, state, config):\n425:   lastFocuses = [i.focus for i in stuckIterations[-2:]]\n426: \n427:   // Same dimension stuck? Change granularity\n428:   if len(set(lastFocuses)) <= 1:\n429:     return { strategy: \"change_granularity\", dimension: lastFocuses[0] }\n430: \n431:   // Required protocol plateau?\n432:   if hasRequiredProtocolPlateau(state.traceabilityChecks):\n433:     return { strategy: \"protocol_first_replay\" }\n434: \n435:   // Default: escalate severity\n436:   return { strategy: \"escalate_severity_review\" }\n437: ```\n438: \n439: **Recovery evaluation**:\n440: - If recovery iteration finds any new P0/P1 or materially advances required traceability coverage: recovery successful. Reset stuck count. Continue.\n441: - If recovery iteration finds only P2 or nothing: recovery failed. If all dimensions are already covered, exit to synthesis. Otherwise, move to the next unreviewed dimension.\n442: \n443: ---\n444: \n445: ## 4. PHASE 3: SYNTHESIS\n446: \n447: ### Purpose\n448: \n449: Compile all iteration findings into the final `{artifact_dir}/review-report.md`. The synthesis phase owns the canonical review report output.\n450: \n451: ### Steps\n452: \n453: #### Step 1: Finding Registry Deduplication\n454: \n455: Consolidate findings across all iterations:\n456: \n457: 1. Read all iteration files: `{artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-*.md`\n458: 2. Group findings by file + line range + root cause\n459: 3. Merge duplicates, keeping the highest severity and all evidence\n460: 4. Assign final finding IDs: `F001`, `F002`, ...\n461: 5. Preserve the audit trail: note which iterations contributed to each merged finding\n462: \n463: #### Step 2: Severity Reconciliation\n464: \n465: Use adjudicated `finalSeverity` for any P0/P1 that was downgraded during claim adjudication (Step 4a of the iteration loop). The original severity from the iteration file is preserved in the audit appendix.\n466: \n467: #### Step 3: Replay Validation\n468: \n469: Recompute the convergence outcome from JSONL state before finalizing the report:\n470: \n471: 1. Read `deep-review-state.jsonl` and select review-mode iteration records in run order\n472: 2. Recompute `newFindingsRatio`, rolling-average votes, MAD votes, and coverage votes from stored JSONL fields only\n473: 3. Recompute `traceabilityChecks.summary` and confirm required protocol statuses match the recorded coverage vote\n474: 4. Re-run the evidence, scope, and coverage gates against stored findings and scope data\n475: 5. Compare the replayed decision and stop reason to the recorded synthesis event\n476: \n477: This synthesis-stage replay is a **full-history audit replay** over the stored JSONL state. It follows the same full-history replay discipline as the per-iteration reducer refresh above, but runs as an explicit pre-synthesis audit.\n478: \n479: Replay passes only when the recomputed decision, thresholds, and gate outcomes agree with the persisted result. If replay fails, log a warning in the audit appendix but proceed with synthesis.\n480: \n481: #### Step 4: Compile review-report.md\n482: \n483: Generate the 9 core review-report sections (defined in `review_mode_contract.yaml` under `outputs.reviewReport`) and insert `## Resource Map Coverage Gate` between `Traceability Status` and `Deferred Items` when `config.resource_map_present == true`:\n484: \n485: | # | Section | Purpose |\n486: |---|---------|---------|\n487: | 1 | Executive Summary | Verdict, active P0/P1/P2 counts, scope, `hasAdvisories` metadata |\n488: | 2 | Planning Trigger | Why the verdict routes to planning or changelog follow-up |\n489: | 3 | Active Finding Registry | Deduplicated active findings with evidence and final severity |\n490: | 4 | Remediation Workstreams | Grouped action lanes derived from active findings |\n491: | 5 | Spec Seed | Minimal spec delta derived from review results |\n492: | 6 | Plan Seed | Action-ready plan starter for remediation |\n493: | 7 | Traceability Status | Core vs overlay protocol status and unresolved gaps |\n494: | 8 | Resource Map Coverage Gate | Present only when `config.resource_map_present == true`, reports touched entries, untouched entries (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`), and implementation paths absent from the map |\n495: | 9 | Deferred Items | P2 advisories, blocked checks, and follow-up items |\n496: | 10 | Audit Appendix | Coverage, replay validation, convergence evidence |\n497: \n498: #### Step 5: Verdict Determination\n499: \n500: Apply the verdict contract from `review_mode_contract.yaml`:\n501: \n502: | Verdict | Condition | Next Command |\n503: |---------|-----------|--------------|\n504: | **FAIL** | Active P0 remains OR any required binary gate fails | `/speckit:plan` for remediation |\n505: | **CONDITIONAL** | No active P0, but active P1 remains | `/speckit:plan` for fixes |\n506: | **PASS** | No active P0/P1 | `/create:changelog` |\n507: \n508: When `PASS` verdict is issued and active P2 findings remain, set `hasAdvisories = true` in the report metadata.\n509: \n510: #### Step 6: Finalize State\n511: \n512: 1. Update config status: Set `status: \"complete\"` in `deep-review-config.json`\n513: 2. Write final JSONL entry:\n514:    ```json\n515:    {\n516:      \"type\": \"event\",\n517:      \"event\": \"synthesis_complete\",\n518:      \"mode\": \"review\",\n519:      \"totalIterations\": N,\n520:      \"verdict\": \"PASS|CONDITIONAL|FAIL\",\n521:      \"activeP0\": N,\n522:      \"activeP1\": N,\n523:      \"activeP2\": N,\n524:      \"dimensionCoverage\": X,\n525:      \"stopReason\": \"...\",\n526:      \"timestamp\": \"...\"\n527:    }\n528:    ```\n529: \n530: ---\n531: \n532: ## 5. PHASE 4: SAVE\n533: \n534: ### Purpose\n535: \n536: Preserve review context to the memory system for future session recovery and cross-session continuity.\n537: \n538: ### Steps\n539: \n540: 1. **Compose context payload**: Create a structured JSON payload with the review summary, active findings, verdict, next action, and relevant artifacts. Use `specFolder` for the target packet and include curated `observations`, `recent_context`, `toolCalls`, and `exchanges` when available.\n541: \n542: 2. **Generate context**: Run the memory save script with structured JSON via `--stdin`, `--json`, or a session-scoped JSON file:\n543:    ```bash\n544:    node .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/dist/memory/generate-context.js --json '{\"specFolder\":\"{spec_folder}\",\"sessionSummary\":\"Deep review completed; see review/review-report.md for verdict and findings.\"}' {spec_folder}\n545:    ```\n546: \n547: 3. **No extra indexing step in the live contract**: `generate-context.js` is the supported save boundary for this workflow.\n548: \n549: 4. **Verify**: Confirm the routed canonical spec document carries the review continuity update. Expected targets are `implementation-summary.md`, `decision-record.md`, or `handover.md`; standalone `memory/*.md` files are retired and should not be created.\n550: \n551: ### On Save Failure\n552: \n553: If memory save fails:\n554: - Preserve the current `review/` packet as backup (the disk state is the ground truth)\n555: - Log the error\n556: - The review results remain intact in `{artifact_dir}/review-report.md` regardless of memory save status\n557: \n558: ---\n559: \n560: ## 6. AUTO-RESUME PROTOCOL\n561: \n562: ### Purpose\n563: \n564: Enable review sessions to resume cleanly from prior state when interrupted by context compaction, process termination, or intentional pause.\n565: \n566: ### Resume Detection\n567: \n568: If state files already exist from a prior session:\n569: \n570: 1. **Verify agreement**: Confirm config, JSONL, findings registry, and strategy all exist and agree on target/spec folder\n571: 2. **Count progress**: Read JSONL, count iteration records, determine last completed iteration\n572: 3. **Read strategy**: Load current dimension progress, findings, and next focus from `deep-review-strategy.md`\n573: 4. **Set counter**: Set iteration counter to last completed + 1\n574: 5. **Log resume**: Append the canonical resume event to `deep-review-state.jsonl`. The reducer requires every field below:\n575:    ```json\n576:    {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"sessionId\":\"rvw-2026-03-24T10-00-00Z\",\"parentSessionId\":\"rvw-2026-03-24T10-00-00Z\",\"lineageMode\":\"resume\",\"continuedFromRun\":4,\"generation\":1,\"archivedPath\":null,\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-24T14:05:00Z\"}\n577:    ```\n578: 6. **Continue**: Enter the iteration loop from step_read_state\n579: \n580: ### Lifecycle Branches (current release)\n581: \n582: The runtime supports three lineage modes today. `fork` and `completed-continue` were described in earlier drafts but have no workflow wiring in this release, so they MUST NOT be exposed to operators. If the long-form lineage feature is picked up later it will arrive with first-class event emission, reducer ancestry handling, and replay fixtures. Until then treat the contract below as canonical.\n583: \n584: | Mode | Session id | Generation | Archive | JSONL event | When to pick |\n585: |------|-----------|-----------|---------|-------------|--------------|\n586: | `new` | fresh | 1 | n/a | implicit (config record) | no existing state |\n587: | `resume` | same | same | none | `resumed` (see example above) | operator wants to continue the current lineage boundary |\n588: | `restart` | fresh | `prior + 1` | prior `review/` tree moved under `review_archive/{timestamp}/` | `restarted` (same field set plus non-null `archivedPath`) | operator wants to clear the workspace and replay with a new angle |\n589: \n590: **Contract for every persisted lifecycle event**:\n591: \n592: ```json\n593: {\n594:   \"type\": \"event\",\n595:   \"event\": \"resumed | restarted\",\n596:   \"mode\": \"review\",\n597:   \"sessionId\": \"<session id of the new or continuing lineage>\",\n598:   \"parentSessionId\": \"<session id of the prior lineage (equals sessionId on resume)>\",\n599:   \"lineageMode\": \"resume | restart\",\n600:   \"generation\": <number>,\n601:   \"continuedFromRun\": <number or null>,\n602:   \"archivedPath\": \"<path or null>\",\n603:   \"timestamp\": \"<ISO 8601>\"\n604: }\n605: ```\n606: \n607: Every field in the contract MUST be present on every persisted lifecycle event. `archivedPath` is null for `resumed` and set to the archive destination for `restarted`. `continuedFromRun` is the number of completed iteration records before the lifecycle boundary. Reducer parity tests ensure the dashboard `Lifecycle` section reads exactly those fields.\n608: \n609: ### State Validation on Resume\n610: \n611: | Condition | Classification | Action |\n612: |-----------|---------------|--------|\n613: | Config + JSONL + strategy all exist and agree | `resume` | Continue from last iteration + 1 |\n614: | All exist, config says `status: \"complete\"` | `completed-session` | Report completion, ask user if re-review desired |\n615: | Partial files or contradictions | `invalid-state` | Halt for repair, do not guess |\n616: | No files exist | `fresh` | Start new initialization |\n617: \n618: ### State Recovery Cascade\n619: \n620: When state files are missing or corrupted, apply this priority cascade:\n621: \n622: | Priority | Condition | Recovery Action |\n623: |----------|-----------|----------------|\n624: | 1 | JSONL exists and parseable | Normal operation |\n625: | 2 | JSONL exists, strategy.md missing | Reconstruct strategy from JSONL: extract dimensions, findings, coverage |\n626: | 3 | JSONL missing, iteration files exist | Scan `review/iterations/iteration-*.md`, reconstruct JSONL with `status: \"reconstructed\"` |\n627: | 4 | Only config.json remains | Restart from initialization phase |\n628: | 5 | Config.json also missing | Cannot recover. Report error and halt. |\n629: \n630: Each priority level is attempted in order. If a level fails, fall through to the next.\n631: \n632: ---\n633: \n634: ## 7. PAUSE/RESUME\n635: \n636: ### Pause Sentinel Behavior\n637: \n638: The pause sentinel provides graceful loop suspension in autonomous mode without killing the process.\n639: \n640: ### Creating a Pause\n641: \n642: Create the sentinel file at any time:\n643: \n644: ```bash\n645: touch {artifact_dir}/.deep-review-pause\n646: ```\n647: \n648: The orchestrator checks for this file between iterations (Step 2a). When detected:\n649: - The current iteration is allowed to complete\n650: - The loop halts before dispatching the next iteration\n651: - A paused event is logged to JSONL\n652: - The user is notified with current state (iteration count, dimensions covered, findings)\n653: \n654: ### Resuming After Pause\n655: \n656: Delete the sentinel file and restart the workflow:\n657: \n658: ```bash\n659: rm {artifact_dir}/.deep-review-pause\n660: ```\n661: \n662: On the next invocation:\n663: - The auto-resume protocol (Section 6) detects the existing state\n664: - A resumed event is logged to JSONL\n665: - The loop continues from the next iteration\n666: \n667: ### Confirm Mode Approval Gates\n668: \n669: In confirm mode (`deep_review_confirm.yaml`), the workflow adds explicit approval gates instead of relying on the pause sentinel:\n670: \n671: | Gate Location | Behavior |\n672: |---------------|----------|\n673: | After initialization | Show config, strategy, and scope. Wait for approval |\n674: | After each iteration | Show iteration findings, dashboard, and convergence status. Options: Continue, Adjust Focus, Stop |\n675: | Before synthesis | Show summary of all iterations. Wait for approval to synthesize |\n676: | After synthesis | Show final review-report.md summary. Approve or request revisions |\n677: \n678: ---\n679: \n680: ## 8. STATE TRANSITIONS, ERROR HANDLING, AND QUALITY GATES\n681: \n682: State-transition rules, error handling, and the review quality gates live in `loop_state_and_gates.md` for navigability.\n683: \n684: ---\n685: \n686: ## 11. RELATED RESOURCES\n687: \n688: ### Shared Protocol Documentation\n689: \n690: Protocol documents from `deep-research` are cross-referenced, not duplicated:\n691: \n692: | Document | Path | Purpose |\n693: |----------|------|---------|\n694: | Loop Protocol (research) | `../deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md` | Research loop lifecycle (this file adapts Section 9) |\n695: | State Format | `../deep-research/references/state/state_format.md` | JSONL, strategy, and config schemas |\n696: | Convergence | `../deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md` | `shouldContinue_review()` (Section 10), stuck recovery, quality guards |\n697: \n698: ### Review-Specific Resources\n699: \n700: | Resource | Path | Purpose |\n701: |----------|------|---------|\n702: | Review Contract | `assets/review_mode_contract.yaml` | Single source of truth for dimensions, verdicts, gates, protocols |\n703: | Quick Reference | `references/protocol/quick_reference.md` | One-page review cheat sheet |\n704: | Strategy Template | `assets/deep_review_strategy.md` | Template for review strategy files |\n705: | Config Template | `assets/deep_review_config.json` | Template for review config files |\n706: | Dashboard Template | `assets/deep_review_dashboard.md` | Template for auto-generated dashboard |\n707: \n708: ### Workflow Files\n709: \n710: | Mode | Path |\n711: |------|------|\n712: | Auto (unattended) | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml` |\n713: | Confirm (step-by-step) | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_confirm.yaml` |\n714: \n715: ### Agent\n716: \n717: | Agent | Path Pattern | Constraint |\n718: |-------|-------------|------------|\n719: | `@deep-review` | `{runtime_dir}/deep-review.{ext}` | LEAF-only, no sub-agents, no WebFetch, target files read-only |\n720: \n721: Runtime paths:\n722: - OpenCode / Copilot: `.opencode/agents/deep-review.md`\n723: - Claude: `.claude/agents/deep-review.md`\n724: \n725: ---\n726: \n727: ## Executor Selection Contract\n728: \n729: Executor settings are owned by the YAML workflow and rendered prompt pack. Do not bypass the workflow by hand-dispatching review iterations; each iteration stays LEAF-only and produces the required markdown plus JSONL delta.\n730: \n731: ### Invariants\n732: \n733: Every executor path MUST satisfy:\n734: \n735: 1. Produce an iteration markdown file at `{state_paths.iteration_pattern}` (non-empty).\n736: 2. Append a JSONL delta record to `{state_paths.state_log}` with required fields: `type`, `iteration`, `dimensions`, `filesReviewed`, `findingsSummary`, `findingsNew`, `findingDetails`, `newFindingsRatio`.\n737: 3. Respect the LEAF-agent constraint: no sub-dispatch, no nested loops. Max 12 tool calls per iteration.\n738: \n739: ### Failure Modes\n740: \n741: - Missing iteration file: `iteration_file_missing` from `post-dispatch-validate.ts`, emits a `schema_mismatch` conflict event.\n742: - Empty iteration file: `iteration_file_empty`, same downstream.\n743: - JSONL not appended: `jsonl_not_appended`.\n744: - JSONL missing required fields: `jsonl_missing_fields`.\n745: - JSONL malformed: `jsonl_parse_error`.\n746: - 3 consecutive failures: existing `stuck_recovery` event (unchanged).\n747: \n748: ### JSONL Audit Field\n749: \n750: Non-native executor runs append an `executor` block with model and runtime settings to the iteration's JSONL record via `executor-audit.ts`. Native runs are recoverable from YAML alone.\n751: \n752: ### Template And Config Surface\n753: \n754: The executor-agnostic iteration prompt lives at `assets/prompt_pack_iteration.md.tmpl`, rendered by `prompt-pack.ts` before dispatch and either injected as the agent's context (native) or piped to `opencode run` stdin (cli-opencode). Config is in `assets/deep_review_config.json` under the `executor` key; schema in `runtime//lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`. CLI flag precedence: `--executor/--model/--reasoning-effort/--service-tier/--executor-timeout > config file > schema default`.\n755: \n756: ### What Never Changes Regardless Of Executor Route\n757: \n758: - YAML owns state (`deep-review-state.jsonl`, strategy.md, registry, dashboard).\n759: - `reduce-state.cjs` is the single state writer.\n760: - Convergence detection, lifecycle events (new/resume/restart), the review dimensions pass, and stuck_recovery stay YAML-driven.\n761: - The `@deep-review` LEAF agent definition is untouched: it is the native executor, not the only one.\n762: \n763: ### Code-Graph Readiness TrustState Surface\n764: \n765: On this skill surface, the live code-graph readiness contract only reaches four TrustState values: `live`, `stale`, `absent`, and `unavailable`. The values `cached`, `imported`, `rebuilt`, and `rehomed` remain declared in the shared TrustState type for compatibility and downstream schema stability, but the seven code-graph handlers and readiness helpers used here do not emit them today.\n\n(End of file - total 765 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Loop Protocol\ndescription: Complete lifecycle specification for the autonomous deep review loop, initialization, iteration, convergence, synthesis, and save phases.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep review loop protocol\"\n  - \"review iteration lifecycle\"\n  - \"review loop initialization\"\n  - \"review auto resume\"\n  - \"review synthesis phase\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.29\n---\n\n# Deep Review Loop Protocol\n\nComplete lifecycle specification for the autonomous deep review loop.\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Loop Protocol\ndescription: Complete lifecycle specification for the autonomous deep review loop, initialization, iteration, convergence, synthesis, and save phases.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep review loop protocol\"\n  - \"review iteration lifecycle\"\n  - \"review loop initialization\"\n  - \"review auto resume\"\n  - \"review synthesis phase\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.29\n---\n\n# Deep Review Loop Protocol\n\nComplete lifecycle specification for the autonomous deep review loop.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThe deep review loop has 4 phases: initialization, iteration (repeated), synthesis, and save. The YAML workflow manages the lifecycle. The `@deep-review` agent (LEAF-only, no WebFetch) executes individual review iterations with fresh context each time.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Initiating a deep-review loop on a spec folder, skill, agent, or track.\n- Resuming a paused or interrupted review session from prior state.\n- Validating the 4-phase lifecycle and lineage protocol against current behavior.\n- Auditing iteration-dispatch, convergence, or save-phase contracts before changes.\n\n```\n┌──────────────┐     ┌───────────────────────────────┐     ┌───────────────┐     ┌──────────┐\n│  INIT        │────>│  LOOP                         │────>│  SYNTHESIS    │────>│  SAVE    │\n│              │     │  ┌─────────────────────────┐  │     │               │     │          │\n│ Scope        │     │  │ Read State              │  │     │ Finding       │     │ Memory   │\n│ Discovery    │     │  │ Check Convergence       │  │     │ Registry      │     │ Context  │\n│ Dimension    │     │  │ Check Pause Sentinel    │  │     │ Dedup         │     │ Save     │\n│ Ordering     │     │  │ Generate State Summary  │  │     │               │     │          │\n│ Traceability │     │  │ Dispatch @deep-review   │  │     │ Severity      │     │          │\n│ Planning     │     │  │ Evaluate Results        │  │     │ Reconcile     │     │          │\n│ State Files  │     │  │ Claim Adjudication      │  │     │               │     │          │\n│              │     │  │ Dashboard Generation    │  │     │ Replay        │     │          │\n│              │     │  │ Loop Decision           │  │     │ Validation    │     │          │\n│              │     │  └────────┬────────────────┘  │     │               │     │          │\n│              │     │           │ repeat            │     │ review-report │     │          │\n│              │     │           │                   │     │ (9 core +     │     │          │\n│              │     │           │                   │     │  resource-map)│     │          │\n└──────────────┘     └───────────────────────────────┘     └───────────────┘     └──────────┘\n```\n\n### Core Innovation\n\nEach agent dispatch gets a fresh context window. State continuity comes from files on disk, not in-context memory. This eliminates context degradation in long review sessions where accumulated findings would otherwise bias subsequent dimensions.\n\n### Key References\n\n| Resource | Path | Purpose |\n|----------|------|---------|\n| Review contract | `assets/review_mode_contract.yaml` | Dimensions, verdicts, gates, protocols |\n| Auto workflow | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml` | Unattended review loop |\n| Confirm workflow | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_confirm.yaml` | Step-by-step review with approval gates |\n| Agent | `@deep-review` (LEAF) | Single iteration executor, no sub-agents, no WebFetch |\n| Memory save | `generate-context.js` | Context preservation script |\n\n---\n\n## 2. PHASE 1: INITIALIZATION\n\n### Purpose\n\nSet up all state files for a new review session. Discover the scope, order dimensions by risk priority, establish the traceability protocol plan, and create the review state packet.\n\n### Steps\n\n1. **Classify session state before writing**:\n   - `fresh`: no config/state/strategy files exist\n   - `resume`: config + state + strategy all exist and agree\n   - `completed-session`: consistent prior state with `config.status == \"complete\"`\n   - `invalid-state`: partial or contradictory artifacts\n\n2. **Resolve local artifact owner**: `artifact_dir = resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'review').artifactDir`, then `mkdir -p {artifact_dir}/iterations`\n\n3. **Scope discovery**: Resolve the review target into a concrete file list using one of 5 target types:\n\n   | Target Type | CLI Value | Resolution Strategy |\n   |-------------|-----------|---------------------|\n   | **Spec Folder** | `spec-folder` | Read `spec.md`, `plan.md`, implementation files listed in `tasks.md` |\n   | **Skill** | `skill` | Read `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, `scripts/`, find agent definitions and command entry points |\n   | **Agent** | `agent` | Find agent definitions across all runtimes, compare for consistency |\n   | **Track** | `track` | List all child spec folders under the track, read `spec.md` + `checklist.md` for each |\n   | **Files** | `files` | Expand glob patterns, validate existence, discover cross-references |\n\n   Store the resolved file list in strategy.md \"Files Under Review\".\n\n4. **Dimension ordering**: Order the 4 review dimensions for iteration based on risk priority:\n\n   | Priority | Dimension | Rationale |\n   |----------|-----------|-----------|\n   | 1 | Correctness | Logic errors have the highest blast radius |\n   | 2 | Security | Vulnerabilities require immediate attention |\n   | 3 | Traceability | Spec/code alignment ensures completeness |\n   | 4 | Maintainability | Patterns and documentation quality (lowest immediate risk) |\n\n   Default order: D1 Correctness, D2 Security, D3 Traceability, D4 Maintainability. This order is configurable but the default prioritizes highest-impact dimensions first.\n\n5. **Traceability protocol planning**: Partition the 6 cross-reference protocols into core vs overlay, and schedule only applicable overlays for the target type:\n\n   | Level | Protocol | Applies To | Gate Class | Purpose |\n   |-------|----------|------------|------------|---------|\n   | Core | `spec_code` | all targets | hard | Verify normative claims resolve to shipped behavior |\n   | Core | `checklist_evidence` | all targets | hard | Verify checked completion claims have evidence |\n   | Overlay | `skill_agent` | skill | advisory | Verify SKILL.md and runtime agents agree |\n   | Overlay | `agent_cross_runtime` | agent | advisory | Verify runtime agent parity |\n   | Overlay | `feature_catalog_code` | skill, spec-folder, track, files | advisory | Verify catalog claims match capability |\n   | Overlay | `playbook_capability` | skill, agent, spec-folder | advisory | Verify playbook scenarios match executable reality |\n\n   Only schedule overlay protocols that apply to the resolved target type.\n\n6. **Write config**: `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json` with `mode: \"review\"`, lineage metadata (`sessionId`, `parentSessionId`, `lineageMode`, `generation`, `continuedFromRun`, `releaseReadinessState`), and review-specific fields including target, target type, dimensions, protocol plan, and release-readiness state.\n\n7. **Initialize state log**: First line of `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl` with config record including `mode: \"review\"` and the lineage fields.\n\n8. **Initialize reducer state**: Create `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json` with empty `openFindings`, `resolvedFindings`, `repeatedFindings`, `dimensionCoverage`, `findingsBySeverity`, and `convergenceScore`.\n\n9. **Initialize strategy**: `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md` from review template with:\n   - Topic (review target description)\n   - Review Dimensions checklist\n   - Files Under Review table\n   - Cross-Reference Status table grouped by core vs overlay\n   - Known Context from `memory_context()` results (if any)\n   - Resource-map snapshot when `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` exists at init\n   - `resource-map.md not present. Skipping coverage gate` when it does not\n   - Review Boundaries from config\n9a. **Initialize resource-map coverage state**:\n   - If `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` exists at init: set `resource_map_present = true`, add `Resource Map Coverage` to the Review Charter, and persist a concise map summary in `Known Context`\n   - If absent: set `resource_map_present = false`, record the skip note in `Known Context`, and continue without failing\n\n10. **Validate review charter**:\n   - Verify strategy.md contains Non-Goals and Stop Conditions sections (may be empty but must exist)\n   - In **confirm mode**: present the charter (target, dimensions, scope, non-goals) for user review before proceeding\n   - In **auto mode**: accept automatically and continue\n\n11. **Resume only if config, JSONL, strategy, and findings registry agree**. Otherwise halt for repair instead of guessing.\n\n### Outputs\n\n| File | Location | Purpose |\n|------|----------|---------|\n| Config | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json` | Review parameters (immutable after init) |\n| State | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl` | Iteration log (1 initial line) |\n| Registry | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json` | Reducer-owned findings state |\n| Strategy | `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md` | Dimensions, findings, next focus |\n\n---\n\n## 3. PHASE 2: ITERATION LOOP\n\n### Loop Steps (repeated until convergence)\n\n#### Step 1: Read State\n\n- Read `deep-review-state.jsonl` -- count iterations, extract `newFindingsRatio`, `findingsSummary`, `findingsNew`, `traceabilityChecks`, and lineage data\n- Read `deep-review-findings-registry.json` -- extract `dimensionsCovered`, `findingsBySeverity`, `openFindings`, `resolvedFindings`, and `convergenceScore`\n- Read `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md` -- get next focus dimension/files, remaining dimensions, and protocol gaps\n\nReducer contract for every loop refresh:\n\n| Reducer Part | Canonical Value | Notes |\n|--------------|-----------------|-------|\n| Inputs | `fullJSONLHistory`, `iterationFiles`, `priorReducedState` | Normal loop refresh is full-history: replay the persisted JSONL state and current iteration corpus each refresh so reducer output stays deterministic across restart, compaction, and synthesis audit paths. |\n| Outputs | `findingsRegistry`, `dashboardMetrics`, `strategyUpdates` | The same refresh pass updates the canonical registry, refreshes dashboard metrics, and applies strategy updates. |\n| Metrics | `dimensionsCovered`, `findingsBySeverity`, `openFindings`, `resolvedFindings`, `convergenceScore` | These metrics drive convergence decisions, dashboard summaries, and synthesis readiness. |\n\n#### Step 2: Check Convergence\n\nRun `shouldContinue_review()` (see `../deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md` Section 10.3):\n\n- Max iterations reached? `STOP`\n- Stuck count `>= 2` using `noProgressThreshold = 0.05`? `STUCK_RECOVERY`\n- Composite convergence votes `STOP` only after:\n  - Rolling average uses `rollingStopThreshold = 0.08`\n  - Dimension coverage reaches 100% across the 4-dimension model\n  - Coverage has aged through `minStabilizationPasses >= 1`\n  - Required traceability protocols are covered\n  - Evidence, scope, and coverage gates pass\n- Otherwise: `CONTINUE`\n\nIf convergence math or a hard-stop candidate points to STOP, the workflow must run the review legal-stop decision tree before actually stopping. That decision tree records nine review-specific gates: `convergenceGate`, `dimensionCoverageGate`, `p0ResolutionGate`, `evidenceDensityGate`, `hotspotSaturationGate`, `claimAdjudicationGate`, `fixCompletenessReplayGate`, `candidateCoverageGate`, and `graphlessFallbackGate` (see `../convergence/convergence.md` §Section-1 blocked_stop event example for the authoritative shape). The Step 4a claim-adjudication path treats `claimAdjudicationGate` as a hard STOP gate, so the count covers both the convergence decision tree and the adjudication enforcement path. `candidateCoverageGate` and `graphlessFallbackGate` are v2-rollout gates that pass trivially when the review-depth-v2 search path is inactive. If any gate fails, the loop does **not** stop. Instead it emits a first-class `blocked_stop` JSONL event with:\n\n- `blockedBy`: array of the failed review gate names\n- `gateResults`: per-gate pass/fail payloads using the review gate names above\n- `recoveryStrategy`: one-line hint describing the next review action\n\nThe blocked-stop event is append-only evidence that legal-stop blocked the run. The loop then continues with the recovery or next-focus path rather than synthesizing.\n\nConvergence signals and weights:\n\n| Signal | Weight | Description |\n|--------|--------|-------------|\n| Rolling Average | 0.30 | Last 2 severity-weighted `newFindingsRatio` values average below `rollingStopThreshold` |\n| MAD Noise Floor | 0.25 | Latest ratio within noise floor derived from historical ratios |\n| Dimension Coverage | 0.45 | All 4 dimensions plus required traceability protocols covered, with stabilization |\n\n**P0 override**: Any new P0 finding sets `newFindingsRatio >= 0.50`, blocking convergence regardless of composite score.\n\n#### Step 2a: Check Pause Sentinel\n\nBefore dispatching, check for a pause sentinel file:\n\n1. Check if `review/.deep-review-pause` exists (note: the file name uses the shared `-pause` suffix)\n2. If present:\n   - Log event to JSONL: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"userPaused\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"stopReason\":\"userPaused\",\"reason\":\"sentinel file detected\"}`\n   - Halt the loop with message:\n     ```\n     Review paused. Delete review/.deep-review-pause to resume.\n     Current state: Iteration {N}, {reviewed}/{total} dimensions complete, {P0}/{P1}/{P2} findings.\n     ```\n   - Do NOT exit to synthesis -- the loop is suspended, not stopped\n3. On resume (file deleted and loop restarted):\n   - Log event: `{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"fromIteration\":N}`\n   - Continue from step_read_state\n\n**Use case**: In autonomous mode, this provides the only graceful intervention mechanism short of killing the process. Users can create the sentinel file at any time to pause review between iterations.\n\nNormalization rule: if the runtime first observes a raw `paused` condition or a raw `stuck_recovery` condition, it MUST rewrite the emitted JSONL event names to `userPaused` and `stuckRecovery` before appending them. Persisted review JSONL should never contain raw `paused` or raw `stuck_recovery` rows after emission.\n\n#### Step 2b: Generate State Summary\n\nGenerate a compact state summary (~200 tokens) for injection into the dispatch prompt:\n\n```\nSTATE SUMMARY (auto-generated, review mode):\nIteration: {N} of {max} | Mode: review\nTarget: {config.reviewTarget} ({config.reviewTargetType})\nDimensions: {reviewed}/{total} complete | Next: {nextDimension}\nFindings: P0:{count} P1:{count} P2:{count} active\nTraceability: core={core_status} overlay={overlay_status}\nLast 2 ratios: {ratio_N-1} -> {ratio_N} | Stuck count: {stuck_count}\nProvisional verdict: {PASS|CONDITIONAL|FAIL|PENDING} | hasAdvisories={hasAdvisories}\nNext focus: {strategy.nextFocus}\n```\n\nThis summary is prepended to the dispatch context (Step 3) to ensure the agent has baseline context even if detailed strategy.md reading fails or is incomplete.\n\n#### Step 3: Dispatch Agent\n\nDispatch `@deep-review` with review-specific context:\n\n```\n{state_summary}  // Auto-generated (Step 2b)\n\nReview Target: {config.reviewTarget}\nReview Mode: {config.reviewTargetType}\nIteration: {N} of {maxIterations}\nFocus Dimension: {strategy.nextFocus.dimension}\nFocus Files: {strategy.nextFocus.files}\nRemaining Dimensions: {strategy.remainingDimensions}\nTraceability Protocols:\n  - Core: {core_protocols}\n  - Overlay: {overlay_protocols}\nActive Findings: {findingsSummary}\nState Files:\n  - Config: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-config.json\n  - State: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-state.jsonl\n  - Registry: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-findings-registry.json\n  - Strategy: {artifact_dir}/deep-review-strategy.md\nOutput: Write findings to {artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md\nCONSTRAINT: LEAF agent -- do NOT dispatch sub-agents\nCONSTRAINT: Target files are READ-ONLY -- never modify code under review\n```\n\n#### Executor Resolution (spec 018 + 019)\n\nBefore dispatching, the YAML resolves the executor via `parseExecutorConfig` from `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`. The resolved `config.executor.kind` selects the dispatch branch:\n\n- `native` (spec 018): dispatch `@deep-review` agent with model Opus.\n- `cli-opencode` (spec 018): pipe rendered prompt via stdin to `opencode run --model X --format json --dangerously-skip-permissions --pure --dir {repo_root} [--variant Y]`. **This grants full OS-level workspace write access.** There is no `--sandbox workspace-write` flag in the live command, and `sandboxMode='read-only'` is NOT currently honored/enforced by opencode (no opencode equivalent exists). The only real containment is (a) the prompt-level \"ALLOWED WRITE PATHS\" / \"BANNED OPERATIONS\" contract rendered into the iteration prompt (`assets/prompt_pack_iteration.md.tmpl`), which relies on the model obeying instructions rather than an OS-level sandbox, and (b) post-dispatch validation (`validateIterationOutputs`) catching some violations after the fact. Because review targets are arbitrary code/spec files, they MUST be treated as potentially adversarial content (untrusted) for prompt-injection purposes — the same containment posture as untrusted fetched content in deep-research.\n- `cli-claude-code` (spec 019): `claude -p \"$(cat prompt)\" --model X --permission-mode acceptEdits --output-format text` with optional `--effort Y`. Default permission-mode is `plan` (read-only). We override to `acceptEdits` so iteration writes succeed.\n\nAll branches share:\n1. Pre-dispatch prompt rendering via `renderPromptPack` (writes to `{artifact_dir}/prompts/iteration-{n}.md`).\n2. Post-dispatch validation via `validateIterationOutputs` (asserts iteration file + JSONL delta + required fields).\n3. Executor audit append via `appendExecutorAuditToLastRecord` (skipped when kind=='native').\n\nPer-kind flag-compatibility is enforced at config parse time by `EXECUTOR_KIND_FLAG_SUPPORT` in `executor-config.ts`. Setting a flag that the chosen kind does not support throws `ExecutorConfigError` before dispatch.\n\nCross-CLI delegation (a running executor invoking other CLIs via its shell) is documented design intent. Runtime recursion detection is out of scope. See the SKILL.md Cross-CLI Delegation subsection.\n\nFailure handling remains unchanged from spec 018: `schema_mismatch` → conflict event → 3 consecutive failures → `stuck_recovery`.\n\n**Agent constraints**:\n- `@deep-review` is LEAF-only: it cannot dispatch sub-agents\n- No WebFetch: review is code-only and read-only\n- Target 8-11 tool calls per iteration (max 12). Breadth over depth per cycle\n- Tools available: Read, Grep, Glob, Edit (state files only), code_graph_query + Grep\n\n#### Step 3a: Cross-Reference Protocol Execution\n\nDuring iterations focused on the Traceability dimension, the agent executes applicable cross-reference protocols. Each protocol produces a structured result appended to the JSONL `traceabilityChecks.results[]` array.\n\n| Protocol | Execution | Expected Output |\n|----------|-----------|-----------------|\n| `spec_code` | Compare normative claims in spec.md against shipped implementation | Pass/partial/fail per claim with file:line evidence |\n| `checklist_evidence` | Verify every `[x]` mark in checklist.md has supporting evidence | Pass/partial/fail per checked item |\n| `skill_agent` | Compare SKILL.md contracts against runtime agent definitions | Agreement/drift/disagreement per capability |\n| `agent_cross_runtime` | Compare agent definitions across runtimes (.opencode, .claude, .opencode) | Parity/drift/divergence per runtime pair |\n| `feature_catalog_code` | Compare catalog claims against discoverable implementation | Match/stale/missing per feature |\n| `playbook_capability` | Validate playbook scenarios against executable reality | Executable/needs-update/impossible per scenario |\n\nEach protocol result includes:\n- `protocolId`: Protocol identifier\n- `status`: `pass`, `partial`, or `fail`\n- `gateClass`: `hard` or `advisory`\n- `applicable`: Whether the protocol applies to this target type\n- `counts`: `{ pass, partial, fail, skipped }`\n- `evidence`: Array of file:line citations\n- `findingRefs`: Array of finding IDs generated from this protocol\n- `summary`: Human-readable summary text\n\n#### Step 3b: Resource Map Coverage Audit\n\nWhen `config.resource_map_present == true`, at least one loop iteration MUST audit implementation-vs-resource-map coverage:\n\n1. Read `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md`\n2. Read applied reports under `{spec_folder}/applied/T-*.md`\n3. Cross-check `target_files` from the applied reports against resource-map entries\n4. Classify outcomes into:\n   - entries touched\n   - entries not touched (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`)\n   - implementation paths absent from the map\n5. Emit any resulting findings with category `resource-map-coverage`\n\nWhen `config.resource_map_present == false`, skip this audit and rely on the `Known Context` note: `resource-map.md not present. Skipping coverage gate`.\n\n#### Step 4: Evaluate Results\n\nAfter agent completes:\n\n1. Verify `{artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-{NNN}.md` was created\n2. Verify JSONL was appended with review iteration fields:\n   - `dimensions` (array of dimensions covered)\n   - `filesReviewed` (array of file paths)\n   - `findingsSummary` (cumulative P0/P1/P2 counts)\n   - `findingsNew` (this iteration's new findings)\n   - `traceabilityChecks` (protocol results if applicable)\n3. Verify strategy.md was updated (dimension progress, findings count, protocol status)\n4. Extract `newFindingsRatio` from JSONL record\n5. Update stuck tracking using `noProgressThreshold = 0.05`:\n   - Skip if `status == \"thought\"` (no change)\n   - Reset to 0 if `status == \"insight\"` (breakthrough counts as progress)\n   - Increment if `newFindingsRatio < noProgressThreshold`\n   - Reset otherwise\n\n#### Step 4a: Claim Adjudication\n\nBefore the next convergence pass, the orchestrator adjudicates every new P0/P1 finding with a **typed claim-adjudication packet**. This step prevents false positives from inflating severity and distorting convergence, AND acts as a hard STOP gate: `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication` appends a `claim_adjudication` event to `deep-review-state.jsonl`, and the next iteration's `step_check_convergence` legal-stop decision tree consults that event via `claimAdjudicationGate` (gate `f`). A missing or failing packet vetoes STOP even when every other gate passes.\n\nEach new P0/P1 must carry a typed packet with the following required fields (see `../state/state_format.md` §9 for the full schema and a worked example):\n\n| Field | Type | Description |\n|-------|------|-------------|\n| `findingId` | string | Matches the finding ID in the iteration body |\n| `claim` | string | The single assertion the finding makes |\n| `evidenceRefs` | string[] | `file:line` or `file:range` citations (≥ 1) |\n| `counterevidenceSought` | string | Where the orchestrator looked for contradicting evidence |\n| `alternativeExplanation` | string | An alternative explanation, even if rejected |\n| `finalSeverity` | `\"P0\"` \\| `\"P1\"` \\| `\"P2\"` | Severity after adjudication |\n| `confidence` | number `[0, 1]` | Orchestrator confidence in `finalSeverity` |\n| `downgradeTrigger` | string | Concrete condition that would cause a future downgrade |\n| `transitions` | object[] | Optional, required when `finalSeverity` differs from the originally asserted severity |\n\n**Protocol**:\n\n1. Re-read the cited evidence at the referenced file:line locations.\n2. Seek counterevidence in adjacent code, docs, or prior iteration history.\n3. Record an alternative explanation even if it is rejected.\n4. Confirm or downgrade severity before the finding becomes convergence-visible.\n5. Emit the typed packet inside the iteration file so `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication` can parse it.\n\n**Failure semantics**: when any new P0/P1 finding is missing a packet or a required field, the workflow records `{\"event\":\"claim_adjudication\",\"passed\":false,\"missingPackets\":[...]}` in `deep-review-state.jsonl`. On the next loop, `step_check_convergence` step 0 (universal pre-check) routes STOP to `BLOCKED` with `blockedBy: [\"claimAdjudicationGate\"]` until a follow-up iteration rewrites the packet. Downgraded findings have their `finalSeverity` updated. The original severity is preserved in the iteration file for audit trail.\n\n#### Step 4b: Generate Dashboard\n\nGenerate `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-dashboard.md` with review-specific sections:\n\n| Section | Content |\n|---------|---------|\n| Status | Provisional verdict (`PASS`/`CONDITIONAL`/`FAIL`/`PENDING`) and `hasAdvisories` flag |\n| Findings Summary | P0/P1/P2 counts with deltas from previous iteration |\n| Progress Table | Iteration number, focus dimension, `newFindingsRatio`, findings count, status |\n| Coverage | Files reviewed, dimensions completed, traceability protocol status |\n| Trend | Last 3 `newFindingsRatio` values with direction indicator (ascending/descending/flat) |\n| Active Risks | Guard violations, stuck count, budget warnings |\n\nDashboard behavior:\n- Auto-generated only -- never manually edited\n- Overwritten each iteration (not appended)\n- Non-blocking: if generation fails, log a warning and continue the loop\n- In **confirm mode**: displayed to the user at each iteration approval gate\n- In **auto mode**: written silently for post-hoc review\n\n#### Step 5: Loop Decision\n\n- If convergence check returns STOP: exit to synthesis\n- If STUCK_RECOVERY: apply review-specific recovery strategies (see Section 3a), reset stuck count, continue\n- Otherwise: increment iteration counter, go to Step 1\n\n### Stuck Recovery (Review-Specific)\n\n**Threshold:** 2 consecutive no-progress iterations (`noProgressThreshold = 0.05`).\n\n| Failure Mode | Detection | Recovery Strategy |\n|-------------|-----------|-------------------|\n| Same dimension stuck | Last 2 iterations reviewed the same dimension with ratios `< 0.05` | **Change granularity**: if reviewing at file level, zoom into functions, if reviewing functions, zoom out to module level |\n| Traceability plateau | Required protocols remain partial while ratios stay `< 0.05` | **Protocol-first replay**: re-run the unresolved traceability protocol directly against the conflicting artifacts |\n| Low-value advisory churn | Last 2 iterations found only P2 work | **Escalate severity review**: explicitly search for P0/P1 patterns or downgrade unsupported severity claims |\n\n**Selection logic**:\n\n```\nfunction selectReviewRecoveryStrategy(stuckIterations, state, config):\n  lastFocuses = [i.focus for i in stuckIterations[-2:]]\n\n  // Same dimension stuck? Change granularity\n  if len(set(lastFocuses)) <= 1:\n    return { strategy: \"change_granularity\", dimension: lastFocuses[0] }\n\n  // Required protocol plateau?\n  if hasRequiredProtocolPlateau(state.traceabilityChecks):\n    return { strategy: \"protocol_first_replay\" }\n\n  // Default: escalate severity\n  return { strategy: \"escalate_severity_review\" }\n```\n\n**Recovery evaluation**:\n- If recovery iteration finds any new P0/P1 or materially advances required traceability coverage: recovery successful. Reset stuck count. Continue.\n- If recovery iteration finds only P2 or nothing: recovery failed. If all dimensions are already covered, exit to synthesis. Otherwise, move to the next unreviewed dimension.\n\n---\n\n## 4. PHASE 3: SYNTHESIS\n\n### Purpose\n\nCompile all iteration findings into the final `{artifact_dir}/review-report.md`. The synthesis phase owns the canonical review report output.\n\n### Steps\n\n#### Step 1: Finding Registry Deduplication\n\nConsolidate findings across all iterations:\n\n1. Read all iteration files: `{artifact_dir}/iterations/iteration-*.md`\n2. Group findings by file + line range + root cause\n3. Merge duplicates, keeping the highest severity and all evidence\n4. Assign final finding IDs: `F001`, `F002`, ...\n5. Preserve the audit trail: note which iterations contributed to each merged finding\n\n#### Step 2: Severity Reconciliation\n\nUse adjudicated `finalSeverity` for any P0/P1 that was downgraded during claim adjudication (Step 4a of the iteration loop). The original severity from the iteration file is preserved in the audit appendix.\n\n#### Step 3: Replay Validation\n\nRecompute the convergence outcome from JSONL state before finalizing the report:\n\n1. Read `deep-review-state.jsonl` and select review-mode iteration records in run order\n2. Recompute `newFindingsRatio`, rolling-average votes, MAD votes, and coverage votes from stored JSONL fields only\n3. Recompute `traceabilityChecks.summary` and confirm required protocol statuses match the recorded coverage vote\n4. Re-run the evidence, scope, and coverage gates against stored findings and scope data\n5. Compare the replayed decision and stop reason to the recorded synthesis event\n\nThis synthesis-stage replay is a **full-history audit replay** over the stored JSONL state. It follows the same full-history replay discipline as the per-iteration reducer refresh above, but runs as an explicit pre-synthesis audit.\n\nReplay passes only when the recomputed decision, thresholds, and gate outcomes agree with the persisted result. If replay fails, log a warning in the audit appendix but proceed with synthesis.\n\n#### Step 4: Compile review-report.md\n\nGenerate the 9 core review-report sections (defined in `review_mode_contract.yaml` under `outputs.reviewReport`) and insert `## Resource Map Coverage Gate` between `Traceability Status` and `Deferred Items` when `config.resource_map_present == true`:\n\n| # | Section | Purpose |\n|---|---------|---------|\n| 1 | Executive Summary | Verdict, active P0/P1/P2 counts, scope, `hasAdvisories` metadata |\n| 2 | Planning Trigger | Why the verdict routes to planning or changelog follow-up |\n| 3 | Active Finding Registry | Deduplicated active findings with evidence and final severity |\n| 4 | Remediation Workstreams | Grouped action lanes derived from active findings |\n| 5 | Spec Seed | Minimal spec delta derived from review results |\n| 6 | Plan Seed | Action-ready plan starter for remediation |\n| 7 | Traceability Status | Core vs overlay protocol status and unresolved gaps |\n| 8 | Resource Map Coverage Gate | Present only when `config.resource_map_present == true`, reports touched entries, untouched entries (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`), and implementation paths absent from the map |\n| 9 | Deferred Items | P2 advisories, blocked checks, and follow-up items |\n| 10 | Audit Appendix | Coverage, replay validation, convergence evidence |\n\n#### Step 5: Verdict Determination\n\nApply the verdict contract from `review_mode_contract.yaml`:\n\n| Verdict | Condition | Next Command |\n|---------|-----------|--------------|\n| **FAIL** | Active P0 remains OR any required binary gate fails | `/speckit:plan` for remediation |\n| **CONDITIONAL** | No active P0, but active P1 remains | `/speckit:plan` for fixes |\n| **PASS** | No active P0/P1 | `/create:changelog` |\n\nWhen `PASS` verdict is issued and active P2 findings remain, set `hasAdvisories = true` in the report metadata.\n\n#### Step 6: Finalize State\n\n1. Update config status: Set `status: \"complete\"` in `deep-review-config.json`\n2. Write final JSONL entry:\n   ```json\n   {\n     \"type\": \"event\",\n     \"event\": \"synthesis_complete\",\n     \"mode\": \"review\",\n     \"totalIterations\": N,\n     \"verdict\": \"PASS|CONDITIONAL|FAIL\",\n     \"activeP0\": N,\n     \"activeP1\": N,\n     \"activeP2\": N,\n     \"dimensionCoverage\": X,\n     \"stopReason\": \"...\",\n     \"timestamp\": \"...\"\n   }\n   ```\n\n---\n\n## 5. PHASE 4: SAVE\n\n### Purpose\n\nPreserve review context to the memory system for future session recovery and cross-session continuity.\n\n### Steps\n\n1. **Compose context payload**: Create a structured JSON payload with the review summary, active findings, verdict, next action, and relevant artifacts. Use `specFolder` for the target packet and include curated `observations`, `recent_context`, `toolCalls`, and `exchanges` when available.\n\n2. **Generate context**: Run the memory save script with structured JSON via `--stdin`, `--json`, or a session-scoped JSON file:\n   ```bash\n   node .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/dist/memory/generate-context.js --json '{\"specFolder\":\"{spec_folder}\",\"sessionSummary\":\"Deep review completed; see review/review-report.md for verdict and findings.\"}' {spec_folder}\n   ```\n\n3. **No extra indexing step in the live contract**: `generate-context.js` is the supported save boundary for this workflow.\n\n4. **Verify**: Confirm the routed canonical spec document carries the review continuity update. Expected targets are `implementation-summary.md`, `decision-record.md`, or `handover.md`; standalone `memory/*.md` files are retired and should not be created.\n\n### On Save Failure\n\nIf memory save fails:\n- Preserve the current `review/` packet as backup (the disk state is the ground truth)\n- Log the error\n- The review results remain intact in `{artifact_dir}/review-report.md` regardless of memory save status\n\n---\n\n## 6. AUTO-RESUME PROTOCOL\n\n### Purpose\n\nEnable review sessions to resume cleanly from prior state when interrupted by context compaction, process termination, or intentional pause.\n\n### Resume Detection\n\nIf state files already exist from a prior session:\n\n1. **Verify agreement**: Confirm config, JSONL, findings registry, and strategy all exist and agree on target/spec folder\n2. **Count progress**: Read JSONL, count iteration records, determine last completed iteration\n3. **Read strategy**: Load current dimension progress, findings, and next focus from `deep-review-strategy.md`\n4. **Set counter**: Set iteration counter to last completed + 1\n5. **Log resume**: Append the canonical resume event to `deep-review-state.jsonl`. The reducer requires every field below:\n   ```json\n   {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"resumed\",\"mode\":\"review\",\"sessionId\":\"rvw-2026-03-24T10-00-00Z\",\"parentSessionId\":\"rvw-2026-03-24T10-00-00Z\",\"lineageMode\":\"resume\",\"continuedFromRun\":4,\"generation\":1,\"archivedPath\":null,\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-24T14:05:00Z\"}\n   ```\n6. **Continue**: Enter the iteration loop from step_read_state\n\n### Lifecycle Branches (current release)\n\nThe runtime supports three lineage modes today. `fork` and `completed-continue` were described in earlier drafts but have no workflow wiring in this release, so they MUST NOT be exposed to operators. If the long-form lineage feature is picked up later it will arrive with first-class event emission, reducer ancestry handling, and replay fixtures. Until then treat the contract below as canonical.\n\n| Mode | Session id | Generation | Archive | JSONL event | When to pick |\n|------|-----------|-----------|---------|-------------|--------------|\n| `new` | fresh | 1 | n/a | implicit (config record) | no existing state |\n| `resume` | same | same | none | `resumed` (see example above) | operator wants to continue the current lineage boundary |\n| `restart` | fresh | `prior + 1` | prior `review/` tree moved under `review_archive/{timestamp}/` | `restarted` (same field set plus non-null `archivedPath`) | operator wants to clear the workspace and replay with a new angle |\n\n**Contract for every persisted lifecycle event**:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"resumed | restarted\",\n  \"mode\": \"review\",\n  \"sessionId\": \"<session id of the new or continuing lineage>\",\n  \"parentSessionId\": \"<session id of the prior lineage (equals sessionId on resume)>\",\n  \"lineageMode\": \"resume | restart\",\n  \"generation\": <number>,\n  \"continuedFromRun\": <number or null>,\n  \"archivedPath\": \"<path or null>\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"<ISO 8601>\"\n}\n```\n\nEvery field in the contract MUST be present on every persisted lifecycle event. `archivedPath` is null for `resumed` and set to the archive destination for `restarted`. `continuedFromRun` is the number of completed iteration records before the lifecycle boundary. Reducer parity tests ensure the dashboard `Lifecycle` section reads exactly those fields.\n\n### State Validation on Resume\n\n| Condition | Classification | Action |\n|-----------|---------------|--------|\n| Config + JSONL + strategy all exist and agree | `resume` | Continue from last iteration + 1 |\n| All exist, config says `status: \"complete\"` | `completed-session` | Report completion, ask user if re-review desired |\n| Partial files or contradictions | `invalid-state` | Halt for repair, do not guess |\n| No files exist | `fresh` | Start new initialization |\n\n### State Recovery Cascade\n\nWhen state files are missing or corrupted, apply this priority cascade:\n\n| Priority | Condition | Recovery Action |\n|----------|-----------|----------------|\n| 1 | JSONL exists and parseable | Normal operation |\n| 2 | JSONL exists, strategy.md missing | Reconstruct strategy from JSONL: extract dimensions, findings, coverage |\n| 3 | JSONL missing, iteration files exist | Scan `review/iterations/iteration-*.md`, reconstruct JSONL with `status: \"reconstructed\"` |\n| 4 | Only config.json remains | Restart from initialization phase |\n| 5 | Config.json also missing | Cannot recover. Report error and halt. |\n\nEach priority level is attempted in order. If a level fails, fall through to the next.\n\n---\n\n## 7. PAUSE/RESUME\n\n### Pause Sentinel Behavior\n\nThe pause sentinel provides graceful loop suspension in autonomous mode without killing the process.\n\n### Creating a Pause\n\nCreate the sentinel file at any time:\n\n```bash\ntouch {artifact_dir}/.deep-review-pause\n```\n\nThe orchestrator checks for this file between iterations (Step 2a). When detected:\n- The current iteration is allowed to complete\n- The loop halts before dispatching the next iteration\n- A paused event is logged to JSONL\n- The user is notified with current state (iteration count, dimensions covered, findings)\n\n### Resuming After Pause\n\nDelete the sentinel file and restart the workflow:\n\n```bash\nrm {artifact_dir}/.deep-review-pause\n```\n\nOn the next invocation:\n- The auto-resume protocol (Section 6) detects the existing state\n- A resumed event is logged to JSONL\n- The loop continues from the next iteration\n\n### Confirm Mode Approval Gates\n\nIn confirm mode (`deep_review_confirm.yaml`), the workflow adds explicit approval gates instead of relying on the pause sentinel:\n\n| Gate Location | Behavior |\n|---------------|----------|\n| After initialization | Show config, strategy, and scope. Wait for approval |\n| After each iteration | Show iteration findings, dashboard, and convergence status. Options: Continue, Adjust Focus, Stop |\n| Before synthesis | Show summary of all iterations. Wait for approval to synthesize |\n| After synthesis | Show final review-report.md summary. Approve or request revisions |\n\n---\n\n## 8. STATE TRANSITIONS, ERROR HANDLING, AND QUALITY GATES\n\nState-transition rules, error handling, and the review quality gates live in `loop_state_and_gates.md` for navigability.\n\n---\n\n## 11. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n### Shared Protocol Documentation\n\nProtocol documents from `deep-research` are cross-referenced, not duplicated:\n\n| Document | Path | Purpose |\n|----------|------|---------|\n| Loop Protocol (research) | `../deep-research/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md` | Research loop lifecycle (this file adapts Section 9) |\n| State Format | `../deep-research/references/state/state_format.md` | JSONL, strategy, and config schemas |\n| Convergence | `../deep-research/references/convergence/convergence.md` | `shouldContinue_review()` (Section 10), stuck recovery, quality guards |\n\n### Review-Specific Resources\n\n| Resource | Path | Purpose |\n|----------|------|---------|\n| Review Contract | `assets/review_mode_contract.yaml` | Single source of truth for dimensions, verdicts, gates, protocols |\n| Quick Reference | `references/protocol/quick_reference.md` | One-page review cheat sheet |\n| Strategy Template | `assets/deep_review_strategy.md` | Template for review strategy files |\n| Config Template | `assets/deep_review_config.json` | Template for review config files |\n| Dashboard Template | `assets/deep_review_dashboard.md` | Template for auto-generated dashboard |\n\n### Workflow Files\n\n| Mode | Path |\n|------|------|\n| Auto (unattended) | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml` |\n| Confirm (step-by-step) | `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_confirm.yaml` |\n\n### Agent\n\n| Agent | Path Pattern | Constraint |\n|-------|-------------|------------|\n| `@deep-review` | `{runtime_dir}/deep-review.{ext}` | LEAF-only, no sub-agents, no WebFetch, target files read-only |\n\nRuntime paths:\n- OpenCode / Copilot: `.opencode/agents/deep-review.md`\n- Claude: `.claude/agents/deep-review.md`\n\n---\n\n## Executor Selection Contract\n\nExecutor settings are owned by the YAML workflow and rendered prompt pack. Do not bypass the workflow by hand-dispatching review iterations; each iteration stays LEAF-only and produces the required markdown plus JSONL delta.\n\n### Invariants\n\nEvery executor path MUST satisfy:\n\n1. Produce an iteration markdown file at `{state_paths.iteration_pattern}` (non-empty).\n2. Append a JSONL delta record to `{state_paths.state_log}` with required fields: `type`, `iteration`, `dimensions`, `filesReviewed`, `findingsSummary`, `findingsNew`, `findingDetails`, `newFindingsRatio`.\n3. Respect the LEAF-agent constraint: no sub-dispatch, no nested loops. Max 12 tool calls per iteration.\n\n### Failure Modes\n\n- Missing iteration file: `iteration_file_missing` from `post-dispatch-validate.ts`, emits a `schema_mismatch` conflict event.\n- Empty iteration file: `iteration_file_empty`, same downstream.\n- JSONL not appended: `jsonl_not_appended`.\n- JSONL missing required fields: `jsonl_missing_fields`.\n- JSONL malformed: `jsonl_parse_error`.\n- 3 consecutive failures: existing `stuck_recovery` event (unchanged).\n\n### JSONL Audit Field\n\nNon-native executor runs append an `executor` block with model and runtime settings to the iteration's JSONL record via `executor-audit.ts`. Native runs are recoverable from YAML alone.\n\n### Template And Config Surface\n\nThe executor-agnostic iteration prompt lives at `assets/prompt_pack_iteration.md.tmpl`, rendered by `prompt-pack.ts` before dispatch and either injected as the agent's context (native) or piped to `opencode run` stdin (cli-opencode). Config is in `assets/deep_review_config.json` under the `executor` key; schema in `runtime//lib/deep-loop/executor-config.ts`. CLI flag precedence: `--executor/--model/--reasoning-effort/--service-tier/--executor-timeout > config file > schema default`.\n\n### What Never Changes Regardless Of Executor Route\n\n- YAML owns state (`deep-review-state.jsonl`, strategy.md, registry, dashboard).\n- `reduce-state.cjs` is the single state writer.\n- Convergence detection, lifecycle events (new/resume/restart), the review dimensions pass, and stuck_recovery stay YAML-driven.\n- The `@deep-review` LEAF agent definition is untouched: it is the native executor, not the only one.\n\n### Code-Graph Readiness TrustState Surface\n\nOn this skill surface, the live code-graph readiness contract only reaches four TrustState values: `live`, `stale`, `absent`, and `unavailable`. The values `cached`, `imported`, `rebuilt`, and `rehomed` remain declared in the shared TrustState type for compatibility and downstream schema stability, but the seven code-graph handlers and readiness helpers used here do not emit them today.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":765,"totalLines":765,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/loop_protocol.md","time":{"start":1783806723737,"end":1783806723741}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb0398588191adae18b6824d1a7a"}},"id":"prt_f532a868b001rS6eaMbzjGZynd","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723765,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_QejjmC6LsLV3sxgdrxInzwWu","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/convergence/convergence.md","offset":1,"limit":1500},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/convergence/convergence.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Review Convergence\n3: description: Stop condition algorithms, quality guards, and recovery strategies for the autonomous deep review loop.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"review convergence detection\"\n6:   - \"severity weighted stop ratio\"\n7:   - \"legal stop gate bundle\"\n8:   - \"review stuck detection\"\n9:   - \"composite convergence vote\"\n10: importance_tier: important\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.11.0.22\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Deep Review Convergence\n16: \n17: Stop condition algorithms, quality guards, and stuck recovery for the deep review loop.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Purpose\n24: \n25: Convergence detection determines when the autonomous review loop should stop iterating. After every iteration the orchestrator evaluates three possible outcomes:\n26: \n27: | Outcome | Meaning |\n28: |---------|---------|\n29: | **CONTINUE** | More review work is expected to yield meaningful new findings. Dispatch the next iteration. |\n30: | **STOP** | The review has reached saturation. Proceed to synthesis and verdict. |\n31: | **STUCK_RECOVERY** | No progress detected for consecutive iterations. Attempt a recovery strategy before deciding. |\n32: \n33: Convergence is checked **after** each iteration completes and **before** the next iteration is dispatched. The check consumes the full JSONL state history and the current dimension coverage snapshot.\n34: \n35: Release-readiness states are derived alongside convergence:\n36: - `in-progress` while coverage is incomplete or new P0/P1 findings are still appearing\n37: - `converged` once coverage and stabilization pass without new P0/P1 findings\n38: - `release-blocking` whenever unresolved P0 findings remain active\n39: \n40: When the loop stops and enters synthesis, the workflow emits `{artifact_dir}/resource-map.md` from converged review deltas before compiling `review-report.md`. Operators can disable that write with `--no-resource-map`.\n41: \n42: ### When to Use\n43: \n44: - Evaluating whether the autonomous review loop should stop, continue, or recover.\n45: - Tuning convergence thresholds, stuck-recovery cadence, or stabilization windows.\n46: - Debugging a stuck-recovery escalation or a premature STOP vote.\n47: - Auditing the release-readiness classification logic before shipping.\n48: \n49: ### Key Defaults\n50: \n51: | Setting | Value | Purpose |\n52: |---------|-------|---------|\n53: | `maxIterations` | 7 | Hard ceiling on loop iterations |\n54: | `convergenceThreshold` | 0.10 | General convergence sensitivity |\n55: | `rollingStopThreshold` | 0.08 | Rolling-average STOP vote threshold |\n56: | `noProgressThreshold` | 0.05 | Stuck / no-progress classification threshold |\n57: | `stuckThreshold` | 2 | Consecutive no-progress iterations before recovery |\n58: | `minStabilizationPasses` | 1 | Coverage signal requires at least one stabilization pass |\n59: | `compositeStopScore` | 0.60 | Weighted stop-score needed before guard evaluation |\n60: \n61: ### Threshold Semantics and Sibling Parity\n62: \n63: `convergenceThreshold` (default 0.10) compares new severity-weighted findings (P0=10, P1=5, P2=1) against accumulated findings. Lower values demand more iterations and a higher signal threshold before STOP is legal.\n64: \n65: **Not interchangeable with sibling deep-loop skills:**\n66: \n67: | Skill | Default | Signal |\n68: |---|---|---|\n69: | `deep-review` | 0.10 | severity-weighted P0/P1/P2 ratio |\n70: | `deep-research` | 0.05 | newInfoRatio (negative-knowledge emphasis) |\n71: | `deep-ai-council` (proposed) | 0.20 | adjudicator-verdict stability |\n72: \n73: Carrying threshold expectations across siblings will cause unexpected iteration counts. Tune each skill against its own default and its own signal, not by analogy.\n74: \n75: ### Security-Sensitive Fix Overrides\n76: \n77: > **STATUS: SPEC ONLY (future implementation).** The override matrix below describes the contract that a future release should apply automatically when the review target involves security-sensitive surfaces. As of v1.9.0.0, the runtime does NOT auto-detect security-sensitivity and does NOT apply these overrides. `requiredClosedFindingReplay` and `requiredFixCompletenessGate` exist in no config / yaml / reducer surface (verified by grep). Operators running a security-sensitive review must manually tighten thresholds via `--convergence` + `--max-iterations` and manually maintain the closed-gate replay table. The contract below stands as the target spec for the next implementation pass. (Provenance for this deferred contract is recorded in this skill's changelog.)\n78: \n79: For review reruns after fixes involving security, path disclosure, auth/authz, sandboxing, env precedence, public schemas, persistence, or user-visible error payloads (intended contract, not yet runtime-enforced):\n80: \n81: | Setting | General Default | Security-Sensitive Fix Default |\n82: |---------|-----------------|--------------------------------|\n83: | `minStabilizationPasses` | 1 | 2 |\n84: | `requiredClosedFindingReplay` | false | true for prior P0/P1 and any prior security/path P2 |\n85: | `requiredFixCompletenessGate` | false | true |\n86: \n87: When implemented, STOP must not be legal until the review report contains a closed-gate replay table that marks each prior active or remediated P0/P1 as `PASS`, `FAIL`, or `carried forward`, with file:line or command evidence. Operators today must enforce this rule manually.\n88: \n89: ### Shared Stop Contract\n90: \n91: Every terminal stop and every blocked-stop vote MUST emit the shared stop contract from REQ-001: a named `stopReason` enum plus, when STOP is vetoed, a `blocked_stop` event written to `deep-review-state.jsonl`. There is no nested `legalStop` wrapper on the persisted path. Earlier drafts of this document implied one, and that drift was the source of F009 in the 042 closing audit.\n92: \n93: ### Convergence Modes\n94: \n95: The shared convergence runtime accepts four values. Review legality, security gates, target authority, and verdict derivation remain owned by the review workflow rather than the convergence mode.\n96: \n97: | Mode | Live Behavior |\n98: |------|---------------|\n99: | `default` | Uses normal full-history convergence signals and sends a legal STOP to synthesis and verdict derivation. This is the fallback when no mode is supplied. |\n100: | `off` | Is accepted and persisted, but the shipped review YAML has no `off` decision branch; review therefore follows the same legal-stop and synthesis path as `default`. Use `stopPolicy: \"max-iterations\"` when convergence must remain telemetry-only until the iteration ceiling. |\n101: | `sliding-window` | Is accepted and persisted, but windowed graph-novelty telemetry is research-only in the shared runtime; review therefore retains its ordinary full-history signals, legal-stop gates, and synthesis path. |\n102: | `divergent` | After all review gates pass, translates the eligible `all_dimensions_clean` STOP into a read-only three-seat direction-selection pivot and continues with the selected review direction. |\n103: \n104: #### Divergent Pivot Contract\n105: \n106: Review has one eligible reason: the exact internal reason `all_dimensions_clean` with decision `STOP`. The nine legal-stop gates run before the divergent branch and remain unchanged. `maxIterationsReached`, `blockedStop`, `stuckRecovery`, `error`, `manualStop`, and `userPaused` are explicitly excluded. Max iterations, pause or cancellation, manual stop, unrecoverable error, and any blocked security or quality gate therefore never dispatch a pivot Council.\n107: \n108: Each eligible pivot runs one native, in-process Council round with exactly three distinct seats: analytical, critical, and pragmatic. It does not use an external CLI. The transaction requires all three seat returns to be parse-valid and at least two seats to materially endorse the same candidate without a high-severity blocker. Candidate sources are persisted unswept dimensions, search debt, producer-consumer gaps, negative-test gaps, and traceability gaps. Candidate generation rejects directions without in-scope evidence and directions that imply implementation, a fix, mutation, writing, or target expansion.\n109: \n110: The guarantees are absolute: divergent mode never changes the PASS/CONDITIONAL/FAIL mapping, never authorizes a fix, and never makes the review target writable. A successful pivot returns to the loop before `phase_synthesis`; verdict computation exists only inside `phase_synthesis`, where active P0 yields FAIL, active P1 yields CONDITIONAL, and no active P0/P1 yields PASS. A failed pivot fails closed to that existing synthesis path.\n111: \n112: Every pivot dispatches three seats, so a run that pivots has proportionally higher model cost and duration than the same run under `default`, `off`, or `sliding-window`. Pivot evidence is isolated under `<artifactRoot>/divergent/pivots/<pivotId>/council/**`, including config, append-only state, three seat artifacts, deliberation, and report. This path is distinct from ordinary planning Council artifacts under a spec packet's `ai-council/**` tree.\n113: \n114: #### stopReason Enum\n115: \n116: | `stopReason` | Meaning |\n117: |--------------|---------|\n118: | `converged` | All convergence signals met and legal-stop gates passed. |\n119: | `maxIterationsReached` | Iteration limit hit before convergence. |\n120: | `userPaused` | User requested pause via sentinel. |\n121: | `blockedStop` | Convergence math voted stop but legal-stop gates failed. |\n122: | `stuckRecovery` | Stuck detection triggered recovery. |\n123: | `error` | Unrecoverable error during iteration or reducer flow. |\n124: | `manualStop` | Operator explicitly halted outside the pause sentinel path. |\n125: \n126: #### blocked_stop Event (canonical, persisted)\n127: \n128: `step_emit_blocked_stop` in both `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml` appends the following record to `deep-review-state.jsonl` whenever the legal-stop decision tree vetoes STOP. The gate names and their shapes are load-bearing, the reducer reads them verbatim:\n129: \n130: ```json\n131: {\n132:   \"type\": \"event\",\n133:   \"event\": \"blocked_stop\",\n134:   \"mode\": \"review\",\n135:   \"run\": 5,\n136:   \"blockedBy\": [\"dimensionCoverageGate\", \"p0ResolutionGate\"],\n137:   \"gateResults\": {\n138:     \"convergenceGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"score\": 0.72 },\n139:     \"dimensionCoverageGate\": {\n140:       \"pass\": false,\n141:       \"covered\": [\"correctness\", \"security\", \"traceability\"],\n142:       \"missing\": [\"maintainability\"]\n143:     },\n144:     \"p0ResolutionGate\": { \"pass\": false, \"activeP0\": 1 },\n145:     \"evidenceDensityGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"avgEvidencePerFinding\": 1.6 },\n146:     \"hotspotSaturationGate\": { \"pass\": true },\n147:     \"claimAdjudicationGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"activeP0P1\": 2 },\n148:     \"fixCompletenessReplayGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"securitySensitive\": false, \"requiredRows\": 0, \"passingRows\": 0 },\n149:     \"candidateCoverageGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"searchDebt\": [], \"missing\": [] },\n150:     \"graphlessFallbackGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"mode\": \"graph_available\", \"missing\": [], \"unavailabilityReason\": \"\" }\n151:   },\n152:   \"graphBlockerDetail\": [],\n153:   \"recoveryStrategy\": \"Dispatch the next iteration at the maintainability dimension and re-check after resolving the remaining P0.\",\n154:   \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-24T15:02:00Z\",\n155:   \"sessionId\": \"rvw-2026-03-24T10-00-00Z\",\n156:   \"generation\": 1\n157: }\n158: ```\n159: \n160: - `blockedBy`: array of gate names that failed (string[], never structured objects). Empty when STOP is legal, in which case no `blocked_stop` event is emitted.\n161: - `gateResults`: named sub-records keyed by `convergenceGate`, `dimensionCoverageGate`, `p0ResolutionGate`, `evidenceDensityGate`, `hotspotSaturationGate`, `claimAdjudicationGate`, `fixCompletenessReplayGate`, `candidateCoverageGate`, and `graphlessFallbackGate`. This is the full 9-gate set emitted by `step_emit_blocked_stop` in both `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml`. Each sub-record has a `pass` boolean plus gate-specific fields (score, covered/missing, activeP0, avgEvidencePerFinding, activeP0P1, securitySensitive, requiredRows, passingRows, searchDebt, mode, unavailabilityReason). The reducer reads these verbatim and does not coerce shapes. `candidateCoverageGate` and `graphlessFallbackGate` are v2-rollout gates, they pass trivially when the review-depth-v2 search path is inactive (no search debt, graph available).\n162: - `graphBlockerDetail`: array of structured graph blockers copied from the latest graph convergence decision. Empty when graph convergence did not veto STOP.\n163: - `recoveryStrategy`: human-readable one-liner describing what the next iteration should do before another stop attempt.\n164: - When the graph convergence verdict is `STOP_BLOCKED`, fold the graph blocker gate name into `blockedBy` and preserve the structured blocker objects under `graphBlockerDetail`.\n165: \n166: ### Decision Priority\n167: \n168: Checks are evaluated in this order (first match wins):\n169: \n170: 1. **Max iterations** -- hard cap, always checked first.\n171: 2. **All dimensions covered + clean** -- all 4 dimensions covered, no active P0/P1, stabilization passed, gates passed.\n172: 3. **Stuck detection** -- 2+ consecutive no-progress iterations.\n173: 4. **Composite convergence** -- 3-signal weighted vote with threshold 0.60.\n174: 5. **Legal-stop gate bundle** -- review-specific stop gates. If a stop vote fails any gate, persist `stopReason=blockedStop` and continue.\n175: 6. **Default CONTINUE** -- none of the above triggered.\n176: \n177: ---\n178: \n179: ## 2. HARD STOPS\n180: \n181: Hard stops are evaluated first and override all other signals.\n182: \n183: ### Max Iterations Reached\n184: \n185: ```\n186: if len(iterations) >= config.maxIterations:       // default 7\n187:   return { action: \"STOP\", stopReason: \"maxIterationsReached\" }\n188: ```\n189: \n190: The loop stops unconditionally. Synthesis runs with whatever findings exist.\n191: \n192: ### All Dimensions Covered with Stabilization\n193: \n194: ```\n195: if coverage.dimensionCoverage == 1.0 and activeP0 == 0 and activeP1 == 0:\n196:   if stabilizationPasses >= config.coverageAge.minStabilizationPasses:\n197:     if buildReviewLegalStop(state, config, coverage).passed:\n198:       return { action: \"STOP\", stopReason: \"converged\" }\n199: ```\n200: \n201: Triggers when all 4 dimensions (correctness, security, traceability, maintainability) are covered, no active P0/P1 remains, at least 1 stabilization pass has occurred, and the 5-gate legal-stop bundle passes. If gates fail, the loop records `stopReason=blockedStop` and continues despite full coverage.\n202: \n203: ---\n204: \n205: ## 3. STUCK DETECTION\n206: \n207: Identifies when the review loop makes no meaningful progress across consecutive iterations.\n208: \n209: ```\n210: function countConsecutiveStuck_review(evidenceIterations, noProgressThreshold):\n211:   count = 0\n212:   for i in reversed(evidenceIterations):\n213:     if i.status == \"thought\":   continue    // invisible to stuck counter\n214:     if i.status == \"insight\":   break       // resets stuck counter (genuine progress)\n215:     if i.newFindingsRatio < noProgressThreshold or i.status == \"stuck\":\n216:       count += 1\n217:     else:\n218:       break\n219:   return count\n220: ```\n221: \n222: **Threshold:** `stuckThreshold = 2` consecutive no-progress iterations (using `noProgressThreshold = 0.05`).\n223: \n224: **Status exclusions:**\n225: - `insight`: Resets stuck counter -- a conceptual breakthrough counts as progress even with a low ratio.\n226: - `thought`: Skipped entirely -- analytical iterations produce no evidence to measure.\n227: \n228: When `stuckCount >= stuckThreshold`, the orchestrator invokes the recovery protocol (Section 8) before deciding whether to continue or stop.\n229: \n230: The recovery entry uses `stopReason=stuckRecovery` while the loop is in recovery. If recovery later terminates the run, the terminal record keeps the same shared enum value instead of minting a review-only label.\n231: \n232: ---\n233: \n234: ## 4. COMPOSITE CONVERGENCE\n235: \n236: Three independent signals each cast a stop/continue vote. Stop when the weighted stop-score meets or exceeds the consensus threshold. The signal set below matches the authoritative 3-signal vote in `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml` `step_check_convergence` and the quick-reference convergence table, the 3rd signal is **dimension coverage**, not a standalone novelty ratio.\n237: \n238: | Signal | Weight | Min Iterations | Measures |\n239: |--------|--------|---------------|----------|\n240: | Rolling Average | 0.30 | 2 | Recent severity-weighted finding yield |\n241: | MAD Noise Floor | 0.25 | 3 | Signal vs noise in newFindingsRatio |\n242: | Dimension Coverage | 0.45 | 1 | Configured review dimensions fully covered AND required traceability protocols covered AND `coverage_age >= minStabilizationPasses` |\n243: \n244: ### Signal 1: Rolling Average (weight 0.30)\n245: \n246: Averages the last 2 severity-weighted `newFindingsRatio` values from evidence-bearing iterations (excludes `thought` status). Votes STOP when the average drops below `rollingStopThreshold` (0.08).\n247: \n248: ```\n249: if len(evidenceIterations) >= 2:\n250:   recent = evidenceIterations[-2:]\n251:   avgRatio = mean(i.newFindingsRatio for i in recent)\n252:   rollingStop = avgRatio < 0.08\n253: ```\n254: \n255: ### Signal 2: MAD Noise Floor (weight 0.25)\n256: \n257: Robust statistical test using Median Absolute Deviation. Votes STOP when the latest ratio is at or below the computed noise floor.\n258: \n259: ```\n260: if len(evidenceIterations) >= 3:\n261:   allRatios = [i.newFindingsRatio for i in evidenceIterations]\n262:   med = median(allRatios)\n263:   mad = median([abs(r - med) for r in allRatios])\n264:   noiseFloor = mad * 1.4826     // normal distribution estimator\n265:   madStop = evidenceIterations[-1].newFindingsRatio <= noiseFloor\n266: ```\n267: \n268: ### Signal 3: Dimension Coverage (weight 0.45)\n269: \n270: Highest-weight signal. Votes STOP once every configured review dimension AND every required traceability protocol has been covered by at least one iteration, and the coverage set has been stable for at least `minStabilizationPasses` iterations (default 1). This is the signal the YAML workflow evaluates.\n271: \n272: ```\n273: dimensionStop =\n274:   dimensions_covered_count == configured_dimensions_count\n275:   AND required_traceability_protocols_covered\n276:   AND coverage_age >= config.minStabilizationPasses\n277: ```\n278: \n279: The latest severity-weighted newFindingsRatio is still tracked (the dashboard and registry surface it as `newFindingsRatio`), but it does NOT cast an independent stop vote, it feeds the rolling average and MAD noise-floor signals only.\n280: \n281: ### Weighted Vote\n282: \n283: ```\n284: stopScore = sum(s.weight * (1 if s.stop else 0) for s in signals) / totalWeight\n285: if stopScore >= 0.60:   // proceed to quality gate evaluation\n286: ```\n287: \n288: Weights are redistributed across active signals only. If only 2 signals have enough data, their weights are normalized to sum to 1.0.\n289: \n290: ### Semantic Convergence Signals\n291: \n292: Two additional signals provide deeper semantic analysis of review iteration quality. These signals are ADDITIONAL to the 3-signal composite vote above and participate in the legal-stop gate evaluation rather than the composite stop-score.\n293: \n294: #### semanticNovelty (0.0-1.0)\n295: \n296: Measures how much genuinely new review insight each iteration contributes beyond surface-level overlap with prior findings. Unlike `newFindingsRatio` (which is severity-weighted), `semanticNovelty` evaluates the conceptual novelty of findings independent of severity weighting.\n297: \n298: | Value | Meaning |\n299: |-------|---------|\n300: | 0.8-1.0 | Iteration uncovered substantially new defect patterns, architectural concerns, or review angles |\n301: | 0.4-0.7 | Mix of new review insights and restatements of prior findings |\n302: | 0.1-0.3 | Mostly refinements or rewordings of previously identified issues |\n303: | 0.0 | No semantically novel findings detected |\n304: \n305: Computation:\n306: ```\n307: function computeSemanticNovelty_review(currentFindings, priorCumulativeFindings):\n308:   newPatterns = extractDefectPatterns(currentFindings) - extractDefectPatterns(priorCumulativeFindings)\n309:   totalPatterns = extractDefectPatterns(currentFindings)\n310:   if len(totalPatterns) == 0: return 0.0\n311:   return len(newPatterns) / len(totalPatterns)\n312: ```\n313: \n314: When `semanticNovelty` drops below 0.15 for 2+ consecutive evidence iterations, it provides strong supporting evidence for a legal STOP decision. This signal catches cases where `newFindingsRatio` stays moderate (due to severity weighting of refinements) but the review has exhausted genuinely new defect categories.\n315: \n316: #### findingStability (0.0-1.0)\n317: \n318: Measures how stable the cumulative finding set is across iterations. A high stability score means the finding registry is not materially changing between iterations -- findings are not being added, upgraded, downgraded, or invalidated at a significant rate.\n319: \n320: | Value | Meaning |\n321: |-------|---------|\n322: | 0.9-1.0 | Finding set is highly stable, minimal churn between iterations |\n323: | 0.6-0.8 | Moderate stability, some findings still evolving |\n324: | 0.3-0.5 | Active churn, findings being added, merged, or reclassified frequently |\n325: | 0.0-0.2 | Highly unstable, the review is still in early discovery |\n326: \n327: Computation:\n328: ```\n329: function computeFindingStability(currentRegistry, priorRegistry):\n330:   if priorRegistry is null: return 0.0  // first iteration\n331:   unchangedFindings = count(f for f in currentRegistry\n332:     if f.id in priorRegistry and f.severity == priorRegistry[f.id].severity\n333:     and f.status == priorRegistry[f.id].status)\n334:   totalFindings = max(len(currentRegistry), len(priorRegistry))\n335:   if totalFindings == 0: return 1.0\n336:   return unchangedFindings / totalFindings\n337: ```\n338: \n339: Convergence behavior:\n340: - `findingStability >= 0.85` supports STOP: the finding set has stabilized and further iterations are unlikely to materially change the review outcome.\n341: - `findingStability < 0.50` prevents STOP: the finding set is still in flux and the review has not reached a stable assessment.\n342: \n343: #### Integration with Legal-Stop Gate Bundle\n344: \n345: The two semantic signals integrate with the existing 5-gate legal-stop bundle (Section 6):\n346: \n347: 1. **findingStability gate** (existing): The existing `findingStability` gate already evaluates rolling average, MAD noise floor, and novelty ratio. The new `semanticNovelty` signal adds a sub-check:\n348:    - `semanticNoveltyPlateau`: `semanticNovelty < 0.15` for 2+ consecutive evidence iterations\n349:    - When this sub-check fails while the existing churn signals pass, the gate records the mismatch as a diagnostic note but does not independently block STOP.\n350: \n351: 2. **findingStability signal** (new): The `findingStability` metric (0.0-1.0) is surfaced alongside the existing convergence signals. It supports the `findingStability` gate evaluation by providing a registry-level stability measure that complements the ratio-based churn signals.\n352: \n353: The gate passes only when both the existing churn-based checks AND the semantic stability checks agree. When a semantic check fails, the persisted `blocked_stop.gateResults.findingStability` payload includes the semantic signal values.\n354: \n355: #### Stop-Decision Trace\n356: \n357: The stop-decision event includes which semantic signals supported or prevented STOP:\n358: \n359: ```json\n360: {\n361:   \"type\": \"event\",\n362:   \"event\": \"stop_decision\",\n363:   \"semanticSignals\": {\n364:     \"semanticNovelty\": { \"value\": 0.06, \"consecutiveLow\": 3, \"supportsStop\": true },\n365:     \"findingStability\": { \"value\": 0.92, \"supportsStop\": true }\n366:   },\n367:   \"semanticVerdict\": \"all_support_stop\",\n368:   ...\n369: }\n370: ```\n371: \n372: | `semanticVerdict` | Meaning |\n373: |-------------------|---------|\n374: | `all_support_stop` | Both semantic signals support stopping |\n375: | `mixed` | One signal supports stop, the other does not |\n376: | `all_prevent_stop` | Both semantic signals indicate more work is needed |\n377: | `insufficient_data` | Not enough iterations to compute semantic signals |\n378: \n379: ### Graceful Degradation\n380: \n381: | Iterations Completed | Active Signals | Behavior |\n382: |---------------------|----------------|----------|\n383: | 1 | Novelty ratio only (weight 1.0) | Very unlikely to stop without later confirmation from rolling churn signals |\n384: | 2 | Rolling avg + novelty ratio | Two-signal vote, reweighted |\n385: | 3+ | All three signals | Full composite, most reliable |\n386: \n387: Semantic convergence signals (`semanticNovelty`, `findingStability`) require at least 2 evidence iterations to produce meaningful values. They are omitted from legal-stop evaluation when insufficient data exists.\n388: \n389: ---\n390: \n391: ## 5. SEVERITY-WEIGHTED RATIO\n392: \n393: The review loop uses `newFindingsRatio` instead of `newInfoRatio`. It weights findings by severity so that critical discoveries count far more than minor suggestions.\n394: \n395: ### Severity Weights\n396: \n397: | Severity | Weight | Description |\n398: |----------|--------|-------------|\n399: | **P0** (Blocker) | 10.0 | Correctness failures, security vulnerabilities, spec contradictions |\n400: | **P1** (Required) | 5.0 | Degraded behavior, incomplete implementation, missing validation |\n401: | **P2** (Suggestion) | 1.0 | Style, naming, minor improvements, documentation gaps |\n402: \n403: ### Computation\n404: \n405: ```\n406: SEVERITY_WEIGHTS = { P0: 10.0, P1: 5.0, P2: 1.0 }\n407: refinementMultiplier = 0.5\n408: \n409: weightedNew       = sum(SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[f.severity] for f in fully_new_findings)\n410: weightedRefinement = sum(SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[f.severity] * 0.5 for f in refinement_findings)\n411: weightedTotal     = sum(SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[f.severity] for f in all_findings_this_iteration)\n412: \n413: newFindingsRatio = (weightedNew + weightedRefinement) / weightedTotal\n414: ```\n415: \n416: - `fully_new_findings` -- findings not present in any prior iteration (new findingId).\n417: - `refinement_findings` -- findings that refine or upgrade an existing finding (same root cause, new evidence or severity change).\n418: - `refinementMultiplier = 0.5` -- refinements count at half weight.\n419: \n420: ### P0 Override Rule\n421: \n422: ```\n423: if ANY new P0 found this iteration:\n424:   newFindingsRatio = max(calculated, 0.50)\n425: \n426: if total_findings == 0:\n427:   newFindingsRatio = 0.0\n428: ```\n429: \n430: A new critical finding always signals significant remaining work. The 0.50 floor prevents premature convergence when critical issues are still being discovered.\n431: \n432: ---\n433: \n434: ## 6. LEGAL-STOP GATE BUNDLE\n435: \n436: > **GATE MODEL, two naming conventions mapped to one authoritative set.** The authoritative producer is `step_emit_blocked_stop` in both `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, which emits **9 gates** with the `Gate` suffix: `convergenceGate` / `dimensionCoverageGate` / `p0ResolutionGate` / `evidenceDensityGate` / `hotspotSaturationGate` / `claimAdjudicationGate` / `fixCompletenessReplayGate` / `candidateCoverageGate` / `graphlessFallbackGate`. The §Section-1 event shape (lines 98-119) mirrors this set verbatim and the reducer reads those names verbatim, so treat the event shape as authoritative when writing or reading JSONL state. The §6 table below is the high-level conceptual model and uses descriptive names WITHOUT the `Gate` suffix where one reads more naturally (for example `findingStability` maps to `convergenceGate`); each row carries its event-shape name so the mapping is explicit. `candidateCoverageGate` and `graphlessFallbackGate` are v2-rollout gates that pass trivially when the review-depth-v2 search path is inactive. The gate-model drift cluster (LG-0013, LG-0016, LG-0031, LG-0032) was reconciled in `006-gate-model-reconciliation`.\n437: \n438: Deep review treats STOP as legal only when the full review-specific gate bundle passes together. Convergence math may request STOP, but the workflow must still evaluate these 9 gates and persist a blocked-stop event when any gate fails.\n439: \n440: | Gate (§6 conceptual) | Event-shape name (§Section-1) | Rule | Fail Action |\n441: |------|------|------|-------------|\n442: | **findingStability** | `convergenceGate` | Rolling average, MAD noise floor, and novelty ratio must all indicate low-yield review churn | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n443: | **dimensionCoverage** | `dimensionCoverageGate` | Every configured review dimension must have been examined at least once, with required traceability coverage stabilized | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n444: | **p0Resolution** | `p0ResolutionGate` | No unresolved P0 findings may remain active at stop time | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n445: | **evidenceDensity** | `evidenceDensityGate` | Evidence density across active findings must meet the configured threshold | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n446: | **hotspotSaturation** | `hotspotSaturationGate` | Review hotspots must be revisited enough times to satisfy the saturation heuristic | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n447: | (no §6 counterpart) | `claimAdjudicationGate` | Each new P0/P1 finding must carry a typed adjudication packet, missing or failing packets veto STOP | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n448: | **fixCompletenessReplay** | `fixCompletenessReplayGate` | Security-sensitive fix reruns must replay previously closed P0/P1 gates and validate producer/consumer/matrix coverage from the remediation packet | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n449: | **candidateCoverage** (v2 rollout) | `candidateCoverageGate` | Search debt must be cleared and every required bug class must have candidate coverage before STOP, passes trivially when the v2 search path is inactive | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n450: | **graphlessFallback** (v2 rollout) | `graphlessFallbackGate` | When the code graph is unavailable, required bug classes must carry cited fallback ledger rows, passes trivially when the graph is available | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n451: \n452: ### Gate Evaluation\n453: \n454: ```\n455: function buildReviewLegalStop(state, config, coverage):\n456:   gateResults = {\n457:     findingStability: {\n458:       pass: rollingStop and madStop and state.latestNoveltyRatio <= config.convergenceThreshold,\n459:       detail: \"Rolling average, MAD noise floor, and novelty ratio are all below stop thresholds.\"\n460:     },\n461:     dimensionCoverage: {\n462:       pass: everyConfiguredDimensionExaminedAtLeastOnce(coverage, config.reviewDimensions) and\n463:             coverage.requiredProtocolsCovered and\n464:             coverage.stabilizationPasses >= 1,\n465:       detail: \"All configured review dimensions have been examined, required traceability protocols are covered, and stabilization has aged enough to stop.\"\n466:     },\n467:     p0Resolution: {\n468:       pass: countActiveFindings(state, [\"P0\"]) == 0 and state.claimAdjudicationPassed != false,\n469:       detail: \"No unresolved P0 findings remain and blocker adjudication is complete.\"\n470:     },\n471:     evidenceDensity: {\n472:       pass: computeEvidenceDensity(state.activeFindings) >= config.evidenceDensityThreshold,\n473:       detail: \"Evidence density meets the configured threshold for active findings.\"\n474:     },\n475:     hotspotSaturation: {\n476:       pass: computeHotspotSaturation(state.hotspots) >= config.hotspotSaturationThreshold,\n477:       detail: \"Priority hotspots received enough revisits to satisfy saturation.\"\n478:     },\n479:     fixCompletenessReplay: {\n480:       pass: not isSecuritySensitiveFixRerun(state, config) or allRequiredReplayRowsPass(state.reviewReport),\n481:       detail: \"Security-sensitive fix reruns include closed-gate replay evidence and producer/consumer/matrix coverage before STOP.\"\n482:     },\n483:     candidateCoverage: {\n484:       pass: not isReviewDepthV2Active(state, config) or (searchDebtCleared(state) and allRequiredBugClassesCovered(state)),\n485:       detail: \"Search debt is cleared and every required bug class has candidate coverage. Passes trivially when the v2 search path is inactive.\"\n486:     },\n487:     graphlessFallback: {\n488:       pass: state.searchCoverage.graphCoverageMode == \"graph_available\" or allRequiredBugClassesHaveFallbackRows(state),\n489:       detail: \"When the code graph is unavailable, required bug classes carry cited fallback ledger rows. Passes trivially when the graph is available.\"\n490:     }\n491:   }\n492: \n493:   blockedBy = [name for name, result in gateResults.items() if not result.pass]\n494:   return {\n495:     pass: len(blockedBy) == 0,\n496:     blockedBy,\n497:     gateResults\n498:   }\n499: ```\n500: \n501: When convergence math returns STOP, invoke `buildReviewLegalStop()`. If it returns `pass: false`, persist a first-class `blocked_stop` event with the failing `blockedBy` gates, the full `gateResults` bundle, a `recoveryStrategy`, and the normal run/timestamp/session lineage fields before overriding the decision to CONTINUE.\n502: \n503: ### Blocked-Stop Recovery Strategy\n504: \n505: | Failed Gate | Recovery Strategy |\n506: |-------------|-------------------|\n507: | `findingStability` | Revisit the noisiest recent dimension and reduce novelty by closing obvious follow-up loops before re-checking STOP. |\n508: | `dimensionCoverage` | Schedule the next uncovered review dimension immediately. |\n509: | `p0Resolution` | Re-open the active blocker path and verify whether the P0 is real, downgraded, or still unresolved. |\n510: | `evidenceDensity` | Re-read weakly supported findings and add concrete `file:line` citations before they count toward a stop decision. |\n511: | `hotspotSaturation` | Revisit undersampled hotspots or adjacent call sites until the saturation heuristic passes. |\n512: | `fixCompletenessReplay` | Replay prior active or remediated P0/P1 gates, then record producer, consumer, and matrix coverage evidence before re-checking STOP. |\n513: | `candidateCoverage` | Clear outstanding search debt and run candidate discovery for the missing bug classes before re-checking STOP. |\n514: | `graphlessFallback` | Add cited fallback ledger rows for the required bug classes, or restore graph availability, before re-checking STOP. |\n515: \n516: ### Legacy Stop-Reason Mapping\n517: \n518: Use this table when replaying old packets or translating older prose/docs into the shared stop contract.\n519: \n520: | Legacy label | New `stopReason` | Mapping note |\n521: |--------------|------------------|--------------|\n522: | `all_dimensions_clean` | `converged` | Legacy review-specific terminal label, now expressed by the shared enum. |\n523: | `composite_converged` | `converged` | Legacy convergence-math wording now rolls into shared terminal success. |\n524: | `all dimensions clean` | `converged` | Old operator-facing prose for the same successful stop. |\n525: | `max_iterations_reached` | `maxIterationsReached` | Legacy machine label for the hard iteration cap. |\n526: | `max iterations` | `maxIterationsReached` | Old operator-facing hard-stop wording. |\n527: | `pause sentinel detected` | `userPaused` | Sentinel pause is now a shared user-directed stop reason. |\n528: | `guard_override` | `blockedStop` | Legacy continue override when a stop vote failed legal gates. |\n529: | `quality guard failed` | `blockedStop` | Older prose for the same blocked-stop outcome. |\n530: | `P0 override blocks convergence` | `blockedStop` | Legacy review wording for a stop attempt that was not legal to finalize. |\n531: | `stuck_detected` | `stuckRecovery` | Legacy recovery trigger label. |\n532: | `stuck_unrecoverable` | `stuckRecovery` | Legacy terminal wording for the same recovery path family. |\n533: | `manual halt` | `manualStop` | Operator-directed halt outside normal pause sentinel flow. |\n534: \n535: ---\n536: \n537: ## 7. PROVISIONAL VERDICT\n538: \n539: The provisional verdict is determined from active findings at the time the loop stops. It appears in both the convergence report and the final `review-report.md`.\n540: \n541: | Verdict | Condition | Meaning |\n542: |---------|-----------|---------|\n543: | **FAIL** | `activeP0 > 0` OR any legal-stop gate fails at terminal stop time | Does not meet quality standards. Blocks release. |\n544: | **CONDITIONAL** | `activeP0 == 0` AND `activeP1 > 0` | Meets threshold but has required fixes before release. |\n545: | **PASS** | `activeP0 == 0` AND `activeP1 == 0` | Shippable. Set `hasAdvisories: true` when `activeP2 > 0`. |\n546: \n547: ### Determination\n548: \n549: ```\n550: function determineVerdict(state, gateResult):\n551:   activeP0 = countActiveFindings(state, [\"P0\"])\n552:   activeP1 = countActiveFindings(state, [\"P1\"])\n553:   activeP2 = countActiveFindings(state, [\"P2\"])\n554: \n555:   if activeP0 > 0 or not gateResult.passed:\n556:     return { verdict: \"FAIL\", nextCommand: \"/speckit:plan\" }\n557:   if activeP1 > 0:\n558:     return { verdict: \"CONDITIONAL\", nextCommand: \"/speckit:plan\" }\n559: \n560:   hasAdvisories = activeP2 > 0\n561:   return { verdict: \"PASS\", hasAdvisories, nextCommand: \"/create:changelog\" }\n562: ```\n563: \n564: ### Post-Verdict Routing\n565: \n566: | Verdict | Next Step |\n567: |---------|-----------|\n568: | FAIL | `/speckit:plan` -- create remediation plan from findings |\n569: | CONDITIONAL | `/speckit:plan` -- create fix plan for P1 findings |\n570: | PASS | `/create:changelog` -- record the clean audit |\n571: \n572: ---\n573: \n574: ## 8. RECOVERY, REPORTING, AND GRAPH-AWARE CONVERGENCE\n575: \n576: Stuck-recovery strategies, the convergence report format, and graph-aware review convergence live in `convergence_recovery.md` for navigability.\n577: \n578: ---\n579: \n580: ## OPTIMIZER-TUNABLE THRESHOLDS\n581: \n582: The following convergence thresholds are managed by the offline loop optimizer (042.004). Changes to these fields are proposed through the optimizer's advisory-only promotion gate and reviewed by humans before adoption.\n583: \n584: ### Tunable Fields (Optimizer-Managed)\n585: \n586: | Field | Default | Range | Description |\n587: |-------|---------|-------|-------------|\n588: | `convergenceThreshold` | 0.10 | 0.01-0.20 | General convergence sensitivity |\n589: | `stuckThreshold` | 2 | 1-5 | Consecutive no-progress iterations before recovery |\n590: | `maxIterations` | 7 | 3-20 | Hard iteration ceiling |\n591: | `compositeStopScore` | 0.60 | 0.40-0.80 | Weighted stop score needed before guard evaluation |\n592: \n593: ### Locked Fields (Not Optimizer-Tunable)\n594: \n595: The following fields are runtime contracts and MUST NOT be modified by the optimizer:\n596: \n597: - `stopReason` enum values and semantics\n598: - `blocked_stop` event structure and gate names\n599: - Lineage fields (`sessionId`, `lineageMode`, `generation`)\n600: - Reducer configuration and file protection policies\n601: - Review dimensions (`reviewDimensions`) and product mode (`mode`)\n602: \n603: ### Canonical Manifest\n604: \n605: The authoritative registry of tunable vs locked fields is maintained at:\n606: `.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json`\n\n(End of file - total 606 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Convergence\ndescription: Stop condition algorithms, quality guards, and recovery strategies for the autonomous deep review loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"review convergence detection\"\n  - \"severity weighted stop ratio\"\n  - \"legal stop gate bundle\"\n  - \"review stuck detection\"\n  - \"composite convergence vote\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.22\n---\n\n# Deep Review Convergence\n\nStop condition algorithms, quality guards, and stuck recovery for the deep review loop.\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/convergence/convergence.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Convergence\ndescription: Stop condition algorithms, quality guards, and recovery strategies for the autonomous deep review loop.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"review convergence detection\"\n  - \"severity weighted stop ratio\"\n  - \"legal stop gate bundle\"\n  - \"review stuck detection\"\n  - \"composite convergence vote\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.22\n---\n\n# Deep Review Convergence\n\nStop condition algorithms, quality guards, and stuck recovery for the deep review loop.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nConvergence detection determines when the autonomous review loop should stop iterating. After every iteration the orchestrator evaluates three possible outcomes:\n\n| Outcome | Meaning |\n|---------|---------|\n| **CONTINUE** | More review work is expected to yield meaningful new findings. Dispatch the next iteration. |\n| **STOP** | The review has reached saturation. Proceed to synthesis and verdict. |\n| **STUCK_RECOVERY** | No progress detected for consecutive iterations. Attempt a recovery strategy before deciding. |\n\nConvergence is checked **after** each iteration completes and **before** the next iteration is dispatched. The check consumes the full JSONL state history and the current dimension coverage snapshot.\n\nRelease-readiness states are derived alongside convergence:\n- `in-progress` while coverage is incomplete or new P0/P1 findings are still appearing\n- `converged` once coverage and stabilization pass without new P0/P1 findings\n- `release-blocking` whenever unresolved P0 findings remain active\n\nWhen the loop stops and enters synthesis, the workflow emits `{artifact_dir}/resource-map.md` from converged review deltas before compiling `review-report.md`. Operators can disable that write with `--no-resource-map`.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Evaluating whether the autonomous review loop should stop, continue, or recover.\n- Tuning convergence thresholds, stuck-recovery cadence, or stabilization windows.\n- Debugging a stuck-recovery escalation or a premature STOP vote.\n- Auditing the release-readiness classification logic before shipping.\n\n### Key Defaults\n\n| Setting | Value | Purpose |\n|---------|-------|---------|\n| `maxIterations` | 7 | Hard ceiling on loop iterations |\n| `convergenceThreshold` | 0.10 | General convergence sensitivity |\n| `rollingStopThreshold` | 0.08 | Rolling-average STOP vote threshold |\n| `noProgressThreshold` | 0.05 | Stuck / no-progress classification threshold |\n| `stuckThreshold` | 2 | Consecutive no-progress iterations before recovery |\n| `minStabilizationPasses` | 1 | Coverage signal requires at least one stabilization pass |\n| `compositeStopScore` | 0.60 | Weighted stop-score needed before guard evaluation |\n\n### Threshold Semantics and Sibling Parity\n\n`convergenceThreshold` (default 0.10) compares new severity-weighted findings (P0=10, P1=5, P2=1) against accumulated findings. Lower values demand more iterations and a higher signal threshold before STOP is legal.\n\n**Not interchangeable with sibling deep-loop skills:**\n\n| Skill | Default | Signal |\n|---|---|---|\n| `deep-review` | 0.10 | severity-weighted P0/P1/P2 ratio |\n| `deep-research` | 0.05 | newInfoRatio (negative-knowledge emphasis) |\n| `deep-ai-council` (proposed) | 0.20 | adjudicator-verdict stability |\n\nCarrying threshold expectations across siblings will cause unexpected iteration counts. Tune each skill against its own default and its own signal, not by analogy.\n\n### Security-Sensitive Fix Overrides\n\n> **STATUS: SPEC ONLY (future implementation).** The override matrix below describes the contract that a future release should apply automatically when the review target involves security-sensitive surfaces. As of v1.9.0.0, the runtime does NOT auto-detect security-sensitivity and does NOT apply these overrides. `requiredClosedFindingReplay` and `requiredFixCompletenessGate` exist in no config / yaml / reducer surface (verified by grep). Operators running a security-sensitive review must manually tighten thresholds via `--convergence` + `--max-iterations` and manually maintain the closed-gate replay table. The contract below stands as the target spec for the next implementation pass. (Provenance for this deferred contract is recorded in this skill's changelog.)\n\nFor review reruns after fixes involving security, path disclosure, auth/authz, sandboxing, env precedence, public schemas, persistence, or user-visible error payloads (intended contract, not yet runtime-enforced):\n\n| Setting | General Default | Security-Sensitive Fix Default |\n|---------|-----------------|--------------------------------|\n| `minStabilizationPasses` | 1 | 2 |\n| `requiredClosedFindingReplay` | false | true for prior P0/P1 and any prior security/path P2 |\n| `requiredFixCompletenessGate` | false | true |\n\nWhen implemented, STOP must not be legal until the review report contains a closed-gate replay table that marks each prior active or remediated P0/P1 as `PASS`, `FAIL`, or `carried forward`, with file:line or command evidence. Operators today must enforce this rule manually.\n\n### Shared Stop Contract\n\nEvery terminal stop and every blocked-stop vote MUST emit the shared stop contract from REQ-001: a named `stopReason` enum plus, when STOP is vetoed, a `blocked_stop` event written to `deep-review-state.jsonl`. There is no nested `legalStop` wrapper on the persisted path. Earlier drafts of this document implied one, and that drift was the source of F009 in the 042 closing audit.\n\n### Convergence Modes\n\nThe shared convergence runtime accepts four values. Review legality, security gates, target authority, and verdict derivation remain owned by the review workflow rather than the convergence mode.\n\n| Mode | Live Behavior |\n|------|---------------|\n| `default` | Uses normal full-history convergence signals and sends a legal STOP to synthesis and verdict derivation. This is the fallback when no mode is supplied. |\n| `off` | Is accepted and persisted, but the shipped review YAML has no `off` decision branch; review therefore follows the same legal-stop and synthesis path as `default`. Use `stopPolicy: \"max-iterations\"` when convergence must remain telemetry-only until the iteration ceiling. |\n| `sliding-window` | Is accepted and persisted, but windowed graph-novelty telemetry is research-only in the shared runtime; review therefore retains its ordinary full-history signals, legal-stop gates, and synthesis path. |\n| `divergent` | After all review gates pass, translates the eligible `all_dimensions_clean` STOP into a read-only three-seat direction-selection pivot and continues with the selected review direction. |\n\n#### Divergent Pivot Contract\n\nReview has one eligible reason: the exact internal reason `all_dimensions_clean` with decision `STOP`. The nine legal-stop gates run before the divergent branch and remain unchanged. `maxIterationsReached`, `blockedStop`, `stuckRecovery`, `error`, `manualStop`, and `userPaused` are explicitly excluded. Max iterations, pause or cancellation, manual stop, unrecoverable error, and any blocked security or quality gate therefore never dispatch a pivot Council.\n\nEach eligible pivot runs one native, in-process Council round with exactly three distinct seats: analytical, critical, and pragmatic. It does not use an external CLI. The transaction requires all three seat returns to be parse-valid and at least two seats to materially endorse the same candidate without a high-severity blocker. Candidate sources are persisted unswept dimensions, search debt, producer-consumer gaps, negative-test gaps, and traceability gaps. Candidate generation rejects directions without in-scope evidence and directions that imply implementation, a fix, mutation, writing, or target expansion.\n\nThe guarantees are absolute: divergent mode never changes the PASS/CONDITIONAL/FAIL mapping, never authorizes a fix, and never makes the review target writable. A successful pivot returns to the loop before `phase_synthesis`; verdict computation exists only inside `phase_synthesis`, where active P0 yields FAIL, active P1 yields CONDITIONAL, and no active P0/P1 yields PASS. A failed pivot fails closed to that existing synthesis path.\n\nEvery pivot dispatches three seats, so a run that pivots has proportionally higher model cost and duration than the same run under `default`, `off`, or `sliding-window`. Pivot evidence is isolated under `<artifactRoot>/divergent/pivots/<pivotId>/council/**`, including config, append-only state, three seat artifacts, deliberation, and report. This path is distinct from ordinary planning Council artifacts under a spec packet's `ai-council/**` tree.\n\n#### stopReason Enum\n\n| `stopReason` | Meaning |\n|--------------|---------|\n| `converged` | All convergence signals met and legal-stop gates passed. |\n| `maxIterationsReached` | Iteration limit hit before convergence. |\n| `userPaused` | User requested pause via sentinel. |\n| `blockedStop` | Convergence math voted stop but legal-stop gates failed. |\n| `stuckRecovery` | Stuck detection triggered recovery. |\n| `error` | Unrecoverable error during iteration or reducer flow. |\n| `manualStop` | Operator explicitly halted outside the pause sentinel path. |\n\n#### blocked_stop Event (canonical, persisted)\n\n`step_emit_blocked_stop` in both `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml` appends the following record to `deep-review-state.jsonl` whenever the legal-stop decision tree vetoes STOP. The gate names and their shapes are load-bearing, the reducer reads them verbatim:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"blocked_stop\",\n  \"mode\": \"review\",\n  \"run\": 5,\n  \"blockedBy\": [\"dimensionCoverageGate\", \"p0ResolutionGate\"],\n  \"gateResults\": {\n    \"convergenceGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"score\": 0.72 },\n    \"dimensionCoverageGate\": {\n      \"pass\": false,\n      \"covered\": [\"correctness\", \"security\", \"traceability\"],\n      \"missing\": [\"maintainability\"]\n    },\n    \"p0ResolutionGate\": { \"pass\": false, \"activeP0\": 1 },\n    \"evidenceDensityGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"avgEvidencePerFinding\": 1.6 },\n    \"hotspotSaturationGate\": { \"pass\": true },\n    \"claimAdjudicationGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"activeP0P1\": 2 },\n    \"fixCompletenessReplayGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"securitySensitive\": false, \"requiredRows\": 0, \"passingRows\": 0 },\n    \"candidateCoverageGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"searchDebt\": [], \"missing\": [] },\n    \"graphlessFallbackGate\": { \"pass\": true, \"mode\": \"graph_available\", \"missing\": [], \"unavailabilityReason\": \"\" }\n  },\n  \"graphBlockerDetail\": [],\n  \"recoveryStrategy\": \"Dispatch the next iteration at the maintainability dimension and re-check after resolving the remaining P0.\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-24T15:02:00Z\",\n  \"sessionId\": \"rvw-2026-03-24T10-00-00Z\",\n  \"generation\": 1\n}\n```\n\n- `blockedBy`: array of gate names that failed (string[], never structured objects). Empty when STOP is legal, in which case no `blocked_stop` event is emitted.\n- `gateResults`: named sub-records keyed by `convergenceGate`, `dimensionCoverageGate`, `p0ResolutionGate`, `evidenceDensityGate`, `hotspotSaturationGate`, `claimAdjudicationGate`, `fixCompletenessReplayGate`, `candidateCoverageGate`, and `graphlessFallbackGate`. This is the full 9-gate set emitted by `step_emit_blocked_stop` in both `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml`. Each sub-record has a `pass` boolean plus gate-specific fields (score, covered/missing, activeP0, avgEvidencePerFinding, activeP0P1, securitySensitive, requiredRows, passingRows, searchDebt, mode, unavailabilityReason). The reducer reads these verbatim and does not coerce shapes. `candidateCoverageGate` and `graphlessFallbackGate` are v2-rollout gates, they pass trivially when the review-depth-v2 search path is inactive (no search debt, graph available).\n- `graphBlockerDetail`: array of structured graph blockers copied from the latest graph convergence decision. Empty when graph convergence did not veto STOP.\n- `recoveryStrategy`: human-readable one-liner describing what the next iteration should do before another stop attempt.\n- When the graph convergence verdict is `STOP_BLOCKED`, fold the graph blocker gate name into `blockedBy` and preserve the structured blocker objects under `graphBlockerDetail`.\n\n### Decision Priority\n\nChecks are evaluated in this order (first match wins):\n\n1. **Max iterations** -- hard cap, always checked first.\n2. **All dimensions covered + clean** -- all 4 dimensions covered, no active P0/P1, stabilization passed, gates passed.\n3. **Stuck detection** -- 2+ consecutive no-progress iterations.\n4. **Composite convergence** -- 3-signal weighted vote with threshold 0.60.\n5. **Legal-stop gate bundle** -- review-specific stop gates. If a stop vote fails any gate, persist `stopReason=blockedStop` and continue.\n6. **Default CONTINUE** -- none of the above triggered.\n\n---\n\n## 2. HARD STOPS\n\nHard stops are evaluated first and override all other signals.\n\n### Max Iterations Reached\n\n```\nif len(iterations) >= config.maxIterations:       // default 7\n  return { action: \"STOP\", stopReason: \"maxIterationsReached\" }\n```\n\nThe loop stops unconditionally. Synthesis runs with whatever findings exist.\n\n### All Dimensions Covered with Stabilization\n\n```\nif coverage.dimensionCoverage == 1.0 and activeP0 == 0 and activeP1 == 0:\n  if stabilizationPasses >= config.coverageAge.minStabilizationPasses:\n    if buildReviewLegalStop(state, config, coverage).passed:\n      return { action: \"STOP\", stopReason: \"converged\" }\n```\n\nTriggers when all 4 dimensions (correctness, security, traceability, maintainability) are covered, no active P0/P1 remains, at least 1 stabilization pass has occurred, and the 5-gate legal-stop bundle passes. If gates fail, the loop records `stopReason=blockedStop` and continues despite full coverage.\n\n---\n\n## 3. STUCK DETECTION\n\nIdentifies when the review loop makes no meaningful progress across consecutive iterations.\n\n```\nfunction countConsecutiveStuck_review(evidenceIterations, noProgressThreshold):\n  count = 0\n  for i in reversed(evidenceIterations):\n    if i.status == \"thought\":   continue    // invisible to stuck counter\n    if i.status == \"insight\":   break       // resets stuck counter (genuine progress)\n    if i.newFindingsRatio < noProgressThreshold or i.status == \"stuck\":\n      count += 1\n    else:\n      break\n  return count\n```\n\n**Threshold:** `stuckThreshold = 2` consecutive no-progress iterations (using `noProgressThreshold = 0.05`).\n\n**Status exclusions:**\n- `insight`: Resets stuck counter -- a conceptual breakthrough counts as progress even with a low ratio.\n- `thought`: Skipped entirely -- analytical iterations produce no evidence to measure.\n\nWhen `stuckCount >= stuckThreshold`, the orchestrator invokes the recovery protocol (Section 8) before deciding whether to continue or stop.\n\nThe recovery entry uses `stopReason=stuckRecovery` while the loop is in recovery. If recovery later terminates the run, the terminal record keeps the same shared enum value instead of minting a review-only label.\n\n---\n\n## 4. COMPOSITE CONVERGENCE\n\nThree independent signals each cast a stop/continue vote. Stop when the weighted stop-score meets or exceeds the consensus threshold. The signal set below matches the authoritative 3-signal vote in `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml` `step_check_convergence` and the quick-reference convergence table, the 3rd signal is **dimension coverage**, not a standalone novelty ratio.\n\n| Signal | Weight | Min Iterations | Measures |\n|--------|--------|---------------|----------|\n| Rolling Average | 0.30 | 2 | Recent severity-weighted finding yield |\n| MAD Noise Floor | 0.25 | 3 | Signal vs noise in newFindingsRatio |\n| Dimension Coverage | 0.45 | 1 | Configured review dimensions fully covered AND required traceability protocols covered AND `coverage_age >= minStabilizationPasses` |\n\n### Signal 1: Rolling Average (weight 0.30)\n\nAverages the last 2 severity-weighted `newFindingsRatio` values from evidence-bearing iterations (excludes `thought` status). Votes STOP when the average drops below `rollingStopThreshold` (0.08).\n\n```\nif len(evidenceIterations) >= 2:\n  recent = evidenceIterations[-2:]\n  avgRatio = mean(i.newFindingsRatio for i in recent)\n  rollingStop = avgRatio < 0.08\n```\n\n### Signal 2: MAD Noise Floor (weight 0.25)\n\nRobust statistical test using Median Absolute Deviation. Votes STOP when the latest ratio is at or below the computed noise floor.\n\n```\nif len(evidenceIterations) >= 3:\n  allRatios = [i.newFindingsRatio for i in evidenceIterations]\n  med = median(allRatios)\n  mad = median([abs(r - med) for r in allRatios])\n  noiseFloor = mad * 1.4826     // normal distribution estimator\n  madStop = evidenceIterations[-1].newFindingsRatio <= noiseFloor\n```\n\n### Signal 3: Dimension Coverage (weight 0.45)\n\nHighest-weight signal. Votes STOP once every configured review dimension AND every required traceability protocol has been covered by at least one iteration, and the coverage set has been stable for at least `minStabilizationPasses` iterations (default 1). This is the signal the YAML workflow evaluates.\n\n```\ndimensionStop =\n  dimensions_covered_count == configured_dimensions_count\n  AND required_traceability_protocols_covered\n  AND coverage_age >= config.minStabilizationPasses\n```\n\nThe latest severity-weighted newFindingsRatio is still tracked (the dashboard and registry surface it as `newFindingsRatio`), but it does NOT cast an independent stop vote, it feeds the rolling average and MAD noise-floor signals only.\n\n### Weighted Vote\n\n```\nstopScore = sum(s.weight * (1 if s.stop else 0) for s in signals) / totalWeight\nif stopScore >= 0.60:   // proceed to quality gate evaluation\n```\n\nWeights are redistributed across active signals only. If only 2 signals have enough data, their weights are normalized to sum to 1.0.\n\n### Semantic Convergence Signals\n\nTwo additional signals provide deeper semantic analysis of review iteration quality. These signals are ADDITIONAL to the 3-signal composite vote above and participate in the legal-stop gate evaluation rather than the composite stop-score.\n\n#### semanticNovelty (0.0-1.0)\n\nMeasures how much genuinely new review insight each iteration contributes beyond surface-level overlap with prior findings. Unlike `newFindingsRatio` (which is severity-weighted), `semanticNovelty` evaluates the conceptual novelty of findings independent of severity weighting.\n\n| Value | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| 0.8-1.0 | Iteration uncovered substantially new defect patterns, architectural concerns, or review angles |\n| 0.4-0.7 | Mix of new review insights and restatements of prior findings |\n| 0.1-0.3 | Mostly refinements or rewordings of previously identified issues |\n| 0.0 | No semantically novel findings detected |\n\nComputation:\n```\nfunction computeSemanticNovelty_review(currentFindings, priorCumulativeFindings):\n  newPatterns = extractDefectPatterns(currentFindings) - extractDefectPatterns(priorCumulativeFindings)\n  totalPatterns = extractDefectPatterns(currentFindings)\n  if len(totalPatterns) == 0: return 0.0\n  return len(newPatterns) / len(totalPatterns)\n```\n\nWhen `semanticNovelty` drops below 0.15 for 2+ consecutive evidence iterations, it provides strong supporting evidence for a legal STOP decision. This signal catches cases where `newFindingsRatio` stays moderate (due to severity weighting of refinements) but the review has exhausted genuinely new defect categories.\n\n#### findingStability (0.0-1.0)\n\nMeasures how stable the cumulative finding set is across iterations. A high stability score means the finding registry is not materially changing between iterations -- findings are not being added, upgraded, downgraded, or invalidated at a significant rate.\n\n| Value | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| 0.9-1.0 | Finding set is highly stable, minimal churn between iterations |\n| 0.6-0.8 | Moderate stability, some findings still evolving |\n| 0.3-0.5 | Active churn, findings being added, merged, or reclassified frequently |\n| 0.0-0.2 | Highly unstable, the review is still in early discovery |\n\nComputation:\n```\nfunction computeFindingStability(currentRegistry, priorRegistry):\n  if priorRegistry is null: return 0.0  // first iteration\n  unchangedFindings = count(f for f in currentRegistry\n    if f.id in priorRegistry and f.severity == priorRegistry[f.id].severity\n    and f.status == priorRegistry[f.id].status)\n  totalFindings = max(len(currentRegistry), len(priorRegistry))\n  if totalFindings == 0: return 1.0\n  return unchangedFindings / totalFindings\n```\n\nConvergence behavior:\n- `findingStability >= 0.85` supports STOP: the finding set has stabilized and further iterations are unlikely to materially change the review outcome.\n- `findingStability < 0.50` prevents STOP: the finding set is still in flux and the review has not reached a stable assessment.\n\n#### Integration with Legal-Stop Gate Bundle\n\nThe two semantic signals integrate with the existing 5-gate legal-stop bundle (Section 6):\n\n1. **findingStability gate** (existing): The existing `findingStability` gate already evaluates rolling average, MAD noise floor, and novelty ratio. The new `semanticNovelty` signal adds a sub-check:\n   - `semanticNoveltyPlateau`: `semanticNovelty < 0.15` for 2+ consecutive evidence iterations\n   - When this sub-check fails while the existing churn signals pass, the gate records the mismatch as a diagnostic note but does not independently block STOP.\n\n2. **findingStability signal** (new): The `findingStability` metric (0.0-1.0) is surfaced alongside the existing convergence signals. It supports the `findingStability` gate evaluation by providing a registry-level stability measure that complements the ratio-based churn signals.\n\nThe gate passes only when both the existing churn-based checks AND the semantic stability checks agree. When a semantic check fails, the persisted `blocked_stop.gateResults.findingStability` payload includes the semantic signal values.\n\n#### Stop-Decision Trace\n\nThe stop-decision event includes which semantic signals supported or prevented STOP:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"type\": \"event\",\n  \"event\": \"stop_decision\",\n  \"semanticSignals\": {\n    \"semanticNovelty\": { \"value\": 0.06, \"consecutiveLow\": 3, \"supportsStop\": true },\n    \"findingStability\": { \"value\": 0.92, \"supportsStop\": true }\n  },\n  \"semanticVerdict\": \"all_support_stop\",\n  ...\n}\n```\n\n| `semanticVerdict` | Meaning |\n|-------------------|---------|\n| `all_support_stop` | Both semantic signals support stopping |\n| `mixed` | One signal supports stop, the other does not |\n| `all_prevent_stop` | Both semantic signals indicate more work is needed |\n| `insufficient_data` | Not enough iterations to compute semantic signals |\n\n### Graceful Degradation\n\n| Iterations Completed | Active Signals | Behavior |\n|---------------------|----------------|----------|\n| 1 | Novelty ratio only (weight 1.0) | Very unlikely to stop without later confirmation from rolling churn signals |\n| 2 | Rolling avg + novelty ratio | Two-signal vote, reweighted |\n| 3+ | All three signals | Full composite, most reliable |\n\nSemantic convergence signals (`semanticNovelty`, `findingStability`) require at least 2 evidence iterations to produce meaningful values. They are omitted from legal-stop evaluation when insufficient data exists.\n\n---\n\n## 5. SEVERITY-WEIGHTED RATIO\n\nThe review loop uses `newFindingsRatio` instead of `newInfoRatio`. It weights findings by severity so that critical discoveries count far more than minor suggestions.\n\n### Severity Weights\n\n| Severity | Weight | Description |\n|----------|--------|-------------|\n| **P0** (Blocker) | 10.0 | Correctness failures, security vulnerabilities, spec contradictions |\n| **P1** (Required) | 5.0 | Degraded behavior, incomplete implementation, missing validation |\n| **P2** (Suggestion) | 1.0 | Style, naming, minor improvements, documentation gaps |\n\n### Computation\n\n```\nSEVERITY_WEIGHTS = { P0: 10.0, P1: 5.0, P2: 1.0 }\nrefinementMultiplier = 0.5\n\nweightedNew       = sum(SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[f.severity] for f in fully_new_findings)\nweightedRefinement = sum(SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[f.severity] * 0.5 for f in refinement_findings)\nweightedTotal     = sum(SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[f.severity] for f in all_findings_this_iteration)\n\nnewFindingsRatio = (weightedNew + weightedRefinement) / weightedTotal\n```\n\n- `fully_new_findings` -- findings not present in any prior iteration (new findingId).\n- `refinement_findings` -- findings that refine or upgrade an existing finding (same root cause, new evidence or severity change).\n- `refinementMultiplier = 0.5` -- refinements count at half weight.\n\n### P0 Override Rule\n\n```\nif ANY new P0 found this iteration:\n  newFindingsRatio = max(calculated, 0.50)\n\nif total_findings == 0:\n  newFindingsRatio = 0.0\n```\n\nA new critical finding always signals significant remaining work. The 0.50 floor prevents premature convergence when critical issues are still being discovered.\n\n---\n\n## 6. LEGAL-STOP GATE BUNDLE\n\n> **GATE MODEL, two naming conventions mapped to one authoritative set.** The authoritative producer is `step_emit_blocked_stop` in both `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, which emits **9 gates** with the `Gate` suffix: `convergenceGate` / `dimensionCoverageGate` / `p0ResolutionGate` / `evidenceDensityGate` / `hotspotSaturationGate` / `claimAdjudicationGate` / `fixCompletenessReplayGate` / `candidateCoverageGate` / `graphlessFallbackGate`. The §Section-1 event shape (lines 98-119) mirrors this set verbatim and the reducer reads those names verbatim, so treat the event shape as authoritative when writing or reading JSONL state. The §6 table below is the high-level conceptual model and uses descriptive names WITHOUT the `Gate` suffix where one reads more naturally (for example `findingStability` maps to `convergenceGate`); each row carries its event-shape name so the mapping is explicit. `candidateCoverageGate` and `graphlessFallbackGate` are v2-rollout gates that pass trivially when the review-depth-v2 search path is inactive. The gate-model drift cluster (LG-0013, LG-0016, LG-0031, LG-0032) was reconciled in `006-gate-model-reconciliation`.\n\nDeep review treats STOP as legal only when the full review-specific gate bundle passes together. Convergence math may request STOP, but the workflow must still evaluate these 9 gates and persist a blocked-stop event when any gate fails.\n\n| Gate (§6 conceptual) | Event-shape name (§Section-1) | Rule | Fail Action |\n|------|------|------|-------------|\n| **findingStability** | `convergenceGate` | Rolling average, MAD noise floor, and novelty ratio must all indicate low-yield review churn | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| **dimensionCoverage** | `dimensionCoverageGate` | Every configured review dimension must have been examined at least once, with required traceability coverage stabilized | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| **p0Resolution** | `p0ResolutionGate` | No unresolved P0 findings may remain active at stop time | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| **evidenceDensity** | `evidenceDensityGate` | Evidence density across active findings must meet the configured threshold | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| **hotspotSaturation** | `hotspotSaturationGate` | Review hotspots must be revisited enough times to satisfy the saturation heuristic | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| (no §6 counterpart) | `claimAdjudicationGate` | Each new P0/P1 finding must carry a typed adjudication packet, missing or failing packets veto STOP | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| **fixCompletenessReplay** | `fixCompletenessReplayGate` | Security-sensitive fix reruns must replay previously closed P0/P1 gates and validate producer/consumer/matrix coverage from the remediation packet | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| **candidateCoverage** (v2 rollout) | `candidateCoverageGate` | Search debt must be cleared and every required bug class must have candidate coverage before STOP, passes trivially when the v2 search path is inactive | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n| **graphlessFallback** (v2 rollout) | `graphlessFallbackGate` | When the code graph is unavailable, required bug classes must carry cited fallback ledger rows, passes trivially when the graph is available | Block STOP, persist `blockedStop` |\n\n### Gate Evaluation\n\n```\nfunction buildReviewLegalStop(state, config, coverage):\n  gateResults = {\n    findingStability: {\n      pass: rollingStop and madStop and state.latestNoveltyRatio <= config.convergenceThreshold,\n      detail: \"Rolling average, MAD noise floor, and novelty ratio are all below stop thresholds.\"\n    },\n    dimensionCoverage: {\n      pass: everyConfiguredDimensionExaminedAtLeastOnce(coverage, config.reviewDimensions) and\n            coverage.requiredProtocolsCovered and\n            coverage.stabilizationPasses >= 1,\n      detail: \"All configured review dimensions have been examined, required traceability protocols are covered, and stabilization has aged enough to stop.\"\n    },\n    p0Resolution: {\n      pass: countActiveFindings(state, [\"P0\"]) == 0 and state.claimAdjudicationPassed != false,\n      detail: \"No unresolved P0 findings remain and blocker adjudication is complete.\"\n    },\n    evidenceDensity: {\n      pass: computeEvidenceDensity(state.activeFindings) >= config.evidenceDensityThreshold,\n      detail: \"Evidence density meets the configured threshold for active findings.\"\n    },\n    hotspotSaturation: {\n      pass: computeHotspotSaturation(state.hotspots) >= config.hotspotSaturationThreshold,\n      detail: \"Priority hotspots received enough revisits to satisfy saturation.\"\n    },\n    fixCompletenessReplay: {\n      pass: not isSecuritySensitiveFixRerun(state, config) or allRequiredReplayRowsPass(state.reviewReport),\n      detail: \"Security-sensitive fix reruns include closed-gate replay evidence and producer/consumer/matrix coverage before STOP.\"\n    },\n    candidateCoverage: {\n      pass: not isReviewDepthV2Active(state, config) or (searchDebtCleared(state) and allRequiredBugClassesCovered(state)),\n      detail: \"Search debt is cleared and every required bug class has candidate coverage. Passes trivially when the v2 search path is inactive.\"\n    },\n    graphlessFallback: {\n      pass: state.searchCoverage.graphCoverageMode == \"graph_available\" or allRequiredBugClassesHaveFallbackRows(state),\n      detail: \"When the code graph is unavailable, required bug classes carry cited fallback ledger rows. Passes trivially when the graph is available.\"\n    }\n  }\n\n  blockedBy = [name for name, result in gateResults.items() if not result.pass]\n  return {\n    pass: len(blockedBy) == 0,\n    blockedBy,\n    gateResults\n  }\n```\n\nWhen convergence math returns STOP, invoke `buildReviewLegalStop()`. If it returns `pass: false`, persist a first-class `blocked_stop` event with the failing `blockedBy` gates, the full `gateResults` bundle, a `recoveryStrategy`, and the normal run/timestamp/session lineage fields before overriding the decision to CONTINUE.\n\n### Blocked-Stop Recovery Strategy\n\n| Failed Gate | Recovery Strategy |\n|-------------|-------------------|\n| `findingStability` | Revisit the noisiest recent dimension and reduce novelty by closing obvious follow-up loops before re-checking STOP. |\n| `dimensionCoverage` | Schedule the next uncovered review dimension immediately. |\n| `p0Resolution` | Re-open the active blocker path and verify whether the P0 is real, downgraded, or still unresolved. |\n| `evidenceDensity` | Re-read weakly supported findings and add concrete `file:line` citations before they count toward a stop decision. |\n| `hotspotSaturation` | Revisit undersampled hotspots or adjacent call sites until the saturation heuristic passes. |\n| `fixCompletenessReplay` | Replay prior active or remediated P0/P1 gates, then record producer, consumer, and matrix coverage evidence before re-checking STOP. |\n| `candidateCoverage` | Clear outstanding search debt and run candidate discovery for the missing bug classes before re-checking STOP. |\n| `graphlessFallback` | Add cited fallback ledger rows for the required bug classes, or restore graph availability, before re-checking STOP. |\n\n### Legacy Stop-Reason Mapping\n\nUse this table when replaying old packets or translating older prose/docs into the shared stop contract.\n\n| Legacy label | New `stopReason` | Mapping note |\n|--------------|------------------|--------------|\n| `all_dimensions_clean` | `converged` | Legacy review-specific terminal label, now expressed by the shared enum. |\n| `composite_converged` | `converged` | Legacy convergence-math wording now rolls into shared terminal success. |\n| `all dimensions clean` | `converged` | Old operator-facing prose for the same successful stop. |\n| `max_iterations_reached` | `maxIterationsReached` | Legacy machine label for the hard iteration cap. |\n| `max iterations` | `maxIterationsReached` | Old operator-facing hard-stop wording. |\n| `pause sentinel detected` | `userPaused` | Sentinel pause is now a shared user-directed stop reason. |\n| `guard_override` | `blockedStop` | Legacy continue override when a stop vote failed legal gates. |\n| `quality guard failed` | `blockedStop` | Older prose for the same blocked-stop outcome. |\n| `P0 override blocks convergence` | `blockedStop` | Legacy review wording for a stop attempt that was not legal to finalize. |\n| `stuck_detected` | `stuckRecovery` | Legacy recovery trigger label. |\n| `stuck_unrecoverable` | `stuckRecovery` | Legacy terminal wording for the same recovery path family. |\n| `manual halt` | `manualStop` | Operator-directed halt outside normal pause sentinel flow. |\n\n---\n\n## 7. PROVISIONAL VERDICT\n\nThe provisional verdict is determined from active findings at the time the loop stops. It appears in both the convergence report and the final `review-report.md`.\n\n| Verdict | Condition | Meaning |\n|---------|-----------|---------|\n| **FAIL** | `activeP0 > 0` OR any legal-stop gate fails at terminal stop time | Does not meet quality standards. Blocks release. |\n| **CONDITIONAL** | `activeP0 == 0` AND `activeP1 > 0` | Meets threshold but has required fixes before release. |\n| **PASS** | `activeP0 == 0` AND `activeP1 == 0` | Shippable. Set `hasAdvisories: true` when `activeP2 > 0`. |\n\n### Determination\n\n```\nfunction determineVerdict(state, gateResult):\n  activeP0 = countActiveFindings(state, [\"P0\"])\n  activeP1 = countActiveFindings(state, [\"P1\"])\n  activeP2 = countActiveFindings(state, [\"P2\"])\n\n  if activeP0 > 0 or not gateResult.passed:\n    return { verdict: \"FAIL\", nextCommand: \"/speckit:plan\" }\n  if activeP1 > 0:\n    return { verdict: \"CONDITIONAL\", nextCommand: \"/speckit:plan\" }\n\n  hasAdvisories = activeP2 > 0\n  return { verdict: \"PASS\", hasAdvisories, nextCommand: \"/create:changelog\" }\n```\n\n### Post-Verdict Routing\n\n| Verdict | Next Step |\n|---------|-----------|\n| FAIL | `/speckit:plan` -- create remediation plan from findings |\n| CONDITIONAL | `/speckit:plan` -- create fix plan for P1 findings |\n| PASS | `/create:changelog` -- record the clean audit |\n\n---\n\n## 8. RECOVERY, REPORTING, AND GRAPH-AWARE CONVERGENCE\n\nStuck-recovery strategies, the convergence report format, and graph-aware review convergence live in `convergence_recovery.md` for navigability.\n\n---\n\n## OPTIMIZER-TUNABLE THRESHOLDS\n\nThe following convergence thresholds are managed by the offline loop optimizer (042.004). Changes to these fields are proposed through the optimizer's advisory-only promotion gate and reviewed by humans before adoption.\n\n### Tunable Fields (Optimizer-Managed)\n\n| Field | Default | Range | Description |\n|-------|---------|-------|-------------|\n| `convergenceThreshold` | 0.10 | 0.01-0.20 | General convergence sensitivity |\n| `stuckThreshold` | 2 | 1-5 | Consecutive no-progress iterations before recovery |\n| `maxIterations` | 7 | 3-20 | Hard iteration ceiling |\n| `compositeStopScore` | 0.60 | 0.40-0.80 | Weighted stop score needed before guard evaluation |\n\n### Locked Fields (Not Optimizer-Tunable)\n\nThe following fields are runtime contracts and MUST NOT be modified by the optimizer:\n\n- `stopReason` enum values and semantics\n- `blocked_stop` event structure and gate names\n- Lineage fields (`sessionId`, `lineageMode`, `generation`)\n- Reducer configuration and file protection policies\n- Review dimensions (`reviewDimensions`) and product mode (`mode`)\n\n### Canonical Manifest\n\nThe authoritative registry of tunable vs locked fields is maintained at:\n`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/optimizer/optimizer-manifest.json`","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":606,"totalLines":606,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/convergence/convergence.md","time":{"start":1783806723758,"end":1783806723763}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb039880819187a2a2b6ee2a461a"}},"id":"prt_f532a869a0013PE3EDrC88Suza","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723795,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_JqZtn8EPRCjaWIEhcBBtkTbD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/completion_criteria.md","offset":1,"limit":1500},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/completion_criteria.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Review Completion Criteria\n3: description: Full definition-of-done checklist for a deep-review loop -- loop completion conditions, the binary quality gates that must pass before STOP, and release-readiness validation success criteria.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"review loop completion criteria\"\n6:   - \"review success criteria\"\n7:   - \"review definition of done\"\n8:   - \"review release readiness validation\"\n9: importance_tier: important\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.11.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Deep Review Completion Criteria\n15: \n16: Full definition-of-done checklist for a deep-review loop: loop completion conditions, the binary quality gates STOP must clear, and release-readiness validation success criteria.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: This reference is the authoritative checklist for \"is this review loop actually done.\" SKILL.md §6 SUCCESS CRITERIA carries a condensed summary and links here for the full enumeration; use this file when verifying a completed run, debugging a premature STOP, or reconciling completion metadata against the loop's real state.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Verifying a review loop's completion before accepting its verdict.\n29: - Debugging why STOP was blocked or why synthesis produced an incomplete report.\n30: - Reconciling `review-report.md` claims against the canonical state files.\n31: - Auditing a run for the release-readiness handoff.\n32: \n33: ### Relationship to `loop_state_and_gates.md`\n34: \n35: `references/protocol/loop_state_and_gates.md` defines the three state-machine-level binary gates (Evidence, Scope, Coverage) that block a STOP *decision* inside the convergence check. This file is the broader definition-of-done: it also covers artifact existence, report structure, severity-field completeness, and the release-readiness handoff -- checked once the loop believes it has already reached STOP.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. LOOP COMPLETION\n40: \n41: A review loop is considered complete when every item below holds:\n42: \n43: - The loop reached convergence (composite stop score above `compositeStopScore`, with required gates green) OR hit `maxIterations` without false-positive STOP.\n44: - Every configured review dimension has at least one full iteration of coverage recorded in `deep-review-state.jsonl` and reflected in `deep-review-strategy.md`.\n45: - Required traceability protocols (`spec_code`, `checklist_evidence`) executed at least once. Overlay protocols that apply to the target type ran or were explicitly marked N/A.\n46: - All canonical state files exist and parse cleanly: `deep-review-config.json`, `deep-review-state.jsonl`, `deep-review-findings-registry.json`, `deep-review-strategy.md`, `deep-review-dashboard.md`, and one `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` per dispatched iteration.\n47: - `review/resource-map.md` was emitted from converged delta evidence unless `config.resource_map.emit == false` (operator flag `--no-resource-map`).\n48: - `review/review-report.md` carries all 9 core sections (Executive Summary, Planning Trigger, Active Finding Registry, Remediation Workstreams, Spec Seed, Plan Seed, Traceability Status, Deferred Items, Audit Appendix) plus the conditional `## Resource Map Coverage Gate` section when `resource_map_present == true`.\n49: - Canonical continuity surfaces updated via `generate-context.js` (description.json, graph-metadata.json, indexed memory entries).\n50: \n51: ---\n52: \n53: ## 3. QUALITY GATES\n54: \n55: Each gate is binary: pass or block. STOP cannot be legal until every gate passes.\n56: \n57: - **Config validity**: `deep-review-config.json` parses, names every required field, and lineage block matches the current run (`sessionId`, `parentSessionId`, `lineageMode`, `generation`, `continuedFromRun`, `releaseReadinessState`).\n58: - **Strategy initialization**: `deep-review-strategy.md` carries the Files Under Review table, Cross-Reference Status grouped by core vs overlay, Known Context, and Review Boundaries.\n59: - **State consistency**: `deep-review-state.jsonl` opens with the config record and appends one iteration record per dispatched iteration. Reducer-owned fields in `deep-review-findings-registry.json` reconcile against JSONL totals.\n60: - **Iteration completeness**: every dispatched iteration produced both an `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` (non-empty, ending with the canonical `Review verdict: PASS|CONDITIONAL|FAIL` line) AND a JSONL delta record with `findingDetails[]`, `findingsSummary`, `newFindingsRatio`.\n61: - **Severity coverage**: every reported finding carries `severity` in {P0, P1, P2}, `category`, `file:line` evidence, `finding_class`, and a `content_hash` for synthesis dedup.\n62: - **Advisory numeric score**: `riskScore` may appear in finding details as non-gating context only; verdict logic must ignore it.\n63: - **Adversarial replay**: every P0 finding survived adversarial self-check. Rejected P0s downgraded with rationale recorded in the iteration narrative.\n64: - **Coverage threshold**: `dimensions_covered_count == configured_dimensions_count` AND required traceability protocols covered, stable for at least `minStabilizationPasses` iterations.\n65: - **Acceptance coverage**: when the spec-folder lifecycle predicate is active, the final report records `AC_COVERAGE` status, covered/total, floor, and next action; default-off INFO output is advisory and does not by itself block STOP.\n66: - **Security-sensitive override**: when the run targets security, path handling, env precedence, schema boundaries, persistence, or shared policy, the gates from `references/convergence/convergence.md` \"Security-Sensitive Fix Overrides\" apply (`minStabilizationPasses=2`, closed-finding replay required, fix-completeness gate enforced).\n67: \n68: ---\n69: \n70: ## 4. VALIDATION SUCCESS\n71: \n72: The release-readiness handoff is valid when:\n73: \n74: - The final report records stop reason, iteration count, dimension coverage, severity counts (P0/P1/P2), verdict (PASS / CONDITIONAL / FAIL), and release-readiness state (`in-progress`, `converged`, `release-blocking`).\n75: - Verdict logic matches: PASS = no P0/P1 findings (P2 advisories permitted with `hasAdvisories: true`). CONDITIONAL = P1 findings present with remediation plan. FAIL = any P0 confirmed after adversarial self-check.\n76: - `resource-map.md` Phase-5 Augmentation section (if present) lists novel logic gaps with iteration source links, or explicitly records the empty-result case.\n77: - `skill_advisor.py \"run a deep review loop\" --threshold 0.8` still surfaces the skill after any graph-metadata edits.\n78: - `bash .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/spec/validate.sh <spec-folder> --strict` exits 0 on the target spec folder.\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n83: \n84: - `references/protocol/loop_state_and_gates.md` -- state transitions, error handling, and the Evidence/Scope/Coverage STOP-decision gates.\n85: - `references/state/state_outputs.md` -- packet file ownership and the `review-report.md` section list.\n86: - `references/state/state_format.md` -- schemas for every state file referenced above.\n87: - `references/convergence/convergence.md` -- composite stop score, `minStabilizationPasses`, and Security-Sensitive Fix Overrides.\n\n(End of file - total 87 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Completion Criteria\ndescription: Full definition-of-done checklist for a deep-review loop -- loop completion conditions, the binary quality gates that must pass before STOP, and release-readiness validation success criteria.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"review loop completion criteria\"\n  - \"review success criteria\"\n  - \"review definition of done\"\n  - \"review release readiness validation\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.0\n---\n\n# Deep Review Completion Criteria\n\nFull definition-of-done checklist for a deep-review loop: loop completion conditions, the binary quality gates STOP must clear, and release-readiness validation success criteria.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/completion_criteria.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Review Completion Criteria\ndescription: Full definition-of-done checklist for a deep-review loop -- loop completion conditions, the binary quality gates that must pass before STOP, and release-readiness validation success criteria.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"review loop completion criteria\"\n  - \"review success criteria\"\n  - \"review definition of done\"\n  - \"review release readiness validation\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.0\n---\n\n# Deep Review Completion Criteria\n\nFull definition-of-done checklist for a deep-review loop: loop completion conditions, the binary quality gates STOP must clear, and release-readiness validation success criteria.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThis reference is the authoritative checklist for \"is this review loop actually done.\" SKILL.md §6 SUCCESS CRITERIA carries a condensed summary and links here for the full enumeration; use this file when verifying a completed run, debugging a premature STOP, or reconciling completion metadata against the loop's real state.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Verifying a review loop's completion before accepting its verdict.\n- Debugging why STOP was blocked or why synthesis produced an incomplete report.\n- Reconciling `review-report.md` claims against the canonical state files.\n- Auditing a run for the release-readiness handoff.\n\n### Relationship to `loop_state_and_gates.md`\n\n`references/protocol/loop_state_and_gates.md` defines the three state-machine-level binary gates (Evidence, Scope, Coverage) that block a STOP *decision* inside the convergence check. This file is the broader definition-of-done: it also covers artifact existence, report structure, severity-field completeness, and the release-readiness handoff -- checked once the loop believes it has already reached STOP.\n\n---\n\n## 2. LOOP COMPLETION\n\nA review loop is considered complete when every item below holds:\n\n- The loop reached convergence (composite stop score above `compositeStopScore`, with required gates green) OR hit `maxIterations` without false-positive STOP.\n- Every configured review dimension has at least one full iteration of coverage recorded in `deep-review-state.jsonl` and reflected in `deep-review-strategy.md`.\n- Required traceability protocols (`spec_code`, `checklist_evidence`) executed at least once. Overlay protocols that apply to the target type ran or were explicitly marked N/A.\n- All canonical state files exist and parse cleanly: `deep-review-config.json`, `deep-review-state.jsonl`, `deep-review-findings-registry.json`, `deep-review-strategy.md`, `deep-review-dashboard.md`, and one `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` per dispatched iteration.\n- `review/resource-map.md` was emitted from converged delta evidence unless `config.resource_map.emit == false` (operator flag `--no-resource-map`).\n- `review/review-report.md` carries all 9 core sections (Executive Summary, Planning Trigger, Active Finding Registry, Remediation Workstreams, Spec Seed, Plan Seed, Traceability Status, Deferred Items, Audit Appendix) plus the conditional `## Resource Map Coverage Gate` section when `resource_map_present == true`.\n- Canonical continuity surfaces updated via `generate-context.js` (description.json, graph-metadata.json, indexed memory entries).\n\n---\n\n## 3. QUALITY GATES\n\nEach gate is binary: pass or block. STOP cannot be legal until every gate passes.\n\n- **Config validity**: `deep-review-config.json` parses, names every required field, and lineage block matches the current run (`sessionId`, `parentSessionId`, `lineageMode`, `generation`, `continuedFromRun`, `releaseReadinessState`).\n- **Strategy initialization**: `deep-review-strategy.md` carries the Files Under Review table, Cross-Reference Status grouped by core vs overlay, Known Context, and Review Boundaries.\n- **State consistency**: `deep-review-state.jsonl` opens with the config record and appends one iteration record per dispatched iteration. Reducer-owned fields in `deep-review-findings-registry.json` reconcile against JSONL totals.\n- **Iteration completeness**: every dispatched iteration produced both an `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` (non-empty, ending with the canonical `Review verdict: PASS|CONDITIONAL|FAIL` line) AND a JSONL delta record with `findingDetails[]`, `findingsSummary`, `newFindingsRatio`.\n- **Severity coverage**: every reported finding carries `severity` in {P0, P1, P2}, `category`, `file:line` evidence, `finding_class`, and a `content_hash` for synthesis dedup.\n- **Advisory numeric score**: `riskScore` may appear in finding details as non-gating context only; verdict logic must ignore it.\n- **Adversarial replay**: every P0 finding survived adversarial self-check. Rejected P0s downgraded with rationale recorded in the iteration narrative.\n- **Coverage threshold**: `dimensions_covered_count == configured_dimensions_count` AND required traceability protocols covered, stable for at least `minStabilizationPasses` iterations.\n- **Acceptance coverage**: when the spec-folder lifecycle predicate is active, the final report records `AC_COVERAGE` status, covered/total, floor, and next action; default-off INFO output is advisory and does not by itself block STOP.\n- **Security-sensitive override**: when the run targets security, path handling, env precedence, schema boundaries, persistence, or shared policy, the gates from `references/convergence/convergence.md` \"Security-Sensitive Fix Overrides\" apply (`minStabilizationPasses=2`, closed-finding replay required, fix-completeness gate enforced).\n\n---\n\n## 4. VALIDATION SUCCESS\n\nThe release-readiness handoff is valid when:\n\n- The final report records stop reason, iteration count, dimension coverage, severity counts (P0/P1/P2), verdict (PASS / CONDITIONAL / FAIL), and release-readiness state (`in-progress`, `converged`, `release-blocking`).\n- Verdict logic matches: PASS = no P0/P1 findings (P2 advisories permitted with `hasAdvisories: true`). CONDITIONAL = P1 findings present with remediation plan. FAIL = any P0 confirmed after adversarial self-check.\n- `resource-map.md` Phase-5 Augmentation section (if present) lists novel logic gaps with iteration source links, or explicitly records the empty-result case.\n- `skill_advisor.py \"run a deep review loop\" --threshold 0.8` still surfaces the skill after any graph-metadata edits.\n- `bash .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/spec/validate.sh <spec-folder> --strict` exits 0 on the target spec folder.\n\n---\n\n## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- `references/protocol/loop_state_and_gates.md` -- state transitions, error handling, and the Evidence/Scope/Coverage STOP-decision gates.\n- `references/state/state_outputs.md` -- packet file ownership and the `review-report.md` section list.\n- `references/state/state_format.md` -- schemas for every state file referenced above.\n- `references/convergence/convergence.md` -- composite stop score, `minStabilizationPasses`, and Security-Sensitive Fix Overrides.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":87,"totalLines":87,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/protocol/completion_criteria.md","time":{"start":1783806723772,"end":1783806723789}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb0398908191bd26f14ef7e48c0c"}},"id":"prt_f532a86bb00140Ym784IabE9St","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723795,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_GIysmqICUElyLkcnpGFyUqrY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/state/state_format.md","offset":1,"limit":1500},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/state/state_format.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Review State Format\n3: description: State file schemas for the autonomous deep review loop, config, JSONL log, strategy, iteration files, and review report.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"deep review state format\"\n6:   - \"deep review config schema\"\n7:   - \"review severity weights\"\n8:   - \"file protection levels\"\n9:   - \"review iteration file structure\"\n10: importance_tier: important\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.11.0.28\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Deep Review State Format\n16: \n17: State file schemas for the autonomous deep review loop.\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: The deep review loop uses 8 state files under the resolved `{artifact_dir}/` owned by the target spec:\n24: \n25: | File | Format | Mutability |\n26: |------|--------|------------|\n27: | `deep-review-config.json` | JSON | Immutable after init |\n28: | `deep-review-state.jsonl` | JSON Lines | Append-only |\n29: | `deep-review-findings-registry.json` | JSON | Auto-generated reducer state |\n30: | `deep-review-strategy.md` | Markdown | Updated each iteration |\n31: | `deep-review-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Auto-generated (read-only) |\n32: | `.deep-review-pause` | Sentinel | Created/deleted by user |\n33: | `review-report.md` | Markdown | Updated at synthesis |\n34: | `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Write-once |\n35: \n36: ```text\n37: {artifact_dir}/\n38:   deep-review-config.json\n39:   deep-review-state.jsonl\n40:   deep-review-findings-registry.json\n41:   deep-review-strategy.md\n42:   deep-review-dashboard.md\n43:   .deep-review-pause\n44:   review-report.md\n45:   iterations/\n46:     iteration-001.md\n47:     iteration-002.md\n48:     ...\n49: ```\n50: \n51: `{artifact_dir}` comes from `resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'review')`. Root-spec runs resolve directly to `{spec_folder}/review/`. Child-phase and sub-phase runs use **flat-first**: a first run with an empty `review/` resolves directly to `{spec_folder}/review/` (no `pt-NN` wrapper). A `pt-NN` packet is allocated only when prior content for a non-matching target already exists. Continuation runs reuse the existing flat artifact (or matching `pt-NN` packet). This avoids the unnecessary `pt-01` wrapper on first runs.\n52: \n53: Example (first run on a child phase): `.../026-graph.../006-continuity-refactor-gates/003-gate-c-writer-ready/` → `003-gate-c-writer-ready/review/` (flat, no subfolder).\n54: \n55: Example (subsequent run with prior content for a different target): `003-gate-c-writer-ready/review/003-gate-c-writer-ready-pt-02/` (`pt-NN` allocated as a sibling to the prior content; subfolder name is `{basename(spec_folder)}-pt-{NN}`).\n56: \n57: ### When to Use\n58: \n59: - Validating deep-review state files emitted by an iteration or by the reducer.\n60: - Implementing a state consumer (e.g. dashboard, advisor probe, downstream packet).\n61: - Debugging JSONL reducer output or auditing schema-version transitions.\n62: - Authoring fixtures that need to round-trip through the reducer.\n63: \n64: ---\n65: \n66: ## 2. CONFIG FILE (deep-review-config.json)\n67: \n68: Created during initialization. Not modified after creation.\n69: \n70: ```json\n71: {\n72:   \"topic\": \"Review of deep-review skill package\",\n73:   \"mode\": \"review\",\n74:   \"reviewTarget\": \"specs/030-deep-review-review-mode\",\n75:   \"reviewTargetType\": \"spec-folder\",\n76:   \"reviewDimensions\": [\"correctness\", \"security\", \"traceability\", \"maintainability\"],\n77:   \"resource_map_present\": false,\n78:   \"sessionId\": \"rvw-2026-04-03T12-00-00Z\",\n79:   \"parentSessionId\": null,\n80:   \"lineageMode\": \"new\",\n81:   \"generation\": 1,\n82:   \"continuedFromRun\": null,\n83:   \"maxIterations\": 7,\n84:   \"convergenceThreshold\": 0.10,\n85:   \"stuckThreshold\": 2,\n86:   \"severityThreshold\": \"P2\",\n87:   \"crossReference\": {\n88:     \"core\": [\"spec_code\", \"checklist_evidence\"],\n89:     \"overlay\": [\"feature_catalog_code\", \"playbook_capability\"]\n90:   },\n91:   \"qualityGateThreshold\": true,\n92:   \"releaseReadinessState\": \"in-progress\",\n93:   \"specFolder\": \"030-deep-review-review-mode\",\n94:   \"createdAt\": \"2026-03-24T14:00:00Z\",\n95:   \"status\": \"initialized\",\n96:   \"executionMode\": \"auto\",\n97:   \"fileProtection\": {\n98:     \"deep-review-config.json\": \"immutable\",\n99:     \"deep-review-state.jsonl\": \"append-only\",\n100:     \"deep-review-findings-registry.json\": \"auto-generated\",\n101:     \"deep-review-strategy.md\": \"mutable\",\n102:     \"deep-review-dashboard.md\": \"auto-generated\",\n103:     \".deep-review-pause\": \"operator-controlled\",\n104:     \"review-report.md\": \"mutable\",\n105:     \"review-report-v*.md\": \"write-once\",\n106:     \"iteration-*.md\": \"write-once\"\n107:   },\n108:   \"reducer\": {\n109:     \"enabled\": true,\n110:     \"inputs\": [\"latestJSONLDelta\", \"newIterationFile\", \"priorReducedState\"],\n111:     \"outputs\": [\"findingsRegistry\", \"dashboardMetrics\", \"strategyUpdates\"],\n112:     \"metrics\": [\n113:       \"dimensionsCovered\",\n114:       \"findingsBySeverity\",\n115:       \"openFindings\",\n116:       \"resolvedFindings\",\n117:       \"convergenceScore\"\n118:     ]\n119:   }\n120: }\n121: ```\n122: \n123: ### Field Reference\n124: \n125: | Field | Type | Default | Description |\n126: |-------|------|---------|-------------|\n127: | mode | `\"review\"` | -- | Session mode discriminator (required) |\n128: | reviewTarget | string | -- | Path or identifier of the review target |\n129: | reviewTargetType | string | `\"spec-folder\"` | `spec-folder`, `skill`, `agent`, `track`, `files` |\n130: | reviewDimensions | string[] | all 4 | Dimensions to evaluate |\n131: | resource_map_present | boolean | false | True only when `{specFolder}/resource-map.md` existed during init, enables the Resource Map Coverage audit pass and conditional report section |\n132: | sessionId | string | -- | Stable identifier for the current review lineage |\n133: | parentSessionId | string \\| null | `null` | Parent lineage reference for restart flows |\n134: | lineageMode | string | `\"new\"` | `new`, `resume`, `restart`. `fork` and `completed-continue` are deferred and not emitted by the current runtime |\n135: | generation | number | 1 | Lineage generation number, incremented on `restart`, unchanged on `resume` |\n136: | continuedFromRun | number \\| null | `null` | Count of completed iteration records at the lifecycle boundary (set on `resume` and `restart`) |\n137: | maxIterations | number | 7 | Hard cap on loop iterations |\n138: | convergenceThreshold | number | 0.10 | Stop when severity-weighted new findings ratio below this |\n139: | stuckThreshold | number | 2 | Consecutive no-progress iterations before recovery |\n140: | severityThreshold | string | `\"P2\"` | Minimum severity to report: `P0`, `P1`, `P2` |\n141: | crossReference | object | -- | Core (hard-gated) and overlay (advisory) protocol sets |\n142: | qualityGateThreshold | boolean | true | Whether binary quality gates are enforced |\n143: | specFolder | string | -- | Spec folder path (relative to specs/) |\n144: | status | string | `\"initialized\"` | `initialized`, `running`, `converged`, `stuck`, `complete`, `error` |\n145: | releaseReadinessState | string | `\"in-progress\"` | `in-progress`, `converged`, `release-blocking` |\n146: | fileProtection | object | -- | Mutability declarations (see protection levels below) |\n147: | reducer | object | -- | Canonical reducer inputs, outputs, and metrics names |\n148: \n149: ### File Protection Levels\n150: \n151: | Level | Meaning |\n152: |-------|---------|\n153: | immutable | Cannot be modified after creation |\n154: | append-only | New content added at end only |\n155: | mutable | Can be read, edited, overwritten |\n156: | write-once | Created once, never modified |\n157: | auto-generated | System-managed, overwritten each refresh |\n158: | operator-controlled | Created or deleted only by the human/operator to control loop state |\n159: \n160: ### Review Dimensions\n161: \n162: | Dimension | Priority | Required for Coverage |\n163: |-----------|----------|---------------------|\n164: | correctness | 1 | Yes |\n165: | security | 2 | Yes |\n166: | traceability | 3 | Yes |\n167: | maintainability | 4 | Yes |\n168: \n169: ### Severity Weights\n170: \n171: | Severity | Weight | Label | Requires file:line |\n172: |----------|--------|-------|--------------------|\n173: | P0 | 10.0 | Blocker | Yes |\n174: | P1 | 5.0 | Required | Yes |\n175: | P2 | 1.0 | Suggestion | Yes |\n176: \n177: ---\n178: \n179: ## 3. STATE LOG\n180: \n181: The `deep-review-state.jsonl` record schemas (config, iteration, event, lineage) and the Review Depth Schema (v2) live in `state_jsonl.md` for navigability.\n182: \n183: ---\n184: \n185: ## 4. STRATEGY FILE (deep-review-strategy.md)\n186: \n187: Updated at the end of each iteration. Serves as the persistent brain across fresh-context iterations.\n188: \n189: ### Required Sections\n190: \n191: | Section | Updated By | Purpose |\n192: |---------|-----------|---------|\n193: | topic | Init only | Review topic from config |\n194: | review-dimensions | Each iteration | Unchecked dimensions drive next focus |\n195: | completed-dimensions | Each iteration | Checked dimensions with verdict summary |\n196: | running-findings | Each iteration | P0/P1/P2 active counts + deltas |\n197: | what-worked | Each iteration | Successful approaches for reuse |\n198: | what-failed | Each iteration | Failed approaches to avoid |\n199: | exhausted-approaches | When fully tried | \"Do not retry\" registry |\n200: | ruled-out-directions | Each iteration | Eliminated directions with reasons |\n201: | next-focus | Each iteration | Recommended direction for next iteration |\n202: | known-context | Init only | Prior work from memory context |\n203: | cross-reference-status | Each iteration | Core vs overlay protocol status |\n204: | files-under-review | Each iteration | Per-file coverage state table |\n205: | review-boundaries | Init only | Max iterations, thresholds, config |\n206: \n207: ### Mapping from Research Mode\n208: \n209: | Review Section | Research Equivalent |\n210: |---------------|-------------------|\n211: | review-dimensions | Key Questions (remaining) |\n212: | completed-dimensions | Answered Questions |\n213: | running-findings | _(none, review-specific)_ |\n214: | cross-reference-status | _(none, review-specific)_ |\n215: | files-under-review | _(none, review-specific)_ |\n216: | review-boundaries | Research Boundaries |\n217: \n218: Sections unchanged from research: topic, what-worked, what-failed, exhausted-approaches, ruled-out-directions, next-focus, known-context.\n219: \n220: ### Update Protocol\n221: \n222: 1. Read current strategy file\n223: 2. Move completed dimensions from \"remaining\" to \"completed\" with `[x]` and verdict\n224: 3. Update running-findings with P0/P1/P2 counts and deltas\n225: 4. Add to what-worked / what-failed with iteration number\n226: 5. Move exhausted approaches. Update cross-reference-status and files-under-review\n227: 6. Set next-focus based on remaining dimensions and open findings\n228: \n229: ---\n230: \n231: ## 5. FINDINGS REGISTRY (deep-review-findings-registry.json)\n232: \n233: Reducer-owned JSON document regenerated after every iteration and lifecycle transition.\n234: \n235: ```json\n236: {\n237:   \"sessionId\": \"rvw-2026-04-03T12-00-00Z\",\n238:   \"generation\": 1,\n239:   \"lineageMode\": \"resume\",\n240:   \"openFindings\": [],\n241:   \"resolvedFindings\": [],\n242:   \"blockedStopHistory\": [],\n243:   \"persistentSameSeverity\": [],\n244:   \"severityChanged\": [],\n245:   \"repeatedFindings\": [],\n246:   \"dimensionCoverage\": {\n247:     \"correctness\": true,\n248:     \"security\": true,\n249:     \"traceability\": false,\n250:     \"maintainability\": false\n251:   },\n252:   \"findingsBySeverity\": {\n253:     \"P0\": 0,\n254:     \"P1\": 1,\n255:     \"P2\": 2\n256:   },\n257:   \"openFindingsCount\": 3,\n258:   \"resolvedFindingsCount\": 1,\n259:   \"convergenceScore\": 0.44,\n260:   \"graphConvergenceScore\": 1.01,\n261:   \"graphDecision\": \"STOP_ALLOWED\",\n262:   \"graphBlockers\": [],\n263:   \"corruptionWarnings\": []\n264: }\n265: ```\n266: \n267: This file is machine-owned and must stay synchronized with the latest iteration delta, dashboard metrics, and synthesized review report.\n268: \n269: ### Blocked-Stop and Corruption-Tracking Additions\n270: \n271: | Field | Type | Description |\n272: |-------|------|-------------|\n273: | `blockedStopHistory` | array | One entry per `blocked_stop` JSONL event: `{run, blockedBy, gateResults, recoveryStrategy, timestamp}`. Rendered in the dashboard `BLOCKED STOPS` section and can drive the strategy `next-focus` anchor when blocked-stop is the most recent loop event. |\n274: | `persistentSameSeverity` | array | Findings observed in ≥2 iterations with NO severity transitions beyond initial discovery. REQ-018 split of the deprecated `repeatedFindings` bucket. |\n275: | `severityChanged` | array | Findings that went through at least one severity transition (P0↔P1↔P2) in their `transitions` history. |\n276: | `repeatedFindings` | array | **Deprecated.** Union of `persistentSameSeverity` and `severityChanged`. Retained for backward compatibility, new code should read the split arrays. |\n277: | `corruptionWarnings` | array | Per-line corruption reports from `parseJsonlDetailed()`: `{line, raw, error}`. Non-empty means the reducer detected malformed JSONL. |\n278: \n279: ### Default Values\n280: \n281: When no `graph_convergence` event has been recorded yet, defaults are `graphConvergenceScore: 0`, `graphDecision: null`, and `graphBlockers: []`.\n282: When no `blocked_stop` event has been recorded yet, `blockedStopHistory: []`.\n283: When JSONL parses cleanly, `corruptionWarnings: []`.\n284: \n285: ### Fail-Closed Semantics (REQ-015, REQ-016)\n286: \n287: - **Malformed JSONL**: The reducer CLI exits with code `2` and writes a warning to stderr when `corruptionWarnings.length > 0`. Pass `--lenient` (or `lenient:true` to `reduceReviewState`) to escape-hatch out and preserve the v1.2.0.0 fail-open behavior for legacy packets.\n288: - **Missing machine-owned anchors**: `replaceAnchorSection()` throws `Error('Missing machine-owned anchor \"<id>\" in deep-review strategy file.')` when the strategy file is present but lacks one of the required anchors. Pass `--create-missing-anchors` (or `createMissingAnchors:true`) to bootstrap empty strategy files by appending the missing anchor blocks.\n289: - **Dashboard surfaces**: `CORRUPTION WARNINGS` section lists detected lines. `BLOCKED STOPS` section lists `blockedStopHistory` entries. `GRAPH CONVERGENCE` section reports `graphConvergenceScore` / `graphDecision` / `graphBlockers`.\n290: - **Strategy next-focus override**: When the latest `blocked_stop` event timestamp is newer than the latest iteration timestamp, the reducer rewrites the strategy `next-focus` anchor to surface the blocking gates and recovery hint so operators see the blocker before choosing the next iteration direction.\n291: \n292: ---\n293: \n294: ## 6. ITERATION FILES (review/iterations/iteration-NNN.md)\n295: \n296: Write-once files. One per iteration, zero-padded 3-digit naming.\n297: \n298: ### Structure\n299: \n300: ```markdown\n301: # Iteration [N]: [Focus Area]\n302: \n303: ## Focus\n304: [Dimension(s), files, scope investigated]\n305: \n306: ## Scorecard\n307: - Dimensions covered: [list]\n308: - Files reviewed: [count]\n309: - New findings: P0=[n] P1=[n] P2=[n]\n310: - Refined findings: P0=[n] P1=[n] P2=[n]\n311: - New findings ratio: [0.0-1.0]\n312: \n313: ## Findings\n314: \n315: ### P0, Blocker\n316: - **F[NNN]**: [Title], `file:line`, [Description with evidence]\n317: \n318: ### P1, Required\n319: - **F[NNN]**: [Title], `file:line`, [Description with evidence]\n320: \n321: ### P2, Suggestion\n322: - **F[NNN]**: [Title], `file:line`, [Description with evidence]\n323: \n324: ## Cross-Reference Results\n325: | Protocol | Status | Gate | Evidence | Notes |\n326: |----------|--------|------|----------|-------|\n327: | spec_code | pass/partial/fail | hard | file:line | ... |\n328: \n329: ## Assessment\n330: - New findings ratio: [0.0-1.0]\n331: - Dimensions addressed: [list]\n332: - Novelty justification: [breakdown]\n333: \n334: ## Ruled Out\n335: - [Approach]: [Why], [Evidence]\n336: \n337: ## Dead Ends\n338: - [Direction]: [Why]\n339: \n340: ## Recommended Next Focus\n341: [What to investigate next]\n342: ```\n343: \n344: Every finding must include: unique ID (`F001`...), severity (`P0`/`P1`/`P2`), concrete `file:line` evidence, and dimension tag.\n345: \n346: ---\n347: \n348: ## 7. REVIEW REPORT (review/review-report.md)\n349: \n350: The review synthesis output contains 9 core sections plus a conditional `## Resource Map Coverage Gate` section when `resource_map_present` is true:\n351: \n352: | # | Section | Description |\n353: |---|---------|-------------|\n354: | 1 | Executive Summary | Verdict, active P0/P1/P2 counts, scope, `hasAdvisories` flag |\n355: | 2 | Planning Trigger | Why result routes to planning or changelog |\n356: | 3 | Active Finding Registry | Deduped active findings with evidence, severity, dimension |\n357: | 4 | Remediation Workstreams | Ordered lanes grouped by dependency or area |\n358: | 5 | Spec Seed | Minimal spec updates implied by findings |\n359: | 6 | Plan Seed | Initial remediation tasks from findings |\n360: | 7 | Traceability Status | Core vs overlay protocol outcomes and gaps |\n361: | 8 | Resource Map Coverage Gate | Present only when `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` existed at init, contains touched entries, untouched entries (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`), and implementation paths absent from the map |\n362: | 9 | Deferred Items | Advisory findings, blocked items, follow-up checks |\n363: | 10 | Audit Appendix | Coverage, convergence replay, audit detail |\n364: \n365: **Executive Summary** includes verdict (`PASS`/`CONDITIONAL`/`FAIL`), active finding counts, `hasAdvisories` boolean (PASS + P2 > 0), scope description, and convergence reason.\n366: \n367: **Planning Trigger** routes FAIL/CONDITIONAL to remediation planning, PASS to changelog creation.\n368: \n369: **Active Finding Registry** lists each active finding with findingId, severity, dimension, title, file:line evidence, first/last seen iteration, and status.\n370: \n371: **Remediation Workstreams** group related findings into ordered lanes with constituent finding IDs and execution order.\n372: \n373: **Spec Seed / Plan Seed** provide minimal spec updates and initial remediation tasks referencing finding IDs and target files.\n374: \n375: **Traceability Status** reports per-protocol pass/partial/fail with gating class and evidence.\n376: \n377: **Resource Map Coverage Gate** is emitted only when `resource_map_present` is true and MUST contain exactly three bullets: touched entries, untouched entries (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`), and implementation paths absent from the map.\n378: \n379: **Deferred Items** captures advisory findings, blocked protocols, and future follow-up checks.\n380: \n381: **Audit Appendix** contains iteration table, convergence signal replay, file coverage matrix, and dimension breakdown.\n382: \n383: ---\n384: \n385: ## 8. DASHBOARD (review/deep-review-dashboard.md)\n386: \n387: Auto-generated summary. Never manually edited.\n388: \n389: - **Path**: `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-dashboard.md`\n390: - **Generated from**: JSONL state log + strategy + findings registry\n391: - **Refresh**: Regenerated after every iteration\n392: - **Protection**: `auto-generated` in fileProtection\n393: \n394: ### Sections\n395: \n396: | Section | Source | Description |\n397: |---------|--------|-------------|\n398: | Findings Summary | JSONL | Active P0/P1/P2 counts, new vs refined |\n399: | Progress Table | JSONL | Run, status, focus, dimensions, ratio, duration |\n400: | Coverage | Strategy + JSONL | Dimension completion, file coverage, protocol status |\n401: | Trend | JSONL signals | Rolling average, composite stop score, trajectory |\n402: \n403: **Rules:** Sole inputs are JSONL + strategy. Overwrite entirely on refresh. Read-only for all agents.\n404: \n405: ---\n406: \n407: ## 9. CLAIM ADJUDICATION\n408: \n409: Every new P0/P1 finding must carry a **typed claim-adjudication packet**. The packet is parsed by `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication` in the review workflow and its pass/fail result is persisted as a `claim_adjudication` event in `deep-review-state.jsonl`. The next iteration's `step_check_convergence` legal-stop decision tree reads the latest event via `claimAdjudicationGate` (gate `f`), a missing or failed packet vetoes STOP even if every other gate passes. Prose-only adjudication blocks are no longer accepted.\n410: \n411: ### Typed Packet Schema (required)\n412: \n413: Embed the packet inside the iteration file for each new P0/P1 finding. The orchestrator parses it after evaluation and persists the validation result.\n414: \n415: ```json\n416: {\n417:   \"findingId\": \"F003\",\n418:   \"claim\": \"Coverage-graph upsert identity is bare `id`, so cross-session collisions overwrite prior rows.\",\n419:   \"evidenceRefs\": [\n420:     \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:154\",\n421:     \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:292-302\"\n422:   ],\n423:   \"counterevidenceSought\": \"Grepped the module for compound-key upserts, checked migration scripts, and inspected session-isolation.vitest.ts for a collision regression, none found.\",\n424:   \"alternativeExplanation\": \"Could be intentional single-tenant design, but REQ-024 explicitly requires session isolation, so this is rejected.\",\n425:   \"finalSeverity\": \"P1\",\n426:   \"confidence\": 0.86,\n427:   \"downgradeTrigger\": \"If a composite primary key `(spec_folder, loop_type, session_id, id)` lands and a collision regression covers the ID-reuse path, downgrade to P2 tech-debt.\",\n428:   \"transitions\": [\n429:     { \"iteration\": 2, \"from\": null, \"to\": \"P1\", \"reason\": \"Initial discovery\" }\n430:   ]\n431: }\n432: ```\n433: \n434: ### Required Fields\n435: \n436: | Field | Type | Description |\n437: |-------|------|-------------|\n438: | `findingId` | string | Must match the finding ID in the iteration body and registry |\n439: | `claim` | string | The single assertion the finding makes (one sentence, evidence-backed) |\n440: | `evidenceRefs` | string[] | `file:line` or `file:range` citations that substantiate the claim (at least one entry) |\n441: | `counterevidenceSought` | string | Where the reviewer looked for contradicting evidence (commands, paths, docs), blank string is not acceptable |\n442: | `alternativeExplanation` | string | An alternative reading of the evidence, even if the reviewer rejects it |\n443: | `finalSeverity` | `\"P0\"` \\| `\"P1\"` \\| `\"P2\"` | Severity after adjudication (may differ from the severity originally asserted) |\n444: | `confidence` | number `[0, 1]` | Reviewer confidence in `finalSeverity` |\n445: | `downgradeTrigger` | string | The concrete condition under which this finding should be downgraded in a future iteration |\n446: | `transitions` | object[] | Optional severity transition log, required when `finalSeverity` differs from the originally asserted severity |\n447: \n448: ### Validation Rules (enforced by `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication`)\n449: \n450: 1. A packet MUST exist for every new P0/P1 finding introduced in this iteration. Carried-forward findings reuse the previous packet unless severity transitioned.\n451: 2. All required fields MUST be present and non-empty. `confidence` MUST be a number in `[0, 1]`.\n452: 3. Each `evidenceRefs` entry MUST contain a `:` separating the path from a line or range.\n453: 4. `finalSeverity` MUST match the severity the finding is registered under in the iteration's `Findings` section and in `deep-review-findings-registry.json`.\n454: 5. When any rule fails, the workflow appends `{\"event\":\"claim_adjudication\",\"passed\":false,\"missingPackets\":[...]}` to the state log. The next `step_check_convergence` call reads that event and sets `claimAdjudicationGate` = `false`, producing a `blockedStop` event with `blockedBy: [\"claimAdjudicationGate\"]` until a follow-up iteration rewrites the packet.\n455: \n456: ### Severity Transition Rules\n457: \n458: - **P2 → P1**: confirmed exploitable impact or spec violation with direct evidence\n459: - **P1 → P0**: demonstrated data loss, security breach, or hard-gate failure\n460: - **Downgrade**: requires explicit counterevidence or a confirmed alternative explanation\n461: - Every transition is recorded in the packet's `transitions` array and mirrored into the finding registry's `transitions` field\n462: \n463: ---\n464: \n465: ## 10. FINDING REGISTRY\n466: \n467: Each finding is tracked with a unique identifier enabling deduplication, severity transitions, and status lifecycle.\n468: \n469: ### Schema\n470: \n471: ```json\n472: {\n473:   \"findingId\": \"F003\",\n474:   \"severity\": \"P1\",\n475:   \"category\": \"resource-map-coverage\",\n476:   \"status\": \"active\",\n477:   \"dimension\": \"traceability\",\n478:   \"title\": \"Applied target file missing from resource-map inventory\",\n479:   \"file\": \".opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml\",\n480:   \"line\": 955,\n481:   \"firstSeen\": 2,\n482:   \"lastSeen\": 4,\n483:   \"transitions\": [\n484:     { \"iteration\": 2, \"from\": null, \"to\": \"P2\", \"reason\": \"Initial discovery\" },\n485:     { \"iteration\": 4, \"from\": \"P2\", \"to\": \"P1\", \"reason\": \"Confirmed real coverage gap against applied target inventory\" }\n486:   ]\n487: }\n488: ```\n489: \n490: | Field | Type | Description |\n491: |-------|------|-------------|\n492: | findingId | string | Sequential unique ID: `F001`, `F002`, ... |\n493: | severity | `\"P0\"` / `\"P1\"` / `\"P2\"` | Current severity |\n494: | category | `\"correctness\"` / `\"security\"` / `\"traceability\"` / `\"maintainability\"` / `\"resource-map-coverage\"` | Primary audit category for the finding, `resource-map-coverage` is reserved for implementation-vs-map coverage gaps |\n495: | status | `\"active\"` / `\"resolved\"` / `\"deferred\"` / `\"disproved\"` | Current status |\n496: | dimension | string | Primary dimension: correctness, security, traceability, maintainability |\n497: | title | string | Short description |\n498: | file | string | File path |\n499: | line | number | Line number (approximate) |\n500: | firstSeen / lastSeen | number | Iteration where first discovered / last referenced |\n501: | transitions | array | Severity and status change history |\n502: \n503: ### Status Lifecycle\n504: \n505: ```text\n506: [discovered] --> active --> resolved    (fixed or confirmed non-issue)\n507:                   |\n508:                   +--> deferred    (advisory, below threshold)\n509:                   |\n510:                   +--> disproved   (counterevidence invalidated)\n511: ```\n512: \n513: | Status | Counts Toward Verdict |\n514: |--------|----------------------|\n515: | active | Yes |\n516: | resolved | No |\n517: | deferred | No (listed in Deferred Items) |\n518: | disproved | No |\n519: \n520: ### Deduplication\n521: \n522: Same file + line range + root cause as an existing finding = **refinement**, not new. The existing findingId is updated. Refinements count at half weight (`refinementMultiplier: 0.5`) and are tracked via `findingsRefined` in JSONL.\n523: \n524: ### Cross-Reference Protocols\n525: \n526: | Protocol | Level | Applies To | Gate |\n527: |----------|-------|------------|------|\n528: | spec_code | core | all types | hard |\n529: | checklist_evidence | core | all types | hard |\n530: | skill_agent | overlay | skill | advisory |\n531: | agent_cross_runtime | overlay | agent | advisory |\n532: | feature_catalog_code | overlay | skill, spec-folder, track, files | advisory |\n533: | playbook_capability | overlay | skill, agent, spec-folder | advisory |\n534: \n535: Severity for `resource-map-coverage` findings is calibrated to the coverage-gate outcome:\n536: - `P2` when an untouched map entry is explicitly `expected-by-scope`\n537: - `P1` when an untouched or absent path represents a real coverage gap\n538: - `P0` only when the missing coverage masks a release-blocking correctness or security risk\n539: \n540: ### Quality Gates\n541: \n542: | Gate | Rule |\n543: |------|------|\n544: | Evidence | Every active finding backed by concrete file:line evidence |\n545: | Scope | Reviewed files and conclusions stay inside declared scope |\n546: | Coverage | Required dimensions and required protocols covered |\n547: \n548: All three gates must pass before STOP. Gate failure forces `verdict: \"FAIL\"` regardless of finding counts.\n\n(End of file - total 548 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Review State Format\ndescription: State file schemas for the autonomous deep review loop, config, JSONL log, strategy, iteration files, and review report.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep review state format\"\n  - \"deep review config schema\"\n  - \"review severity weights\"\n  - \"file protection levels\"\n  - \"review iteration file structure\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.28\n---\n\n# Deep Review State Format\n\nState file schemas for the autonomous deep review loop.\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/state/state_format.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Review State Format\ndescription: State file schemas for the autonomous deep review loop, config, JSONL log, strategy, iteration files, and review report.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep review state format\"\n  - \"deep review config schema\"\n  - \"review severity weights\"\n  - \"file protection levels\"\n  - \"review iteration file structure\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.11.0.28\n---\n\n# Deep Review State Format\n\nState file schemas for the autonomous deep review loop.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThe deep review loop uses 8 state files under the resolved `{artifact_dir}/` owned by the target spec:\n\n| File | Format | Mutability |\n|------|--------|------------|\n| `deep-review-config.json` | JSON | Immutable after init |\n| `deep-review-state.jsonl` | JSON Lines | Append-only |\n| `deep-review-findings-registry.json` | JSON | Auto-generated reducer state |\n| `deep-review-strategy.md` | Markdown | Updated each iteration |\n| `deep-review-dashboard.md` | Markdown | Auto-generated (read-only) |\n| `.deep-review-pause` | Sentinel | Created/deleted by user |\n| `review-report.md` | Markdown | Updated at synthesis |\n| `iterations/iteration-NNN.md` | Markdown | Write-once |\n\n```text\n{artifact_dir}/\n  deep-review-config.json\n  deep-review-state.jsonl\n  deep-review-findings-registry.json\n  deep-review-strategy.md\n  deep-review-dashboard.md\n  .deep-review-pause\n  review-report.md\n  iterations/\n    iteration-001.md\n    iteration-002.md\n    ...\n```\n\n`{artifact_dir}` comes from `resolveArtifactRoot(specFolder, 'review')`. Root-spec runs resolve directly to `{spec_folder}/review/`. Child-phase and sub-phase runs use **flat-first**: a first run with an empty `review/` resolves directly to `{spec_folder}/review/` (no `pt-NN` wrapper). A `pt-NN` packet is allocated only when prior content for a non-matching target already exists. Continuation runs reuse the existing flat artifact (or matching `pt-NN` packet). This avoids the unnecessary `pt-01` wrapper on first runs.\n\nExample (first run on a child phase): `.../026-graph.../006-continuity-refactor-gates/003-gate-c-writer-ready/` → `003-gate-c-writer-ready/review/` (flat, no subfolder).\n\nExample (subsequent run with prior content for a different target): `003-gate-c-writer-ready/review/003-gate-c-writer-ready-pt-02/` (`pt-NN` allocated as a sibling to the prior content; subfolder name is `{basename(spec_folder)}-pt-{NN}`).\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Validating deep-review state files emitted by an iteration or by the reducer.\n- Implementing a state consumer (e.g. dashboard, advisor probe, downstream packet).\n- Debugging JSONL reducer output or auditing schema-version transitions.\n- Authoring fixtures that need to round-trip through the reducer.\n\n---\n\n## 2. CONFIG FILE (deep-review-config.json)\n\nCreated during initialization. Not modified after creation.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"topic\": \"Review of deep-review skill package\",\n  \"mode\": \"review\",\n  \"reviewTarget\": \"specs/030-deep-review-review-mode\",\n  \"reviewTargetType\": \"spec-folder\",\n  \"reviewDimensions\": [\"correctness\", \"security\", \"traceability\", \"maintainability\"],\n  \"resource_map_present\": false,\n  \"sessionId\": \"rvw-2026-04-03T12-00-00Z\",\n  \"parentSessionId\": null,\n  \"lineageMode\": \"new\",\n  \"generation\": 1,\n  \"continuedFromRun\": null,\n  \"maxIterations\": 7,\n  \"convergenceThreshold\": 0.10,\n  \"stuckThreshold\": 2,\n  \"severityThreshold\": \"P2\",\n  \"crossReference\": {\n    \"core\": [\"spec_code\", \"checklist_evidence\"],\n    \"overlay\": [\"feature_catalog_code\", \"playbook_capability\"]\n  },\n  \"qualityGateThreshold\": true,\n  \"releaseReadinessState\": \"in-progress\",\n  \"specFolder\": \"030-deep-review-review-mode\",\n  \"createdAt\": \"2026-03-24T14:00:00Z\",\n  \"status\": \"initialized\",\n  \"executionMode\": \"auto\",\n  \"fileProtection\": {\n    \"deep-review-config.json\": \"immutable\",\n    \"deep-review-state.jsonl\": \"append-only\",\n    \"deep-review-findings-registry.json\": \"auto-generated\",\n    \"deep-review-strategy.md\": \"mutable\",\n    \"deep-review-dashboard.md\": \"auto-generated\",\n    \".deep-review-pause\": \"operator-controlled\",\n    \"review-report.md\": \"mutable\",\n    \"review-report-v*.md\": \"write-once\",\n    \"iteration-*.md\": \"write-once\"\n  },\n  \"reducer\": {\n    \"enabled\": true,\n    \"inputs\": [\"latestJSONLDelta\", \"newIterationFile\", \"priorReducedState\"],\n    \"outputs\": [\"findingsRegistry\", \"dashboardMetrics\", \"strategyUpdates\"],\n    \"metrics\": [\n      \"dimensionsCovered\",\n      \"findingsBySeverity\",\n      \"openFindings\",\n      \"resolvedFindings\",\n      \"convergenceScore\"\n    ]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Field Reference\n\n| Field | Type | Default | Description |\n|-------|------|---------|-------------|\n| mode | `\"review\"` | -- | Session mode discriminator (required) |\n| reviewTarget | string | -- | Path or identifier of the review target |\n| reviewTargetType | string | `\"spec-folder\"` | `spec-folder`, `skill`, `agent`, `track`, `files` |\n| reviewDimensions | string[] | all 4 | Dimensions to evaluate |\n| resource_map_present | boolean | false | True only when `{specFolder}/resource-map.md` existed during init, enables the Resource Map Coverage audit pass and conditional report section |\n| sessionId | string | -- | Stable identifier for the current review lineage |\n| parentSessionId | string \\| null | `null` | Parent lineage reference for restart flows |\n| lineageMode | string | `\"new\"` | `new`, `resume`, `restart`. `fork` and `completed-continue` are deferred and not emitted by the current runtime |\n| generation | number | 1 | Lineage generation number, incremented on `restart`, unchanged on `resume` |\n| continuedFromRun | number \\| null | `null` | Count of completed iteration records at the lifecycle boundary (set on `resume` and `restart`) |\n| maxIterations | number | 7 | Hard cap on loop iterations |\n| convergenceThreshold | number | 0.10 | Stop when severity-weighted new findings ratio below this |\n| stuckThreshold | number | 2 | Consecutive no-progress iterations before recovery |\n| severityThreshold | string | `\"P2\"` | Minimum severity to report: `P0`, `P1`, `P2` |\n| crossReference | object | -- | Core (hard-gated) and overlay (advisory) protocol sets |\n| qualityGateThreshold | boolean | true | Whether binary quality gates are enforced |\n| specFolder | string | -- | Spec folder path (relative to specs/) |\n| status | string | `\"initialized\"` | `initialized`, `running`, `converged`, `stuck`, `complete`, `error` |\n| releaseReadinessState | string | `\"in-progress\"` | `in-progress`, `converged`, `release-blocking` |\n| fileProtection | object | -- | Mutability declarations (see protection levels below) |\n| reducer | object | -- | Canonical reducer inputs, outputs, and metrics names |\n\n### File Protection Levels\n\n| Level | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| immutable | Cannot be modified after creation |\n| append-only | New content added at end only |\n| mutable | Can be read, edited, overwritten |\n| write-once | Created once, never modified |\n| auto-generated | System-managed, overwritten each refresh |\n| operator-controlled | Created or deleted only by the human/operator to control loop state |\n\n### Review Dimensions\n\n| Dimension | Priority | Required for Coverage |\n|-----------|----------|---------------------|\n| correctness | 1 | Yes |\n| security | 2 | Yes |\n| traceability | 3 | Yes |\n| maintainability | 4 | Yes |\n\n### Severity Weights\n\n| Severity | Weight | Label | Requires file:line |\n|----------|--------|-------|--------------------|\n| P0 | 10.0 | Blocker | Yes |\n| P1 | 5.0 | Required | Yes |\n| P2 | 1.0 | Suggestion | Yes |\n\n---\n\n## 3. STATE LOG\n\nThe `deep-review-state.jsonl` record schemas (config, iteration, event, lineage) and the Review Depth Schema (v2) live in `state_jsonl.md` for navigability.\n\n---\n\n## 4. STRATEGY FILE (deep-review-strategy.md)\n\nUpdated at the end of each iteration. Serves as the persistent brain across fresh-context iterations.\n\n### Required Sections\n\n| Section | Updated By | Purpose |\n|---------|-----------|---------|\n| topic | Init only | Review topic from config |\n| review-dimensions | Each iteration | Unchecked dimensions drive next focus |\n| completed-dimensions | Each iteration | Checked dimensions with verdict summary |\n| running-findings | Each iteration | P0/P1/P2 active counts + deltas |\n| what-worked | Each iteration | Successful approaches for reuse |\n| what-failed | Each iteration | Failed approaches to avoid |\n| exhausted-approaches | When fully tried | \"Do not retry\" registry |\n| ruled-out-directions | Each iteration | Eliminated directions with reasons |\n| next-focus | Each iteration | Recommended direction for next iteration |\n| known-context | Init only | Prior work from memory context |\n| cross-reference-status | Each iteration | Core vs overlay protocol status |\n| files-under-review | Each iteration | Per-file coverage state table |\n| review-boundaries | Init only | Max iterations, thresholds, config |\n\n### Mapping from Research Mode\n\n| Review Section | Research Equivalent |\n|---------------|-------------------|\n| review-dimensions | Key Questions (remaining) |\n| completed-dimensions | Answered Questions |\n| running-findings | _(none, review-specific)_ |\n| cross-reference-status | _(none, review-specific)_ |\n| files-under-review | _(none, review-specific)_ |\n| review-boundaries | Research Boundaries |\n\nSections unchanged from research: topic, what-worked, what-failed, exhausted-approaches, ruled-out-directions, next-focus, known-context.\n\n### Update Protocol\n\n1. Read current strategy file\n2. Move completed dimensions from \"remaining\" to \"completed\" with `[x]` and verdict\n3. Update running-findings with P0/P1/P2 counts and deltas\n4. Add to what-worked / what-failed with iteration number\n5. Move exhausted approaches. Update cross-reference-status and files-under-review\n6. Set next-focus based on remaining dimensions and open findings\n\n---\n\n## 5. FINDINGS REGISTRY (deep-review-findings-registry.json)\n\nReducer-owned JSON document regenerated after every iteration and lifecycle transition.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"sessionId\": \"rvw-2026-04-03T12-00-00Z\",\n  \"generation\": 1,\n  \"lineageMode\": \"resume\",\n  \"openFindings\": [],\n  \"resolvedFindings\": [],\n  \"blockedStopHistory\": [],\n  \"persistentSameSeverity\": [],\n  \"severityChanged\": [],\n  \"repeatedFindings\": [],\n  \"dimensionCoverage\": {\n    \"correctness\": true,\n    \"security\": true,\n    \"traceability\": false,\n    \"maintainability\": false\n  },\n  \"findingsBySeverity\": {\n    \"P0\": 0,\n    \"P1\": 1,\n    \"P2\": 2\n  },\n  \"openFindingsCount\": 3,\n  \"resolvedFindingsCount\": 1,\n  \"convergenceScore\": 0.44,\n  \"graphConvergenceScore\": 1.01,\n  \"graphDecision\": \"STOP_ALLOWED\",\n  \"graphBlockers\": [],\n  \"corruptionWarnings\": []\n}\n```\n\nThis file is machine-owned and must stay synchronized with the latest iteration delta, dashboard metrics, and synthesized review report.\n\n### Blocked-Stop and Corruption-Tracking Additions\n\n| Field | Type | Description |\n|-------|------|-------------|\n| `blockedStopHistory` | array | One entry per `blocked_stop` JSONL event: `{run, blockedBy, gateResults, recoveryStrategy, timestamp}`. Rendered in the dashboard `BLOCKED STOPS` section and can drive the strategy `next-focus` anchor when blocked-stop is the most recent loop event. |\n| `persistentSameSeverity` | array | Findings observed in ≥2 iterations with NO severity transitions beyond initial discovery. REQ-018 split of the deprecated `repeatedFindings` bucket. |\n| `severityChanged` | array | Findings that went through at least one severity transition (P0↔P1↔P2) in their `transitions` history. |\n| `repeatedFindings` | array | **Deprecated.** Union of `persistentSameSeverity` and `severityChanged`. Retained for backward compatibility, new code should read the split arrays. |\n| `corruptionWarnings` | array | Per-line corruption reports from `parseJsonlDetailed()`: `{line, raw, error}`. Non-empty means the reducer detected malformed JSONL. |\n\n### Default Values\n\nWhen no `graph_convergence` event has been recorded yet, defaults are `graphConvergenceScore: 0`, `graphDecision: null`, and `graphBlockers: []`.\nWhen no `blocked_stop` event has been recorded yet, `blockedStopHistory: []`.\nWhen JSONL parses cleanly, `corruptionWarnings: []`.\n\n### Fail-Closed Semantics (REQ-015, REQ-016)\n\n- **Malformed JSONL**: The reducer CLI exits with code `2` and writes a warning to stderr when `corruptionWarnings.length > 0`. Pass `--lenient` (or `lenient:true` to `reduceReviewState`) to escape-hatch out and preserve the v1.2.0.0 fail-open behavior for legacy packets.\n- **Missing machine-owned anchors**: `replaceAnchorSection()` throws `Error('Missing machine-owned anchor \"<id>\" in deep-review strategy file.')` when the strategy file is present but lacks one of the required anchors. Pass `--create-missing-anchors` (or `createMissingAnchors:true`) to bootstrap empty strategy files by appending the missing anchor blocks.\n- **Dashboard surfaces**: `CORRUPTION WARNINGS` section lists detected lines. `BLOCKED STOPS` section lists `blockedStopHistory` entries. `GRAPH CONVERGENCE` section reports `graphConvergenceScore` / `graphDecision` / `graphBlockers`.\n- **Strategy next-focus override**: When the latest `blocked_stop` event timestamp is newer than the latest iteration timestamp, the reducer rewrites the strategy `next-focus` anchor to surface the blocking gates and recovery hint so operators see the blocker before choosing the next iteration direction.\n\n---\n\n## 6. ITERATION FILES (review/iterations/iteration-NNN.md)\n\nWrite-once files. One per iteration, zero-padded 3-digit naming.\n\n### Structure\n\n```markdown\n# Iteration [N]: [Focus Area]\n\n## Focus\n[Dimension(s), files, scope investigated]\n\n## Scorecard\n- Dimensions covered: [list]\n- Files reviewed: [count]\n- New findings: P0=[n] P1=[n] P2=[n]\n- Refined findings: P0=[n] P1=[n] P2=[n]\n- New findings ratio: [0.0-1.0]\n\n## Findings\n\n### P0, Blocker\n- **F[NNN]**: [Title], `file:line`, [Description with evidence]\n\n### P1, Required\n- **F[NNN]**: [Title], `file:line`, [Description with evidence]\n\n### P2, Suggestion\n- **F[NNN]**: [Title], `file:line`, [Description with evidence]\n\n## Cross-Reference Results\n| Protocol | Status | Gate | Evidence | Notes |\n|----------|--------|------|----------|-------|\n| spec_code | pass/partial/fail | hard | file:line | ... |\n\n## Assessment\n- New findings ratio: [0.0-1.0]\n- Dimensions addressed: [list]\n- Novelty justification: [breakdown]\n\n## Ruled Out\n- [Approach]: [Why], [Evidence]\n\n## Dead Ends\n- [Direction]: [Why]\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n[What to investigate next]\n```\n\nEvery finding must include: unique ID (`F001`...), severity (`P0`/`P1`/`P2`), concrete `file:line` evidence, and dimension tag.\n\n---\n\n## 7. REVIEW REPORT (review/review-report.md)\n\nThe review synthesis output contains 9 core sections plus a conditional `## Resource Map Coverage Gate` section when `resource_map_present` is true:\n\n| # | Section | Description |\n|---|---------|-------------|\n| 1 | Executive Summary | Verdict, active P0/P1/P2 counts, scope, `hasAdvisories` flag |\n| 2 | Planning Trigger | Why result routes to planning or changelog |\n| 3 | Active Finding Registry | Deduped active findings with evidence, severity, dimension |\n| 4 | Remediation Workstreams | Ordered lanes grouped by dependency or area |\n| 5 | Spec Seed | Minimal spec updates implied by findings |\n| 6 | Plan Seed | Initial remediation tasks from findings |\n| 7 | Traceability Status | Core vs overlay protocol outcomes and gaps |\n| 8 | Resource Map Coverage Gate | Present only when `{spec_folder}/resource-map.md` existed at init, contains touched entries, untouched entries (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`), and implementation paths absent from the map |\n| 9 | Deferred Items | Advisory findings, blocked items, follow-up checks |\n| 10 | Audit Appendix | Coverage, convergence replay, audit detail |\n\n**Executive Summary** includes verdict (`PASS`/`CONDITIONAL`/`FAIL`), active finding counts, `hasAdvisories` boolean (PASS + P2 > 0), scope description, and convergence reason.\n\n**Planning Trigger** routes FAIL/CONDITIONAL to remediation planning, PASS to changelog creation.\n\n**Active Finding Registry** lists each active finding with findingId, severity, dimension, title, file:line evidence, first/last seen iteration, and status.\n\n**Remediation Workstreams** group related findings into ordered lanes with constituent finding IDs and execution order.\n\n**Spec Seed / Plan Seed** provide minimal spec updates and initial remediation tasks referencing finding IDs and target files.\n\n**Traceability Status** reports per-protocol pass/partial/fail with gating class and evidence.\n\n**Resource Map Coverage Gate** is emitted only when `resource_map_present` is true and MUST contain exactly three bullets: touched entries, untouched entries (`expected-by-scope` vs `gap`), and implementation paths absent from the map.\n\n**Deferred Items** captures advisory findings, blocked protocols, and future follow-up checks.\n\n**Audit Appendix** contains iteration table, convergence signal replay, file coverage matrix, and dimension breakdown.\n\n---\n\n## 8. DASHBOARD (review/deep-review-dashboard.md)\n\nAuto-generated summary. Never manually edited.\n\n- **Path**: `{artifact_dir}/deep-review-dashboard.md`\n- **Generated from**: JSONL state log + strategy + findings registry\n- **Refresh**: Regenerated after every iteration\n- **Protection**: `auto-generated` in fileProtection\n\n### Sections\n\n| Section | Source | Description |\n|---------|--------|-------------|\n| Findings Summary | JSONL | Active P0/P1/P2 counts, new vs refined |\n| Progress Table | JSONL | Run, status, focus, dimensions, ratio, duration |\n| Coverage | Strategy + JSONL | Dimension completion, file coverage, protocol status |\n| Trend | JSONL signals | Rolling average, composite stop score, trajectory |\n\n**Rules:** Sole inputs are JSONL + strategy. Overwrite entirely on refresh. Read-only for all agents.\n\n---\n\n## 9. CLAIM ADJUDICATION\n\nEvery new P0/P1 finding must carry a **typed claim-adjudication packet**. The packet is parsed by `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication` in the review workflow and its pass/fail result is persisted as a `claim_adjudication` event in `deep-review-state.jsonl`. The next iteration's `step_check_convergence` legal-stop decision tree reads the latest event via `claimAdjudicationGate` (gate `f`), a missing or failed packet vetoes STOP even if every other gate passes. Prose-only adjudication blocks are no longer accepted.\n\n### Typed Packet Schema (required)\n\nEmbed the packet inside the iteration file for each new P0/P1 finding. The orchestrator parses it after evaluation and persists the validation result.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"findingId\": \"F003\",\n  \"claim\": \"Coverage-graph upsert identity is bare `id`, so cross-session collisions overwrite prior rows.\",\n  \"evidenceRefs\": [\n    \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:154\",\n    \".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/lib/coverage-graph/coverage-graph-db.ts:292-302\"\n  ],\n  \"counterevidenceSought\": \"Grepped the module for compound-key upserts, checked migration scripts, and inspected session-isolation.vitest.ts for a collision regression, none found.\",\n  \"alternativeExplanation\": \"Could be intentional single-tenant design, but REQ-024 explicitly requires session isolation, so this is rejected.\",\n  \"finalSeverity\": \"P1\",\n  \"confidence\": 0.86,\n  \"downgradeTrigger\": \"If a composite primary key `(spec_folder, loop_type, session_id, id)` lands and a collision regression covers the ID-reuse path, downgrade to P2 tech-debt.\",\n  \"transitions\": [\n    { \"iteration\": 2, \"from\": null, \"to\": \"P1\", \"reason\": \"Initial discovery\" }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n### Required Fields\n\n| Field | Type | Description |\n|-------|------|-------------|\n| `findingId` | string | Must match the finding ID in the iteration body and registry |\n| `claim` | string | The single assertion the finding makes (one sentence, evidence-backed) |\n| `evidenceRefs` | string[] | `file:line` or `file:range` citations that substantiate the claim (at least one entry) |\n| `counterevidenceSought` | string | Where the reviewer looked for contradicting evidence (commands, paths, docs), blank string is not acceptable |\n| `alternativeExplanation` | string | An alternative reading of the evidence, even if the reviewer rejects it |\n| `finalSeverity` | `\"P0\"` \\| `\"P1\"` \\| `\"P2\"` | Severity after adjudication (may differ from the severity originally asserted) |\n| `confidence` | number `[0, 1]` | Reviewer confidence in `finalSeverity` |\n| `downgradeTrigger` | string | The concrete condition under which this finding should be downgraded in a future iteration |\n| `transitions` | object[] | Optional severity transition log, required when `finalSeverity` differs from the originally asserted severity |\n\n### Validation Rules (enforced by `step_post_iteration_claim_adjudication`)\n\n1. A packet MUST exist for every new P0/P1 finding introduced in this iteration. Carried-forward findings reuse the previous packet unless severity transitioned.\n2. All required fields MUST be present and non-empty. `confidence` MUST be a number in `[0, 1]`.\n3. Each `evidenceRefs` entry MUST contain a `:` separating the path from a line or range.\n4. `finalSeverity` MUST match the severity the finding is registered under in the iteration's `Findings` section and in `deep-review-findings-registry.json`.\n5. When any rule fails, the workflow appends `{\"event\":\"claim_adjudication\",\"passed\":false,\"missingPackets\":[...]}` to the state log. The next `step_check_convergence` call reads that event and sets `claimAdjudicationGate` = `false`, producing a `blockedStop` event with `blockedBy: [\"claimAdjudicationGate\"]` until a follow-up iteration rewrites the packet.\n\n### Severity Transition Rules\n\n- **P2 → P1**: confirmed exploitable impact or spec violation with direct evidence\n- **P1 → P0**: demonstrated data loss, security breach, or hard-gate failure\n- **Downgrade**: requires explicit counterevidence or a confirmed alternative explanation\n- Every transition is recorded in the packet's `transitions` array and mirrored into the finding registry's `transitions` field\n\n---\n\n## 10. FINDING REGISTRY\n\nEach finding is tracked with a unique identifier enabling deduplication, severity transitions, and status lifecycle.\n\n### Schema\n\n```json\n{\n  \"findingId\": \"F003\",\n  \"severity\": \"P1\",\n  \"category\": \"resource-map-coverage\",\n  \"status\": \"active\",\n  \"dimension\": \"traceability\",\n  \"title\": \"Applied target file missing from resource-map inventory\",\n  \"file\": \".opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_review_auto.yaml\",\n  \"line\": 955,\n  \"firstSeen\": 2,\n  \"lastSeen\": 4,\n  \"transitions\": [\n    { \"iteration\": 2, \"from\": null, \"to\": \"P2\", \"reason\": \"Initial discovery\" },\n    { \"iteration\": 4, \"from\": \"P2\", \"to\": \"P1\", \"reason\": \"Confirmed real coverage gap against applied target inventory\" }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n| Field | Type | Description |\n|-------|------|-------------|\n| findingId | string | Sequential unique ID: `F001`, `F002`, ... |\n| severity | `\"P0\"` / `\"P1\"` / `\"P2\"` | Current severity |\n| category | `\"correctness\"` / `\"security\"` / `\"traceability\"` / `\"maintainability\"` / `\"resource-map-coverage\"` | Primary audit category for the finding, `resource-map-coverage` is reserved for implementation-vs-map coverage gaps |\n| status | `\"active\"` / `\"resolved\"` / `\"deferred\"` / `\"disproved\"` | Current status |\n| dimension | string | Primary dimension: correctness, security, traceability, maintainability |\n| title | string | Short description |\n| file | string | File path |\n| line | number | Line number (approximate) |\n| firstSeen / lastSeen | number | Iteration where first discovered / last referenced |\n| transitions | array | Severity and status change history |\n\n### Status Lifecycle\n\n```text\n[discovered] --> active --> resolved    (fixed or confirmed non-issue)\n                  |\n                  +--> deferred    (advisory, below threshold)\n                  |\n                  +--> disproved   (counterevidence invalidated)\n```\n\n| Status | Counts Toward Verdict |\n|--------|----------------------|\n| active | Yes |\n| resolved | No |\n| deferred | No (listed in Deferred Items) |\n| disproved | No |\n\n### Deduplication\n\nSame file + line range + root cause as an existing finding = **refinement**, not new. The existing findingId is updated. Refinements count at half weight (`refinementMultiplier: 0.5`) and are tracked via `findingsRefined` in JSONL.\n\n### Cross-Reference Protocols\n\n| Protocol | Level | Applies To | Gate |\n|----------|-------|------------|------|\n| spec_code | core | all types | hard |\n| checklist_evidence | core | all types | hard |\n| skill_agent | overlay | skill | advisory |\n| agent_cross_runtime | overlay | agent | advisory |\n| feature_catalog_code | overlay | skill, spec-folder, track, files | advisory |\n| playbook_capability | overlay | skill, agent, spec-folder | advisory |\n\nSeverity for `resource-map-coverage` findings is calibrated to the coverage-gate outcome:\n- `P2` when an untouched map entry is explicitly `expected-by-scope`\n- `P1` when an untouched or absent path represents a real coverage gap\n- `P0` only when the missing coverage masks a release-blocking correctness or security risk\n\n### Quality Gates\n\n| Gate | Rule |\n|------|------|\n| Evidence | Every active finding backed by concrete file:line evidence |\n| Scope | Reviewed files and conclusions stay inside declared scope |\n| Coverage | Required dimensions and required protocols covered |\n\nAll three gates must pass before STOP. Gate failure forces `verdict: \"FAIL\"` regardless of finding counts.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":548,"totalLines":548,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/references/state/state_format.md","time":{"start":1783806723769,"end":1783806723790}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb0398888191aab8440d93216daa"}},"id":"prt_f532a86af001lHLniSOcfhXWFw","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723795,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_o0nFwt7znQZjDCMZ0NA9RQpE","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md","offset":1,"limit":800},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\n3: description: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"opencode cli reference\"\n6:   - \"opencode run flags\"\n7:   - \"opencode model selection\"\n8:   - \"opencode provider auth pre-flight\"\n9:   - \"opencode variant reasoning effort\"\n10:   - \"opencode version drift\"\n11: importance_tier: important\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 1.3.0.28\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n17: \n18: Comprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: ### Core Principle\n25: \n26: OpenCode is the framework that owns this repository. The same binary that hosts the operator's TUI session also accepts non-interactive invocations through `opencode run`. The cli-opencode skill calls `opencode run` from external runtimes (Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell) so the calling AI can dispatch a task into a fresh OpenCode session that loads the full plugin, skill, MCP, and Spec Kit Memory runtime.\n27: \n28: ### Purpose\n29: \n30: Provide a single-source reference for the OpenCode CLI surface — every subcommand cli-opencode invokes, every flag it pins, every agent it can route to, the version baseline it is built against, and the error envelopes that need explicit recovery.\n31: \n32: ### When to Use\n33: \n34: - Looking up an OpenCode CLI subcommand or flag during a delegation\n35: - Selecting a model + variant + agent for a dispatch\n36: - Confirming the version baseline before pinning a flag set\n37: - Troubleshooting a failed `opencode run` invocation\n38: - Confirming the self-invocation guard signal against the live binary\n39: \n40: ### Key Sources\n41: \n42: | Source | URL |\n43: |--------|-----|\n44: | **Binary** | `$(command -v opencode)` (typically `~/.superset/bin/opencode` or another local bin path) |\n45: | **Repository** | https://github.com/sst/opencode |\n46: | **Version baseline** | v1.3.17 (pinned in this reference) |\n47: | **Runtime** | Node.js 18+ for the npm install path; standalone binary on macOS |\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ## 2. INSTALLATION\n52: \n53: | Method | Command | Notes |\n54: |--------|---------|-------|\n55: | **Standalone** | `curl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install \\| bash` | macOS / Linux installer |\n56: | **Homebrew** | `brew install opencode` | macOS package manager |\n57: | **npm global** | `npm install -g opencode-ai` | Cross-platform when Node.js 18+ is present |\n58: | **Upgrade** | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Pin a specific version with the `target` argument |\n59: | **Uninstall** | `opencode uninstall` | Removes the binary and related state |\n60: \n61: After installation, run `opencode --version` to confirm. The cli-opencode skill is pinned to v1.3.17. Newer binaries may add or rename flags — consult Section 9 (Version Drift) before relying on a non-pinned flag.\n62: \n63: ---\n64: \n65: ## 3. SUBCOMMAND MAP\n66: \n67: OpenCode exposes a multi-subcommand surface. The cli-opencode skill primarily invokes `run`, with secondary use of `serve`, `web`, `agent`, and `debug`.\n68: \n69: | Subcommand | Purpose | Invoked by cli-opencode |\n70: |------------|---------|-------------------------|\n71: | `opencode` (default) | Start the TUI in the current project | No (interactive only) |\n72: | `opencode run [message..]` | Non-interactive single-shot dispatch | YES (canonical use case) |\n73: | `opencode serve` | Start a headless server | YES (for parallel detached sessions) |\n74: | `opencode web` | Start a server plus open the web interface | YES (when the operator wants a browser surface) |\n75: | `opencode acp` | Start an ACP (Agent Client Protocol) server | No (specialized integration path) |\n76: | `opencode attach <url>` | Attach to a running OpenCode server | YES (for share-URL flows) |\n77: | `opencode agent` | Manage agent definitions | YES (for agent listing) |\n78: | `opencode debug` | Debugging and troubleshooting tools | YES (for `debug skill` and `debug agent` listings) |\n79: | `opencode mcp` | Manage MCP server registrations | No |\n80: | `opencode providers` (alias `auth`) | Manage AI providers and credentials | No (operator-driven setup) |\n81: | `opencode models [provider]` | List available models | YES (for capability discovery) |\n82: | `opencode session` | Manage sessions | No (state inspection only) |\n83: | `opencode export [sessionID]` | Export session data as JSON | YES (for memory handback flows) |\n84: | `opencode stats` | Token and cost statistics | No |\n85: | `opencode db` | Database tools | No |\n86: | `opencode plugin <module>` (alias `plug`) | Install a plugin | No (operator-driven setup) |\n87: | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Upgrade the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n88: | `opencode uninstall` | Uninstall the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 4. `opencode run` FLAGS\n93: \n94: `opencode run [message..]` is the canonical non-interactive entry point. The cli-opencode skill builds every dispatch around this subcommand.\n95: \n96: ### Core flags\n97: \n98: | Flag / Option | Type | Purpose |\n99: |---------------|------|---------|\n100: | `[message..]` | positional | One or more positional message strings |\n101: | `--print-logs` | boolean | Stream logs to stderr |\n102: | `--log-level` | enum | `DEBUG`, `INFO`, `WARN`, `ERROR` |\n103: | `--pure` | boolean | Run without external plugins (skill loads disabled) |\n104: | `--command` | string | Run a known command, the message becomes its args |\n105: | `-c`, `--continue` | boolean | Continue the last session in this project |\n106: | `-s`, `--session` | string | Continue a specific session id |\n107: | `--fork` | boolean | Fork before continuing — requires `--continue` or `--session` |\n108: | `--share` | boolean | Publish a shareable URL for this session |\n109: | `-m`, `--model` | string | Provider/model selector — e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` |\n110: | `--agent` | string | Agent slug (loads from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md`) |\n111: | `--format` | enum | `default` (formatted) or `json` (raw event stream) |\n112: | `-f`, `--file` | array | Attach files to the message |\n113: | `--title` | string | Session title (truncated message used when omitted) |\n114: | `--attach` | string | Attach to a running OpenCode server URL |\n115: | `-p`, `--password` | string | Basic auth password (or `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD`) |\n116: | `--dir` | string | Working directory or remote-server path |\n117: | `--port` | number | Local server port (random when omitted) |\n118: | `--variant` | string | Provider-specific reasoning effort (`high`, `max`, `minimal`, etc.) |\n119: | `--thinking` | boolean | Show thinking blocks (default false) |\n120: \n121: > **`--command` semantics (verified on v1.17.4):** the `run` message is plain text — slash-command syntax inside it (`opencode run \"/memory:search query\"`) is NOT expanded, so the command's template never reaches the model. Executing a registered command non-interactively requires `--command <family>/<name>` with the args as the message (they become `$ARGUMENTS`). Registry names are slash-namespaced (`memory/search` for `/memory:search`); a wrong name fails with the full registry list. Behavior probes of slash commands MUST use `--command`; the raw-text form only measures the model freestyling without the contract.\n122: \n123: ### cli-opencode default invocation shape\n124: \n125: The skill builds every dispatch from a base shape and overlays use-case-specific flags:\n126: \n127: ```bash\n128: opencode run \\\n129:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n130:   --agent <agent-slug> \\\n131:   --variant high \\\n132:   --format json \\\n133:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n134:   \"<prompt>\"\n135: ```\n136: \n137: | Flag | Default | Reason |\n138: |------|---------|--------|\n139: | `--model` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Direct DeepSeek is the default provider — elevated reasoning at low cost; operator may override (e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash`, `kimi-for-coding/k2p7`, or any live OpenAI GPT-5.6 slug: `openai/gpt-5.6`, `openai/gpt-5.6-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) |\n140: | `--agent` | per use case | Required for use case 1 / 3; optional for use case 2 |\n141: | `--variant high` | high | Routine cli-opencode dispatches benefit from elevated reasoning effort |\n142: | `--format json` | json | Structured event stream is what external runtimes parse |\n143: | `--dir` | repo root | Pin the working directory to avoid CWD ambiguity |\n144: \n145: ### Stdin handling — `</dev/null` is required for non-interactive dispatch\n146: \n147: > **opencode v1.14.39 reads stdin at startup before session creation.** If you redirect stdout/stderr to files in automation (`> stdout.log 2> stderr.log`), opencode hangs at 0% CPU after the `+60s snapshot prune cleanup` log line because stdin remains attached to the parent terminal and never receives EOF.\n148: \n149: ALWAYS append `</dev/null` AFTER the prompt argument and BEFORE the stdout/stderr redirects:\n150: \n151: ```bash\n152: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n153: #                                  ^^^^^^^^^^\n154: #                                  redirects stdin from /dev/null → immediate EOF\n155: ```\n156: \n157: Foreground `| tail` accidentally works because the upstream pipe stage provides closed stdin, but `> file 2> file` does not. See `references/integration_patterns.md` §6 for the full failure-mode + fix matrix and `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 for the discovery context.\n158: \n159: ### Sessions, share URLs, and ports\n160: \n161: `--share` publishes the session over the OpenCode share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). External-runtime dispatches do NOT publish share URLs by default.\n162: \n163: `--port` only matters when the dispatch needs to bind a known port (e.g. for a parallel detached session that another tool will attach to). The default random port is correct for one-shot dispatches.\n164: \n165: `--continue` and `--session <id>` reuse prior session state. `--fork` branches an existing session into a new one. cli-opencode uses session continuation in memory handback flows where the calling AI wants to thread context across multiple delegations.\n166: \n167: ### Provider Auth Pre-Flight (smart fallback)\n168: \n169: Before the first dispatch in a session, run a one-shot auth pre-flight against `opencode providers list` so a missing default doesn't fail mid-dispatch. Cache the result for the session; only re-run on auth failure.\n170: \n171: ```bash\n172: # Pre-flight — one call per session\n173: PROVIDERS=$(opencode providers list 2>&1)\n174: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"deepseek\"            && DEEPSEEK_OK=1       || DEEPSEEK_OK=0\n175: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"minimax-coding-plan\" && MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1  || MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0   # MiniMax Token Plan (default MiniMax path)\n176: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"minimax([^-]|$)\"    && MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1 || MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0  # MiniMax Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the coding-plan provider\n177: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"xiaomi-token-plan-ams\" && XIAOMI_OK=1       || XIAOMI_OK=0          # Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\n178: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"xiaomi([^-]|$)\"     && XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1 || XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0   # Xiaomi Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the token-plan-ams provider\n179: echo \"default=$DEEPSEEK_OK minimax_token=$MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK minimax_direct=$MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK xiaomi=$XIAOMI_OK xiaomi_direct=$XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK\"\n180: ```\n181: \n182: | State | DEEPSEEK_OK | Action |\n183: |-------|-------------|--------|\n184: | Default available | 1 | Proceed with `--model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --variant high` |\n185: | Default missing | 0 | **ASK user** before substituting (offer A: openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro, B: login deepseek and retry, C: name a different model) — do not dispatch until configured |\n186: \n187: **MiniMax routing** (default = Token Plan; Direct API is the pay-per-token alternative):\n188: \n189: | State | Condition | Action |\n190: |-------|-----------|--------|\n191: | MiniMax requested (default) | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` — **omit `--agent`** (rejected on opencode 1.15.13) |\n192: | Token Plan not configured | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → MiniMax Token Plan — never substitute silently |\n193: | Direct API explicitly requested | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax/MiniMax-M3` (pay-per-token; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax`) |\n194: | Direct API requested, not configured | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to configure the `minimax` provider (`MINIMAX_API_KEY`) — do not substitute silently |\n195: \n196: **MiMo routing** (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe and Xiaomi Direct API; explicitly-selectable — first match wins):\n197: \n198: | State | Condition | Action |\n199: |-------|-----------|--------|\n200: | MiMo requested (default) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` — **omit `--agent`** (`--agent general` warns and falls back on opencode 1.15.13). Confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n201: | MiMo speed variant (\"ultraspeed\", latency-sensitive) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` — low-latency MiMo-V2.5-Pro tier, same prompt contract |\n202: | Token Plan explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_OK=1` | `--model xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` — NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead |\n203: | Token Plan not configured | `XIAOMI_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — never substitute silently |\n204: | Direct API explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` or `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` (pay-per-token; confirm live ids via `opencode models xiaomi`) |\n205: | Direct API requested, not configured | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode providers login xiaomi` — never substitute silently |\n206: \n207: **Login / setup command shapes** (the AI surfaces these to the user; the user runs them in their own terminal):\n208: \n209: ```bash\n210: # Recommended default — direct DeepSeek API\n211: opencode providers login deepseek\n212: \n213: # MiniMax Token Plan — DEFAULT MiniMax path (subscription). Interactive: pick \"MiniMax Token Plan (minimax.io)\".\n214: opencode auth login          # → provider minimax-coding-plan; Anthropic-compatible https://api.minimax.io/anthropic/v1 (China: api.minimaxi.com)\n215: \n216: # MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative (needs MINIMAX_API_KEY; platform endpoint https://api.minimax.io/v1)\n217: opencode providers login minimax\n218: \n219: # Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — provider-managed endpoint. Interactive: pick \"Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\".\n220: opencode auth login          # → provider xiaomi-token-plan-ams (Xiaomi Token Plan, Europe)\n221: \n222: # Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token alternative\n223: opencode providers login xiaomi\n224: \n225: # Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM coding subscription. Interactive: pick \"Z.AI Coding Plan\".\n226: opencode auth login          # → provider zai-coding-plan; model zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2\n227: ```\n228: \n229: > Do not mix region endpoints (international `minimax.io` vs China `minimaxi.com`). Confirm live model ids with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan`. The Xiaomi endpoint is provider-managed (no documented base URL — do not invent one); confirm live model ids with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Token Plan) or `opencode models xiaomi` (Direct API).\n230: \n231: **On auth-error mid-dispatch** (`401 Unauthorized`, `provider/model not found`): invalidate the cache, rerun the pre-flight, and apply the same decision tree before retrying. Never substitute a model the user didn't approve.\n232: \n233: ---\n234: \n235: ## 5. MODEL SELECTION\n236: \n237: OpenCode resolves models through configured providers. The cli-opencode skill supports `deepseek` (default), `minimax-coding-plan` (MiniMax Token Plan — default MiniMax path), `minimax` (MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative), `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe — MiMo, explicitly-selectable; NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead), and `xiaomi` (Xiaomi Direct API — MiMo: `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` + low-latency `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, pay-per-token) — confirmed against `opencode providers list` and `opencode models`. Run `opencode models [provider]` for the full live list on a given install.\n238: \n239: | Provider | Example model id | Use case |\n240: |----------|------------------|----------|\n241: | `deepseek` (DEFAULT) | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Default — deep reasoning at low cost via direct DeepSeek API |\n242: | `deepseek` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash` | Latency-optimized direct-API sibling |\n243: | `kimi-for-coding` | `kimi-for-coding/k2p7` | Long-context Kimi K2.7 Code (256k; subscription plan) |\n244: | `zai-coding-plan` | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2` | Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM-5.2 flagship long-horizon coding (1M context; subscription); omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models zai-coding-plan` |\n245: | `minimax-coding-plan` (DEFAULT MiniMax) | `minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Token Plan (subscription) — default MiniMax dispatch; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan` |\n246: | `minimax` | `minimax/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative; needs `MINIMAX_API_KEY`; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax` |\n247: | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — MiMo-V2.5-Pro: 1M-token context, strongly agentic (1000+ tool calls), token-efficient; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` |\n248: | `xiaomi` | `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token; MiMo-V2.5-Pro; confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n249: \n250: `opencode models <provider>` lists every model id the provider exposes. The model string passed to `--model` is always `provider/model-id`.\n251: \n252: ### Reasoning effort via `--variant`\n253: \n254: The `--variant` flag maps to provider-specific reasoning effort. Underlying-model conventions apply per provider routing.\n255: \n256: | Provider | Variant values |\n257: |----------|----------------|\n258: | `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-pro`) | reasoning effort accepted |\n259: | `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-flash`) | non-reasoning — `--variant` ignored |\n260: | `minimax-coding-plan` / `minimax` (MiniMax-M3) | `--variant` behavior unverified — omitted by default; confirm against the MiniMax API before relying on it |\n261: | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (mimo-v2.5-pro) | `--variant` maps to MiMo reasoning effort (low/medium/high); **always use `--variant high`** (confirmed accepted on opencode 1.15.13) |\n262: | `zai-coding-plan` (glm-5.2) | GLM has native `reasoning_effort` (high/max); whether opencode `--variant` forwards to it is unverified — smoke-test before relying on it |\n263: | `openai` GPT-5.6 (`gpt-5.6` / `gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) | `--variant` maps to OpenAI reasoning effort — a separate lever from the model tier: `none`/`low`/`medium`/`high`/**`xhigh`** (Pro tiers — `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`: `medium`/`high`/`xhigh` — **inferred from the now-retired `gpt-5.5-pro` mapping and unverified against the live catalog (which no longer lists `gpt-5.5-pro` to re-check); smoke-test a Pro slug at `--variant low` before relying on the restriction**). **The `-fast` slugs** (`gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast`) are the low-latency **Fast** model tier (OpenAI `priority` service tier) with the same effort range — e.g. `--model openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast --variant xhigh`. `gpt-5.6-sol` is the flagship default; confirm live slugs via `opencode models openai`. |\n264: \n265: Default skill behavior: pass `--variant high` for cross-AI dispatches. Operators may override via the prompt template's variant field.\n266: \n267: ---\n268: \n269: ## 6. AGENT FLAG\n270: \n271: `--agent <slug>` loads an agent definition from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md` (project-local) or the user-level fallback. The agent definition's frontmatter pins the model, tool permissions, and system prompt that shape the dispatch.\n272: \n273: ### Discovering agents\n274: \n275: | Command | What it shows |\n276: |---------|---------------|\n277: | `opencode agent list` | All registered agent slugs across project + user scopes |\n278: | `opencode debug agent <slug>` | Resolved frontmatter and system prompt for a slug |\n279: | `opencode debug skill <slug>` | Skill resolution for a slug if the agent loads one |\n280: \n281: ### Agent slugs in this repo\n282: \n283: | Slug | Role |\n284: |------|------|\n285: | `general` | Implementation, default subagent |\n286: | `context` | Read-only retrieval and search |\n287: | `orchestrate` | Multi-agent coordination |\n288: | `write` | Documentation generation |\n289: | `review` | Code review and PR analysis |\n290: | `debug` | Fresh-perspective debugging |\n291: | `deep-research` | Iterative research loop executor |\n292: | `deep-review` | Iterative code review loop executor |\n293: | `ai-council` | Multi-strategy planning |\n294: | `deep-improvement` | Agent improvement proposal mutator |\n295: \n296: The cli-opencode skill defers to the calling AI on agent selection — see `references/agent_delegation.md` for the routing matrix and `assets/prompt_templates.md` for canonical invocation shapes.\n297: \n298: ---\n299: \n300: ## 7. OUTPUT FORMAT AND EVENT STREAM\n301: \n302: `--format default` produces a human-formatted log. `--format json` emits a newline-delimited JSON event stream.\n303: \n304: ### JSON event shape (v1.3.17)\n305: \n306: Each line is a JSON object with at minimum:\n307: \n308: | Field | Meaning |\n309: |-------|---------|\n310: | `type` | Event type (`session.started`, `message.delta`, `tool.call`, `tool.result`, `session.completed`, ...) |\n311: | `timestamp` | ISO 8601 UTC timestamp |\n312: | `session_id` | The session id assigned by OpenCode |\n313: | `payload` | Type-specific payload |\n314: \n315: External runtimes parse the stream incrementally to surface tool calls, partial messages, and the final summary. cli-opencode prompt templates always pass `--format json` so the calling AI parses structured events instead of guessing format boundaries.\n316: \n317: ---\n318: \n319: ## 8. STATE LOCATION AND SHARE URLS\n320: \n321: ### State directory\n322: \n323: OpenCode persists session state in a shared SQLite database and storage tree under `~/.local/share/opencode/`:\n324: \n325: - `opencode.db` (`-shm`/`-wal` companions) — the session/message database\n326: - `storage/` — per-session structured artifacts\n327: - `snapshot/` — working-tree snapshots\n328: \n329: There is no per-session directory under `~/.opencode/state/<session_id>/` on a standard install — that path does not exist on this runtime layout. To inspect a specific session, use `opencode export <session_id>` (§3) rather than reading files from a state directory. The cli-opencode self-invocation guard's Layer 3 lock-file probe (`~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock`, per ADR-001) targets the older path as a best-effort third layer on top of the env-var and process-ancestry checks; treat it as a heuristic, not a verified-present artifact, on installs where `~/.opencode/state/` does not exist.\n330: \n331: ### Share URLs\n332: \n333: `--share` publishes a session URL via OpenCode's share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). The CHK-033 P1 checklist item requires operator confirmation before publishing a share URL because the URL exposes the session contents.\n334: \n335: ---\n336: \n337: ## 9. VERSION DRIFT\n338: \n339: This reference is pinned to OpenCode v1.3.17. If the live binary reports a different version, do the following:\n340: \n341: 1. Run `opencode run --help` and diff the flag list against Section 4.\n342: 2. Run `opencode --help` and diff the subcommand list against Section 3.\n343: 3. If a flag was renamed, prefer the new name in the dispatch. If a flag was removed, fall back to the closest analogue and surface the drift in the calling AI's response.\n344: 4. If the operator's machine has a major version bump (v1.4+, v2.x), re-validate the entire skill against the new flag table and bump the cli-opencode minor version.\n345: \n346: ### Failure modes specific to drift\n347: \n348: | Symptom | Likely cause |\n349: |---------|--------------|\n350: | `unknown option --variant` | v1.2 or earlier — variant flag was named `--reasoning` |\n351: | `unknown option --share` | Older standalone build without share infrastructure |\n352: | `unknown option --format json` | v1.0 — JSON event stream was the default and the flag did not exist |\n353: | `MODULE_NOT_FOUND` | Plugin loader crash; rerun with `--pure` to bypass plugins |\n354: \n355: ---\n356: \n357: ## 10. TROUBLESHOOTING\n358: \n359: | Symptom | Cause | Fix |\n360: |---------|-------|-----|\n361: | `command not found: opencode` | Binary not on PATH | Install via standalone installer or `brew install opencode` |\n362: | `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD required` | Server enforces basic auth | Pass `-p <password>` or set the env var |\n363: | `provider/model not found` | Provider not configured | Run `opencode providers` to enumerate, then `auth login <provider>` |\n364: | Empty output stream | `--format default` with non-TTY parent | Pass `--format json` and parse the event stream |\n365: | Session never finishes | Tool call hung | Run `opencode export <session_id>` and inspect the message log it returns |\n366: | Plugin load crash | Misconfigured plugin | Rerun with `--pure` to bypass all plugins |\n367: | Self-invocation refused | cli-opencode detected an in-OpenCode runtime | Use a sibling cli-* skill or a fresh shell session — see ADR-001 |\n368: | `--share` URL leaks | Share infrastructure published a session containing secrets | Operator MUST confirm before publishing per CHK-033 |\n369: \n370: ---\n371: \n372: ## 11. RELATED RESOURCES\n373: \n374: - `./integration_patterns.md` - The three documented use cases and their copy-paste invocation shapes\n375: - `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix and invocation patterns\n376: - `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique capabilities (full plugin/skill/MCP runtime, parallel detached sessions)\n377: - `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste prompt templates per use case\n378: - `../assets/prompt_quality_card.md` - Framework selection and CLEAR 5-check\n379: - `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router\n\n(End of file - total 379 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\ndescription: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode cli reference\"\n  - \"opencode run flags\"\n  - \"opencode model selection\"\n  - \"opencode provider auth pre-flight\"\n  - \"opencode variant reasoning effort\"\n  - \"opencode version drift\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.28\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n\nComprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\ndescription: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode cli reference\"\n  - \"opencode run flags\"\n  - \"opencode model selection\"\n  - \"opencode provider auth pre-flight\"\n  - \"opencode variant reasoning effort\"\n  - \"opencode version drift\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.28\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n\nComprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\n\nOpenCode is the framework that owns this repository. The same binary that hosts the operator's TUI session also accepts non-interactive invocations through `opencode run`. The cli-opencode skill calls `opencode run` from external runtimes (Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell) so the calling AI can dispatch a task into a fresh OpenCode session that loads the full plugin, skill, MCP, and Spec Kit Memory runtime.\n\n### Purpose\n\nProvide a single-source reference for the OpenCode CLI surface — every subcommand cli-opencode invokes, every flag it pins, every agent it can route to, the version baseline it is built against, and the error envelopes that need explicit recovery.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Looking up an OpenCode CLI subcommand or flag during a delegation\n- Selecting a model + variant + agent for a dispatch\n- Confirming the version baseline before pinning a flag set\n- Troubleshooting a failed `opencode run` invocation\n- Confirming the self-invocation guard signal against the live binary\n\n### Key Sources\n\n| Source | URL |\n|--------|-----|\n| **Binary** | `$(command -v opencode)` (typically `~/.superset/bin/opencode` or another local bin path) |\n| **Repository** | https://github.com/sst/opencode |\n| **Version baseline** | v1.3.17 (pinned in this reference) |\n| **Runtime** | Node.js 18+ for the npm install path; standalone binary on macOS |\n\n---\n\n## 2. INSTALLATION\n\n| Method | Command | Notes |\n|--------|---------|-------|\n| **Standalone** | `curl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install \\| bash` | macOS / Linux installer |\n| **Homebrew** | `brew install opencode` | macOS package manager |\n| **npm global** | `npm install -g opencode-ai` | Cross-platform when Node.js 18+ is present |\n| **Upgrade** | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Pin a specific version with the `target` argument |\n| **Uninstall** | `opencode uninstall` | Removes the binary and related state |\n\nAfter installation, run `opencode --version` to confirm. The cli-opencode skill is pinned to v1.3.17. Newer binaries may add or rename flags — consult Section 9 (Version Drift) before relying on a non-pinned flag.\n\n---\n\n## 3. SUBCOMMAND MAP\n\nOpenCode exposes a multi-subcommand surface. The cli-opencode skill primarily invokes `run`, with secondary use of `serve`, `web`, `agent`, and `debug`.\n\n| Subcommand | Purpose | Invoked by cli-opencode |\n|------------|---------|-------------------------|\n| `opencode` (default) | Start the TUI in the current project | No (interactive only) |\n| `opencode run [message..]` | Non-interactive single-shot dispatch | YES (canonical use case) |\n| `opencode serve` | Start a headless server | YES (for parallel detached sessions) |\n| `opencode web` | Start a server plus open the web interface | YES (when the operator wants a browser surface) |\n| `opencode acp` | Start an ACP (Agent Client Protocol) server | No (specialized integration path) |\n| `opencode attach <url>` | Attach to a running OpenCode server | YES (for share-URL flows) |\n| `opencode agent` | Manage agent definitions | YES (for agent listing) |\n| `opencode debug` | Debugging and troubleshooting tools | YES (for `debug skill` and `debug agent` listings) |\n| `opencode mcp` | Manage MCP server registrations | No |\n| `opencode providers` (alias `auth`) | Manage AI providers and credentials | No (operator-driven setup) |\n| `opencode models [provider]` | List available models | YES (for capability discovery) |\n| `opencode session` | Manage sessions | No (state inspection only) |\n| `opencode export [sessionID]` | Export session data as JSON | YES (for memory handback flows) |\n| `opencode stats` | Token and cost statistics | No |\n| `opencode db` | Database tools | No |\n| `opencode plugin <module>` (alias `plug`) | Install a plugin | No (operator-driven setup) |\n| `opencode upgrade [target]` | Upgrade the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n| `opencode uninstall` | Uninstall the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n\n---\n\n## 4. `opencode run` FLAGS\n\n`opencode run [message..]` is the canonical non-interactive entry point. The cli-opencode skill builds every dispatch around this subcommand.\n\n### Core flags\n\n| Flag / Option | Type | Purpose |\n|---------------|------|---------|\n| `[message..]` | positional | One or more positional message strings |\n| `--print-logs` | boolean | Stream logs to stderr |\n| `--log-level` | enum | `DEBUG`, `INFO`, `WARN`, `ERROR` |\n| `--pure` | boolean | Run without external plugins (skill loads disabled) |\n| `--command` | string | Run a known command, the message becomes its args |\n| `-c`, `--continue` | boolean | Continue the last session in this project |\n| `-s`, `--session` | string | Continue a specific session id |\n| `--fork` | boolean | Fork before continuing — requires `--continue` or `--session` |\n| `--share` | boolean | Publish a shareable URL for this session |\n| `-m`, `--model` | string | Provider/model selector — e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` |\n| `--agent` | string | Agent slug (loads from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md`) |\n| `--format` | enum | `default` (formatted) or `json` (raw event stream) |\n| `-f`, `--file` | array | Attach files to the message |\n| `--title` | string | Session title (truncated message used when omitted) |\n| `--attach` | string | Attach to a running OpenCode server URL |\n| `-p`, `--password` | string | Basic auth password (or `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD`) |\n| `--dir` | string | Working directory or remote-server path |\n| `--port` | number | Local server port (random when omitted) |\n| `--variant` | string | Provider-specific reasoning effort (`high`, `max`, `minimal`, etc.) |\n| `--thinking` | boolean | Show thinking blocks (default false) |\n\n> **`--command` semantics (verified on v1.17.4):** the `run` message is plain text — slash-command syntax inside it (`opencode run \"/memory:search query\"`) is NOT expanded, so the command's template never reaches the model. Executing a registered command non-interactively requires `--command <family>/<name>` with the args as the message (they become `$ARGUMENTS`). Registry names are slash-namespaced (`memory/search` for `/memory:search`); a wrong name fails with the full registry list. Behavior probes of slash commands MUST use `--command`; the raw-text form only measures the model freestyling without the contract.\n\n### cli-opencode default invocation shape\n\nThe skill builds every dispatch from a base shape and overlays use-case-specific flags:\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent <agent-slug> \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt>\"\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Reason |\n|------|---------|--------|\n| `--model` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Direct DeepSeek is the default provider — elevated reasoning at low cost; operator may override (e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash`, `kimi-for-coding/k2p7`, or any live OpenAI GPT-5.6 slug: `openai/gpt-5.6`, `openai/gpt-5.6-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) |\n| `--agent` | per use case | Required for use case 1 / 3; optional for use case 2 |\n| `--variant high` | high | Routine cli-opencode dispatches benefit from elevated reasoning effort |\n| `--format json` | json | Structured event stream is what external runtimes parse |\n| `--dir` | repo root | Pin the working directory to avoid CWD ambiguity |\n\n### Stdin handling — `</dev/null` is required for non-interactive dispatch\n\n> **opencode v1.14.39 reads stdin at startup before session creation.** If you redirect stdout/stderr to files in automation (`> stdout.log 2> stderr.log`), opencode hangs at 0% CPU after the `+60s snapshot prune cleanup` log line because stdin remains attached to the parent terminal and never receives EOF.\n\nALWAYS append `</dev/null` AFTER the prompt argument and BEFORE the stdout/stderr redirects:\n\n```bash\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n#                                  ^^^^^^^^^^\n#                                  redirects stdin from /dev/null → immediate EOF\n```\n\nForeground `| tail` accidentally works because the upstream pipe stage provides closed stdin, but `> file 2> file` does not. See `references/integration_patterns.md` §6 for the full failure-mode + fix matrix and `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 for the discovery context.\n\n### Sessions, share URLs, and ports\n\n`--share` publishes the session over the OpenCode share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). External-runtime dispatches do NOT publish share URLs by default.\n\n`--port` only matters when the dispatch needs to bind a known port (e.g. for a parallel detached session that another tool will attach to). The default random port is correct for one-shot dispatches.\n\n`--continue` and `--session <id>` reuse prior session state. `--fork` branches an existing session into a new one. cli-opencode uses session continuation in memory handback flows where the calling AI wants to thread context across multiple delegations.\n\n### Provider Auth Pre-Flight (smart fallback)\n\nBefore the first dispatch in a session, run a one-shot auth pre-flight against `opencode providers list` so a missing default doesn't fail mid-dispatch. Cache the result for the session; only re-run on auth failure.\n\n```bash\n# Pre-flight — one call per session\nPROVIDERS=$(opencode providers list 2>&1)\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"deepseek\"            && DEEPSEEK_OK=1       || DEEPSEEK_OK=0\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"minimax-coding-plan\" && MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1  || MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0   # MiniMax Token Plan (default MiniMax path)\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"minimax([^-]|$)\"    && MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1 || MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0  # MiniMax Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the coding-plan provider\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"xiaomi-token-plan-ams\" && XIAOMI_OK=1       || XIAOMI_OK=0          # Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"xiaomi([^-]|$)\"     && XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1 || XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0   # Xiaomi Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the token-plan-ams provider\necho \"default=$DEEPSEEK_OK minimax_token=$MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK minimax_direct=$MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK xiaomi=$XIAOMI_OK xiaomi_direct=$XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK\"\n```\n\n| State | DEEPSEEK_OK | Action |\n|-------|-------------|--------|\n| Default available | 1 | Proceed with `--model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --variant high` |\n| Default missing | 0 | **ASK user** before substituting (offer A: openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro, B: login deepseek and retry, C: name a different model) — do not dispatch until configured |\n\n**MiniMax routing** (default = Token Plan; Direct API is the pay-per-token alternative):\n\n| State | Condition | Action |\n|-------|-----------|--------|\n| MiniMax requested (default) | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` — **omit `--agent`** (rejected on opencode 1.15.13) |\n| Token Plan not configured | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → MiniMax Token Plan — never substitute silently |\n| Direct API explicitly requested | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax/MiniMax-M3` (pay-per-token; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax`) |\n| Direct API requested, not configured | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to configure the `minimax` provider (`MINIMAX_API_KEY`) — do not substitute silently |\n\n**MiMo routing** (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe and Xiaomi Direct API; explicitly-selectable — first match wins):\n\n| State | Condition | Action |\n|-------|-----------|--------|\n| MiMo requested (default) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` — **omit `--agent`** (`--agent general` warns and falls back on opencode 1.15.13). Confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n| MiMo speed variant (\"ultraspeed\", latency-sensitive) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` — low-latency MiMo-V2.5-Pro tier, same prompt contract |\n| Token Plan explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_OK=1` | `--model xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` — NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead |\n| Token Plan not configured | `XIAOMI_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — never substitute silently |\n| Direct API explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` or `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` (pay-per-token; confirm live ids via `opencode models xiaomi`) |\n| Direct API requested, not configured | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode providers login xiaomi` — never substitute silently |\n\n**Login / setup command shapes** (the AI surfaces these to the user; the user runs them in their own terminal):\n\n```bash\n# Recommended default — direct DeepSeek API\nopencode providers login deepseek\n\n# MiniMax Token Plan — DEFAULT MiniMax path (subscription). Interactive: pick \"MiniMax Token Plan (minimax.io)\".\nopencode auth login          # → provider minimax-coding-plan; Anthropic-compatible https://api.minimax.io/anthropic/v1 (China: api.minimaxi.com)\n\n# MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative (needs MINIMAX_API_KEY; platform endpoint https://api.minimax.io/v1)\nopencode providers login minimax\n\n# Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — provider-managed endpoint. Interactive: pick \"Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\".\nopencode auth login          # → provider xiaomi-token-plan-ams (Xiaomi Token Plan, Europe)\n\n# Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token alternative\nopencode providers login xiaomi\n\n# Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM coding subscription. Interactive: pick \"Z.AI Coding Plan\".\nopencode auth login          # → provider zai-coding-plan; model zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2\n```\n\n> Do not mix region endpoints (international `minimax.io` vs China `minimaxi.com`). Confirm live model ids with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan`. The Xiaomi endpoint is provider-managed (no documented base URL — do not invent one); confirm live model ids with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Token Plan) or `opencode models xiaomi` (Direct API).\n\n**On auth-error mid-dispatch** (`401 Unauthorized`, `provider/model not found`): invalidate the cache, rerun the pre-flight, and apply the same decision tree before retrying. Never substitute a model the user didn't approve.\n\n---\n\n## 5. MODEL SELECTION\n\nOpenCode resolves models through configured providers. The cli-opencode skill supports `deepseek` (default), `minimax-coding-plan` (MiniMax Token Plan — default MiniMax path), `minimax` (MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative), `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe — MiMo, explicitly-selectable; NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead), and `xiaomi` (Xiaomi Direct API — MiMo: `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` + low-latency `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, pay-per-token) — confirmed against `opencode providers list` and `opencode models`. Run `opencode models [provider]` for the full live list on a given install.\n\n| Provider | Example model id | Use case |\n|----------|------------------|----------|\n| `deepseek` (DEFAULT) | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Default — deep reasoning at low cost via direct DeepSeek API |\n| `deepseek` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash` | Latency-optimized direct-API sibling |\n| `kimi-for-coding` | `kimi-for-coding/k2p7` | Long-context Kimi K2.7 Code (256k; subscription plan) |\n| `zai-coding-plan` | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2` | Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM-5.2 flagship long-horizon coding (1M context; subscription); omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models zai-coding-plan` |\n| `minimax-coding-plan` (DEFAULT MiniMax) | `minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Token Plan (subscription) — default MiniMax dispatch; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan` |\n| `minimax` | `minimax/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative; needs `MINIMAX_API_KEY`; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax` |\n| `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — MiMo-V2.5-Pro: 1M-token context, strongly agentic (1000+ tool calls), token-efficient; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` |\n| `xiaomi` | `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token; MiMo-V2.5-Pro; confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n\n`opencode models <provider>` lists every model id the provider exposes. The model string passed to `--model` is always `provider/model-id`.\n\n### Reasoning effort via `--variant`\n\nThe `--variant` flag maps to provider-specific reasoning effort. Underlying-model conventions apply per provider routing.\n\n| Provider | Variant values |\n|----------|----------------|\n| `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-pro`) | reasoning effort accepted |\n| `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-flash`) | non-reasoning — `--variant` ignored |\n| `minimax-coding-plan` / `minimax` (MiniMax-M3) | `--variant` behavior unverified — omitted by default; confirm against the MiniMax API before relying on it |\n| `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (mimo-v2.5-pro) | `--variant` maps to MiMo reasoning effort (low/medium/high); **always use `--variant high`** (confirmed accepted on opencode 1.15.13) |\n| `zai-coding-plan` (glm-5.2) | GLM has native `reasoning_effort` (high/max); whether opencode `--variant` forwards to it is unverified — smoke-test before relying on it |\n| `openai` GPT-5.6 (`gpt-5.6` / `gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) | `--variant` maps to OpenAI reasoning effort — a separate lever from the model tier: `none`/`low`/`medium`/`high`/**`xhigh`** (Pro tiers — `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`: `medium`/`high`/`xhigh` — **inferred from the now-retired `gpt-5.5-pro` mapping and unverified against the live catalog (which no longer lists `gpt-5.5-pro` to re-check); smoke-test a Pro slug at `--variant low` before relying on the restriction**). **The `-fast` slugs** (`gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast`) are the low-latency **Fast** model tier (OpenAI `priority` service tier) with the same effort range — e.g. `--model openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast --variant xhigh`. `gpt-5.6-sol` is the flagship default; confirm live slugs via `opencode models openai`. |\n\nDefault skill behavior: pass `--variant high` for cross-AI dispatches. Operators may override via the prompt template's variant field.\n\n---\n\n## 6. AGENT FLAG\n\n`--agent <slug>` loads an agent definition from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md` (project-local) or the user-level fallback. The agent definition's frontmatter pins the model, tool permissions, and system prompt that shape the dispatch.\n\n### Discovering agents\n\n| Command | What it shows |\n|---------|---------------|\n| `opencode agent list` | All registered agent slugs across project + user scopes |\n| `opencode debug agent <slug>` | Resolved frontmatter and system prompt for a slug |\n| `opencode debug skill <slug>` | Skill resolution for a slug if the agent loads one |\n\n### Agent slugs in this repo\n\n| Slug | Role |\n|------|------|\n| `general` | Implementation, default subagent |\n| `context` | Read-only retrieval and search |\n| `orchestrate` | Multi-agent coordination |\n| `write` | Documentation generation |\n| `review` | Code review and PR analysis |\n| `debug` | Fresh-perspective debugging |\n| `deep-research` | Iterative research loop executor |\n| `deep-review` | Iterative code review loop executor |\n| `ai-council` | Multi-strategy planning |\n| `deep-improvement` | Agent improvement proposal mutator |\n\nThe cli-opencode skill defers to the calling AI on agent selection — see `references/agent_delegation.md` for the routing matrix and `assets/prompt_templates.md` for canonical invocation shapes.\n\n---\n\n## 7. OUTPUT FORMAT AND EVENT STREAM\n\n`--format default` produces a human-formatted log. `--format json` emits a newline-delimited JSON event stream.\n\n### JSON event shape (v1.3.17)\n\nEach line is a JSON object with at minimum:\n\n| Field | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| `type` | Event type (`session.started`, `message.delta`, `tool.call`, `tool.result`, `session.completed`, ...) |\n| `timestamp` | ISO 8601 UTC timestamp |\n| `session_id` | The session id assigned by OpenCode |\n| `payload` | Type-specific payload |\n\nExternal runtimes parse the stream incrementally to surface tool calls, partial messages, and the final summary. cli-opencode prompt templates always pass `--format json` so the calling AI parses structured events instead of guessing format boundaries.\n\n---\n\n## 8. STATE LOCATION AND SHARE URLS\n\n### State directory\n\nOpenCode persists session state in a shared SQLite database and storage tree under `~/.local/share/opencode/`:\n\n- `opencode.db` (`-shm`/`-wal` companions) — the session/message database\n- `storage/` — per-session structured artifacts\n- `snapshot/` — working-tree snapshots\n\nThere is no per-session directory under `~/.opencode/state/<session_id>/` on a standard install — that path does not exist on this runtime layout. To inspect a specific session, use `opencode export <session_id>` (§3) rather than reading files from a state directory. The cli-opencode self-invocation guard's Layer 3 lock-file probe (`~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock`, per ADR-001) targets the older path as a best-effort third layer on top of the env-var and process-ancestry checks; treat it as a heuristic, not a verified-present artifact, on installs where `~/.opencode/state/` does not exist.\n\n### Share URLs\n\n`--share` publishes a session URL via OpenCode's share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). The CHK-033 P1 checklist item requires operator confirmation before publishing a share URL because the URL exposes the session contents.\n\n---\n\n## 9. VERSION DRIFT\n\nThis reference is pinned to OpenCode v1.3.17. If the live binary reports a different version, do the following:\n\n1. Run `opencode run --help` and diff the flag list against Section 4.\n2. Run `opencode --help` and diff the subcommand list against Section 3.\n3. If a flag was renamed, prefer the new name in the dispatch. If a flag was removed, fall back to the closest analogue and surface the drift in the calling AI's response.\n4. If the operator's machine has a major version bump (v1.4+, v2.x), re-validate the entire skill against the new flag table and bump the cli-opencode minor version.\n\n### Failure modes specific to drift\n\n| Symptom | Likely cause |\n|---------|--------------|\n| `unknown option --variant` | v1.2 or earlier — variant flag was named `--reasoning` |\n| `unknown option --share` | Older standalone build without share infrastructure |\n| `unknown option --format json` | v1.0 — JSON event stream was the default and the flag did not exist |\n| `MODULE_NOT_FOUND` | Plugin loader crash; rerun with `--pure` to bypass plugins |\n\n---\n\n## 10. TROUBLESHOOTING\n\n| Symptom | Cause | Fix |\n|---------|-------|-----|\n| `command not found: opencode` | Binary not on PATH | Install via standalone installer or `brew install opencode` |\n| `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD required` | Server enforces basic auth | Pass `-p <password>` or set the env var |\n| `provider/model not found` | Provider not configured | Run `opencode providers` to enumerate, then `auth login <provider>` |\n| Empty output stream | `--format default` with non-TTY parent | Pass `--format json` and parse the event stream |\n| Session never finishes | Tool call hung | Run `opencode export <session_id>` and inspect the message log it returns |\n| Plugin load crash | Misconfigured plugin | Rerun with `--pure` to bypass all plugins |\n| Self-invocation refused | cli-opencode detected an in-OpenCode runtime | Use a sibling cli-* skill or a fresh shell session — see ADR-001 |\n| `--share` URL leaks | Share infrastructure published a session containing secrets | Operator MUST confirm before publishing per CHK-033 |\n\n---\n\n## 11. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- `./integration_patterns.md` - The three documented use cases and their copy-paste invocation shapes\n- `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix and invocation patterns\n- `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique capabilities (full plugin/skill/MCP runtime, parallel detached sessions)\n- `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste prompt templates per use case\n- `../assets/prompt_quality_card.md` - Framework selection and CLEAR 5-check\n- `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":379,"totalLines":379,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md","time":{"start":1783806723775,"end":1783806723791}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb0398988191afe1a78f01b8201b"}},"id":"prt_f532a86be0011RBtGdKX1KX4Ey","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723795,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_4Q9zu3pbitIwgMoyx4KOh7hP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md","offset":1,"limit":800},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n3: description: Fast-path prompt discipline for OpenCode CLI dispatches; frameworks and CLEAR are canonical in sk-prompt.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"opencode prompt quality card\"\n6:   - \"opencode model overrides\"\n7:   - \"minimax tidd-ec dense pre-plan\"\n8:   - \"mimo costar lean prompt\"\n9:   - \"opencode dispatch framework precedence\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: planning\n12: version: 1.3.0.21\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n16: \n17: Fast-path dispatch discipline for `opencode run` prompts. The 7-framework table, task-to-framework map, pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are owned by the canonical card — do not inline them here.\n18: \n19: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n20: \n21: ### Purpose\n22: \n23: This card is the OpenCode CLI fast-path prompt-quality reference; it delegates the framework table + CLEAR check to the canonical card and records only OpenCode-specific model overrides plus the precedence rule.\n24: \n25: ### Usage\n26: \n27: Compose a dispatch prompt by starting from the shared layer (canonical card), applying the OpenCode model overrides, and following the precedence rule.\n28: \n29: ---\n30: \n31: ## 2. SHARED LAYER (DELEGATED — DO NOT INLINE)\n32: \n33: The 7-framework selection table, the task->framework map, the pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are OWNED by the canonical card. Do NOT copy them here.\n34: \n35: -> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md`  (deep theory: `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-improve/references/patterns_evaluation.md`)\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 3. OPENCODE MODEL OVERRIDES\n40: \n41: OpenCode dispatches the MiniMax, MiMo, DeepSeek-v4-pro, and Kimi-K2.7 small models, which override or default against the cross-model defaults from the canonical card:\n42: \n43: | Model (dispatchable here) | Override | Profile |\n44: |---|---|---|\n45: | MiniMax M3 (Token Plan default) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n46: | MiniMax M3 (Direct API) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n47: | MiMo V2.5 Pro (Token Plan) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n48: | MiMo V2.5 Pro (Direct API) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n49: | MiMo V2.5 Pro UltraSpeed (Direct API, low-latency) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n50: | GLM-5.2 (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan) | COSTAR + lean (empirical, benchmark 008) | [`glm-5.2.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md) |\n51: | deepseek-v4-pro / kimi-k2.7-code | default RCAF (no model-specific benchmark; shared default-unverified note) | [`deepseek-v4-pro.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/deepseek-v4-pro.md) · [`kimi-k2.7-code.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/kimi-k2.7-code.md) |\n52: \n53: **Executor notes:** Omit `--agent` for all small-model dispatches listed above. OpenCode maps `--variant low/medium/high` to MiMo's reasoning effort; `high` is the standing default for MiMo. MiniMax Token Plan (`minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3`) and Direct API (`minimax/MiniMax-M3`) both serve M3. Xiaomi Token Plan (`xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro`) and Direct API (`xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro`) both serve MiMo-V2.5-Pro; the Direct API additionally serves `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, a low-latency tier with the same prompt contract. Ambiguous use-case (1 vs 2 vs 3) prevents the router from picking a path — resolve before dispatch. Always include a self-invocation guard signal when the dispatched session could loop back.\n54: \n55: ---\n56: \n57: ## 4. DELEGATION / PRECEDENCE\n58: \n59: The 3-tier precedence rule (fast path -> model override -> deep path) is canonical in `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` and restated in `../SKILL.md`.\n60: \n61: OpenCode-specific escalation example: if the task would otherwise need a long `opencode run` prompt plus an explicit Memory Epilogue and a parallel-session decision, ask `@prompt-improver` for the final `ENHANCED_PROMPT` first, then pass that result to OpenCode.\n62: \n63: ---\n64: \n65: ## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n66: \n67: -> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` · `./prompt_templates.md` · `../SKILL.md` · `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/` (per-model profiles)\n\n(End of file - total 67 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\ndescription: Fast-path prompt discipline for OpenCode CLI dispatches; frameworks and CLEAR are canonical in sk-prompt.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode prompt quality card\"\n  - \"opencode model overrides\"\n  - \"minimax tidd-ec dense pre-plan\"\n  - \"mimo costar lean prompt\"\n  - \"opencode dispatch framework precedence\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: planning\nversion: 1.3.0.21\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n\nFast-path dispatch discipline for `opencode run` prompts. The 7-framework table, task-to-framework map, pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are owned by the canonical card — do not inline them here.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md","text":"---\ntitle: OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\ndescription: Fast-path prompt discipline for OpenCode CLI dispatches; frameworks and CLEAR are canonical in sk-prompt.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode prompt quality card\"\n  - \"opencode model overrides\"\n  - \"minimax tidd-ec dense pre-plan\"\n  - \"mimo costar lean prompt\"\n  - \"opencode dispatch framework precedence\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: planning\nversion: 1.3.0.21\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n\nFast-path dispatch discipline for `opencode run` prompts. The 7-framework table, task-to-framework map, pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are owned by the canonical card — do not inline them here.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThis card is the OpenCode CLI fast-path prompt-quality reference; it delegates the framework table + CLEAR check to the canonical card and records only OpenCode-specific model overrides plus the precedence rule.\n\n### Usage\n\nCompose a dispatch prompt by starting from the shared layer (canonical card), applying the OpenCode model overrides, and following the precedence rule.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SHARED LAYER (DELEGATED — DO NOT INLINE)\n\nThe 7-framework selection table, the task->framework map, the pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are OWNED by the canonical card. Do NOT copy them here.\n\n-> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md`  (deep theory: `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-improve/references/patterns_evaluation.md`)\n\n---\n\n## 3. OPENCODE MODEL OVERRIDES\n\nOpenCode dispatches the MiniMax, MiMo, DeepSeek-v4-pro, and Kimi-K2.7 small models, which override or default against the cross-model defaults from the canonical card:\n\n| Model (dispatchable here) | Override | Profile |\n|---|---|---|\n| MiniMax M3 (Token Plan default) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n| MiniMax M3 (Direct API) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n| MiMo V2.5 Pro (Token Plan) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n| MiMo V2.5 Pro (Direct API) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n| MiMo V2.5 Pro UltraSpeed (Direct API, low-latency) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n| GLM-5.2 (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan) | COSTAR + lean (empirical, benchmark 008) | [`glm-5.2.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md) |\n| deepseek-v4-pro / kimi-k2.7-code | default RCAF (no model-specific benchmark; shared default-unverified note) | [`deepseek-v4-pro.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/deepseek-v4-pro.md) · [`kimi-k2.7-code.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/kimi-k2.7-code.md) |\n\n**Executor notes:** Omit `--agent` for all small-model dispatches listed above. OpenCode maps `--variant low/medium/high` to MiMo's reasoning effort; `high` is the standing default for MiMo. MiniMax Token Plan (`minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3`) and Direct API (`minimax/MiniMax-M3`) both serve M3. Xiaomi Token Plan (`xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro`) and Direct API (`xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro`) both serve MiMo-V2.5-Pro; the Direct API additionally serves `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, a low-latency tier with the same prompt contract. Ambiguous use-case (1 vs 2 vs 3) prevents the router from picking a path — resolve before dispatch. Always include a self-invocation guard signal when the dispatched session could loop back.\n\n---\n\n## 4. DELEGATION / PRECEDENCE\n\nThe 3-tier precedence rule (fast path -> model override -> deep path) is canonical in `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` and restated in `../SKILL.md`.\n\nOpenCode-specific escalation example: if the task would otherwise need a long `opencode run` prompt plus an explicit Memory Epilogue and a parallel-session decision, ask `@prompt-improver` for the final `ENHANCED_PROMPT` first, then pass that result to OpenCode.\n\n---\n\n## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n-> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` · `./prompt_templates.md` · `../SKILL.md` · `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/` (per-model profiles)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":67,"totalLines":67,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md","time":{"start":1783806723782,"end":1783806723792}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb0398a08191aab28679a23ae845"}},"id":"prt_f532a86c0001YbSoN4DV9pie43","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806723795,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_IcynapI4f3Y2h2UC5lPWN6PW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md","offset":1,"limit":1000},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\n3: description: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"opencode integration patterns\"\n6:   - \"opencode self-invocation guard\"\n7:   - \"opencode parallel detached session\"\n8:   - \"opencode cross-ai handback\"\n9:   - \"opencode stdin dev null rule\"\n10:   - \"opencode run hang non-interactive\"\n11: importance_tier: important\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 1.3.0.14\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n17: \n18: How cli-opencode positions itself relative to the three sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: The three sibling cli-* skills exist because their target binaries are external runtimes — Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot do not own this repo. OpenCode owns this repo. A naive \"delegate to opencode\" skill makes no sense for an in-OpenCode operator (it would create a circular dispatch).\n25: \n26: cli-opencode resolves this by documenting THREE orthogonal use cases. The smart router selects between them based on the calling AI's runtime context.\n27: \n28: | Use case | Calling runtime | Target | Self-invocation? |\n29: |----------|-----------------|--------|------------------|\n30: | 1. External runtime to OpenCode | Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell | OpenCode for full plugin / skill / MCP runtime | No |\n31: | 2. In-OpenCode parallel detached session | OpenCode itself (TUI / web / serve / acp) | New OpenCode session via `--share --port N` | No (different session id) |\n32: | 3. Cross-AI orchestration handback | OpenCode / Copilot | OpenCode for spec-kit specific workflows | No |\n33: \n34: The cycle ADR-001 protects against is the operator inside OpenCode asking cli-opencode to \"delegate this exact prompt to OpenCode\" — that case is REFUSED at the routing layer.\n35: \n36: ---\n37: \n38: ## 2. USE CASE 1 — EXTERNAL RUNTIME TO OPENCODE\n39: \n40: ### When to use\n41: \n42: The calling AI is Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, or a raw shell. The task needs the project's full plugin / skill / MCP / Spec Kit Memory runtime — not just a raw model dispatch. Examples:\n43: \n44: - Run `memory_search` against the project's spec-doc database\n45: - Call Code Graph for semantic code search across the repo\n46: - Dispatch a `@deep-research` or `@deep-review` agent loop with externalized state\n47: - Run a sub-agent that needs Spec Kit Memory for continuity across iterations\n48: \n49: ### Smart-router signal\n50: \n51: ADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (no OPENCODE_* env var, no opencode parent process, no live state lock).\n52: \n53: ### Prompt template\n54: \n55: ```text\n56: You are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into a fresh OpenCode session via cli-opencode.\n57: \n58: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n59: \n60: Context:\n61: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n62: - Plugins / skills required: <list>\n63: - MCP tools required: <list>\n64: \n65: Constraints:\n66: - <list>\n67: \n68: Success criteria:\n69: - <list>\n70: \n71: Memory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end of the response so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n72: ```\n73: \n74: ### Invocation shape\n75: \n76: ```bash\n77: opencode run \\\n78:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n79:   --agent general \\\n80:   --variant high \\\n81:   --format json \\\n82:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n83:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n84: ```\n85: \n86: ### Why it matters\n87: \n88: This is the canonical cross-AI dispatch path. It gives external runtimes a one-shot bridge into the project's full runtime without forcing the operator to leave their host session.\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 3. USE CASE 2 — IN-OPENCODE PARALLEL DETACHED SESSION\n93: \n94: ### When to use\n95: \n96: The operator is already inside an OpenCode session (TUI, web, serve, acp). They want a SEPARATE OpenCode session — not a continuation, not a fork — to run an ablation suite, a worker farm, or a parallel research sweep. The new session has its own session id, its own state directory, and an optional share URL.\n97: \n98: ### Smart-router signal\n99: \n100: ADR-001's detection signal trips (in-OpenCode runtime). The router checks the prompt for explicit parallel-session keywords:\n101: \n102: - \"parallel detached session\"\n103: - \"ablation suite\"\n104: - \"worker farm\"\n105: - \"parallel research\"\n106: - \"spawn detached\"\n107: - \"share URL\"\n108: \n109: If at least one of these phrases appears AND the prompt does NOT request \"delegate this exact prompt\", the router permits the dispatch with `--share --port <N>`.\n110: \n111: ### Prompt template\n112: \n113: ```text\n114: You are spawning a parallel detached OpenCode session for <purpose>.\n115: \n116: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n117: \n118: Context:\n119: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n120: - Iteration N of <total>\n121: - State file: <path>\n122: \n123: Constraints:\n124: - This session must NOT modify the parent session's state.\n125: - Write results to <state file path>.\n126: - Publish a share URL only if the operator confirmed (CHK-033).\n127: \n128: Success criteria:\n129: - <list>\n130: ```\n131: \n132: ### Invocation shape\n133: \n134: ```bash\n135: opencode run \\\n136:   --share \\\n137:   --port 4096 \\\n138:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n139:   --agent deep-research \\\n140:   --variant high \\\n141:   --format json \\\n142:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n143:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n144: ```\n145: \n146: ### Why it matters\n147: \n148: Parallel research, ablation studies, and worker farms need N concurrent sessions. Each must be independent. The detached pattern makes this possible without leaking state between sessions.\n149: \n150: ### Operator confirmation for share URLs\n151: \n152: Per CHK-033, the calling AI MUST confirm with the operator before passing `--share`. The share URL exposes the session's contents to anyone with the URL, so it is opt-in.\n153: \n154: ---\n155: \n156: ## 4. USE CASE 3 — CROSS-AI ORCHESTRATION HANDBACK\n157: \n158: ### When to use\n159: \n160: The calling AI is a non-Anthropic CLI (OpenCode, Copilot). The task requires OpenCode-specific plugins or skills (e.g. spec-kit workflows, the Spec Kit Memory MCP database, the structural code graph). The non-Anthropic CLI cannot load the project's plugins on its own — cli-opencode is the documented bridge.\n161: \n162: ### Smart-router signal\n163: \n164: ADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (the calling AI is OpenCode / Copilot, not OpenCode). The prompt mentions a project-specific subsystem:\n165: \n166: - \"spec kit\" / \"spec-kit\" / \"spec_kit\"\n167: - \"spec kit memory\"\n168: - \"code graph\"\n169: - \"skill advisor\"\n170: - \"session bootstrap\"\n171: \n172: When the calling AI is non-Anthropic AND a project-specific subsystem is named, this use case is selected over use case 1 (which is the more general path).\n173: \n174: ### Prompt template\n175: \n176: ```text\n177: You are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into OpenCode for a spec-kit-specific workflow.\n178: \n179: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n180: \n181: Context:\n182: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n183: - Subsystem: <spec-kit / memory / code-graph / advisor>\n184: - Operation: <save / search / query / scan / validate>\n185: \n186: Constraints:\n187: - The OpenCode session MUST load the system-spec-kit skill for this dispatch.\n188: - All MCP calls go through the project's local MCP servers.\n189: \n190: Success criteria:\n191: - <list>\n192: \n193: Memory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n194: ```\n195: \n196: ### Invocation shape\n197: \n198: ```bash\n199: opencode run \\\n200:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n201:   --agent general \\\n202:   --variant high \\\n203:   --format json \\\n204:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n205:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n206: ```\n207: \n208: The invocation shape is identical to use case 1 — the difference is the prompt content, which targets a project-specific subsystem.\n209: \n210: ### Why it matters\n211: \n212: OpenCode and Copilot cannot load this project's plugin / skill / MCP runtime on their own. cli-opencode is the documented bridge that lets a OpenCode-led orchestration call into the project's spec-kit workflows without leaving the OpenCode session.\n213: \n214: ---\n215: \n216: ## 5. SMART-ROUTER DECISION TREE\n217: \n218: The skill's smart router picks between the three use cases (or refuses) using this decision tree:\n219: \n220: ```text\n221: INPUT: prompt + calling runtime\n222:                 |\n223:                 v\n224: [ADR-001 SELF-INVOCATION GUARD]\n225: - Layer 1: env var lookup (any OPENCODE_* env var present?)\n226: - Layer 2: process ancestry (opencode in parent process tree?)\n227: - Layer 3: best-effort lock-file probe (~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock present? -- heuristic, not guaranteed on every install)\n228:                 |\n229:         +-------+-------+\n230:         |               |\n231:        NO              YES\n232:         |               |\n233:         v               v\n234: [CALLING RUNTIME]   [PROMPT KEYWORDS]\n235:         |               |\n236:    +----+----+    +-----+-----+\n237:    |         |    |           |\n238: Anthropic  Other  parallel   self-dispatch\n239: (Claude    (OpenCode words    only\n240: Code)      Copilot)        |           |\n241:    |         |             v           v\n242:    v         v        USE CASE 2   REFUSE\n243: USE CASE  [PROJECT     (in-       (cycle —\n244: 1         SUBSYSTEM    OpenCode   surface\n245: (external NAMED?]      parallel)  ADR-001\n246: to                      |          error)\n247: OpenCode)        +------+------+\n248:                  |             |\n249:                 YES            NO\n250:                  |             |\n251:                  v             v\n252:              USE CASE 3     USE CASE 1\n253:              (cross-AI      (external\n254:              handback)      to OpenCode)\n255: ```\n256: \n257: ### Refusal message\n258: \n259: When the router hits the REFUSE leaf, it surfaces this exact message:\n260: \n261: ```text\n262: ERROR: cli-opencode self-invocation refused.\n263: \n264: You are already inside OpenCode (signal: <env|ancestry|lockfile> tripped).\n265: Asking cli-opencode to delegate this exact prompt back to OpenCode would create\n266: a circular dispatch.\n267: \n268: Options:\n269: 1. Use a sibling cli-* skill (cli-claude-code, cli-opencode)\n270:    to dispatch a different model.\n271: 2. Open a fresh shell session (no OpenCode parent) and re-run from there.\n272: 3. If you wanted a parallel detached session (different session id, separate\n273:    state directory), restate the request with explicit \"parallel detached\" /\n274:    \"ablation suite\" / \"worker farm\" / \"share URL\" keywords — that triggers\n275:    use case 2 instead of refusal.\n276: ```\n277: \n278: ---\n279: \n280: ## 6. STDIN HANDLING — `</dev/null` IS REQUIRED FOR ALL NON-INTERACTIVE DISPATCH\n281: \n282: **`opencode run` reads stdin at startup before session creation (opencode v1.14.39).** Without an explicit closed stdin, ANY non-interactive automation that redirects stdout/stderr hangs forever at 0% CPU — even with a clean tool registry, valid model, and `--pure` set. This is the third independent root cause discovered during the 027-xce-research-based-refinement deep-research run on 2026-05-08; see `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 and memory `feedback_opencode_run_requires_dev_null_stdin.md`.\n283: \n284: ### Hang symptom (diagnostic)\n285: \n286: If you see ALL of:\n287: - Process at 0% CPU after >60s\n288: - `~/.local/share/opencode/log/<timestamp>.log` last entry is `service=snapshot prune=7.days cleanup`\n289: - 0 bytes stdout, 0 bytes stderr\n290: - No TCP connections to provider\n291: - 12-min timeout fires, exit code 124\n292: \n293: …it's the stdin-startup-deadlock. Append `</dev/null`.\n294: \n295: ### Failure patterns (all hang)\n296: \n297: ```bash\n298: # WRONG #1 — file redirect without </dev/null\n299: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n300: \n301: # WRONG #2 — combined redirect via tee\n302: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n303: \n304: # WRONG #3 — background opencode in while-read loop without </dev/null\n305: while IFS= read -r line; do\n306:   opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 &\n307: done < input.jsonl\n308: # Both bugs apply: stdin-startup-read AND silent loop-stdin consumption.\n309: ```\n310: \n311: ### Fix patterns (all work)\n312: \n313: ```bash\n314: # RIGHT #1 — file redirect with </dev/null\n315: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n316: \n317: # RIGHT #2 — combined redirect with explicit closed stdin via < /dev/null\n318: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n319: \n320: # RIGHT #3 — background in while-read loop\n321: while IFS= read -r line; do\n322:   opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 </dev/null &\n323: done < input.jsonl\n324: \n325: # RIGHT #4 — foreground pipe to tail (works WITHOUT </dev/null because the empty pipe upstream provides EOF)\n326: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tail -15\n327: ```\n328: \n329: ### Why foreground `| tail` accidentally works\n330: \n331: When you run `opencode run \"...\" 2>&1 | tail`, the shell sets up a pipe BEFORE invoking opencode. opencode's stdin is NOT connected to your terminal — it's connected to the upstream pipe stage, which has no producer (the prompt is the positional argument, not piped via stdin). The shell closes that pipe immediately, opencode reads EOF, and startup proceeds. This is fragile — `2>&1 | tee combined.log` does NOT work because `tee` may keep the pipe open differently depending on shell + tee implementation. **Always use `</dev/null` explicitly** rather than relying on accidental pipe behavior.\n332: \n333: ### Position rule\n334: \n335: `</dev/null` belongs:\n336: - AFTER the prompt positional argument\n337: - BEFORE the `> stdout 2> stderr` redirects (or anywhere on the command line — shell parses redirects independent of position, but right-after-prompt is conventional and easiest to spot during code review)\n338: \n339: ```bash\n340: # canonical order\n341: opencode run --flags \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout 2> stderr\n342: #                              ^^^^^^^^^^\n343: #                              stdin from /dev/null (immediate EOF)\n344: ```\n345: \n346: ### Background dispatch from automation scripts (the deep-research / deep-review pattern)\n347: \n348: ```bash\n349: timeout 720 opencode run \\\n350:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n351:   --variant high \\\n352:   --pure \\\n353:   --dangerously-skip-permissions \\\n354:   \"$(cat prompt.md)\" \\\n355:   </dev/null \\\n356:   > \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stdout.log\" \\\n357:   2> \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stderr.log\"\n358: ```\n359: \n360: This is the pattern enforced by the 4 `if_cli_opencode` blocks in the deep-research and deep-review YAML workflow files. Any new automation that dispatches opencode MUST follow it.\n361: \n362: ### Upstream\n363: \n364: The bug is in opencode v1.14.39. The fix would be: in the `run` subcommand entrypoint, check `process.stdin.isTTY` (or equivalent) and skip the stdin read in non-interactive mode — the message is already provided as a positional argument, so stdin is informational only. Until upstream patches this, `</dev/null` at every callsite is the workaround. File a bug report with opencode-ai/opencode if not already filed.\n365: \n366: ---\n367: \n368: ## 7. MEMORY HANDBACK\n369: \n370: cli-opencode dispatches that produce evidence for a Spec Kit Memory save MUST include the Memory Epilogue at the end of the prompt. The dispatched session adds `MEMORY_HANDBACK_START` / `MEMORY_HANDBACK_END` delimiters around a structured JSON payload that the calling AI extracts and feeds to `generate-context.js`.\n371: \n372: The full Memory Handback Protocol is shared with cli-claude-code and cli-opencode. See SKILL.md Section 4 (RULES) for the canonical 7-step procedure. The same JSON normalization (camelCase / snake_case aliases) and post-010 save gates apply.\n373: \n374: ---\n375: \n376: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n377: \n378: - `./cli_reference.md` - Full subcommand and flag reference\n379: - `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique value props vs sibling cli-* skills\n380: - `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix\n381: - `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste templates per use case\n382: - `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router pseudocode\n\n(End of file - total 382 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\ndescription: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode integration patterns\"\n  - \"opencode self-invocation guard\"\n  - \"opencode parallel detached session\"\n  - \"opencode cross-ai handback\"\n  - \"opencode stdin dev null rule\"\n  - \"opencode run hang non-interactive\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.14\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n\nHow cli-opencode positions itself relative to the three sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\ndescription: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode integration patterns\"\n  - \"opencode self-invocation guard\"\n  - \"opencode parallel detached session\"\n  - \"opencode cross-ai handback\"\n  - \"opencode stdin dev null rule\"\n  - \"opencode run hang non-interactive\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.14\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n\nHow cli-opencode positions itself relative to the three sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThe three sibling cli-* skills exist because their target binaries are external runtimes — Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot do not own this repo. OpenCode owns this repo. A naive \"delegate to opencode\" skill makes no sense for an in-OpenCode operator (it would create a circular dispatch).\n\ncli-opencode resolves this by documenting THREE orthogonal use cases. The smart router selects between them based on the calling AI's runtime context.\n\n| Use case | Calling runtime | Target | Self-invocation? |\n|----------|-----------------|--------|------------------|\n| 1. External runtime to OpenCode | Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell | OpenCode for full plugin / skill / MCP runtime | No |\n| 2. In-OpenCode parallel detached session | OpenCode itself (TUI / web / serve / acp) | New OpenCode session via `--share --port N` | No (different session id) |\n| 3. Cross-AI orchestration handback | OpenCode / Copilot | OpenCode for spec-kit specific workflows | No |\n\nThe cycle ADR-001 protects against is the operator inside OpenCode asking cli-opencode to \"delegate this exact prompt to OpenCode\" — that case is REFUSED at the routing layer.\n\n---\n\n## 2. USE CASE 1 — EXTERNAL RUNTIME TO OPENCODE\n\n### When to use\n\nThe calling AI is Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, or a raw shell. The task needs the project's full plugin / skill / MCP / Spec Kit Memory runtime — not just a raw model dispatch. Examples:\n\n- Run `memory_search` against the project's spec-doc database\n- Call Code Graph for semantic code search across the repo\n- Dispatch a `@deep-research` or `@deep-review` agent loop with externalized state\n- Run a sub-agent that needs Spec Kit Memory for continuity across iterations\n\n### Smart-router signal\n\nADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (no OPENCODE_* env var, no opencode parent process, no live state lock).\n\n### Prompt template\n\n```text\nYou are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into a fresh OpenCode session via cli-opencode.\n\nGoal: <one-sentence goal>\n\nContext:\n- Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n- Plugins / skills required: <list>\n- MCP tools required: <list>\n\nConstraints:\n- <list>\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- <list>\n\nMemory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end of the response so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n```\n\n### Invocation shape\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent general \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n```\n\n### Why it matters\n\nThis is the canonical cross-AI dispatch path. It gives external runtimes a one-shot bridge into the project's full runtime without forcing the operator to leave their host session.\n\n---\n\n## 3. USE CASE 2 — IN-OPENCODE PARALLEL DETACHED SESSION\n\n### When to use\n\nThe operator is already inside an OpenCode session (TUI, web, serve, acp). They want a SEPARATE OpenCode session — not a continuation, not a fork — to run an ablation suite, a worker farm, or a parallel research sweep. The new session has its own session id, its own state directory, and an optional share URL.\n\n### Smart-router signal\n\nADR-001's detection signal trips (in-OpenCode runtime). The router checks the prompt for explicit parallel-session keywords:\n\n- \"parallel detached session\"\n- \"ablation suite\"\n- \"worker farm\"\n- \"parallel research\"\n- \"spawn detached\"\n- \"share URL\"\n\nIf at least one of these phrases appears AND the prompt does NOT request \"delegate this exact prompt\", the router permits the dispatch with `--share --port <N>`.\n\n### Prompt template\n\n```text\nYou are spawning a parallel detached OpenCode session for <purpose>.\n\nGoal: <one-sentence goal>\n\nContext:\n- Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n- Iteration N of <total>\n- State file: <path>\n\nConstraints:\n- This session must NOT modify the parent session's state.\n- Write results to <state file path>.\n- Publish a share URL only if the operator confirmed (CHK-033).\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- <list>\n```\n\n### Invocation shape\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --share \\\n  --port 4096 \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent deep-research \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n```\n\n### Why it matters\n\nParallel research, ablation studies, and worker farms need N concurrent sessions. Each must be independent. The detached pattern makes this possible without leaking state between sessions.\n\n### Operator confirmation for share URLs\n\nPer CHK-033, the calling AI MUST confirm with the operator before passing `--share`. The share URL exposes the session's contents to anyone with the URL, so it is opt-in.\n\n---\n\n## 4. USE CASE 3 — CROSS-AI ORCHESTRATION HANDBACK\n\n### When to use\n\nThe calling AI is a non-Anthropic CLI (OpenCode, Copilot). The task requires OpenCode-specific plugins or skills (e.g. spec-kit workflows, the Spec Kit Memory MCP database, the structural code graph). The non-Anthropic CLI cannot load the project's plugins on its own — cli-opencode is the documented bridge.\n\n### Smart-router signal\n\nADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (the calling AI is OpenCode / Copilot, not OpenCode). The prompt mentions a project-specific subsystem:\n\n- \"spec kit\" / \"spec-kit\" / \"spec_kit\"\n- \"spec kit memory\"\n- \"code graph\"\n- \"skill advisor\"\n- \"session bootstrap\"\n\nWhen the calling AI is non-Anthropic AND a project-specific subsystem is named, this use case is selected over use case 1 (which is the more general path).\n\n### Prompt template\n\n```text\nYou are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into OpenCode for a spec-kit-specific workflow.\n\nGoal: <one-sentence goal>\n\nContext:\n- Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n- Subsystem: <spec-kit / memory / code-graph / advisor>\n- Operation: <save / search / query / scan / validate>\n\nConstraints:\n- The OpenCode session MUST load the system-spec-kit skill for this dispatch.\n- All MCP calls go through the project's local MCP servers.\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- <list>\n\nMemory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n```\n\n### Invocation shape\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent general \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n```\n\nThe invocation shape is identical to use case 1 — the difference is the prompt content, which targets a project-specific subsystem.\n\n### Why it matters\n\nOpenCode and Copilot cannot load this project's plugin / skill / MCP runtime on their own. cli-opencode is the documented bridge that lets a OpenCode-led orchestration call into the project's spec-kit workflows without leaving the OpenCode session.\n\n---\n\n## 5. SMART-ROUTER DECISION TREE\n\nThe skill's smart router picks between the three use cases (or refuses) using this decision tree:\n\n```text\nINPUT: prompt + calling runtime\n                |\n                v\n[ADR-001 SELF-INVOCATION GUARD]\n- Layer 1: env var lookup (any OPENCODE_* env var present?)\n- Layer 2: process ancestry (opencode in parent process tree?)\n- Layer 3: best-effort lock-file probe (~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock present? -- heuristic, not guaranteed on every install)\n                |\n        +-------+-------+\n        |               |\n       NO              YES\n        |               |\n        v               v\n[CALLING RUNTIME]   [PROMPT KEYWORDS]\n        |               |\n   +----+----+    +-----+-----+\n   |         |    |           |\nAnthropic  Other  parallel   self-dispatch\n(Claude    (OpenCode words    only\nCode)      Copilot)        |           |\n   |         |             v           v\n   v         v        USE CASE 2   REFUSE\nUSE CASE  [PROJECT     (in-       (cycle —\n1         SUBSYSTEM    OpenCode   surface\n(external NAMED?]      parallel)  ADR-001\nto                      |          error)\nOpenCode)        +------+------+\n                 |             |\n                YES            NO\n                 |             |\n                 v             v\n             USE CASE 3     USE CASE 1\n             (cross-AI      (external\n             handback)      to OpenCode)\n```\n\n### Refusal message\n\nWhen the router hits the REFUSE leaf, it surfaces this exact message:\n\n```text\nERROR: cli-opencode self-invocation refused.\n\nYou are already inside OpenCode (signal: <env|ancestry|lockfile> tripped).\nAsking cli-opencode to delegate this exact prompt back to OpenCode would create\na circular dispatch.\n\nOptions:\n1. Use a sibling cli-* skill (cli-claude-code, cli-opencode)\n   to dispatch a different model.\n2. Open a fresh shell session (no OpenCode parent) and re-run from there.\n3. If you wanted a parallel detached session (different session id, separate\n   state directory), restate the request with explicit \"parallel detached\" /\n   \"ablation suite\" / \"worker farm\" / \"share URL\" keywords — that triggers\n   use case 2 instead of refusal.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. STDIN HANDLING — `</dev/null` IS REQUIRED FOR ALL NON-INTERACTIVE DISPATCH\n\n**`opencode run` reads stdin at startup before session creation (opencode v1.14.39).** Without an explicit closed stdin, ANY non-interactive automation that redirects stdout/stderr hangs forever at 0% CPU — even with a clean tool registry, valid model, and `--pure` set. This is the third independent root cause discovered during the 027-xce-research-based-refinement deep-research run on 2026-05-08; see `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 and memory `feedback_opencode_run_requires_dev_null_stdin.md`.\n\n### Hang symptom (diagnostic)\n\nIf you see ALL of:\n- Process at 0% CPU after >60s\n- `~/.local/share/opencode/log/<timestamp>.log` last entry is `service=snapshot prune=7.days cleanup`\n- 0 bytes stdout, 0 bytes stderr\n- No TCP connections to provider\n- 12-min timeout fires, exit code 124\n\n…it's the stdin-startup-deadlock. Append `</dev/null`.\n\n### Failure patterns (all hang)\n\n```bash\n# WRONG #1 — file redirect without </dev/null\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n\n# WRONG #2 — combined redirect via tee\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n\n# WRONG #3 — background opencode in while-read loop without </dev/null\nwhile IFS= read -r line; do\n  opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 &\ndone < input.jsonl\n# Both bugs apply: stdin-startup-read AND silent loop-stdin consumption.\n```\n\n### Fix patterns (all work)\n\n```bash\n# RIGHT #1 — file redirect with </dev/null\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n\n# RIGHT #2 — combined redirect with explicit closed stdin via < /dev/null\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n\n# RIGHT #3 — background in while-read loop\nwhile IFS= read -r line; do\n  opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 </dev/null &\ndone < input.jsonl\n\n# RIGHT #4 — foreground pipe to tail (works WITHOUT </dev/null because the empty pipe upstream provides EOF)\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tail -15\n```\n\n### Why foreground `| tail` accidentally works\n\nWhen you run `opencode run \"...\" 2>&1 | tail`, the shell sets up a pipe BEFORE invoking opencode. opencode's stdin is NOT connected to your terminal — it's connected to the upstream pipe stage, which has no producer (the prompt is the positional argument, not piped via stdin). The shell closes that pipe immediately, opencode reads EOF, and startup proceeds. This is fragile — `2>&1 | tee combined.log` does NOT work because `tee` may keep the pipe open differently depending on shell + tee implementation. **Always use `</dev/null` explicitly** rather than relying on accidental pipe behavior.\n\n### Position rule\n\n`</dev/null` belongs:\n- AFTER the prompt positional argument\n- BEFORE the `> stdout 2> stderr` redirects (or anywhere on the command line — shell parses redirects independent of position, but right-after-prompt is conventional and easiest to spot during code review)\n\n```bash\n# canonical order\nopencode run --flags \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout 2> stderr\n#                              ^^^^^^^^^^\n#                              stdin from /dev/null (immediate EOF)\n```\n\n### Background dispatch from automation scripts (the deep-research / deep-review pattern)\n\n```bash\ntimeout 720 opencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --pure \\\n  --dangerously-skip-permissions \\\n  \"$(cat prompt.md)\" \\\n  </dev/null \\\n  > \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stdout.log\" \\\n  2> \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stderr.log\"\n```\n\nThis is the pattern enforced by the 4 `if_cli_opencode` blocks in the deep-research and deep-review YAML workflow files. Any new automation that dispatches opencode MUST follow it.\n\n### Upstream\n\nThe bug is in opencode v1.14.39. The fix would be: in the `run` subcommand entrypoint, check `process.stdin.isTTY` (or equivalent) and skip the stdin read in non-interactive mode — the message is already provided as a positional argument, so stdin is informational only. Until upstream patches this, `</dev/null` at every callsite is the workaround. File a bug report with opencode-ai/opencode if not already filed.\n\n---\n\n## 7. MEMORY HANDBACK\n\ncli-opencode dispatches that produce evidence for a Spec Kit Memory save MUST include the Memory Epilogue at the end of the prompt. The dispatched session adds `MEMORY_HANDBACK_START` / `MEMORY_HANDBACK_END` delimiters around a structured JSON payload that the calling AI extracts and feeds to `generate-context.js`.\n\nThe full Memory Handback Protocol is shared with cli-claude-code and cli-opencode. See SKILL.md Section 4 (RULES) for the canonical 7-step procedure. The same JSON normalization (camelCase / snake_case aliases) and post-010 save gates apply.\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- `./cli_reference.md` - Full subcommand and flag reference\n- `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique value props vs sibling cli-* skills\n- `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix\n- `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste templates per use case\n- `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router pseudocode","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":382,"totalLines":382,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/cli-external/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md","time":{"start":1783806723784,"end":1783806723793}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00ae5cc52b8b4aef016a52bb0398a88191b909cd56d2cd5cc1"}},"id":"prt_f532a86c7001P4noULF2cQPaEr","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532a528f0017cF6gMqRibwBE2"}}
