thm, lowercase encoding, and truncation.\n\n  Line 465: - [ ] No `HashMap`/`HashSet`, filesystem, database, thread, or parallel completion order leaks into output.\n\n  Line 466: - [ ] Serialized field order, omission behavior, nullability, number representation, escaping, encoding, and newline behavior match TypeScript.\n\n  Line 467: - [ ] napi-rs, native platform packages, WASM/WASI, and sidecar outputs match the same oracle where enabled.\n\n  Line 468: - [ ] JS-visible DTOs, generated TypeScript declarations, enum discriminants, and error envelopes match.\n\n  Line 469: - [ ] No JS-controlled path can panic or trap instead of returning the established error shape.\n\n  Line 470: - [ ] The pure core forbids unsafe code.\n\n  Line 471: - [ ] Every boundary unsafe block has an adjacent `// SAFETY:` invariant, safe wrapper, exercising test, and precondition-challenge test.\n\n  Line 472: - [ ] Adapters do not duplicate deterministic core logic.\n\n  Line 473: - [ ] Golden expected files were generated only by the pinned TypeScript oracle.\n\n  Line 474: - [ ] CI cannot automatically accept changed goldens or snapshots.\n\n  Line 475: - [ ] Numbered all-caps sections and durable WHY comments satisfy house style.\n\n  Line 479: - [ ] Exported DTOs are owned and contain no borrowed fields or public lifetimes.\n\n  Line 480: - [ ] Boundary integers are fixed-width and range-checked.\n\n  Line 481: - [ ] `From` is used only for infallible conversions; fallible validation uses `TryFrom`.\n\n  Line 482: - [ ] Core errors are typed with `thiserror`; `anyhow` does not appear in pure-core public APIs.\n\n  Line 483: - [ ] Every core error variant has exhaustive napi-rs and WASM/WASI mapping.\n\n  Line 484: - [ ] JS error `name`, `code`, `message`, `cause`, and throw/rejection behavior are golden-tested.\n\n  Line 485: - [ ] Native and WASM features compile and test independently.\n\n  Line 486: - [ ] `cargo fmt`, locked checks, Clippy, tests, rustdoc, and release builds pass.\n\n  Line 487: - [ ] CI denies `unwrap_used`, `expect_used`, `panic`, `float_cmp`, `as_conversions`, and `indexing_slicing`.\n\n  Line 488: - [ ] Every lint suppression is narrow and justified.\n\n  Line 489: - [ ] The declared MSRV and pinned stable toolchain are tested.\n\n  Line 490: - [ ] Every supported native platform package has a real-load and clean-install test.\n\n  Line 491: - [ ] The oldest claimed Node version and libc floor are exercised.\n\n  Line 492: - [ ] Forced WASI tests use `NAPI_RS_FORCE_WASI=error`.\n\n  Line 493: - [ ] Goldens record oracle provenance and checksums.\n\n  Line 494: - [ ] `proptest-regressions` is committed and minimized failures are promoted to concrete fixtures.\n\n  Line 495: - [ ] Determinism tests permute insertion order and rerun in fresh processes.\n\n  Line 496: - [ ] Public APIs document errors, panics, safety, ownership, and protected parity contracts.\n\n  Line 497: - [ ] `cargo-deny` and `cargo-audit` pass; `cargo-vet` status is recorded.\n\n  Line 498: - [ ] cxx is absent unless a concrete C++ dependency requires it.\n\n  Line 502: - [ ] Advisory pedantic/nursery findings were reviewed.\n\n  Line 503: - [ ] Newtypes protect real score, rank, or identifier semantics.\n\n  Line 504: - [ ] Standard traits are implemented where semantically valid.\n\n  Line 505: - [ ] Boundary allocations and copies were reviewed without making zero-copy an API promise.\n\n  Line 506: - [ ] Criterion benchmark targets compile on pull requests.\n\n  Line 507: - [ ] Kernel, serialization, and boundary costs are reported separately.\n\n  Line 508: - [ ] Tokio, Rayon, unsafe, allocator, and WASM-size changes have measurement evidence.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-code/018-rust-standards-for-code-opencode/001-research/research/iterations/iteration-004.md:\n  Line 36: - Use `Env::throw_type_error` for invalid JS types, `throw_range_error` for valid types outside accepted bounds, and ordinary coded errors for domain failures. Return immediately after `throw_*`; further Node-API calls with a pending exception can replace or obscure it. [SOURCE: https://napi.rs/docs/concepts/error-handling]\n\n  Line 43: - Use exported `async fn`/napi-rs Tokio support for genuinely asynchronous Rust operations. Do not introduce Tokio merely to wrap CPU work, and do not run blocking work on Tokio executor threads.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-code/018-rust-standards-for-code-opencode/001-research/research/iterations/iteration-002.md:\n  Line 139: - **CI-GATE:** `cargo doc --no-deps` with `RUSTDOCFLAGS=\"-D warnings\"` validates the local public boundary documentation without spending time on dependency docs. [SOURCE: https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/commands/cargo-doc.html]\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-code/018-rust-standards-for-code-opencode/001-research/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:\n  Line 177: Use `insta` for stable, human-reviewable serialized diagnostics and complex DTOs. It supports raw string snapshots and structured serializer snapshots, stores changed snapshots as pending files, and provides an explicit review flow. [SOURCE: https://insta.rs/docs/quickstart/]\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-code/018-rust-standards-for-code-opencode/001-research/research/iterations/iteration-007.md:\n  Line 216: - **(quick_reference)** Mirror child `RUST` paths in the parent projection by prepending exactly `code-opencode/`.\n","metadata":{"matches":99,"truncated":false},"title":"\\[ \\]|TODO|TBD|BLOCKED|FAILED|SKIP|not run|pending","time":{"start":1783806787215,"end":1783806787230}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07f317cbd1fea64c016a52bb42ff388191a10dd6fec1e621dd"}},"id":"prt_f532b7e65001itsMlDwPk46x6e","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532b3e1b001k55