n  Line 253: 2. **Load** [`code_quality_checklist.md`](../../../code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview-header-and-comments.md)\n\n  Line 317: - [`../../../assets/webflow/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md`](../../../code-quality/assets/code_quality_checklist/overview-header-and-comments.md) — validation checklist\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/manual_testing_playbook/re-review-and-stale-context/ai-generated-code-suspect-quality.md:\n  Line 33: - Pass/fail: PASS if over-engineering and missing tests are assessed via assets/code_quality_checklist.md and test_quality_checklist.md; FAIL if report relies on AI-generated label alone\n\n  Line 49: | CR-015 | AI-generated suspect quality | Confirm AI-generated code is reviewed for over-abstraction, missing tests, and invented contracts without biasing severity unfairly. | `Review this suspected AI-generated diff for over-abstraction, contract safety, and test adequacy based on behavior, not authorship.` | bash: git diff --staged --stat -> bash: rg -n -e \"TODO\" -e \"placeholder\" -e \"future\" -e \"generic\" -e \"any\" -e \"unknown\" -e \"mock\" path/to/changed/files -> agent: @review generated-code diff | Step 1: changed size visible; Step 2: suspect patterns checked; Step 3: findings tie to behavior not authorship | Diff stat, pattern grep, final report | PASS if over-engineering and missing tests are assessed via assets/code_quality_checklist.md and test_quality_checklist.md; FAIL if report relies on AI-generated label alone | 1. Remove authorship assumptions; 2. Cite behavior risk; 3. Verify tests cover changed behavior |\n\n  Line 71: | `../../assets/code_quality_checklist.md` | Contract, KISS, DRY, and correctness checks |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/manual_testing_playbook/efficiency-and-restraint/reinvent-the-wheel-detection.md:\n  Line 33: - Pass/fail: PASS if a reinvented-wheel instance is flagged with the standard or native replacement per assets/code_quality_checklist.md section 6; FAIL if hand-rolled duplication is waved through.\n\n  Line 49: | CR-020 | Reinvent-the-wheel detection | Confirm the reviewer flags hand-rolled standard-library or native duplication and recommends the built-in primitive. | `Review this diff for code that re-implements standard-library or native platform behavior, and recommend the built-in primitive where the behavior and edge cases match.` | bash: git diff --staged -U5 -> agent: @review for reinvented-wheel maintainability findings -> bash: rg -n \"the duplicated primitive name\" path/to/file | Step 1: diff captured; Step 2: review flags duplication as section 6 maintainability; Step 3: fix names the standard or native API | Diff hunk, the named primitive, final maintainability finding | PASS if a reinvented-wheel instance is flagged with the standard or native replacement per assets/code_quality_checklist.md section 6; FAIL if duplication is waved through | 1. Confirm the primitive truly matches behavior and edge cases; 2. Check section 6 rows loaded; 3. Add the named replacement to the finding |\n\n  Line 70: | `../../assets/code_quality_checklist.md` | Section 6 reinvent-the-wheel maintainability rows and recommended-fix wording |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/shared/dev_workflow/common-commands.md:\n  Line 100: See: [debugging_workflows.md](../../debugging/debugging_workflows/systematic-four-phases.md)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/shared/references/universal/code_quality_standards.md:\n  Line 39: - Surface checklists: `assets/webflow/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md` and `assets/opencode/checklists/`.\n\n  Line 114: | WEBFLOW  | `assets/webflow/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md` | LIVE — JS sections (snake_case, file headers, CDN-safe init); CSS sections (semantic prefixes, BEM, GPU-only animation, `i` flag on data-attribute selectors) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/manual_testing_playbook/efficiency-and-restraint/ceiling-comment-downgrade.md:\n  Line 33: - Pass/fail: PASS if the ceiling comment downgrades only the simplicity finding and never a protected-class finding per assets/code_quality_checklist.md section 7; FAIL if it suppresses a security, auth, persistence, sandbox, public-contract, or correctness finding, or ignores a valid ceiling note.\n\n  Line 49: | CR-022 | Ceiling-comment downgrade | Confirm a concrete ceiling: comment downgrades a matching too-simple KISS or YAGNI P2 while a co-located security or correctness finding stays full severity. | `Review this diff where a deliberate shortcut carries a ceiling: comment; downgrade the matching too-simple KISS or YAGNI finding, but keep any security, auth, persistence, or correctness finding at full severity.` | bash: git diff --staged -U5 -> bash: rg -n \"ceiling:\" path/to/file -> agent: @review for KISS or YAGNI downgrade and protected-class hold | Step 1: ceiling: comment located with shortcut, ceiling, upgrade trigger; Step 2: matching P2 simplicity finding downgraded or suppressed; Step 3: co-located security or correctness finding stays full severity | Diff hunk, the ceiling: line, both findings with final severity | PASS if the ceiling comment downgrades only the simplicity finding and never a protected-class finding per assets/code_quality_checklist.md section 7; FAIL if it suppresses a protected-class finding or ignores a valid ceiling note | 1. Confirm the ceiling: comment is concrete, not a bare label; 2. Check the protected-class exclusion list; 3. Re-grade each finding independently |\n\n  Line 70: | `../../assets/code_quality_checklist.md` | Section 7 ceiling: intentional-simplification downgrade rule and the protected-class exclusion list |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/manual_testing_playbook/re-review-and-stale-context/stale-architecture-fresh-pass.md:\n  Line 71: | `../../assets/code_quality_checklist.md` | Contract, KISS, DRY, and correctness checks |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/changelog/v3.3.0.0.md:\n  Line 178: | `references/webflow/debugging/debugging_workflows.md`, `verification/verification_workflows.md`, `implementation/implementation_workflows.md` | Display-text mismatch fixed (`[shared_patterns.md]` to `[dev_workflow.md]`)                                |\n\n  Line 179: | `assets/webflow/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md`                      | Source Standards lists expanded from two single-stack links to five per-language tree references; section 8 CSS reference correctly routed to `css/style_guide.md` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/manual_testing_playbook/efficiency-and-restraint/unrequested-code-removal.md:\n  Line 33: - Pass/fail: PASS if unrequested code earns a removal recommendation per assets/code_quality_checklist.md section 7 with a Replacement per assets/removal_plan.md section 2; FAIL if it gets only a simplification note or is ignored.\n\n  Line 49: | CR-021 | Unrequested-code removal prompt | Confirm the reviewer recommends removal with a Replacement entry for code tracing to no requirement, P2 default with P1 escalation on added risk. | `Review this diff for code that traces to no stated requirement, and recommend removal with a Replacement entry when nothing in scope asked for it.` | bash: git diff --staged -U5 -> agent: @review with the stated scope for needed-ness -> bash: rg -n \"the unrequested symbol\" path/to/file | Step 1: diff and scope captured; Step 2: removal recommendation with a Replacement entry; Step 3: P2 default, P1 only on added surface or contract or regression risk | Diff hunk, stated scope, removal finding with Replacement | PASS if unrequested code earns a removal recommendation per assets/code_quality_checklist.md section 7 with a Replacement per assets/removal_plan.md section 2; FAIL if it gets only a simplification note | 1. Confirm the code traces to no requirement; 2. Check section 7 needed-ness prompt loaded; 3. Add Replacement and re-grade P2 vs P1 |\n\n  Line 70: | `../../assets/code_quality_checklist.md` | Section 7 needed-ness removal prompt and P2/P1 escalation rule |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/cross-stack-routing/webflow-plus-motion-dev.md:\n  Line 49: - `code-webflow/assets/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/cross-stack-routing/non-webflow-plus-motion-dev.md:\n  Line 45: - `code-webflow/assets/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/references/quick_reference.md:\n  Line 49: | [code_quality_checklist.md](../assets/code_quality_checklist.md) | Non-security correctness, KISS, and DRY checks |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/shared/references/universal-debugging_checklist.md:\n  Line 69: | WEBFLOW | Chrome DevTools (Console + Network + Performance) | `references/webflow/debugging/debugging_workflows.md` |\n\n  Line 91: - `references/webflow/debugging/debugging_workflows.md` — WEBFLOW deep-dive (DevTools workflows, network capture, multi-viewport).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/README.md:\n  Line 204: | [`assets/code_quality_checklist.md`](./assets/code_quality_checklist.md) | Correctness, performance, boundary handling, KISS and DRY |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/references/review_core.md:\n  Line 125: - [code_quality_checklist.md](../assets/code_quality_checklist.md) - Correctness, KISS, DRY, and maintainability checks.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/cross-stack-routing/prefers-reduced-motion.md:\n  Line 46: - `code-review/assets/code_quality_checklist.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/changelog/v1.5.0.0.md:\n  Line 18: Six files were `references/` but are really checklist artifacts a reviewer applies, not doctrine a reviewer reads: `code_quality_checklist.md`, `security_checklist.md`, `solid_checklist.md`, `test_quality_checklist.md`, `fix-completeness-checklist.md`, and `removal_plan.md`. They moved to a new `assets/` folder. The four genuine references stayed in `references/`: `review_core.md` (doctrine), `review_ux_single_pass.md` (single-pass UX behavior), `quick_reference.md` (index), and `pr_state_dedup.md` (the M-1 dedup spec). Every by-path reference was updated in lockstep — the §2 routing tables and `RESOURCE_MAP`, the README table, `graph-metadata.json`, the bidirectional sibling cross-links, nineteen manual-testing per-feature files, and the two cross-skill `sk-code/references/opencode/{python,shell}/quality_standards.md` pointers. The `.claude` and `.codex` runtime mirrors were re-synced. The rule canary keys on `pr_state_dedup.md` (which stayed), so it remains green.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 24: | `.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/code_quality_checklist.md` | Modified | Mentioned in the original changelog. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/performance_patterns/budgets-and-anti-patterns.md:\n  Line 204: - [debugging_workflows.md](../../debugging/debugging_workflows/systematic-four-phases.md) - Performance debugging workflows for identifying bottlenecks\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/changelog/v1.4.0.0.md:\n  Line 18: Reviews used to wave through code that re-implements behavior the language or the platform already hands you. Two new §6 Maintainability checks in `references/code_quality_checklist.md` name the smell directly: hand-rolled standard-library behavior where a clear, readable primitive already exists and its behavior and edge cases match, and custom code or a dependency that duplicates a native platform or runtime capability with no current requirement the native feature cannot satisfy. The recommended fix in both cases is to prefer the standard or native API instead of carrying a bespoke copy.\n\n  Line 50: - `.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/code_quality_checklist.md` — §6 reinvent-the-wheel maintainability rows; §7 needed-ness removal prompt and the `ceiling:` intentional-simplification downgrade rule.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/changelog/v1.2.0.0.md:\n  Line 21: | `.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/code_quality_checklist.md` | Modified | Mentioned in the original changelog. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/shell/quality_standards/validation-security-and-shellcheck.md:\n  Line 225: 2. Use `sk-code/code-review/assets/code_quality_checklist.md`, `security_checklist.md`, and `test_quality_checklist.md` for baseline risk checks.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/debugging/error_recovery.md:\n  Line 114: - [debugging_workflows.md](./debugging_workflows.md) - General debugging\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/implementation_workflows/validation-minification-and-cdn.md:\n  Line 290: - [debugging_workflows.md](../../debugging/debugging_workflows/systematic-four-phases.md) - Debug timing and validation issues with systematic approach\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/references/python/quality_standards.md:\n  Line 438: 2. Use `sk-code/code-review/assets/code_quality_checklist.md`, `security_checklist.md`, and `test_quality_checklist.md` for baseline risk checks.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/verification/verification_workflows/requirements-rules-and-checklist.md:\n  Line 302: - [debugging_workflows.md](../../debugging/debugging_workflows/systematic-four-phases.md) - Verify fixes work after debugging\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/deployment/minification_guide/batch-rules-and-related.md:\n  Line 87: - [debugging_workflows.md](../../debugging/debugging_workflows/systematic-four-phases.md) - Debugging workflows\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-webflow/references/implementation/animation_workflows/motion-dev-advanced.md:\n  Line 218: - [debugging_workflows.md](../../debugging/debugging_workflows/systematic-four-phases.md) - Animation debugging techniques\n","metadata":{"matches":73,"truncated":false},"title":"references/(?:rust/(?:style_guide|quality_standards|quick_reference)\\.md|typescript/(?:style_guide|quality_standards|quick_reference)\\.md|shell/(?:style_guide|quality_standards|quick_reference)\\.md)|code_quality_checklist\\.md|debugging_workflows\\.md","time":{"start":1783806826408,"end":1783806826460}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03560debd78a9e1e016a52bb6a3d488191aae943ed92d73627"}},"id":"prt_f532c177f001uhhuazV9tfrDXM","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532bda63001mH5NGE79SwVby9"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806826582,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_hsH2LLNBzE9XOus6LisQGBxG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/assets/scripts/verify_alignment_drift.py","offset":1,"limit":400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/assets/scripts/verify_alignment_drift.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env python3\n2: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n3: # COMPONENT: ALIGNMENT DRIFT VERIFIER\n4: # ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n5: \n6: \"\"\"Lightweight recurring alignment checks for OpenCode codebases.\n7: \n8: This verifier is intentionally behavior-neutral: it only inspects files and\n9: reports actionable findings. It exits non-zero when violations are found.\n10: \n11: Coverage:\n12: - TypeScript (.ts, .tsx, .mts)\n13: - JavaScript (.js, .mjs, .cjs)\n14: - Python (.py)\n15: - Shell (.sh)\n16: - Rust (.rs)\n17: - JSON (.json)\n18: - JSONC (.jsonc)\n19: \n20: Rust checks stay mechanical and behavior-neutral like the rest of this file:\n21: they detect the two boundary-contract violations that are visible from text\n22: alone -- `unsafe` without a documented `// SAFETY:` invariant, and\n23: panic-prone calls that must not cross the napi-rs/WASM boundary. Deeper\n24: guarantees (borrow/ownership, deterministic sort/hash iteration) need real\n25: compilation and belong to clippy and the quality gate, not this verifier.\n26: \"\"\"\n27: \n28: from __future__ import annotations\n29: \n30: import argparse\n31: import json\n32: import os\n33: import re\n34: import sys\n35: from dataclasses import dataclass\n36: from typing import Dict, Iterable, List, Set\n37: \n38: \n39: SUPPORTED_EXTENSIONS: Dict[str, str] = {\n40:     \".ts\": \"typescript\",\n41:     \".tsx\": \"typescript\",\n42:     \".mts\": \"typescript\",\n43:     \".js\": \"javascript\",\n44:     \".mjs\": \"javascript\",\n45:     \".cjs\": \"javascript\",\n46:     \".py\": \"python\",\n47:     \".sh\": \"shell\",\n48:     \".rs\": \"rust\",\n49:     \".json\": \"json\",\n50:     \".jsonc\": \"jsonc\",\n51: }\n52: \n53: EXCLUDED_DIRS = {\n54:     \".git\",\n55:     \"node_modules\",\n56:     \"dist\",\n57:     \"build\",\n58:     \"coverage\",\n59:     \"__pycache__\",\n60:     \".next\",\n61:     \".venv\",\n62:     \"venv\",\n63: }\n64: \n65: INTEGRITY_RULE_PREFIXES = (\n66:     \"COMMON-\",\n67:     \"JSON-\",\n68:     \"JSONC-\",\n69:     \"SH-SHEBANG\",\n70:     \"SH-STRICT-MODE\",\n71:     \"PY-SHEBANG\",\n72:     \"TS-MODULE-HEADER\",\n73:     \"RUST-UNSAFE\",\n74: )\n75: CONTEXT_ADVISORY_SEGMENTS = {\n76:     \"z_archive\",\n77:     \"scratch\",\n78:     \"memory\",\n79:     \"research\",\n80:     \"context\",\n81:     \"assets\",\n82:     \"examples\",\n83:     \"fixtures\",\n84: }\n85: TS_TEST_SUFFIXES = (\n86:     \".test.ts\",\n87:     \".spec.ts\",\n88:     \".vitest.ts\",\n89:     \".test.tsx\",\n90:     \".spec.tsx\",\n91:     \".vitest.tsx\",\n92: )\n93: TSCONFIG_JSON_RE = re.compile(r\"^tsconfig(\\..+)?\\.json$\")\n94: KNOWN_MALFORMED_JSON_FIXTURE_SUFFIXES = (\n95:     \"/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/001-fix-command-dispatch/\"\n96:     \"z_archive/044-speckit-test-suite/scratch/001-test-agent-08/malformed.json\",\n97: )\n98: \n99: \n100: @dataclass\n101: class Finding:\n102:     path: str\n103:     rule_id: str\n104:     message: str\n105:     fix_hint: str\n106:     line: int = 1\n107:     severity: str = \"WARN\"\n108: \n109: \n110: def parse_args() -> argparse.Namespace:\n111:     parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=\"Verify recurring alignment drift across languages.\")\n112:     parser.add_argument(\n113:         \"--root\",\n114:         action=\"append\",\n115:         default=[],\n116:         help=\"Root directory to scan (repeatable). Defaults to current directory.\",\n117:     )\n118:     parser.add_argument(\n119:         \"--fail-on-warn\",\n120:         action=\"store_true\",\n121:         help=\"Treat warning findings as build-breaking failures.\",\n122:     )\n123:     return parser.parse_args()\n124: \n125: \n126: def iter_code_files(roots: Iterable[str]) -> Iterable[str]:\n127:     seen_paths: Set[str] = set()\n128:     for root in roots:\n129:         abs_root = os.path.realpath(root)\n130:         for current_root, dirs, files in os.walk(abs_root):\n131:             dirs[:] = [entry for entry in dirs if entry not in EXCLUDED_DIRS]\n132:             for filename in files:\n133:                 extension = os.path.splitext(filename)[1].lower()\n134:                 if extension in SUPPORTED_EXTENSIONS:\n135:                     candidate = os.path.realpath(os.path.join(current_root, filename))\n136:                     if candidate in seen_paths:\n137:                         continue\n138:                     seen_paths.add(candidate)\n139:                     yield candidate\n140: \n141: \n142: def find_line(lines: List[str], pattern: str) -> int:\n143:     regex = re.compile(pattern)\n144:     for index, value in enumerate(lines, start=1):\n145:         if regex.search(value):\n146:             return index\n147:     return 0\n148: \n149: \n150: def strip_jsonc_comments(content: str) -> str:\n151:     result: List[str] = []\n152:     in_string = False\n153:     string_delim = \"\"\n154:     escaping = False\n155:     in_line_comment = False\n156:     in_block_comment = False\n157:     i = 0\n158:     length = len(content)\n159: \n160:     while i < length:\n161:         char = content[i]\n162:         next_char = content[i + 1] if i + 1 < length else \"\"\n163: \n164:         if in_line_comment:\n165:             if char == \"\\n\":\n166:                 in_line_comment = False\n167:                 result.append(char)\n168:             i += 1\n169:             continue\n170: \n171:         if in_block_comment:\n172:             if char == \"*\" and next_char == \"/\":\n173:                 in_block_comment = False\n174:                 i += 2\n175:             else:\n176:                 if char == \"\\n\":\n177:                     # Preserve newlines for line-accurate parser errors.\n178:                     result.append(\"\\n\")\n179:                 i += 1\n180:             continue\n181: \n182:         if in_string:\n183:             result.append(char)\n184:             if escaping:\n185:                 escaping = False\n186:             elif char == \"\\\\\":\n187:                 escaping = True\n188:             elif char == string_delim:\n189:                 in_string = False\n190:             i += 1\n191:             continue\n192: \n193:         if char in {'\"', \"'\"}:\n194:             in_string = True\n195:             string_delim = char\n196:             result.append(char)\n197:             i += 1\n198:             continue\n199: \n200:         if char == \"/\" and next_char == \"/\":\n201:             in_line_comment = True\n202:             i += 2\n203:             continue\n204: \n205:         if char == \"/\" and next_char == \"*\":\n206:             in_block_comment = True\n207:             i += 2\n208:             continue\n209: \n210:         result.append(char)\n211:         i += 1\n212: \n213:     return \"\".join(result)\n214: \n215: \n216: def normalize_path(path: str) -> str:\n217:     return path.replace(\"\\\\\", \"/\").lower()\n218: \n219: \n220: def is_path_segment_present(path: str, segment: str) -> bool:\n221:     normalized = f\"/{normalize_path(path).strip('/')}/\"\n222:     return f\"/{segment.lower()}/\" in normalized\n223: \n224: \n225: def is_context_advisory_path(path: str) -> bool:\n226:     if is_test_heavy_path(path):\n227:         return True\n228:     return any(is_path_segment_present(path, segment) for segment in CONTEXT_ADVISORY_SEGMENTS)\n229: \n230: \n231: def is_test_heavy_path(path: str) -> bool:\n232:     normalized = normalize_path(path)\n233:     basename = os.path.basename(normalized)\n234:     if \"/tests/\" in f\"/{normalized.strip('/')}/\":\n235:         return True\n236:     return basename.endswith(TS_TEST_SUFFIXES)\n237: \n238: \n239: def is_ts_pattern_asset(path: str) -> bool:\n240:     normalized = normalize_path(path)\n241:     return \"/assets/\" in normalized and \"/patterns/\" in normalized\n242: \n243: \n244: def is_known_malformed_json_fixture(path: str) -> bool:\n245:     normalized = normalize_path(path)\n246:     return any(normalized.endswith(suffix) for suffix in KNOWN_MALFORMED_JSON_FIXTURE_SUFFIXES)\n247: \n248: \n249: def should_skip_ts_module_header(path: str) -> bool:\n250:     return is_test_heavy_path(path) or is_ts_pattern_asset(path)\n251: \n252: \n253: def classify_severity(path: str, rule_id: str) -> str:\n254:     base_severity = \"ERROR\" if rule_id.startswith(INTEGRITY_RULE_PREFIXES) else \"WARN\"\n255:     if is_context_advisory_path(path):\n256:         return \"WARN\"\n257:     return base_severity\n258: \n259: \n260: def check_javascript(path: str, lines: List[str], extension: str) -> List[Finding]:\n261:     findings: List[Finding] = []\n262:     if extension == \".mjs\":\n263:         return findings\n264: \n265:     strict_line = find_line(lines[:40], r\"^\\s*['\\\"]use strict['\\\"];\\s*$\")\n266:     if strict_line == 0:\n267:         findings.append(\n268:             Finding(\n269:                 path=path,\n270:                 line=1,\n271:                 rule_id=\"JS-USE-STRICT\",\n272:                 message=\"Missing `'use strict';` near file top.\",\n273:                 fix_hint=\"Add `'use strict';` within the first 40 lines for JS runtime scripts.\",\n274:             )\n275:         )\n276:     return findings\n277: \n278: \n279: def check_typescript(path: str, lines: List[str]) -> List[Finding]:\n280:     findings: List[Finding] = []\n281:     if should_skip_ts_module_header(path):\n282:         return findings\n283: \n284:     module_marker = find_line(lines[:40], r\"MODULE:\")\n285:     if module_marker == 0:\n286:         findings.append(\n287:             Finding(\n288:                 path=path,\n289:                 line=1,\n290:                 rule_id=\"TS-MODULE-HEADER\",\n291:                 message=\"Missing TypeScript module header marker (`MODULE:`) near file top.\",\n292:                 fix_hint=\"Add the standard TS header block with `MODULE:` in the first 40 lines.\",\n293:             )\n294:         )\n295:     return findings\n296: \n297: \n298: def check_python(path: str, lines: List[str]) -> List[Finding]:\n299:     findings: List[Finding] = []\n300:     first_line = lines[0].strip() if lines else \"\"\n301:     if first_line != \"#!/usr/bin/env python3\":\n302:         findings.append(\n303:             Finding(\n304:                 path=path,\n305:                 line=1,\n306:                 rule_id=\"PY-SHEBANG\",\n307:                 message=\"Missing canonical Python shebang.\",\n308:                 fix_hint=\"Set first line to `#!/usr/bin/env python3`.\",\n309:             )\n310:         )\n311: \n312:     content = \"\".join(lines[:80])\n313:     if not re.search(r'\"\"\"|\\'\\'\\'', content):\n314:         findings.append(\n315:             Finding(\n316:                 path=path,\n317:                 line=1,\n318:                 rule_id=\"PY-DOCSTRING\",\n319:                 message=\"Missing top-level module docstring near file top.\",\n320:                 fix_hint=\"Add a short module docstring describing purpose and usage.\",\n321:             )\n322:         )\n323:     return findings\n324: \n325: \n326: def check_shell(path: str, lines: List[str]) -> List[Finding]:\n327:     findings: List[Finding] = []\n328:     first_line = lines[0].strip() if lines else \"\"\n329:     # Python script with a .sh extension — shebang validity is checked by check_python.\n330:     if first_line == \"#!/usr/bin/env python3\":\n331:         return findings\n332:     if first_line != \"#!/usr/bin/env bash\":\n333:         findings.append(\n334:             Finding(\n335:                 path=path,\n336:                 line=1,\n337:                 rule_id=\"SH-SHEBANG\",\n338:                 message=\"Missing canonical bash shebang.\",\n339:                 fix_hint=\"Set first line to `#!/usr/bin/env bash`.\",\n340:             )\n341:         )\n342: \n343:     strict_line = find_line(lines[:80], r\"^\\s*set\\s+-euo\\s+pipefail\\s*$\")\n344:     if strict_line == 0:\n345:         findings.append(\n346:             Finding(\n347:                 path=path,\n348:                 line=1,\n349:                 rule_id=\"SH-STRICT-MODE\",\n350:                 message=\"Missing `set -euo pipefail` strict mode declaration.\",\n351:                 fix_hint=\"Add `set -euo pipefail` near the top of the script.\",\n352:             )\n353:         )\n354:     return findings\n355: \n356: \n357: def check_rust(path: str, lines: List[str], content: str) -> List[Finding]:\n358:     findings: List[Finding] = []\n359: \n360:     # The interop-boundary non-negotiable: `unsafe` is only allowed with a\n361:     # documented `// SAFETY:` invariant. Detect the presence of an unsafe block,\n362:     # fn, impl, or trait and require at least one SAFETY comment in the file.\n363:     if re.search(r\"(?:^|\\s)unsafe\\s+(?:\\{|fn\\b|impl\\b|trait\\b)\", content):\n364:         if not re.search(r\"//\\s*SAFETY:\", content):\n365:             findings.append(\n366:                 Finding(\n367:                     path=path,\n368:                     line=find_line(lines, r\"\\bunsafe\\b\") or 1,\n369:                     rule_id=\"RUST-UNSAFE-NO-SAFETY\",\n370:                     message=\"`unsafe` used without a documented `// SAFETY:` invariant.\",\n371:                     fix_hint=\"Add a `// SAFETY:` comment stating the invariant each unsafe block upholds, backed by a test.\",\n372:                 )\n373:             )\n374: \n375:     # Panics must never cross the napi-rs/WASM boundary as raw aborts; flag\n376:     # panic-prone calls so they are translated to Result at the boundary. This\n377:     # is advisory (WARN) and downgraded further on test/fixture paths.\n378:     panic_line = find_line(\n379:         lines,\n380:         r\"\\.unwrap\\(\\)|\\.expect\\(|(?:^|\\s)panic!\\(|(?:^|\\s)unreachable!\\(|(?:^|\\s)todo!\\(|(?:^|\\s)unimplemented!\\(\",\n381:     )\n382:     if panic_line:\n383:         findings.append(\n384:             Finding(\n385:                 path=path,\n386:                 line=panic_line,\n387:                 rule_id=\"RUST-PANIC-BOUNDARY\",\n388:                 message=\"Panic-prone call (`unwrap`/`expect`/`panic!`) in a boundary-visible path.\",\n389:                 fix_hint=\"Return a `Result` and translate errors at the boundary; a panic must never cross into JS/WASM.\",\n390:             )\n391:         )\n392:     return findings\n393: \n394: \n395: def check_json(path: str, content: str) -> List[Finding]:\n396:     findings: List[Finding] = []\n397:     if is_known_malformed_json_fixture(path):\n398:         return findings\n399: \n400:     try:\n\n(Showing lines 1-400 of 558. Use offset=401 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# COMPONENT: ALIGNMENT DRIFT VERIFIER\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n\"\"\"Lightweight recurring alignment checks for OpenCode codebases.\n\nThis verifier is intentionally behavior-neutral: it only inspects files and\nreports actionable findings. It exits non-zero when violations are found.\n\nCoverage:\n- TypeScript (.ts, .tsx, .mts)\n- JavaScript (.js, .mjs, .cjs)\n- Python (.py)\n- Shell (.sh)\n- Rust (.rs)\n- JSON (.json)\n- JSONC (.jsonc)\n\nRust checks stay mechanical and behavior-neutral like the rest of this file:","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/assets/scripts/verify_alignment_drift.py","text":"#!/usr/bin/env python3\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# COMPONENT: ALIGNMENT DRIFT VERIFIER\n# ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n\"\"\"Lightweight recurring alignment checks for OpenCode codebases.\n\nThis verifier is intentionally behavior-neutral: it only inspects files and\nreports actionable findings. It exits non-zero when violations are found.\n\nCoverage:\n- TypeScript (.ts, .tsx, .mts)\n- JavaScript (.js, .mjs, .cjs)\n- Python (.py)\n- Shell (.sh)\n- Rust (.rs)\n- JSON (.json)\n- JSONC (.jsonc)\n\nRust checks stay mechanical and behavior-neutral like the rest of this file:\nthey detect the two boundary-contract violations that are visible from text\nalone -- `unsafe` without a documented `// SAFETY:` invariant, and\npanic-prone calls that must not cross the napi-rs/WASM boundary. Deeper\nguarantees (borrow/ownership, deterministic sort/hash iteration) need real\ncompilation and belong to clippy and the quality gate, not this verifier.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport argparse\nimport json\nimport os\nimport re\nimport sys\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import Dict, Iterable, List, Set\n\n\nSUPPORTED_EXTENSIONS: Dict[str, str] = {\n    \".ts\": \"typescript\",\n    \".tsx\": \"typescript\",\n    \".mts\": \"typescript\",\n    \".js\": \"javascript\",\n    \".mjs\": \"javascript\",\n    \".cjs\": \"javascript\",\n    \".py\": \"python\",\n    \".sh\": \"shell\",\n    \".rs\": \"rust\",\n    \".json\": \"json\",\n    \".jsonc\": \"jsonc\",\n}\n\nEXCLUDED_DIRS = {\n    \".git\",\n    \"node_modules\",\n    \"dist\",\n    \"build\",\n    \"coverage\",\n    \"__pycache__\",\n    \".next\",\n    \".venv\",\n    \"venv\",\n}\n\nINTEGRITY_RULE_PREFIXES = (\n    \"COMMON-\",\n    \"JSON-\",\n    \"JSONC-\",\n    \"SH-SHEBANG\",\n    \"SH-STRICT-MODE\",\n    \"PY-SHEBANG\",\n    \"TS-MODULE-HEADER\",\n    \"RUST-UNSAFE\",\n)\nCONTEXT_ADVISORY_SEGMENTS = {\n    \"z_archive\",\n    \"scratch\",\n    \"memory\",\n    \"research\",\n    \"context\",\n    \"assets\",\n    \"examples\",\n    \"fixtures\",\n}\nTS_TEST_SUFFIXES = (\n    \".test.ts\",\n    \".spec.ts\",\n    \".vitest.ts\",\n    \".test.tsx\",\n    \".spec.tsx\",\n    \".vitest.tsx\",\n)\nTSCONFIG_JSON_RE = re.compile(r\"^tsconfig(\\..+)?\\.json$\")\nKNOWN_MALFORMED_JSON_FIXTURE_SUFFIXES = (\n    \"/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/z_archive/001-fix-command-dispatch/\"\n    \"z_archive/044-speckit-test-suite/scratch/001-test-agent-08/malformed.json\",\n)\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass Finding:\n    path: str\n    rule_id: str\n    message: str\n    fix_hint: str\n    line: int = 1\n    severity: str = \"WARN\"\n\n\ndef parse_args() -> argparse.Namespace:\n    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=\"Verify recurring alignment drift across languages.\")\n    parser.add_argument(\n        \"--root\",\n        action=\"append\",\n        default=[],\n        help=\"Root directory to scan (repeatable). Defaults to current directory.\",\n    )\n    parser.add_argument(\n        \"--fail-on-warn\",\n        action=\"store_true\",\n        help=\"Treat warning findings as build-breaking failures.\",\n    )\n    return parser.parse_args()\n\n\ndef iter_code_files(roots: Iterable[str]) -> Iterable[str]:\n    seen_paths: Set[str] = set()\n    for root in roots:\n        abs_root = os.path.realpath(root)\n        for current_root, dirs, files in os.walk(abs_root):\n            dirs[:] = [entry for entry in dirs if entry not in EXCLUDED_DIRS]\n            for filename in files:\n                extension = os.path.splitext(filename)[1].lower()\n                if extension in SUPPORTED_EXTENSIONS:\n                    candidate = os.path.realpath(os.path.join(current_root, filename))\n                    if candidate in seen_paths:\n                        continue\n                    seen_paths.add(candidate)\n                    yield candidate\n\n\ndef find_line(lines: List[str], pattern: str) -> int:\n    regex = re.compile(pattern)\n    for index, value in enumerate(lines, start=1):\n        if regex.search(value):\n            return index\n    return 0\n\n\ndef strip_jsonc_comments(content: str) -> str:\n    result: List[str] = []\n    in_string = False\n    string_delim = \"\"\n    escaping = False\n    in_line_comment = False\n    in_block_comment = False\n    i = 0\n    length = len(content)\n\n    while i < length:\n        char = content[i]\n        next_char = content[i + 1] if i + 1 < length else \"\"\n\n        if in_line_comment:\n            if char == \"\\n\":\n                in_line_comment = False\n                result.append(char)\n            i += 1\n            continue\n\n        if in_block_comment:\n            if char == \"*\" and next_char == \"/\":\n                in_block_comment = False\n                i += 2\n            else:\n                if char == \"\\n\":\n                    # Preserve newlines for line-accurate parser errors.\n                    result.append(\"\\n\")\n                i += 1\n            continue\n\n        if in_string:\n            result.append(char)\n            if escaping:\n                escaping = False\n            elif char == \"\\\\\":\n                escaping = True\n            elif char == string_delim:\n                in_string = False\n            i += 1\n            continue\n\n        if char in {'\"', \"'\"}:\n            in_string = True\n            string_delim = char\n            result.append(char)\n            i += 1\n            continue\n\n        if char == \"/\" and next_char == \"/\":\n            in_line_comment = True\n            i += 2\n            continue\n\n        if char == \"/\" and next_char == \"*\":\n            in_block_comment = True\n            i += 2\n            continue\n\n        result.append(char)\n        i += 1\n\n    return \"\".join(result)\n\n\ndef normalize_path(path: str) -> str:\n    return path.replace(\"\\\\\", \"/\").lower()\n\n\ndef is_path_segment_present(path: str, segment: str) -> bool:\n    normalized = f\"/{normalize_path(path).strip('/')}/\"\n    return f\"/{segment.lower()}/\" in normalized\n\n\ndef is_context_advisory_path(path: str) -> bool:\n    if is_test_heavy_path(path):\n        return True\n    return any(is_path_segment_present(path, segment) for segment in CONTEXT_ADVISORY_SEGMENTS)\n\n\ndef is_test_heavy_path(path: str) -> bool:\n    normalized = normalize_path(path)\n    basename = os.path.basename(normalized)\n    if \"/tests/\" in f\"/{normalized.strip('/')}/\":\n        return True\n    return basename.endswith(TS_TEST_SUFFIXES)\n\n\ndef is_ts_pattern_asset(path: str) -> bool:\n    normalized = normalize_path(path)\n    return \"/assets/\" in normalized and \"/patterns/\" in normalized\n\n\ndef is_known_malformed_json_fixture(path: str) -> bool:\n    normalized = normalize_path(path)\n    return any(normalized.endswith(suffix) for suffix in KNOWN_MALFORMED_JSON_FIXTURE_SUFFIXES)\n\n\ndef should_skip_ts_module_header(path: str) -> bool:\n    return is_test_heavy_path(path) or is_ts_pattern_asset(path)\n\n\ndef classify_severity(path: str, rule_id: str) -> str:\n    base_severity = \"ERROR\" if rule_id.startswith(INTEGRITY_RULE_PREFIXES) else \"WARN\"\n    if is_context_advisory_path(path):\n        return \"WARN\"\n    return base_severity\n\n\ndef check_javascript(path: str, lines: List[str], extension: str) -> List[Finding]:\n    findings: List[Finding] = []\n    if extension == \".mjs\":\n        return findings\n\n    strict_line = find_line(lines[:40], r\"^\\s*['\\\"]use strict['\\\"];\\s*$\")\n    if strict_line == 0:\n        findings.append(\n            Finding(\n                path=path,\n                line=1,\n                rule_id=\"JS-USE-STRICT\",\n                message=\"Missing `'use strict';` near file top.\",\n                fix_hint=\"Add `'use strict';` within the first 40 lines for JS runtime scripts.\",\n            )\n        )\n    return findings\n\n\ndef check_typescript(path: str, lines: List[str]) -> List[Finding]:\n    findings: List[Finding] = []\n    if should_skip_ts_module_header(path):\n        return findings\n\n    module_marker = find_line(lines[:40], r\"MODULE:\")\n    if module_marker == 0:\n        findings.append(\n            Finding(\n                path=path,\n                line=1,\n                rule_id=\"TS-MODULE-HEADER\",\n                message=\"Missing TypeScript module header marker (`MODULE:`) near file top.\",\n                fix_hint=\"Add the standard TS header block with `MODULE:` in the first 40 lines.\",\n            )\n        )\n    return findings\n\n\ndef check_python(path: str, lines: List[str]) -> List[Finding]:\n    findings: List[Finding] = []\n    first_line = lines[0].strip() if lines else \"\"\n    if first_line != \"#!/usr/bin/env python3\":\n        findings.append(\n            Finding(\n                path=path,\n                line=1,\n                rule_id=\"PY-SHEBANG\",\n                message=\"Missing canonical Python shebang.\",\n                fix_hint=\"Set first line to `#!/usr/bin/env python3`.\",\n            )\n        )\n\n    content = \"\".join(lines[:80])\n    if not re.search(r'\"\"\"|\\'\\'\\'', content):\n        findings.append(\n            Finding(\n                path=path,\n                line=1,\n                rule_id=\"PY-DOCSTRING\",\n                message=\"Missing top-level module docstring near file top.\",\n                fix_hint=\"Add a short module docstring describing purpose and usage.\",\n            )\n        )\n    return findings\n\n\ndef check_shell(path: str, lines: List[str]) -> List[Finding]:\n    findings: List[Finding] = []\n    first_line = lines[0].strip() if lines else \"\"\n    # Python script with a .sh extension — shebang validity is checked by check_python.\n    if first_line == \"#!/usr/bin/env python3\":\n        return findings\n    if first_line != \"#!/usr/bin/env bash\":\n        findings.append(\n            Finding(\n                path=path,\n                line=1,\n                rule_id=\"SH-SHEBANG\",\n                message=\"Missing canonical bash shebang.\",\n                fix_hint=\"Set first line to `#!/usr/bin/env bash`.\",\n            )\n        )\n\n    strict_line = find_line(lines[:80], r\"^\\s*set\\s+-euo\\s+pipefail\\s*$\")\n    if strict_line == 0:\n        findings.append(\n            Finding(\n                path=path,\n                line=1,\n                rule_id=\"SH-STRICT-MODE\",\n                message=\"Missing `set -euo pipefail` strict mode declaration.\",\n                fix_hint=\"Add `set -euo pipefail` near the top of the script.\",\n            )\n        )\n    return findings\n\n\ndef check_rust(path: str, lines: List[str], content: str) -> List[Finding]:\n    findings: List[Finding] = []\n\n    # The interop-boundary non-negotiable: `unsafe` is only allowed with a\n    # documented `// SAFETY:` invariant. Detect the presence of an unsafe block,\n    # fn, impl, or trait and require at least one SAFETY comment in the file.\n    if re.search(r\"(?:^|\\s)unsafe\\s+(?:\\{|fn\\b|impl\\b|trait\\b)\", content):\n        if not re.search(r\"//\\s*SAFETY:\", content):\n            findings.append(\n                Finding(\n                    path=path,\n                    line=find_line(lines, r\"\\bunsafe\\b\") or 1,\n                    rule_id=\"RUST-UNSAFE-NO-SAFETY\",\n                    message=\"`unsafe` used without a documented `// SAFETY:` invariant.\",\n                    fix_hint=\"Add a `// SAFETY:` comment stating the invariant each unsafe block upholds, backed by a test.\",\n                )\n            )\n\n    # Panics must never cross the napi-rs/WASM boundary as raw aborts; flag\n    # panic-prone calls so they are translated to Result at the boundary. This\n    # is advisory (WARN) and downgraded further on test/fixture paths.\n    panic_line = find_line(\n        lines,\n        r\"\\.unwrap\\(\\)|\\.expect\\(|(?:^|\\s)panic!\\(|(?:^|\\s)unreachable!\\(|(?:^|\\s)todo!\\(|(?:^|\\s)unimplemented!\\(\",\n    )\n    if panic_line:\n        findings.append(\n            Finding(\n                path=path,\n                line=panic_line,\n                rule_id=\"RUST-PANIC-BOUNDARY\",\n                message=\"Panic-prone call (`unwrap`/`expect`/`panic!`) in a boundary-visible path.\",\n                fix_hint=\"Return a `Result` and translate errors at the boundary; a panic must never cross into JS/WASM.\",\n            )\n        )\n    return findings\n\n\ndef check_json(path: str, content: str) -> List[Finding]:\n    findings: List[Finding] = []\n    if is_known_malformed_json_fixture(path):\n        return findings\n\n    try:","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":400,"totalLines":558,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/assets/scripts/verify_alignment_drift.py","time":{"start":1783806826544,"end":1783806826580}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03560debd78a9e1e016a52bb6a3d548191b8b82d970a3a03b4"}},"id":"prt_f532c17a9001J3ioN74Fl9fj05","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532bda63001mH5NGE79SwVby9"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1783806826604,"sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dhZlFP7ToZXH4Ar95lUivz9m","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs","offset":1,"limit":500},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env node\n2: // ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n3: // ║ router-replay — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay        ║\n4: // ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n5: 'use strict';\n6: \n7: /**\n8:  * router-replay.cjs — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay.\n9:  *\n10:  * The converged design needs the intra-skill router replayed deterministically\n11:  * (zero leakage, CI-friendly) as the D1-intra signal and the D2 discovery proxy.\n12:  * The router lives as INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP inside a fenced block in the\n13:  * target SKILL.md; it is documentation, not an importable module, so this script\n14:  * extracts the dictionaries and reproduces the exact substring-scoring semantics:\n15:  * lowercase the task, score each intent by whether each keyword is a substring,\n16:  * keep intents within an ambiguity delta of the top score, then union the default\n17:  * resource + RESOURCE_MAP[intent] for the selected intents.\n18:  *\n19:  * Exit: 0 on a successful replay (even with zero intents), 2 on unparseable router.\n20:  */\n21: \n22: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n23: // 1. IMPORTS\n24: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n25: \n26: const fs = require('fs');\n27: const path = require('path');\n28: \n29: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n30: // 2. CONSTANTS\n31: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n32: \n33: const AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1; // mirror the in-skill router: keep near-tied intents\n34: \n35: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n36: // 3. HELPERS\n37: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n38: \n39: function readSkillMd(skillRoot) {\n40:   const p = path.join(skillRoot, 'SKILL.md');\n41:   if (!fs.existsSync(p)) throw new Error(`SKILL.md not found under ${skillRoot}`);\n42:   return fs.readFileSync(p, 'utf8');\n43: }\n44: \n45: // Pull the {...}-balanced body that follows `NAME = {` from the SKILL.md text.\n46: function extractDictBody(text, name) {\n47:   const start = text.indexOf(`${name} = {`);\n48:   if (start === -1) return null;\n49:   let i = text.indexOf('{', start);\n50:   let depth = 0;\n51:   for (let j = i; j < text.length; j += 1) {\n52:     const ch = text[j];\n53:     if (ch === '{') depth += 1;\n54:     else if (ch === '}') {\n55:       depth -= 1;\n56:       if (depth === 0) return text.slice(i + 1, j);\n57:     }\n58:   }\n59:   return null;\n60: }\n61: \n62: function quotedStrings(segment) {\n63:   const out = [];\n64:   const re = /\"([^\"]*)\"|'([^']*)'/g;\n65:   let m;\n66:   while ((m = re.exec(segment)) !== null) out.push(m[1] !== undefined ? m[1] : m[2]);\n67:   return out;\n68: }\n69: \n70: // INTENT_SIGNALS = { \"KEY\": {\"weight\": N, \"keywords\": [\"a\",\"b\"]}, ... }\n71: function parseIntentSignals(body) {\n72:   const signals = {};\n73:   if (!body) return signals;\n74:   const entryRe = /[\"']([A-Z0-9_]+)[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\{([^}]*)\\}/g;\n75:   let m;\n76:   while ((m = entryRe.exec(body)) !== null) {\n77:     const key = m[1];\n78:     const inner = m[2];\n79:     const weightMatch = /[\"']weight[\"']\\s*:\\s*(\\d+(?:\\.\\d+)?)/.exec(inner);\n80:     const kwMatch = /[\"']keywords[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\[([^\\]]*)\\]/.exec(inner);\n81:     signals[key] = {\n82:       weight: weightMatch ? Number(weightMatch[1]) : 1,\n83:       keywords: kwMatch ? quotedStrings(kwMatch[1]).map((k) => k.toLowerCase()) : [],\n84:     };\n85:   }\n86:   return signals;\n87: }\n88: \n89: // RESOURCE_MAP = { \"KEY\": [\"path/a.md\", \"path/b.md\"], ... }\n90: function parseResourceMap(body) {\n91:   const map = {};\n92:   if (!body) return map;\n93:   const entryRe = /[\"']([A-Z0-9_]+)[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\[([^\\]]*)\\]/g;\n94:   let m;\n95:   while ((m = entryRe.exec(body)) !== null) map[m[1]] = quotedStrings(m[2]);\n96:   return map;\n97: }\n98: \n99: // DEFAULT_RESOURCE may be a single quoted path or a list of them. A skill's\n100: // always-loaded routing preamble (e.g. stack/phase detection plus the router\n101: // doc) is genuinely consulted on every route, so the replay seeds every result\n102: // with the whole set. Always returns an array; [] when absent.\n103: function parseDefaultResource(text) {\n104:   const listM = /DEFAULT_RESOURCES?\\s*=\\s*\\[([\\s\\S]*?)\\]/.exec(text);\n105:   if (listM) {\n106:     return [...listM[1].matchAll(/[\"']([^\"']+)[\"']/g)].map((m) => m[1]);\n107:   }\n108:   const strM = /DEFAULT_RESOURCES?\\s*=\\s*[\"']([^\"']+)[\"']/.exec(text);\n109:   return strM ? [strM[1]] : [];\n110: }\n111: \n112: function projectHubRouter(filePath) {\n113:   const data = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8'));\n114:   const signals = data.routerSignals && typeof data.routerSignals === 'object' ? data.routerSignals : {};\n115:   const vocabulary = data.vocabularyClasses && typeof data.vocabularyClasses === 'object'\n116:     ? data.vocabularyClasses\n117:     : {};\n118:   const intentSignals = {};\n119:   const resourceMap = {};\n120: \n121:   for (const [mode, signal] of Object.entries(signals)) {\n122:     const keywords = new Set();\n123:     for (const className of signal.classes || []) {\n124:       const klass = vocabulary[className];\n125:       for (const keyword of klass && Array.isArray(klass.keywords) ? klass.keywords : []) {\n126:         keywords.add(String(keyword).toLowerCase());\n127:       }\n128:     }\n129:     for (const keyword of Array.isArray(signal.keywords) ? signal.keywords : []) {\n130:       keywords.add(String(keyword).toLowerCase());\n131:     }\n132: \n133:     intentSignals[mode] = {\n134:       weight: Number.isFinite(Number(signal.weight)) ? Number(signal.weight) : 1,\n135:       keywords: [...keywords],\n136:     };\n137:     resourceMap[mode] = Array.isArray(signal.resources) ? signal.resources : [];\n138:   }\n139: \n140:   const policy = data.routerPolicy && typeof data.routerPolicy === 'object' ? data.routerPolicy : {};\n141:   return {\n142:     intentSignals,\n143:     resourceMap,\n144:     defaultResource: Array.isArray(policy.defaultResource) ? policy.defaultResource : [],\n145:   };\n146: }\n147: \n148: function readJsonObject(filePath) {\n149:   try {\n150:     if (!fs.existsSync(filePath)) return null;\n151:     const data = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8'));\n152:     return data && typeof data === 'object' ? data : null;\n153:   } catch {\n154:     return null;\n155:   }\n156: }\n157: \n158: function buildRegistryIndex(skillRoot) {\n159:   const registry = readJsonObject(path.join(skillRoot, 'mode-registry.json'));\n160:   const modes = registry && Array.isArray(registry.modes) ? registry.modes : [];\n161:   const byMode = {};\n162:   for (const mode of modes) {\n163:     if (!mode || typeof mode !== 'object' || !mode.workflowMode) continue;\n164:     byMode[String(mode.workflowMode)] = mode;\n165:   }\n166:   return byMode;\n167: }\n168: \n169: function buildHubRouteTelemetry({ skillRoot, intents, router, taskLower }) {\n170:   if (!router || router.routerSource !== 'hub-router.json') {\n171:     return { observed: false, reason: 'no-hub-router' };\n172:   }\n173: \n174:   const hub = readJsonObject(path.join(skillRoot, 'hub-router.json')) || {};\n175:   const policy = hub.routerPolicy && typeof hub.routerPolicy === 'object' ? hub.routerPolicy : {};\n176:   const selectedModes = Array.isArray(intents) ? intents : [];\n177:   const matchedAliases = [];\n178: \n179:   for (const mode of selectedModes) {\n180:     const signal = router.intentSignals && router.intentSignals[mode] ? router.intentSignals[mode] : {};\n181:     for (const keyword of Array.isArray(signal.keywords) ? signal.keywords : []) {\n182:       if (keywordHits(taskLower, keyword)) matchedAliases.push(keyword);\n183:     }\n184:   }\n185: \n186:   const registry = buildRegistryIndex(skillRoot);\n187:   const backendKind = [];\n188:   const packet = [];\n189:   for (const mode of selectedModes) {\n190:     const entry = registry[mode];\n191:     if (!entry) continue;\n192:     if (entry.backendKind) backendKind.push(entry.backendKind);\n193:     if (entry.packet) packet.push(entry.packet);\n194:   }\n195: \n196:   const defaultApplied = selectedModes.length === 0 && policy.defaultMode != null;\n197:   const deferReason = selectedModes.length === 0\n198:     ? 'no-mode-scored'\n199:     : (selectedModes.length > 1 ? 'ambiguous-multi-axis' : null);\n200: \n201:   return {\n202:     observed: true,\n203:     source: 'hub-router',\n204:     workflowMode: selectedModes.length ? selectedModes : null,\n205:     matchedAliases: [...new Set(matchedAliases)],\n206:     defaultApplied,\n207:     deferReason,\n208:     backendKind,\n209:     packet,\n210:   };\n211: }\n212: \n213: // Some skills keep the authoritative router in a referenced doc (e.g.\n214: // references/smart_routing.md) rather than inlining it in SKILL.md. When the\n215: // inline dictionaries are absent we follow that pointer and parse the same\n216: // INTENT_SIGNALS / RESOURCE_MAP block from the referenced file. Inline always\n217: // wins; a skill with no inline block and no parseable referenced doc stays\n218: // unparseable, so a genuinely router-less skill is still reported as such.\n219: const ROUTER_REF_HINT = /(resource_map|intent_signals|intent_model|smart[ _-]?rout|routing logic)/i;\n220: \n221: function findReferencedRouterDoc(skillMdText, skillRoot) {\n222:   const pathRe = /(?:\\.\\/)?(references\\/[A-Za-z0-9_./-]+\\.md)/;\n223:   for (const line of skillMdText.split('\\n')) {\n224:     if (!ROUTER_REF_HINT.test(line)) continue;\n225:     const m = pathRe.exec(line);\n226:     if (m) {\n227:       const candidate = path.join(skillRoot, m[1]);\n228:       if (fs.existsSync(candidate)) return candidate;\n229:     }\n230:   }\n231:   // Convention fallback: a router doc at the well-known location.\n232:   const conventional = path.join(skillRoot, 'references', 'smart_routing.md');\n233:   return fs.existsSync(conventional) ? conventional : null;\n234: }\n235: \n236: /**\n237:  * Extract the in-skill router (INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP + DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n238:  * from SKILL.md, falling back to a referenced router doc when the inline block\n239:  * is absent.\n240:  *\n241:  * @param {string} skillMdText - The SKILL.md text.\n242:  * @param {string} skillRoot - Skill root dir (for resolving referenced docs).\n243:  * @returns {{intentSignals:Object,resourceMap:Object,defaultResource:string[],parseable:boolean,routerSource:string}} Parsed router.\n244:  */\n245: function parseRouter(skillMdText, skillRoot) {\n246:   let intentSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(skillMdText, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n247:   let resourceMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(skillMdText, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n248:   let defaultResource = parseDefaultResource(skillMdText);\n249:   let routerSource = 'inline';\n250: \n251:   const inlineEmpty = Object.keys(intentSignals).length === 0 && Object.keys(resourceMap).length === 0;\n252:   if (inlineEmpty && skillRoot) {\n253:     const refDoc = findReferencedRouterDoc(skillMdText, skillRoot);\n254:     if (refDoc) {\n255:       const refText = fs.readFileSync(refDoc, 'utf8');\n256:       const refSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(refText, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n257:       const refMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(refText, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n258:       if (Object.keys(refSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(refMap).length > 0) {\n259:         intentSignals = refSignals;\n260:         resourceMap = refMap;\n261:         defaultResource = defaultResource.length ? defaultResource : parseDefaultResource(refText);\n262:         routerSource = path.relative(skillRoot, refDoc);\n263:       }\n264:     }\n265: \n266:     const routerStillEmpty = Object.keys(intentSignals).length === 0 && Object.keys(resourceMap).length === 0;\n267:     const hubRouter = path.join(skillRoot, 'hub-router.json');\n268:     if (routerStillEmpty && fs.existsSync(hubRouter)) {\n269:       const projected = projectHubRouter(hubRouter);\n270:       if (Object.keys(projected.intentSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(projected.resourceMap).length > 0) {\n271:         intentSignals = projected.intentSignals;\n272:         resourceMap = projected.resourceMap;\n273:         defaultResource = defaultResource.length ? defaultResource : projected.defaultResource;\n274:         routerSource = 'hub-router.json';\n275:       }\n276:     }\n277:   }\n278: \n279:   const parseable = Object.keys(intentSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(resourceMap).length > 0;\n280:   return { intentSignals, resourceMap, defaultResource, parseable, routerSource };\n281: }\n282: \n283: /**\n284:  * Score each intent by summing its weight for every keyword that is a substring\n285:  * of the lowercased task, keeping only positive-scoring intents (sorted desc).\n286:  *\n287:  * @param {string} taskLower - Lowercased task text.\n288:  * @param {Object} intentSignals - Map of intent -> {weight, keywords}.\n289:  * @returns {Array<{intent:string,score:number}>} Scored intents, highest first.\n290:  */\n291: const WORD_BOUNDARY_KEYWORDS = new Set(['review', 'lcp', 'inp', 'cls']);\n292: \n293: // A bare keyword like \"review\" gets swallowed by unrelated longer words\n294: // (\"preview\" contains \"review\"), so match those on word boundaries. The short\n295: // performance acronyms need the same guard for the opposite reason: bare \"inp\"\n296: // would substring-match \"input\", firing the performance intent on unrelated\n297: // prompts. Path- and identifier-style keywords keep substring matching so\n298: // \"javascript\" still matches inside \"2_javascript\".\n299: function keywordHits(taskLower, kw) {\n300:   if (!kw) return false;\n301:   if (WORD_BOUNDARY_KEYWORDS.has(kw)) {\n302:     return new RegExp(`\\\\b${kw.replace(/[.*+?^${}()|[\\]\\\\]/g, '\\\\$&')}\\\\b`, 'i').test(taskLower);\n303:   }\n304:   return taskLower.includes(kw);\n305: }\n306: \n307: function scoreIntents(taskLower, intentSignals) {\n308:   const scores = [];\n309:   for (const [key, sig] of Object.entries(intentSignals)) {\n310:     let score = 0;\n311:     for (const kw of sig.keywords) {\n312:       if (keywordHits(taskLower, kw)) score += sig.weight;\n313:     }\n314:     if (score > 0) scores.push({ intent: key, score });\n315:   }\n316:   scores.sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score);\n317:   return scores;\n318: }\n319: \n320: /**\n321:  * Select intents within AMBIGUITY_DELTA of the top score (keeps near-tied\n322:  * intents, mirroring the in-skill router).\n323:  *\n324:  * @param {Array<{intent:string,score:number}>} scores - Scored intents, highest first.\n325:  * @returns {string[]} Selected intent keys.\n326:  */\n327: function selectIntents(scores) {\n328:   if (scores.length === 0) return [];\n329:   const top = scores[0].score;\n330:   return scores.filter((s) => top - s.score <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA).map((s) => s.intent);\n331: }\n332: \n333: // Which surface a resource belongs to, by its on-disk path prefix. Webflow and\n334: // OpenCode resources live under their code-<surface>/ packet folders, so the\n335: // prefix IS the surface. Motion.dev is a cross-stack overlay folded into\n336: // code-webflow/{references,assets}/animation/; it is matched FIRST so it stays a\n337: // distinct overlay surface (kept regardless of the detected code surface) rather\n338: // than collapsing into WEBFLOW's broader code-webflow/ prefix. Everything else\n339: // (universal refs, the detection/router preamble) is surface-agnostic.\n340: const SURFACE_PREFIXES = {\n341:   MOTION: ['code-webflow/references/animation/', 'code-webflow/assets/animation/'],\n342:   WEBFLOW: ['code-webflow/'],\n343:   OPENCODE: ['code-opencode/'],\n344: };\n345: function resourceSurface(r) {\n346:   for (const [surface, prefixes] of Object.entries(SURFACE_PREFIXES)) {\n347:     if (prefixes.some((p) => r.startsWith(p))) return surface;\n348:   }\n349:   return 'UNIVERSAL';\n350: }\n351: // Detect the task's code surface from path / extension / marker signals, mirroring\n352: // the prose stack-detection contract: OpenCode system code wins, then Webflow\n353: // markers, else UNKNOWN. A task that names both is MIXED (cross-surface).\n354: function detectSurface(taskLower) {\n355:   const opencode = /\\.opencode\\/|\\bskill\\.md\\b|\\.cjs\\b|\\.mjs\\b|\\.tsx?\\b|\\.py\\b|\\.sh\\b|\\.rs\\b|\\bspec-folder\\b|\\bargparse\\b|graph-metadata/.test(taskLower);\n356:   const webflow = /src\\/2_javascript|\\bwebflow\\b|\\.webflow\\b|--vw-/.test(taskLower);\n357:   if (opencode && webflow) return 'MIXED';\n358:   if (opencode) return 'OPENCODE';\n359:   if (webflow) return 'WEBFLOW';\n360:   return 'UNKNOWN';\n361: }\n362: // OpenCode-only language sub-detection (mirrors SKILL.md §2). A `.opencode/` task\n363: // is one language, so it needs only that language's guides — not every language\n364: // folder. Webflow deliberately has no sub-detection (a frontend task spans\n365: // css + html + js together).\n366: const OPENCODE_LANGUAGES = ['typescript', 'python', 'shell', 'config', 'javascript', 'rust'];\n367: // Returns the SET of languages a task touches. An interop parity task legitimately\n368: // touches more than one (e.g. a napi-rs/WASM sidecar over a TypeScript backend must\n369: // load both the Rust and TypeScript standards), so selection is a set, not a single\n370: // first match. An empty set preserves the \"no language slice\" behaviour that a null\n371: // return used to signal. Rust is recognised by `.rs`, Cargo markers, or the\n372: // napi-rs/wasm-bindgen/WASI/cdylib interop vocabulary; those markers are consulted\n373: // here only after detectSurface has already resolved the OpenCode surface.\n374: function detectOpencodeLanguages(taskLower) {\n375:   const langs = new Set();\n376:   if (/\\.tsx?\\b/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('typescript');\n377:   if (/\\.py\\b|argparse/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('python');\n378:   if (/\\.sh\\b|set -euo|shellcheck/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('shell');\n379:   if (/\\.jsonc?\\b|graph-metadata|descriptor|spec-folder/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('config');\n380:   if (/\\.cjs\\b|\\.mjs\\b/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('javascript');\n381:   if (/\\.rs\\b|cargo\\.toml|cargo\\.lock|napi[-_]rs|wasm[-_]bindgen|\\bwasi\\b|\\bcdylib\\b/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('rust');\n382:   return langs;\n383: }\n384: \n385: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n386: // 4. CORE LOGIC\n387: // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n388: \n389: // A parent hub selects the MODE in hub-router.json but keeps the flat\n390: // surface/phase router (INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP over the deep per-surface\n391: // reference paths) as a retained shared doc. Resource recall must be replayed\n392: // against THAT router: the hub router only emits packet pointers (a mode's\n393: // SKILL.md), not the per-surface resource gold the scenarios assert. Probe the\n394: // conventional locations; a skill with no such doc (every flat skill, and sibling\n395: // hubs without one) yields null and is left on the normal path unchanged.\n396: function loadSurfaceRouter(skillRoot) {\n397:   const candidates = [\n398:     path.join(skillRoot, 'shared', 'references', 'smart_routing.md'),\n399:     path.join(skillRoot, 'references', 'smart_routing.md'),\n400:   ];\n401:   for (const doc of candidates) {\n402:     if (!fs.existsSync(doc)) continue;\n403:     const text = fs.readFileSync(doc, 'utf8');\n404:     const intentSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(text, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n405:     const resourceMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(text, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n406:     const defaultResource = parseDefaultResource(text);\n407:     if (Object.keys(intentSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(resourceMap).length > 0) {\n408:       return { intentSignals, resourceMap, defaultResource, sourceRel: path.relative(skillRoot, doc) };\n409:     }\n410:   }\n411:   return null;\n412: }\n413: \n414: // The roots a hub's surface resources resolve under, for the missing-resource\n415: // report: the surface router's paths are relative to the shared preamble tier\n416: // (stack/phase detection, universal baseline) or a mode packet (post-relocation),\n417: // not the hub root. Returns [] for a non-hub skill (no registry).\n418: function registryPacketRoots(skillRoot) {\n419:   const byMode = buildRegistryIndex(skillRoot);\n420:   const roots = Object.keys(byMode).length ? [path.join(skillRoot, 'shared')] : [];\n421:   for (const mode of Object.values(byMode)) {\n422:     if (mode && mode.packet) roots.push(path.join(skillRoot, String(mode.packet)));\n423:   }\n424:   return roots;\n425: }\n426: \n427: // Union the default preamble with each selected intent's resources, then apply\n428: // surface-aware slicing when the map uses a per-surface layout (sk-code): keep the\n429: // universal tier + Motion.dev overlay + only the DETECTED surface's slice, drop\n430: // the other surface's resources (the documented over-routing source). Assets are\n431: // deferred — never the routing gold. A MIXED task keeps both surfaces; UNKNOWN\n432: // falls back to the universal + Motion tier only. Existence is checked against the\n433: // skill root plus any extra roots (a hub's packet roots), since a hub's surface\n434: // paths resolve under a packet rather than the hub root.\n435: function assembleResources({ skillRoot, taskLower, intents, router, extraRoots = [] }) {\n436:   const resourceSet = new Set();\n437:   for (const r of router.defaultResource || []) resourceSet.add(r);\n438:   for (const intent of intents) {\n439:     for (const r of router.resourceMap[intent] || []) resourceSet.add(r);\n440:   }\n441:   let resources = [...resourceSet];\n442: \n443:   const mapResources = Object.values(router.resourceMap).flat();\n444:   const hasSurfaceLayout = mapResources.some((r) => r.startsWith('code-webflow/references/'))\n445:     && mapResources.some((r) => r.startsWith('code-opencode/references/'));\n446:   let surface;\n447:   if (hasSurfaceLayout) {\n448:     surface = detectSurface(taskLower);\n449:     // Within OpenCode, slice further to the touched-language set so a TypeScript task\n450:     // does not also pull the Python/shell/config guides, while an interop task that\n451:     // touches both Rust and TypeScript keeps both trios. Non-language OpenCode\n452:     // folders (e.g. `shared/`) are always kept.\n453:     const ocLangs = surface === 'OPENCODE' ? detectOpencodeLanguages(taskLower) : new Set();\n454:     resources = resources.filter((r) => {\n455:       if (r.includes('/assets/')) return false;\n456:       const rs = resourceSurface(r);\n457:       if (rs === 'UNIVERSAL' || rs === 'MOTION') return true;\n458:       if (surface === 'MIXED') return true;\n459:       if (surface === 'UNKNOWN') return false;\n460:       if (rs !== surface) return false;\n461:       if (ocLangs.size) {\n462:         const m = /^code-opencode\\/references\\/([^/]+)\\//.exec(r);\n463:         if (m && OPENCODE_LANGUAGES.includes(m[1]) && !ocLangs.has(m[1])) return false;\n464:       }\n465:       return true;\n466:     });\n467:   }\n468: \n469:   const roots = [skillRoot, ...extraRoots];\n470:   const missingResources = resources.filter((r) => !roots.some((root) => fs.existsSync(path.join(root, r))));\n471:   return { resources, missingResources, surface };\n472: }\n473: \n474: /**\n475:  * Replay the in-skill router for a task and return the routed resources.\n476:  *\n477:  * @param {Object} args - Routing inputs.\n478:  * @param {string} args.skillRoot - Skill root dir containing SKILL.md.\n479:  * @param {string} args.taskText - Task text to route.\n480:  * @returns {{ parseable: boolean, intents: string[], resources: string[],\n481:  *   missingResources: string[], scores: Array<{intent:string,score:number}>, surface?: string }}\n482:  */\n483: function routeSkillResources({ skillRoot, taskText }) {\n484:   const skillMd = readSkillMd(skillRoot);\n485:   const router = parseRouter(skillMd, skillRoot);\n486:   if (!router.parseable) {\n487:     return {\n488:       parseable: false,\n489:       intents: [],\n490:       resources: [],\n491:       missingResources: [],\n492:       scores: [],\n493:       routeTelemetry: { observed: false, reason: 'router-unparseable' },\n494:     };\n495:   }\n496:   const taskLower = String(taskText || '').toLowerCase();\n497:   const scores = scoreIntents(taskLower, router.intentSignals);\n498:   const intents = selectIntents(scores);\n499:   const routeTelemetry = buildHubRouteTelemetry({ skillRoot, intents, router, taskLower });\n500: \n\n(Showing lines 1-500 of 560. Use offset=501 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env node\n// ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n// ║ router-replay — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay        ║\n// ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n'use strict';\n\n/**\n * router-replay.cjs — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay.\n *\n * The converged design needs the intra-skill router replayed deterministically\n * (zero leakage, CI-friendly) as the D1-intra signal and the D2 discovery proxy.\n * The router lives as INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP inside a fenced block in the\n * target SKILL.md; it is documentation, not an importable module, so this script\n * extracts the dictionaries and reproduces the exact substring-scoring semantics:\n * lowercase the task, score each intent by whether each keyword is a substring,\n * keep intents within an ambiguity delta of the top score, then union the default\n * resource + RESOURCE_MAP[intent] for the selected intents.\n *\n * Exit: 0 on a successful replay (even with zero intents), 2 on unparseable router.\n */","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs","text":"#!/usr/bin/env node\n// ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗\n// ║ router-replay — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay        ║\n// ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝\n'use strict';\n\n/**\n * router-replay.cjs — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay.\n *\n * The converged design needs the intra-skill router replayed deterministically\n * (zero leakage, CI-friendly) as the D1-intra signal and the D2 discovery proxy.\n * The router lives as INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP inside a fenced block in the\n * target SKILL.md; it is documentation, not an importable module, so this script\n * extracts the dictionaries and reproduces the exact substring-scoring semantics:\n * lowercase the task, score each intent by whether each keyword is a substring,\n * keep intents within an ambiguity delta of the top score, then union the default\n * resource + RESOURCE_MAP[intent] for the selected intents.\n *\n * Exit: 0 on a successful replay (even with zero intents), 2 on unparseable router.\n */\n\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// 1. IMPORTS\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nconst fs = require('fs');\nconst path = require('path');\n\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// 2. CONSTANTS\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nconst AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1; // mirror the in-skill router: keep near-tied intents\n\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// 3. HELPERS\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nfunction readSkillMd(skillRoot) {\n  const p = path.join(skillRoot, 'SKILL.md');\n  if (!fs.existsSync(p)) throw new Error(`SKILL.md not found under ${skillRoot}`);\n  return fs.readFileSync(p, 'utf8');\n}\n\n// Pull the {...}-balanced body that follows `NAME = {` from the SKILL.md text.\nfunction extractDictBody(text, name) {\n  const start = text.indexOf(`${name} = {`);\n  if (start === -1) return null;\n  let i = text.indexOf('{', start);\n  let depth = 0;\n  for (let j = i; j < text.length; j += 1) {\n    const ch = text[j];\n    if (ch === '{') depth += 1;\n    else if (ch === '}') {\n      depth -= 1;\n      if (depth === 0) return text.slice(i + 1, j);\n    }\n  }\n  return null;\n}\n\nfunction quotedStrings(segment) {\n  const out = [];\n  const re = /\"([^\"]*)\"|'([^']*)'/g;\n  let m;\n  while ((m = re.exec(segment)) !== null) out.push(m[1] !== undefined ? m[1] : m[2]);\n  return out;\n}\n\n// INTENT_SIGNALS = { \"KEY\": {\"weight\": N, \"keywords\": [\"a\",\"b\"]}, ... }\nfunction parseIntentSignals(body) {\n  const signals = {};\n  if (!body) return signals;\n  const entryRe = /[\"']([A-Z0-9_]+)[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\{([^}]*)\\}/g;\n  let m;\n  while ((m = entryRe.exec(body)) !== null) {\n    const key = m[1];\n    const inner = m[2];\n    const weightMatch = /[\"']weight[\"']\\s*:\\s*(\\d+(?:\\.\\d+)?)/.exec(inner);\n    const kwMatch = /[\"']keywords[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\[([^\\]]*)\\]/.exec(inner);\n    signals[key] = {\n      weight: weightMatch ? Number(weightMatch[1]) : 1,\n      keywords: kwMatch ? quotedStrings(kwMatch[1]).map((k) => k.toLowerCase()) : [],\n    };\n  }\n  return signals;\n}\n\n// RESOURCE_MAP = { \"KEY\": [\"path/a.md\", \"path/b.md\"], ... }\nfunction parseResourceMap(body) {\n  const map = {};\n  if (!body) return map;\n  const entryRe = /[\"']([A-Z0-9_]+)[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\[([^\\]]*)\\]/g;\n  let m;\n  while ((m = entryRe.exec(body)) !== null) map[m[1]] = quotedStrings(m[2]);\n  return map;\n}\n\n// DEFAULT_RESOURCE may be a single quoted path or a list of them. A skill's\n// always-loaded routing preamble (e.g. stack/phase detection plus the router\n// doc) is genuinely consulted on every route, so the replay seeds every result\n// with the whole set. Always returns an array; [] when absent.\nfunction parseDefaultResource(text) {\n  const listM = /DEFAULT_RESOURCES?\\s*=\\s*\\[([\\s\\S]*?)\\]/.exec(text);\n  if (listM) {\n    return [...listM[1].matchAll(/[\"']([^\"']+)[\"']/g)].map((m) => m[1]);\n  }\n  const strM = /DEFAULT_RESOURCES?\\s*=\\s*[\"']([^\"']+)[\"']/.exec(text);\n  return strM ? [strM[1]] : [];\n}\n\nfunction projectHubRouter(filePath) {\n  const data = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8'));\n  const signals = data.routerSignals && typeof data.routerSignals === 'object' ? data.routerSignals : {};\n  const vocabulary = data.vocabularyClasses && typeof data.vocabularyClasses === 'object'\n    ? data.vocabularyClasses\n    : {};\n  const intentSignals = {};\n  const resourceMap = {};\n\n  for (const [mode, signal] of Object.entries(signals)) {\n    const keywords = new Set();\n    for (const className of signal.classes || []) {\n      const klass = vocabulary[className];\n      for (const keyword of klass && Array.isArray(klass.keywords) ? klass.keywords : []) {\n        keywords.add(String(keyword).toLowerCase());\n      }\n    }\n    for (const keyword of Array.isArray(signal.keywords) ? signal.keywords : []) {\n      keywords.add(String(keyword).toLowerCase());\n    }\n\n    intentSignals[mode] = {\n      weight: Number.isFinite(Number(signal.weight)) ? Number(signal.weight) : 1,\n      keywords: [...keywords],\n    };\n    resourceMap[mode] = Array.isArray(signal.resources) ? signal.resources : [];\n  }\n\n  const policy = data.routerPolicy && typeof data.routerPolicy === 'object' ? data.routerPolicy : {};\n  return {\n    intentSignals,\n    resourceMap,\n    defaultResource: Array.isArray(policy.defaultResource) ? policy.defaultResource : [],\n  };\n}\n\nfunction readJsonObject(filePath) {\n  try {\n    if (!fs.existsSync(filePath)) return null;\n    const data = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8'));\n    return data && typeof data === 'object' ? data : null;\n  } catch {\n    return null;\n  }\n}\n\nfunction buildRegistryIndex(skillRoot) {\n  const registry = readJsonObject(path.join(skillRoot, 'mode-registry.json'));\n  const modes = registry && Array.isArray(registry.modes) ? registry.modes : [];\n  const byMode = {};\n  for (const mode of modes) {\n    if (!mode || typeof mode !== 'object' || !mode.workflowMode) continue;\n    byMode[String(mode.workflowMode)] = mode;\n  }\n  return byMode;\n}\n\nfunction buildHubRouteTelemetry({ skillRoot, intents, router, taskLower }) {\n  if (!router || router.routerSource !== 'hub-router.json') {\n    return { observed: false, reason: 'no-hub-router' };\n  }\n\n  const hub = readJsonObject(path.join(skillRoot, 'hub-router.json')) || {};\n  const policy = hub.routerPolicy && typeof hub.routerPolicy === 'object' ? hub.routerPolicy : {};\n  const selectedModes = Array.isArray(intents) ? intents : [];\n  const matchedAliases = [];\n\n  for (const mode of selectedModes) {\n    const signal = router.intentSignals && router.intentSignals[mode] ? router.intentSignals[mode] : {};\n    for (const keyword of Array.isArray(signal.keywords) ? signal.keywords : []) {\n      if (keywordHits(taskLower, keyword)) matchedAliases.push(keyword);\n    }\n  }\n\n  const registry = buildRegistryIndex(skillRoot);\n  const backendKind = [];\n  const packet = [];\n  for (const mode of selectedModes) {\n    const entry = registry[mode];\n    if (!entry) continue;\n    if (entry.backendKind) backendKind.push(entry.backendKind);\n    if (entry.packet) packet.push(entry.packet);\n  }\n\n  const defaultApplied = selectedModes.length === 0 && policy.defaultMode != null;\n  const deferReason = selectedModes.length === 0\n    ? 'no-mode-scored'\n    : (selectedModes.length > 1 ? 'ambiguous-multi-axis' : null);\n\n  return {\n    observed: true,\n    source: 'hub-router',\n    workflowMode: selectedModes.length ? selectedModes : null,\n    matchedAliases: [...new Set(matchedAliases)],\n    defaultApplied,\n    deferReason,\n    backendKind,\n    packet,\n  };\n}\n\n// Some skills keep the authoritative router in a referenced doc (e.g.\n// references/smart_routing.md) rather than inlining it in SKILL.md. When the\n// inline dictionaries are absent we follow that pointer and parse the same\n// INTENT_SIGNALS / RESOURCE_MAP block from the referenced file. Inline always\n// wins; a skill with no inline block and no parseable referenced doc stays\n// unparseable, so a genuinely router-less skill is still reported as such.\nconst ROUTER_REF_HINT = /(resource_map|intent_signals|intent_model|smart[ _-]?rout|routing logic)/i;\n\nfunction findReferencedRouterDoc(skillMdText, skillRoot) {\n  const pathRe = /(?:\\.\\/)?(references\\/[A-Za-z0-9_./-]+\\.md)/;\n  for (const line of skillMdText.split('\\n')) {\n    if (!ROUTER_REF_HINT.test(line)) continue;\n    const m = pathRe.exec(line);\n    if (m) {\n      const candidate = path.join(skillRoot, m[1]);\n      if (fs.existsSync(candidate)) return candidate;\n    }\n  }\n  // Convention fallback: a router doc at the well-known location.\n  const conventional = path.join(skillRoot, 'references', 'smart_routing.md');\n  return fs.existsSync(conventional) ? conventional : null;\n}\n\n/**\n * Extract the in-skill router (INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP + DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n * from SKILL.md, falling back to a referenced router doc when the inline block\n * is absent.\n *\n * @param {string} skillMdText - The SKILL.md text.\n * @param {string} skillRoot - Skill root dir (for resolving referenced docs).\n * @returns {{intentSignals:Object,resourceMap:Object,defaultResource:string[],parseable:boolean,routerSource:string}} Parsed router.\n */\nfunction parseRouter(skillMdText, skillRoot) {\n  let intentSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(skillMdText, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n  let resourceMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(skillMdText, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n  let defaultResource = parseDefaultResource(skillMdText);\n  let routerSource = 'inline';\n\n  const inlineEmpty = Object.keys(intentSignals).length === 0 && Object.keys(resourceMap).length === 0;\n  if (inlineEmpty && skillRoot) {\n    const refDoc = findReferencedRouterDoc(skillMdText, skillRoot);\n    if (refDoc) {\n      const refText = fs.readFileSync(refDoc, 'utf8');\n      const refSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(refText, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n      const refMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(refText, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n      if (Object.keys(refSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(refMap).length > 0) {\n        intentSignals = refSignals;\n        resourceMap = refMap;\n        defaultResource = defaultResource.length ? defaultResource : parseDefaultResource(refText);\n        routerSource = path.relative(skillRoot, refDoc);\n      }\n    }\n\n    const routerStillEmpty = Object.keys(intentSignals).length === 0 && Object.keys(resourceMap).length === 0;\n    const hubRouter = path.join(skillRoot, 'hub-router.json');\n    if (routerStillEmpty && fs.existsSync(hubRouter)) {\n      const projected = projectHubRouter(hubRouter);\n      if (Object.keys(projected.intentSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(projected.resourceMap).length > 0) {\n        intentSignals = projected.intentSignals;\n        resourceMap = projected.resourceMap;\n        defaultResource = defaultResource.length ? defaultResource : projected.defaultResource;\n        routerSource = 'hub-router.json';\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  const parseable = Object.keys(intentSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(resourceMap).length > 0;\n  return { intentSignals, resourceMap, defaultResource, parseable, routerSource };\n}\n\n/**\n * Score each intent by summing its weight for every keyword that is a substring\n * of the lowercased task, keeping only positive-scoring intents (sorted desc).\n *\n * @param {string} taskLower - Lowercased task text.\n * @param {Object} intentSignals - Map of intent -> {weight, keywords}.\n * @returns {Array<{intent:string,score:number}>} Scored intents, highest first.\n */\nconst WORD_BOUNDARY_KEYWORDS = new Set(['review', 'lcp', 'inp', 'cls']);\n\n// A bare keyword like \"review\" gets swallowed by unrelated longer words\n// (\"preview\" contains \"review\"), so match those on word boundaries. The short\n// performance acronyms need the same guard for the opposite reason: bare \"inp\"\n// would substring-match \"input\", firing the performance intent on unrelated\n// prompts. Path- and identifier-style keywords keep substring matching so\n// \"javascript\" still matches inside \"2_javascript\".\nfunction keywordHits(taskLower, kw) {\n  if (!kw) return false;\n  if (WORD_BOUNDARY_KEYWORDS.has(kw)) {\n    return new RegExp(`\\\\b${kw.replace(/[.*+?^${}()|[\\]\\\\]/g, '\\\\$&')}\\\\b`, 'i').test(taskLower);\n  }\n  return taskLower.includes(kw);\n}\n\nfunction scoreIntents(taskLower, intentSignals) {\n  const scores = [];\n  for (const [key, sig] of Object.entries(intentSignals)) {\n    let score = 0;\n    for (const kw of sig.keywords) {\n      if (keywordHits(taskLower, kw)) score += sig.weight;\n    }\n    if (score > 0) scores.push({ intent: key, score });\n  }\n  scores.sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score);\n  return scores;\n}\n\n/**\n * Select intents within AMBIGUITY_DELTA of the top score (keeps near-tied\n * intents, mirroring the in-skill router).\n *\n * @param {Array<{intent:string,score:number}>} scores - Scored intents, highest first.\n * @returns {string[]} Selected intent keys.\n */\nfunction selectIntents(scores) {\n  if (scores.length === 0) return [];\n  const top = scores[0].score;\n  return scores.filter((s) => top - s.score <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA).map((s) => s.intent);\n}\n\n// Which surface a resource belongs to, by its on-disk path prefix. Webflow and\n// OpenCode resources live under their code-<surface>/ packet folders, so the\n// prefix IS the surface. Motion.dev is a cross-stack overlay folded into\n// code-webflow/{references,assets}/animation/; it is matched FIRST so it stays a\n// distinct overlay surface (kept regardless of the detected code surface) rather\n// than collapsing into WEBFLOW's broader code-webflow/ prefix. Everything else\n// (universal refs, the detection/router preamble) is surface-agnostic.\nconst SURFACE_PREFIXES = {\n  MOTION: ['code-webflow/references/animation/', 'code-webflow/assets/animation/'],\n  WEBFLOW: ['code-webflow/'],\n  OPENCODE: ['code-opencode/'],\n};\nfunction resourceSurface(r) {\n  for (const [surface, prefixes] of Object.entries(SURFACE_PREFIXES)) {\n    if (prefixes.some((p) => r.startsWith(p))) return surface;\n  }\n  return 'UNIVERSAL';\n}\n// Detect the task's code surface from path / extension / marker signals, mirroring\n// the prose stack-detection contract: OpenCode system code wins, then Webflow\n// markers, else UNKNOWN. A task that names both is MIXED (cross-surface).\nfunction detectSurface(taskLower) {\n  const opencode = /\\.opencode\\/|\\bskill\\.md\\b|\\.cjs\\b|\\.mjs\\b|\\.tsx?\\b|\\.py\\b|\\.sh\\b|\\.rs\\b|\\bspec-folder\\b|\\bargparse\\b|graph-metadata/.test(taskLower);\n  const webflow = /src\\/2_javascript|\\bwebflow\\b|\\.webflow\\b|--vw-/.test(taskLower);\n  if (opencode && webflow) return 'MIXED';\n  if (opencode) return 'OPENCODE';\n  if (webflow) return 'WEBFLOW';\n  return 'UNKNOWN';\n}\n// OpenCode-only language sub-detection (mirrors SKILL.md §2). A `.opencode/` task\n// is one language, so it needs only that language's guides — not every language\n// folder. Webflow deliberately has no sub-detection (a frontend task spans\n// css + html + js together).\nconst OPENCODE_LANGUAGES = ['typescript', 'python', 'shell', 'config', 'javascript', 'rust'];\n// Returns the SET of languages a task touches. An interop parity task legitimately\n// touches more than one (e.g. a napi-rs/WASM sidecar over a TypeScript backend must\n// load both the Rust and TypeScript standards), so selection is a set, not a single\n// first match. An empty set preserves the \"no language slice\" behaviour that a null\n// return used to signal. Rust is recognised by `.rs`, Cargo markers, or the\n// napi-rs/wasm-bindgen/WASI/cdylib interop vocabulary; those markers are consulted\n// here only after detectSurface has already resolved the OpenCode surface.\nfunction detectOpencodeLanguages(taskLower) {\n  const langs = new Set();\n  if (/\\.tsx?\\b/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('typescript');\n  if (/\\.py\\b|argparse/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('python');\n  if (/\\.sh\\b|set -euo|shellcheck/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('shell');\n  if (/\\.jsonc?\\b|graph-metadata|descriptor|spec-folder/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('config');\n  if (/\\.cjs\\b|\\.mjs\\b/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('javascript');\n  if (/\\.rs\\b|cargo\\.toml|cargo\\.lock|napi[-_]rs|wasm[-_]bindgen|\\bwasi\\b|\\bcdylib\\b/.test(taskLower)) langs.add('rust');\n  return langs;\n}\n\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n// 4. CORE LOGIC\n// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n// A parent hub selects the MODE in hub-router.json but keeps the flat\n// surface/phase router (INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP over the deep per-surface\n// reference paths) as a retained shared doc. Resource recall must be replayed\n// against THAT router: the hub router only emits packet pointers (a mode's\n// SKILL.md), not the per-surface resource gold the scenarios assert. Probe the\n// conventional locations; a skill with no such doc (every flat skill, and sibling\n// hubs without one) yields null and is left on the normal path unchanged.\nfunction loadSurfaceRouter(skillRoot) {\n  const candidates = [\n    path.join(skillRoot, 'shared', 'references', 'smart_routing.md'),\n    path.join(skillRoot, 'references', 'smart_routing.md'),\n  ];\n  for (const doc of candidates) {\n    if (!fs.existsSync(doc)) continue;\n    const text = fs.readFileSync(doc, 'utf8');\n    const intentSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(text, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n    const resourceMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(text, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n    const defaultResource = parseDefaultResource(text);\n    if (Object.keys(intentSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(resourceMap).length > 0) {\n      return { intentSignals, resourceMap, defaultResource, sourceRel: path.relative(skillRoot, doc) };\n    }\n  }\n  return null;\n}\n\n// The roots a hub's surface resources resolve under, for the missing-resource\n// report: the surface router's paths are relative to the shared preamble tier\n// (stack/phase detection, universal baseline) or a mode packet (post-relocation),\n// not the hub root. Returns [] for a non-hub skill (no registry).\nfunction registryPacketRoots(skillRoot) {\n  const byMode = buildRegistryIndex(skillRoot);\n  const roots = Object.keys(byMode).length ? [path.join(skillRoot, 'shared')] : [];\n  for (const mode of Object.values(byMode)) {\n    if (mode && mode.packet) roots.push(path.join(skillRoot, String(mode.packet)));\n  }\n  return roots;\n}\n\n// Union the default preamble with each selected intent's resources, then apply\n// surface-aware slicing when the map uses a per-surface layout (sk-code): keep the\n// universal tier + Motion.dev overlay + only the DETECTED surface's slice, drop\n// the other surface's resources (the documented over-routing source). Assets are\n// deferred — never the routing gold. A MIXED task keeps both surfaces; UNKNOWN\n// falls back to the universal + Motion tier only. Existence is checked against the\n// skill root plus any extra roots (a hub's packet roots), since a hub's surface\n// paths resolve under a packet rather than the hub root.\nfunction assembleResources({ skillRoot, taskLower, intents, router, extraRoots = [] }) {\n  const resourceSet = new Set();\n  for (const r of router.defaultResource || []) resourceSet.add(r);\n  for (const intent of intents) {\n    for (const r of router.resourceMap[intent] || []) resourceSet.add(r);\n  }\n  let resources = [...resourceSet];\n\n  const mapResources = Object.values(router.resourceMap).flat();\n  const hasSurfaceLayout = mapResources.some((r) => r.startsWith('code-webflow/references/'))\n    && mapResources.some((r) => r.startsWith('code-opencode/references/'));\n  let surface;\n  if (hasSurfaceLayout) {\n    surface = detectSurface(taskLower);\n    // Within OpenCode, slice further to the touched-language set so a TypeScript task\n    // does not also pull the Python/shell/config guides, while an interop task that\n    // touches both Rust and TypeScript keeps both trios. Non-language OpenCode\n    // folders (e.g. `shared/`) are always kept.\n    const ocLangs = surface === 'OPENCODE' ? detectOpencodeLanguages(taskLower) : new Set();\n    resources = resources.filter((r) => {\n      if (r.includes('/assets/')) return false;\n      const rs = resourceSurface(r);\n      if (rs === 'UNIVERSAL' || rs === 'MOTION') return true;\n      if (surface === 'MIXED') return true;\n      if (surface === 'UNKNOWN') return false;\n      if (rs !== surface) return false;\n      if (ocLangs.size) {\n        const m = /^code-opencode\\/references\\/([^/]+)\\//.exec(r);\n        if (m && OPENCODE_LANGUAGES.includes(m[1]) && !ocLangs.has(m[1])) return false;\n      }\n      return true;\n    });\n  }\n\n  const roots = [skillRoot, ...extraRoots];\n  const missingResources = resources.filter((r) => !roots.some((root) => fs.existsSync(path.join(root, r))));\n  return { resources, missingResources, surface };\n}\n\n/**\n * Replay the in-skill router for a task and return the routed resources.\n *\n * @param {Object} args - Routing inputs.\n * @param {string} args.skillRoot - Skill root dir containing SKILL.md.\n * @param {string} args.taskText - Task text to route.\n * @returns {{ parseable: boolean, intents: string[], resources: string[],\n *   missingResources: string[], scores: Array<{intent:string,score:number}>, surface?: string }}\n */\nfunction routeSkillResources({ skillRoot, taskText }) {\n  const skillMd = readSkillMd(skillRoot);\n  const router = parseRouter(skillMd, skillRoot);\n  if (!router.parseable) {\n    return {\n      parseable: false,\n      intents: [],\n      resources: [],\n      missingResources: [],\n      scores: [],\n      routeTelemetry: { observed: false, reason: 'router-unparseable' },\n    };\n  }\n  const taskLower = String(taskText || '').toLowerCase();\n  const scores = scoreIntents(taskLower, router.intentSignals);\n  const intents = selectIntents(scores);\n  const routeTelemetry = buildHubRouteTelemetry({ skillRoot, intents, router, taskLower });\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":500,"totalLines":560,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs","time":{"start":1783806826547,"end":1783806826602}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03560debd78a9e1e016a52bb6a3d5c8191b43dfcbcee2c2514"}},"id":"prt_f532c1831001CVfCfdXYXHoqda","sessionID":"ses_0acd715bbffezygsvb9LhK73F1","messageID":"msg_f532bda63001mH5NGE79SwVby9"}}
